<HEADLINE>
EXPLOSIVES STOLEN NEAR FLAGSTAFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BEVERLY FORD  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Federal agents searched a remote mining camp southwest of
Flagstaff on Friday, looking for clues to the theft of nearly 1,000
pounds of explosives and questioning workers with access to the
locked area where the missing materials were stored.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said 750 pounds of fuel-soaked ammonium nitrate, 250
pounds of dynamite; 6,000 feet of detonation cord and about 20
blasting caps were stolen after 5 p.m. Monday from the 3 Wins
Mining Co. camp near the tiny community of Drake.
</P>
<P>
   The materials all are commonly used in mining, authorities said,
but they also can be used to make a bomb. Officials stopped short
of connecting the theft to terrorism, but the amount taken _ enough
to level a high-rise _ worries them.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was no security. This is a very remote site,'' said
Special Agent Larry Bettendorf of the federal Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms.
</P>
<P>
   He said the thieves could easily have carted off the explosives
in a pickup truck.
</P>
<P>
   The materials were inside two locked steel-plated boxes beside a
dirt road on the property.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities would not discuss how the thieves opened the boxes,
but said that only about a dozen workers had access to the storage
area.
</P>
<P>
   Ammonium nitrate was the primary ingredient in the 4,800-pound
bomb that exploded outside the Alfred P. Murrah Federal Building in
Oklahoma City in April 1995, killing 138 people.
</P>
<P>
   Nationwide last year, Bettendorf said, 4,000 pounds of ammonium
nitrate was stolen, and 26,000 pounds has been stolen during the
past five years.
</P>
<P>
   ``If someone knew what they were doing, they could do a lot of
damage,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   But it's not clear whether the theft was part of some New Year's
terrorist plot or whether the timing was merely coincidental. The
FBI recently warned of potential terrorism around Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   Sam Whitted, deputy chief with the Coconino County Sheriff's
Department, said no threats have been linked to the theft and no
group has claimed responsibility for it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the use of this material is pure speculation,''
Whitted said. ``We just don't know at this point.''
</P>
<P>
   Workers with California-based 3 Wins Mining, which operates the
M.C. Sandstone Quarry, noticed the theft Monday night or Tuesday
morning but didn't report it until midday Thursday, officials said.
An investigation into that delay was under way Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Company officials could not be reached for comment.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities said workers with access to the area where the
explosives were stored are being questioned about the theft, as are
other quarry workers.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Scott Sterne, owner of Phoenix Demolition Co. and
Salvage, said the amount of explosives stolen is worrisome.
</P>
<P>
   The 750 pounds of ammonium nitrate alone, Sterne said, ``is
enough to create a major national disaster on the order of the
Oklahoma City bombing.''
</P>
<P>
   Add to that 250 pounds of missing dynamite: enough, Sterne
estimates, to bring down the Bank One building in downtown
Phoenix. &QL; 
Republic writer John Stanley contributed to this article. Beverly
Ford can be reached at &QL; 
beverly.ford(at)arizonarepublic.com or (602) 444-8543. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
