<SLUG> BC-KIDNEY-DONOR-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TEACHER DONATES A KIDNEY TO A STUDENT 
</HEADLINE>
   (CLARIFIES reference to father in 5th graf) 
 (DW) 
 By EMILY YELLIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   CHAPEL HILL, N.C. _ Jane Smith, a middle school teacher in
Fayetteville, was always telling Michael Carter, a student of hers,
to pull up his baggy pants. What Ms. Smith did not know was that
Michael suffered from kidney disease and that the illness, and
resulting dialysis, left him routinely sore.
</P>
<P>
   So when she made one too many demands about those pants,
``finally he got exasperated with me,'' Ms. Smith recalled, ``and
said: `I can't. I'm on dialysis. I need a kidney transplant.' And I
said: `Well, I have two. Do you want one?'''
</P>
<P>
   That extraordinary offer led the 14-year-old Michael and the
42-year-old Ms. Smith to the University of North Carolina Hospitals
on Thursday for transplant surgery. Michael is to get his new
kidney, and Ms. Smith is to add organ donor to the roles she
already has in his life, as his teacher for both home room and
general science.
</P>
<P>
   The operation, scheduled for Friday, was postponed after Michael
developed a low-grade fever. The antibiotics that he is now being
given at the hospital to fight the infection, so far of
undetermined cause, meant that he could not be given immune
suppressant drugs that transplant patients receive to ensure that
their bodies will not reject the new organ.
</P>
<P>
   But the delay is only a minor setback to Michael and his
parents, Richard and Deborah Evans who have learned to endure a lot
more. ``This too shall pass,'' his mother said.
</P>
<P>
   Michael, the second of five children of Mrs. Evans and her
husband, Richard, a 50-year-old home builder, was found to have
kidney disease when he was only 16 months old. At 13 years, one
kidney stopped functioning entirely. He has been receiving dialysis
treatment ever since.
</P>
<P>
   For more than a year, a donor was sought from among Michael's
friends and relatives. But medical tests failed to find a match.
</P>
<P>
   Then, soon ater the beginning of the current school year, Ms.
Smith, an eighth-grade teacher at the R. Max Abbott Middle School
in Fayetteville, learned of Michael's illness.
</P>
<P>
   ``I instantly knew that this was something I could do,'' she
said, ``that there was no pain I could suffer that would be as
great as what Michael was going through.''
</P>
<P>
   After a battery of tests and many anxious moments, teacher and
student were told that they were a match, and the surgery was
scheduled to coincide with the school's Christmas break.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith, the divorced mother of a 12-year-old boy, says she
has never had second thoughts about her decision. Michael's illness
``is holding him back,'' she said. ``He's got a good mind, and he's
got the desire. But he just hasn't had the physical energy to
follow through.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Evans says she and her family are still stunned by Ms.
Smith's generosity.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never had anyone to reach out like that,'' she said,
``someone outside my family. It says a lot. No matter what you're
going through, no matter how difficult the situation may appear,
there is an answer out there. You just have to be patient.''
</P>
<P>
   That Michael is black and Ms. Smith white has also inspired
many, not only people here in North Carolina but those across the
country who have seen reports about the two of them on national
television.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, though, Ms. Smith has played down her role,
saying she hopes the story will simply call attention to the need
for organ donations.
</P>
<P>
   ``In this world you need to realize that there's a bond,'' she
said. ``There's a connection between you and everybody else you
see.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith and Mrs. Evans are both devout Baptists, and say their
religious faith has helped them through the experience. ``God chose
us together,'' Mrs. Evans said, ``to accomplish his purpose'' _ to
extend Michael's life and raise consciousness about organ donating.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Smith says that when she found out in October that she was a
match for Michael, she spoke to her own son first.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told him I was not going to be taken away from him because
of it,'' she said, ``and that Michael had a need, and this was
something that was a miracle that we could fix.''
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Evans remembers that when she learned of the match, she
went to the school and found Ms. Smith, and they hugged.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was like our whole soul became one,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Then, Mrs. Evans says, she offered up special prayers for Ms.
Smith.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said to the Lord, `thank you for that lady, thank you for
Jane Smith.' I was so grateful, but I was getting bold with the
Lord. I was getting tough. I said: `Don't you ever let her want for
anything, Lord. Don't even let her want for a Kleenex. God, don't
you let her tire go flat.'
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I was going down the list, because I couldn't ever
repay her enough for what she had done.''
</P>
</TEXT>
