<SLUG> BC-SUPREMACIS18-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GILBERT CRITICIZED FOR HATE-CRIME STAND 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By EDYTHE JENSEN  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   A member of Gilbert's ``Devil Dogs'' White supremacist gang had
some powerful people standing up for him before he was sentenced in
the gang beating of strangers who were taunted with shouts of
``homo'' and ``White power.''
</P>
<P>
   The town's former mayor sent the judge a letter to vouch for
Glenn Cribbin's character, and a high school athletic director
testified in an attempt to spare his former wrestling star from
jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``How many times have we seen a young man inappropriately use
his strength rather than his brains?'' former Mayor James Farley
asked in his letter. ``That is what happened here _ nothing more.''
</P>
<P>
   Such high-powered support has the head of the area chapter of
the National Association for the Advancement of Colored People
questioning whether Gilbert really is serious about combating hate
crime.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's changed the way I think of Gilbert,'' said Floyd
Galloway, who had helped the town host school diversity meetings
after reports of gang violence and intimidation began surfacing
this year.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he believes the meetings were a sham, and he doubts he'll
continue to attend them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gilbert seems more concerned with its public image than with
justice,'' Galloway said.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy County Attorney Hugo Zettler, who is prosecuting Devil
Dog members, agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``These are high school jocks and privileged kids who think it's
OK to pick on Blacks, Asians and Hispanics,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``And Gilbert would just as soon hide it than blemish its
schools.''
</P>
<P>
   Judge Mark Aceto of Maricopa County Superior Court wasn't swayed
by Cribbin's influential supporters. On Nov. 30, he sentenced the
19-year-old former Highland High wrestling champion to a year
behind bars and three years' probation for felony assault.
</P>
<P>
   Cribbin and seven teenagers were accused in the March beating of
two Taco Bell customers, who were picked at random for attack.
Witnesses heard the young people barking like dogs and yelling,
``Hey homo!'' and ``White power!''
</P>
<P>
   Both victims, who are White, were hurt. One was hospitalized for
injuries to his face, eyes and arms.
</P>
<P>
   Town spokesman David Cannella said it's unfair to accuse Gilbert
of tolerating such attacks when town officials have worked hard to
promote tolerance through a ``Community With Character'' program.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are entitled to testify on behalf of whomever they
want,'' Cannella said. ``The Police Department investigates crime.
. . . When it gets to the judicial system, that's separate from the
town.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert, however, has been criticized by some civil rights
leaders for failing to take up the Justice Department on its
4-month-old offer to send in a special team that deals with racial
tensions.
</P>
<P>
   Attacks linked to the Devil Dogs gang have included the May
beating of a Mesa boy who must undergo plastic surgery to repair
damage to his face. In April, three teens approached an
Asian-American couple who were boating in Gilbert's Val Vista Lakes
development. They stole the man's cellular phone, yelled racial
slurs and tried to tip over the boat.
</P>
<P>
   Highland High Athletic Director Kevin Fagan said he was a
character witness at the request of Cribbin's father.
</P>
<P>
   ``His father won a state championship in wrestling . . . and his
son was a good kid in school, very respectful,'' Fagan said.
</P>
<P>
   He said he didn't know that Cribbin had a juvenile record or
that he admitted abusing alcohol and drugs while in high school,
information contained in court records.
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert Schools Superintendent Walter Delecki said he didn't
know Fagan testified in Cribbin's behalf. But he was familiar with
the Taco Bell attack.
</P>
<P>
   Delecki said his teenage son, Jacob, was with some of the
defendants the night of the assault and was listed in police
reports as a witness to the beatings.
</P>
<P>
   The superintendent said his son is a law-abiding boy whose only
offense is being kind to the assailants.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I told him, `You can't run with these kids _ it's guilt by
association.' ''
</P>
<P>
   In Farley's letter pleading for leniency for Cribbin, the former
mayor said he was assured by an ``impeccable source'' that the Taco
Bell violence was not gang-related. Farley later said the source
was his teenage son.
</P>
<P>
   He suggested that steroids may have been the catalyst for the
violence.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're muscle-bound goofballs you don't want at your party
because they fight,'' Farley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``This thing has been monstrously blown out of proportion. I've
known the Cribbin family for years; they're good people, and I'm
proud to call them my friends.''
</P>
<P>
   Gilbert police gang Detective Terry Burchett said in a
presentence report that she believes Cribbin is one of the town's
main gang players. But, Burchett said, building cases is hard
because victims are too scared to come forward for fear of
retribution.
</P>
<P>
   One victim has been threatened through phone calls and
vandalism, and his mother asked that the family not be identified
because of the threats.
</P>
<P>
   Zettler, the deputy county attorney, said the harassment has
included veiled messages that harken to the Taco Bell case, taco
wrappers littered one man's front lawn.
</P>
<P>
   Police in Gilbert and Mesa say they are cooperating in an
ongoing investigation of the White supremacist gang.
</P>
<P>
   They confirmed that police seized a photograph from one youth's
home that depicts a group photograph of gang members flashing their
hand signs on a Gilbert high school campus. &QL; 
Edythe Jensen can be reached at  &QL; 
edythe.jensen(at)arizonarepublic.com or at (602) 444-7939. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
