<HEADLINE>
FIRST LADY IN KANSAS CITY FOR FUND-RAISER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE KRASKE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ First lady Hillary
Rodham Clinton was expected to pull $100,000 out of Kansas City on
Friday to bolster her campaign for the U.S. Senate from New York
and for Democratic Senate candidates nationwide.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Clinton attended two private events: one at the home of Kansas
City jeweler Harold Tivol, and another at the home of Democratic
backer Farhad Azima.
</P>
<P>
   The Tivol event cost $1,000 a person. The Azima event, which
included dinner with Clinton, was $5,000 a couple.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton was expected to raise $100,000 in Kansas City, said
David DiMartino, spokesman for the Democratic Senatorial Campaign
Committee. Proceeds were to go to a fund called ``New York Victory
2000'' that benefits Clinton's campaign and the senatorial campaign
committee.
</P>
<P>
   Among those attending the event at the Tivols were Mayor Kay
Barnes, former Mayor Emanuel Cleaver and U.S. Rep. Dennis Moore of
Lenexa, Kan.
</P>
<P>
   Afterward, Cleaver described Clinton's talk as ``very eloquent''
and said it was important to send her to the Senate. ``Anytime we
have a chance to put somebody into the column of compassion and
concern we need to do it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Kansas City events, including her arrival at Downtown
Airport, were closed to reporters.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've known both of them,'' Azima said, referring to the
president and his wife. ``I've supported both of them. They are
friends. I'm delighted to be able to do whatever I need to do to
help her in her campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   Azima, an aviation executive, was caught up briefly in the
troubles around Democratic fund raising for the 1996 elections. The
Democratic National Committee announced it would return more than
$140,000 of his contributions, but changed its mind and apologized
to Azima after discounting questions of impropriety.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
