<SLUG> BC-IRAQ-U.N.-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DIVIDED COUNCIL APPROVES ARMS INSPECTION SYSTEM FOR IRAQ 
</HEADLINE>
   (REWRITES 18th graf to update, clarify) 
 (th) 
 By BARBARA CROSSETTE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service     
<TEXT>
<P>
   UNITED NATIONS _ A divided Security Council voted Friday to
create a new arms inspection system for Iraq with the promise to
President Saddam Hussein that sanctions against his country could
be suspended within a year and eventually lifted if he cooperates.
</P>
<P>
   The plan immediately removes the ceiling on the amount of oil
Iraq may sell abroad _ now set at $5.26 billion every six months _
to buy food and necessary goods for a population struggling under
economic sanctions imposed after Iraq's invasion of Kuwait in 1990.
</P>
<P>
   It also relaxes some controls on Iraq's import of medical,
agricultural and educational supplies, though the sanctions _
including a ban on international flights except for pilgrimages to
Mecca _ formally remain in place.
</P>
<P>
   An arduous process of persuading Iraq to respond to these
incentives to cooperate with the arms inspection plan will now
begin.
</P>
<P>
   Iraq's envoy at the United Nations, Saeed Hassan, restated his
government's earlier rejection of the resolution. Iraq had already
insisted it would not permit any U.N. inspectors back into Iraq and
demanded that the sanctions _ which under terms ending the 1991
Persian Gulf war are to remain in place until Iraq proves it has
eliminated weapons of mass destruction _ be unconditionally halted.
Iraq has barred inspectors since last December after American and
British warplanes struck Baghdad for not cooperating with the
inspections.
</P>
<P>
   The vote on the 15-member Security Council was 11 in favor with
four abstentions. At the decisive moment, France broke ranks with
the United States and the European Union and abstained along with
Russia, China and Malaysia, which holds a nonpermanent Security
Council seat.
</P>
<P>
   With only two of the five permanent council members voting in
favor, some diplomats predicted that Iraq will be emboldened in its
resistance to the plan. The two permament members who voted for it,
Britain and the United States, are portrayed in Iraq as the
country's worst enemies, and they now appear isolated.
</P>
<P>
   Peter Burleigh, the departing American deputy chief
representative, who has negotiated the Iraqi issue for the United
States here for more than a year, called the vote ``a profoundly
important moment for the Security Council'' and added that what is
now required of Iraq ``could not be more clear.''
</P>
<P>
   Iraq, he said, will be required to allow weapons inspectors to
return, to maximize benefits for the Iraqi people from its earnings
and to cooperate in the accounting for Kuwaitis missing since the
1990 invasion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The vote today was not unanimous,'' Burleigh told the council,
``but no member asserts that Iraq has met its obligations under the
council's resolutions. No council member argues that Iraq has
disarmed as required.''
</P>
<P>
   Sir Jeremy Greenstock of Britain, president of the council for
December and the sponsor of Friday's resolution, called its
adoption ``an exceptional achievement'' in linking relief for
Iraqis living under sanctions with assigned disarmament tasks.
</P>
<P>
   ``We regret,'' he said, ``that on this point, some have been
more inclined to listen to the voice of the Iraqi leadership than
the needs of the Iraqi people.''
</P>
<P>
   British and American diplomats played down the abstentions,
saying that the important fact was that no nation voted against the
plan.
</P>
<P>
   But a number of arms control experts said that whether or not
Iraq eventually agrees to the stationing of inspectors and the
installation of sophisticated monitoring devices, the damage is
already done as far as close surveillance of Iraq is concerned.
</P>
<P>
   To arms control experts, the mystery is why the Clinton
administration agreed to these more lenient provisions, or how
American officials allowed themselves to be drawn into compromises
that in the end did not deliver a united Security Council. Many
believe that compromise was pointless, given strong Russian and
Chinese opposition to sanctions and France's unwillingness to
jeopardize its commercial and diplomatic relations with Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Gambia's representative, Baboucar-laise Jagne, reflecting on
more than a year of debate on how to deal with Iraq since the last
inspectors left a year ago, called the resolution ``the lowest
common denominator.''
</P>
<P>
   There is also a sense among many diplomats and officials here
that the Clinton Administration does not L want Iraq to resurface
as a crisis that might intrude in next fall's elec- tion. Even if
Iraq accepted the plan, it is unlikely that sanctions could be
suspended before late next year, giv- en the timetable set up under
the resolution.
 &UR;  &LR;  Gary Milhollin, director of the Wisconsin Project on Nuclear Arms
Control in Washington, said in an interview that under the new plan
``a much greater amount of equipment is going to go to Iraq without
anybody looking at it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We know already that the Iraqis have abused the medical
exception to import things that can be used to make nuclear
weapons,'' he said. ``Under the new system there is going to be
this whole category of things that don't have to be individually
approved. If the past is any guide, you have to assume that a lot
of those things will be useful for making weapons, and nobody will
be the wiser.''
</P>
<P>
   Milhollin, who reported recently in The New Yorker about an
Iraqi order last year for half a dozen lithotripters, said that
this was an example of how Baghdad may be trying to hide purchases
intended for building weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The lithotripters, sophisticated machines for pulverizing kidney
stones, require electronic switches that produce a high-power burst
of electricity _ enough to trigger a nuclear bomb if 32 of them are
used, Milhollin said. In buying the lithotripters, Iraq tried to
get 120 extra switches from Siemens, the German electronics
company, which turned over the order to a supplier, the Thomson-CSF
company of France, at which point the French government stepped in
and barred the sale.
</P>
<P>
   The case suggests that the French are aware of Iraq's continuing
efforts to assemble the components of nuclear weapons. Moreover,
Iraq is blocking routine inspections of its low-enriched uranium
and natural uranium stocks by the International Atomic Energy
Agency, raising speculation about what it may be trying to hide.
Yet President Jacques Chirac of France said in an interview this
week that nuclear weapons are no longer an issue in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   An informal discussion paper put together by the experts at
UNSCOM _ the U.N. Special Commission that was created after the
Persian Gulf war to disarm Iraq and dismantle industries that could
rebuild biological, chemical and missile systems _ said that there
should be cause for alarm also in a Security Council decision to
remove from Friday's resolution an earlier provision calling for
the new monitoring system to include UNSCOM inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   Without some institutional memory to augment the archives that
the new commission will inherit, experts say, inspectors may not
know what questions must be asked of Iraq, especially on biological
and chemical weapons.
</P>
<P>
   UNSCOM inspectors also complain that the new resolution turns
the burden of proof upside down. Where Iraq had formerly been
expected to set out the tasks it would accomplish _ like accounting
for certain materials or equipment _ which could be accepted or
rejected by UNSCOM, the new system calls for the tasks to be
assigned by inspectors. That allows Iraq to meet only those
requirements, while concealing other activities outside the purview
of the list.
</P>
<P>
   Like Milhollin and other independent arms control experts,
UNSCOM inspectors fear that blanket permission to import certain
relief goods will inevitably be used by the Iraqis to buy equipment
or material usable in making arms. A lifting of controls over spare
parts used in the oil industry could also allow what experts call
``dual use'' items suitable for civilian or military projects to
flow relatively easily into Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   At the Nuclear Control Institute in Washington, Paul L.
Leventhal, president of the independent organization, said that
once in the country, clandestine equipment for a range of tasks
including enriching uranium for use in bombs, could be hidden in
what look like ordinary factories.
</P>
<P>
   International experts who follow Iraq in a number of agencies
and private institutes believe that Iraq's Military Industrial
Commission has reassembled some manufacturing processes critical to
making a range of prohibited weapons. Scientists and researchers
who built Iraqi weapons before 1991 are also available to the Iraqi
government, some of them held as virtual hostages.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution passed Friday creates a new organization to be
called the U.N. Monitoring, Verification and Inspection Commission.
It will have an executive chairman to be appointed within 30 days
by Secretary-General Kofi Annan and approved by the Security
Council.
</P>
<P>
   Under the new resolution, a ``college of commissioners'' will be
created to review the work of the new monitoring system. Within the
first 45 days on the job, the executive chairman must submit an
organizational plan for the staffing and administration of the
commission and its work in Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   Not later than 60 days after inspectors from the new commission
and the International Atomic Energy Agency have started working in
Iraq, the commission is to draw up a work program, listing tasks to
be accomplished by Iraq.
</P>
<P>
   The resolution says that what is required of Iraq ``shall be
clearly defined and precise.'' It is this provision that concerns
arms control experts who say it leaves inspectors little room to
maneuver if they see something unexpected.
</P>
<P>
   Once the monitoring systems have been working for 120 days with
Iraqi cooperation, sanctions on Iraq can be suspended for renewable
periods of 120 days. Financial controls and import surveillance
except on newly excluded items will continue. The existing ``oil
for food'' program, which has allowed Iraq to sell oil to buy
civilian goods, will be folded into the new resolution.
</P>
</TEXT>
