<HEADLINE>
FROM 1999, SOME WORDS FROM OTHERS TO PONDER 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JERRY HEASTER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ In a world awash with
balderdash, those who speak words of wisdom deserve their due.
Here, for your pondering pleasure, are some of 1999's most
insightful observations:
<TEXT>
<P>
   - The hallmark of the 1999 stock market is the devaluation of
knowledge. What is there to know? The stock market is going up;
ergo, buy stocks. Small wonder that what passes for financial
analysis...more and more tastes like brain candy. Knowing that,
people ought to eat less of it. (Jeremy Diamond, financial
publisher)
</P>
<P>
   - As we excitedly enter upon the Information Age, we would do
well to recall T.S. Eliot's lament: Where is the wisdom we have
lost in knowledge? Where is the knowledge we have lost in
information? (Herbert Stein, economist)
</P>
<P>
   - (Peter) Drucker teaches us that organizations perform only
when their purpose is clearly defined and that profit is not a
purpose, but a result....Profits are important because they tell
you whether your theory (of business) is working. (Joan Magretta
and Nan Stone, in The Wall Street Journal)
</P>
<P>
   - Historically, political unification has always preceded
monetary unification. (The euro) is a shot in the dark. Europe is
like someone who first buys a computer and then asks, ``What do I
do with it?'' (Antonio Martino, former Italian foreign minister)
</P>
<P>
   - I have begun to feel foolish being a fan. I feel foolish
giving allegiance to any team made up of players whose loyalty to
the team is patently a good deal less than my own. (Joseph Epstein,
writer)
</P>
<P>
   - Tolerance is amoral: It needs to be morally directed or one
can never know what should be tolerated and what should not be
tolerated....If we continue to teach about tolerance and
intolerance instead of teaching about good and evil, we will end up
with tolerance of evil. (Dennis Prager, writer)
</P>
<P>
   - As risk hyperbolists (chip) away at our country's
technological arsenal _ pesticide, food additives, pharmaceuticals,
industrial chemicals _ they threaten our enviable high standards of
living while offering no health benefits in return. (Elizabeth
Whelan, science advocate)
</P>
<P>
   - The leaders of this new neo-earnestness use the same weapon
earnest people have always used, their ability to bore the rest of
us into submission. (David Brooks, writer)
</P>
<P>
   - Mr. Reagan is like a political North Star: Candidates define
themselves in comparison to him. (Gerald F. Seib, The Wall Street
Journal)
</P>
<P>
   - Never in the course of human history have so many of us
depended on so many other humans not to screw up. (Ed Yardeni,
economist, on lack of Y2K concern)
</P>
<P>
   - In our era, the wealth of nations lies in their human
resources....A debilitated, unhealthy Russia is unlikely to be
capable of maintaining a highly productive economic system.
(Nicholas Eberstadt, economic analyst)
</P>
<P>
   - To congratulate one's self on one's warm commitment to the
environment, or to peace, or to the oppressed, and think no more is
a profound moral fault. (Robert Conquest, historian)
</P>
<P>
   - The idea that you can take smart but inexperienced
25-year-olds who have never managed anything or anybody and turn
them into effective managers via two years of classroom training is
ludicrous. (Henry Mintzberg, business school professor)
</P>
</TEXT>
