<SLUG> BC-Y2K-SUN-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SUN FLARES UNLIKELY TO ADD TO Y2K CONFUSION 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID HAYES and FINN BULLERS  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Cross one more thing
off your Y2K worry list.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Sunspots probably won't knock out satellites or interfere with
radio or television broadcasts over the New Year's weekend.
</P>
<P>
   The worst of a massive solar storm that had been expected to
heat up late this year won't occur until long after Jan. 1,
scientists now believe. Scientists and Y2K watchers had been
concerned that the storm might be at its worst right around Jan. 1,
compounding any Y2K problems that occur.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not likely at this point,'' said Gary Heckman, senior
forecaster at the Space Environment Center in Boulder, Colo.
``They're more likely to appear later in the year.''
</P>
<P>
   The Space Environment Center, part of the National Oceanic and
Atmospheric Administration, tracks solar disturbances. Solar
radiation storms, commonly known as sunspots, occur in cycles 11
years apart.
</P>
<P>
   The last cycle, which peaked in March 1989, knocked out the
electrical grid that serves the Canadian province of Quebec for
nine hours and disrupted some radio and television broadcasts. In a
two-week period, NOAA received thousands of calls about problems,
Heckman said.
</P>
<P>
   The current solar storm cycle had been expected to be among the
two or three strongest on record.
</P>
<P>
   That hasn't happened.
</P>
<P>
   ``So far, there hasn't been as much activity as the last one,''
Heckman said. ``My opinion is that we're going to get hit with some
major storms, but not until later on.''
</P>
<P>
   The current storm cycle will continue until the Year 2002.
 &LR; brk:Mouths of babes
</P>
<P>
   Nearly three out of four school-age children say adults have
overreacted to Y2K and the potential for computer problems,
according to a recent poll by Junior Achievement.
</P>
<P>
   The poll found students are overwhelmingly upbeat about the
future.
</P>
<P>
   About 72 percent of the children polled say adults have gone off
the deep end about Y2K, according to the survey, which polled 1,449
children ages 8 to 18. It was conducted during the first week of
December.
</P>
<P>
   Older students, the survey showed, are more likely to think mom
and dad have been making too big a deal of Y2K.
</P>
<P>
   Two-thirds correctly identified the bug as a computer's
inability to recognize the year 2000, while 36 percent think it is
either a computer virus, the newest Pokemon character, a
genetically engineered insect or a seasonal flu.
</P>
<P>
   One in four think their Nintendo 64 or Playstation will be on
the fritz.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; brk:Clinton: Job done
</P>
<P>
   At the same time the White House has launched a campaign to
convince us technology fails all the time, even without Y2K,
President Clinton is boasting that the federal government's mission
critical systems are 99.9 percent Y2K compliant.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton said this week that only 16 of 6,159 mission critical
systems are not ready for the Year 2000, but would be by Jan. 1.
Six systems will be replaced and 10 will be repaired.
</P>
<P>
   Problems were found at the departments of defense and justice,
including glitches with M1A2 tanks and programs at the FBI's
foreign offices. The total federal pricetag for Y2K fixes: $8.38
billion, $37 million more than the estimate given in September.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton pushed small businesses and local governments to make
every effort to fix as many computer systems as possible before
Jan. 1.
</P>
<P>
   &LR; brk:Bank on it
</P>
<P>
   Every federally insured bank and savings and loan _ all 10,200
of them _ have now met stringent Y2K challenges set by federal
regulators, say both the Federal Reserve and the Federal Deposit
Insurance Corp.
</P>
<P>
   The last bank in the country to do so, a small unidentified
thrift in Jacksonville, Fla., met its Y2K requirements on Monday.
</P>
<P>
   That satisfies the feds. And to satisfy customers, yet another
Kansas City area bank is planning to open its doors Saturday, Jan.
1.
</P>
<P>
   The Bank of Blue Valley's main office will be open from 11 a.m.
to 3 p.m. to give customers an added measure of assurance that
their money is safe, said Bob Regnier, president of the bank.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many people have expressed a concern about what will happen to
their bank accounts as we enter Y2K,'' Regnier said. ``By staying
open, we will prove to our customers that their accounts are
safe.''
</P>
<P>
   Earlier, First National Bank of Olathe said it will be open from
9 a.m. to noon Jan. 1.  &LR; brk:Y2K blast
</P>
<P>
   Those who fear that panic could be the biggest danger poised by
the Y2K computer bug need look no further than Benton Township,
Mich.
</P>
<P>
   Resident Alonzo Anderson had a brush with death Dec. 10 when
leaking gas from one of several 120-pound propane tanks exploded,
pushing out sections of his cement-block structure and bowing his
walls. He had been stockpiling propane.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how he survived,'' said Lt. Ken Doroh of the
Benton Township Fire Department. Anderson's hair was singed and his
cheek was burned, but he had no other injuries.
</P>
<P>
   Afraid of what might happen Jan. 1, the homeowner told
firefighters he was storing large amounts of propane in case the
utilities failed.  &LR; brk:Hackers, have mercy
</P>
<P>
   In an unusual plea for mercy, government Y2K Czar John Koskinen
has asked computer hackers to give him a week to sort through
potential computer problems before launching any cyber strikes.
</P>
<P>
   Some hackers view piercing computer networks to be a great
public service because it exposes cracks in security, Koskinen
said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hopefully those people will recognize we're going to have
enough things going on that weekend that this will not be a
particularly good weekend to demonstrate the need for more
information security,'' Koskinen said. ``If you want to, in fact,
make those points, my hope is you'll make them the following
weekend.''
</P>
</TEXT>
