<SLUG> BC-BOMB-PLOT-SPI </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BORDER ARREST PROMPTS WIDER U.S. PROBE OF POSSIBLE BOMB PLOT 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients.)  
 By SCOTT SUNDE  
 and ELAINE PORTERFIELD  
 c.1999 Seattle Post-Intelligencer  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ Terrorism experts in the United States and Canada
scrambled Friday night to determine whether a cache of powerful
explosives and the Algerian who carried them to an isolated Olympic
Peninsula port are part of a larger plot to bomb American cities.
</P>
<P>
   Ahmed Ressam, 32, was in federal custody Friday, facing
explosives and immigration charges. Ressam was arrested in Port
Angeles, Wash., after he drove off a ferry from Victoria, B.C.
</P>
<P>
   He had reserved a room at a Seattle hotel near the landmark
Space Needle, but intended to stay in the United States only a day
before flying to London.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement sources could not identify possible bombing
targets Friday night.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities apparently are searching for a second man who was
with Ressam for several weeks in Vancouver, B.C.
</P>
<P>
   Agents, in a stroke of luck, arrested Ressam in Port Angeles on
Tuesday night and found in his rented car liquid nitroglycerin and
118 pounds of urea, a component of fertilizers and explosives that
was used in the February 1993 bombing of the World Trade Center.
</P>
<P>
   ``You're definitely going to take a building out with this
stuff,'' a military explosives expert told the Post-Intelligencer
on Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Urea produces a slow explosion said to be ideal for destroying
concrete structures, federal officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The diminutive Ressam made an appearance in federal court in
Seattle on Friday under high security. He was charged with bringing
nitroglycerine into the United States from Canada and with making
false statements to U.S. Customs Service inspectors.
</P>
<P>
   During proceedings that were translated into Arabic, Federal
Magistrate David Wilson ordered Ressam to appear Wednesday for a
detention and preliminary hearing. He will be in federal custody
until then.
</P>
<P>
   Security was so tight at the courthouse that anyone entering _
even employees _ had to produce photo identification. U.S. marshals
blocked the door to Wilson's courtroom and armed officers patrolled
the streets as Ressam was brought to the courthouse.
</P>
<P>
   The case began as a Customs investigation that ultimately
brought in the Border Patrol and the federal Bureau of Alcohol,
Tobacco and Firearms. By Friday, the FBI and CIA had taken over.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam first entered the United States on Feb. 7, when he flew
to Los Angeles from Seoul. He showed up again this fall on a flight
from Quebec to British Columbia, where he lived in a motel 15
minutes from downtown Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   He and a second man checked into the 65-unit 2400 Motel in East
Vancouver in late November, stayed about three weeks, and checked
out one day last week, said a desk clerk who identified herself
only as Joanne.
</P>
<P>
   The Royal Canadian Mounted Police questioned motel workers
Wednesday about Ressam and the man who checked in and out with him,
she said.
</P>
<P>
   Both were clean-shaven, slender and spoke English with what
seemed to be a French accent. ``There was just nothing about them,
no distinguishing marks or anything, that stands out,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam rented a car in Canada and crossed into the United States
on Tuesday aboard the Coho, a privately run ferry between Victoria
and Port Angeles. His rented Chrysler was the last auto on the
ferry.
</P>
<P>
   He became so nervous that his hands reportedly shook when
Customs inspectors questioned him upon arrival in Port Angeles.
Inspectors were curious because he was headed for Seattle and had
taken an out-of-the-way route to get there.
</P>
<P>
   He had a passport, Quebec driver's license and several credit
cards in the name of Benni Noris and a second Quebec driver's
license in the name of Mario Roig, according to court documents.
</P>
<P>
   Customs inspectors searched the trunk of his car and found in
the spare-tire well 10 plastic bags of a fine white powder, two
plastic bags of a crystalline powder and two 22-ounce jars that
were three-quarters full of a yellowish liquid, according to court
documents. A federal agent also said the liquid contained sawdust,
which is sometimes used to pack nitroglycerine.
</P>
<P>
   They also found four black boxes, each containing a circuit
board, digital watch and 9-volt battery connector.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam fled when the material was discovered. He ran up to the
door of a passing car but the woman driver sped off and Customs
inspectors tackled Ressam.
</P>
<P>
   A Washington State Patrol laboratory identified the fine white
powder as urea, the liquid as nitroglycerine and the crystalline
powder as a sulfate used to absorb water. The laboratory in Tacoma,
Wash., described the tested samples of nitroglycerine as extremely
volatile and explosive.
</P>
<P>
   Friday, Wilson ordered the remainder of the liquid to be
destroyed despite objections from Ressam's federal public defender
that the defense had not been able to test it.
</P>
<P>
   Law enforcement agencies throughout the nation have been warned
about possible terrorism attacks as 2000 approaches. The federal
government has included Algeria as a possible source of terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   However, law enforcement officials said the arrest in Port
Angeles was the result of good fortune.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was essentially a cold hit, so we're starting at ground
zero,'' said a federal law enforcement source. ``We're looking for
anything.''
</P>
<P>
   A local law enforcement source called it ``pretty scary'' that
the suspect and bomb materials surfaced by chance.
</P>
<P>
   Federal investigators are looking for links to any known
associates in Seattle or groups the suspect might be connected to,
the source said.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam had reservations at the Best Western Loyal Inn near
Seattle Center for Tuesday night. On New Year's Eve, thousands of
people are expected at a celebration at the nearby Space Needle.
</P>
<P>
   Local law enforcement sources said Friday that federal agents
have warned them that such large structures and public gathering
places could be targets for terrorism.
</P>
<P>
   After learning of Ressam's arrest, Seattle Center officials
stepped up security Friday, and announced they would put gated
fences around the campus for the millennium celebration.
</P>
<P>
   ``We want people to feel safe,'' Allen said.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam apparently had no plans to be in Seattle for the New
Year.
</P>
<P>
   He made the reservations Tuesday for only one night, the motel
manager said. He had plane tickets under another name to fly
Wednesday from Seattle to New York, then London, according to court
documents.
</P>
<P>
   Agents said Ressam also had maps and travel guides in his car
for Washington, Oregon and California.
</P>
<P>
   Vincent Cannistraro, former chief of counterterrorism at the
CIA, said the purpose of bringing the explosives into the United
State was clear.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was an operation to blow something up. It's hard to see
what else it could be,'' said Cannistraro, now a security
consultant in McLean, Va.
</P>
<P>
   Court documents said Ressam was wanted in Canada under an
immigration warrant and for theft under $5,000.
</P>
<P>
   CBS, NBC and CNN reported Friday night that Ressam may have ties
to Osama bin Laden, accused of heading and funding a terrorist
campaign against the United States.
</P>
<P>
   But no one could link Ressam directly to any terrorist
organization.
</P>
<P>
   Montreal, where an apartment was rented under one of the names
Ressam used, has a large Algerian population. Earlier this week,
Montreal police warned citizens that Algerians were extorting money
in that city and using the proceeds to fund the activities of
extremists. Eleven men accused of operating a theft ring to raise
money for Algerian extremists are awaiting trial in the Quebec
city.
</P>
<P>
   Friday night in Montreal, officers evacuated a downtown block
that included the apartment building that was given as the address
for Benni A. Noris, according to the Montreal Gazette. The bomb
squad from the Royal Canadian Mounted Police found no explosives.
</P>
<P>
   In the United States, agents described Ressam, who spoke
primarily in French, as uncooperative.
</P>
<P>
   Cannistraro, the former CIA official, suggested that Ressam may
have been a courier, rather than a ``professional.''
</P>
<P>
   The question authorities are now trying to answer is whether
``there is an infrastructure in place'' in the United States that
is behind this or ``is he the vanguard,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Cannistraro noted that bin Laden's training camps in Afghanistan
have included Algerians. Bin Laden, an exiled Saudi militant, has
been indicted for conspiracy and murder in U.S. embassy bombings in
1998 in Kenya and Tanzania.
</P>
<P>
   Friday in Jordan, police were questioning a man linked to bin
Laden and suspected of leading a group planning terror attacks on
tourist sites and U.S. targets in that country during millennium
celebrations.
</P>
<P>
   The man, identified by the Jordanians as Khalil Deek, was
extradited from Pakistan on Thursday, two days after he was
apprehended in his home in Peshawar on that country's border with
Afghanistan, a Jordanian official said.
</P>
<P>
   The extradition brings to 14 the number of people detained this
week in Jordan and said to be affiliated with bin Laden. Detained
are 12 Jordanians, one Iraqi and one Algerian.
</P>
<P>
   Two more suspects remain at large outside Jordan, said the
official, who spoke on condition of anonymity.
</P>
<P>
   P-I Reporters Mike Barber, Phuong Le and Ed Offley contributed
to this report. It also contains information from The Associated
Press and The New York Times.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
