<HEADER>
A2535 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-DEMS-DEBATE-1STLDE-WR     12-18 1567
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-DEBATE-1STLDE-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BRADLEY PRESSES GORE ON HEALTH CARE , AND GORE PUSHES BACK ON
EDUCATION 
</HEADLINE>
   (SUBS throughout to add details and analysis: lede and 2nd, 3rd
grafs to add details and analysis; adds new 8th graf (bgng `Every
single...')with Gore quote; adds new grafs 10 (bgng `At one...'),
11, 12, 1st sent. of 13th graf to add quotes; rewrites grafs 15-18
to add details; adds new grafs 28-31 (bgng `Strikingly, there...)
to add info on Clinton, Bush and questions of faith; rewrites 2nd
graf from end of 1st take to delete material now moved up.) 
 (DW/js) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ Displaying a calm persistence and aggressiveness,
former Sen. Bill Bradley tried to poke holes Friday night in Vice
President Al Gore's health care, education and gun control
proposals in their second televised encounter. Gore, in turn,
questioned his rival's own commitment to education, health care and
managing the economy.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly two months after their first debate, when he declined to
engage Gore, Bradley tried a strikingly different approach in their
90-minute encounter at Daniel Webster College here, which was
televised Friday on the ABC News program ``Nightline.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking in his usual low voice, Bradley again and again
badgered Gore with a refrain that his health care plan would extend
insurance to all Americans while Gore's would not: ``Who will you
leave out?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't leave out anyone,'' Gore replied at one point. But
Bradley would not stop asking the question.
</P>
<P>
   ``No one,'' the vice president said once again.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's not true,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   While Bradley homed in on health care, Gore scolded his opponent
as lacking a comprehensive education plan and for supporting a
school voucher program when he was in the Senate. This week, Gore
unveiled an education plan that would spend $115 billion over 10
years to increase teacher salaries and improve public education.
</P>
<P>
   ``Every single time vouchers came up in the Senate, Bill, for 18
years, you voted for them,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley defended his education proposals, saying: ``If your
staff had checked the proposals I've made, they would have found
that there's an education component of almost each one of the
proposals. The difference is, I view education as integrated into
the lives of people where they're living their lives, not as a
program that comes from Washington.''
</P>
<P>
   At one point, Ted Koppel, the moderator, cut in as both men
tried to talk over one another on health care. ``Hold it. Hold
it,'' he said. ``Hold it just one second gentlemen.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You made a mistake, Al,'' Bradley interjected. ``You asked
another question.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think it's a mistake at all,'' Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Despite such clashes, the rivals for the Democratic presidential
nomination agreed more than they disagreed. In fact, they agreed so
much _ on everything from maintaining an even-handed relationship
with China and Taiwan to calling on the entertainment industry to
better police itself to advocating gay rights _ that the moderator,
Ted Koppel, noted at the close that their differences did not seem
significant. He asked them to contrast their leadership styles.
</P>
<P>
   The political terrain has changed significantly since Gore and
Bradley's first debate. As Bradley moved up in the polls here in
the state that holds the first primary on Feb. 1, Gore has
repeatedly, and aggressively, attacked his programs. Bradley did
not begin fighting back until about two weeks ago. But his climb in
the polls has stopped and the two men are in a dead-heat in this
state, according to several surveys.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's assertiveness Friday night seemed intended to respond
to criticism that his campaign was too passive.
</P>
<P>
   While Gore was less combative than in the first debate, he was
still far more aggressive than Bradley. More than once, he cut off
Bradley in mid sentence.
</P>
<P>
   Strategists in both camps had predicted far more fireworks
Friday night because of an open format in which an audience of
local residents and Koppel could ask questions _ and the contenders
could quiz each other. The only requirement was that the candidates
had to sit on their stools and could not roam around the stage (as
Gore did last time.)
</P>
<P>
   There were barbed comments, however, such as when Bradley sought
to portray his agenda as more sweeping on gun control. ``I'm the
only candidate in this race who's called for mandatory licensing
and registration and of all handguns in this country,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The evening became particularly heated when the questions turned
to health care, the major point of contention between the two
candidates.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what he would do to get his proposal to expand health care
coverage to more Americans through a Republican-controlled
Congress, Gore instead talked about how his plan could be paid for
without raising taxes or jeopardizing other entitlement programs,
like Medicare, the government health care program for the elderly.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has frequently asserted that Bradley's more expensive
health care plan might require raising taxes and would leave none
of the federal surplus for other programs, including for Medicare.
The vice president then asked Bradley what he would do to bolster
Medicare as the number of senior citizens rises sharply over the
next two decades.
</P>
<P>
   But rather than answer Gore's question, Bradley threw a question
back. Bradley asserted that his health care plan would extend
health insurance to almost all Americans, while Gore's would not.
``Who will you leave out,'' Bradley said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I won't leave out anyone,'' Gore said as the two men proceeded
to talk over each other.
</P>
<P>
   Then Gore focused on another part of Bradley's health care plan
that he has frequently criticized in recent weeks: his proposal to
replace Medicaid, the government health care program for the poor,
with subsidized private insurance.
</P>
<P>
   Gore also used his remarks on health care to tout his role in
the Clinton administration's management of the strong economy,
saying that protecting Medicare and Social Security would keep the
nation strong.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of our achievements of the last six and a half years has
been to have a strong economy,'' the vice president said. ``And
that has been to get the big questions right,'' including
protecting Medicare. ``Bill does not set aside a penny'' for
bolstering Medicare, Gore said.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley responded by saying he considered Medicare ``the most
important government program on health care that we now have'' but
said that it was not yet essential to set aside to bolster the
program.
</P>
<P>
   Strikingly, there were no direct mentions of President Clinton
during the entire debate. And neither contender mentioned the
Republican front-runner, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But the candidates did respond to a question about how Bush and
two other candidates mentioned Christ when they were asked about
their favorite philosopher-thinkers in a Republican debate this
week.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley said he considered religion a personal subject that he
did not want to discuss. But Gore said, ``I affirm my faith when
I'm asked about it.'' He added that ``atheists have just as much of
a right to the public discourse as any _ as people of any religious
faith in this country.''
</P>
<P>
   Though he did not cite Clinton, Gore seized on a question on
terrorism to embrace a Republican presidential candidate, Sen. John
McCain of Arizona. On Thursday, Bradley made a joint appearance in
New Hampshire with McCain to call for overhauling the campaign
finance system. Polls show McCain is very popular among independent
voters in New Hampshire, a group that Bradley is also trying to
court.
</P>
<P>
   Asked what Gore would do to fight terrorism, he noted that he
had sponsored with McCain a bill to control nuclear weapons.
</P>
<P>
   The forum began with Koppel asking both about their wives and
what sort of first ladies they would be. Gore responded that his
wife, Tipper, would be active in the role and pointed out how she
had ``worked hard on the issue of health care'' and had a graduate
degree in psychology. He also said Mrs. Gore ``spends a lot of time
on the plight of the homeless.''
</P>
<P>
   Speaking about his wife, Ernestine, Bradley said, ``In this case
people will find Ernestine a unique human being; she would be the
first immigrant first lady, having been born in Germany.'' He
added: ``She's real; she's dynamic. She will chart her way.''
</P>
<P>
   One of the first questions from the audience involved the issue
of drug use and the questions about whether Bush had or had not
used cocaine. Bradley openly acknowledged that he has smoked
marijuana in the past, and pointed out that Gore had made a similar
acknowledgment, but said, ``I think people have an understanding of
the nuances of life.''
</P>
<P>
   Both candidates also spoke forcefully about the responsibility
of the news media and the entertainment industry in policing the
amount of violence and sex that young people can see. Bradley
recalled the high school seminars he gave in New Jersey and
mentioned how he once asked the students if they had seen someone
killed. Bradley said that two youths said that they had and then he
offered a graphic description of someone being shot in the head.
Speaking of one student, Bradley said, ``Then he said, `You know
senator, it was nothing like it was on TV.'''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 0037EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
