<HEADER>
A2536 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-DEMS-DEBATE-1STLDE-WR     12-18 0163
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DEMS-DEBATE-1STLDE-WRITETHRU-2NDTAKE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 NASHUA, N.H.: on TV.'''  
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gore called for ``self-restraint in the media'' and said, ``Some
kids are vulnerable to having seeds planted that bear bitter
fruit.''
</P>
<P>
   The two Democrats met for their first televised encounter in
Hanover, N.H., on Oct. 27. That event was notable more for what the
two agreed on than for their differences. Although Gore harshly
criticized the cost of the Bradley health care plan in the debate,
Bradley sought to stay above the fray.
</P>
<P>
   As the primary date nears, the pace of the debates will pick up
considerably. On Sunday, Gore and Bradley will appear on the NBC
News program ``Meet the Press.'' Both candidates have agreed to
five televised encounters in January.
</P>
<P>
   Despite Friday night's contentious tone, the Gore campaign
offered a nod to the holiday season. People driving on the road to
Daniel Webster College were greeted with Christmas lights that
blinked, ``Gore 2000.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
