u k BC-EDITORIAL-BANKS-BOS &LR;      12-18 0359
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-BANKS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A QUESTION OF BANKING FAIRNESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Banks and other lending institutions can be penalized heavily if
they deny credit to an individual on the basis of race. But in
dealing with broader patterns of discrimination, federal law makes
an irrational distinction between home mortgages and other loans.
</P>
<P>
   A helpful proposal from the Federal Reserve Board to lessen that
distinction deserves support in Congress but has run into equally
irrational opposition.
</P>
<P>
   Under federal law, lenders are required to collect data on the
race and gender of people applying for mortgages but are prohibited
from collecting similar data from people applying for
small-business loans, car loans, and other credit.
</P>
<P>
   The Fed proposal would allow collection of such data only on a
voluntary basis, but it is still opposed by lenders, ostensibly on
grounds that it would be costly and might become mandatory.
Republican Senator Phil Gramm of Texas and others in Congress are
supporting the industry. Representative Ron Paul, another Texas
Republican, gathered two-dozen signatures of congressmen on a
letter warning that collecting this information ``would very likely
result in a new scheme of government-mandated, race-based lending
quotas.''
</P>
<P>
   Here is the tip-off. The letter is inflamatory in that no one is
talking about quotas; even the Community Reinvestment Act regulates
mortgage lending without coming close to quotas. More to the point,
no ``scheme'' to alleviate racial or gender discrimination will be
proposed unless such bias is shown to exist.
</P>
<P>
   The only way to uncover patterns of bias is to collect the data.
The Community Reinvestment Act, passed in 1977, uprooted deep
traditions of race-based mortgage lending practices in many parts
of the country. More than rigid regulations, disclosure has led to
marked progress. The same might be true of other loans.
</P>
<P>
   America is not colorblind, not yet, not by a long shot. If
Congress continues to bar the collection of evidence that would
uncover discrimination, it is just plain blind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 0050EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0018 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 00:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2544 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-CUISINE-BOS     12-18 0375
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CUISINE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BITTER PILL FOR FRENCH CHEFS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Americans ought to be cautious about criticizing French ways.
Since New Worlders all too often find cause to complain about
French critiques of the American way of life, any carping from this
side of the pond about the Cartesian bizarreness of France might
seem a mimicry of Gallic kibitzing.
</P>
<P>
   Nevertheless, something has to be said about the treatment
accorded to French restaurants by the ``hauts fonctionaires'' who
run the government in Paris. Even the most unworldly hick from
these shores realizes that if there is one enduring glory of French
civilization, it is the traditional French restaurant.
</P>
<P>
   Something truly irreplaceable is preserved in those culinary
establishments. To savor the genius of French cooking one need not
visit some precious, pricey place that has received three stars
from the Michelin guide, the little red book that is still worth
reading. In any unstarred restaurant of ``la douce France,'' the
questing diner may find a gustatory epiphany.
</P>
<P>
   So how does the state treat this national treasure? Do the
rule-makers lavish incentives and protections on these monuments of
haute cuisine?
</P>
<P>
   On the contrary, the taxocrats of Paris burden the nation's
``chefs-proprietaires'' with a value-added tax of 20.6 percent on
every meal. This disincentive is added to the same high social
security charges that encourage unemployment in other businesses.
Most infuriating of all for the chefs who own their restaurants is
the injustice of paying a confiscatory 20.6 percent tax while
fast-food joints such as McDonald's pay a mere 5.5 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The 2,500 chefs and restaurant owners who took to the streets of
Paris last fall to protest their plight could be forgiven for
believing there was an Anglo-Saxon conspiracy to ruin France's
culinary heritage in favor of American fast food.
</P>
<P>
   Every year thousands of real French restaurants close their
doors and disappear, and the truth is that Paris bureaucrats are
killing the geese that produce the golden eggs. Pretty soon, nobody
will want to visit France. Why go there when you can eat fast food
here at the mall?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 0051EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
