u k BC-EDITORIAL-IMPEACH-BOS     12-18 0761
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-IMPEACH-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IMPEACHMENT A YEAR LATER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Sunday, December 19, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   One year later, the impeachment of President Clinton is receding
into memory like a high fever that racked the body politic for a
while and then passed, leaving the patient fatigued.
</P>
<P>
   On this first anniversary of the House votes to impeach the
president for perjury and obstruction of justice, it seems not so
hard to foresee how future generations will regard that
impassioning melodrama. As the emotions of the peculiar moment fade
away, the recklessness of the president stands forth clearer than
ever, as does his obtuse refusal to accept advice from those who
told him, publicly as well as privately, that honesty would be his
best policy.
</P>
<P>
   Whoever recollects in tranquillity the turmoil of that time may
also recognize the excessive zealotry of congressional Republicans
who were so avid to disable Clinton that they lowered the barrier
to impeachment so Clinton's tawdry lies in a civil suit would
qualify as an impeachable offense.
</P>
<P>
   The lessons learned from that time by the politicians aspiring
to succeed Clinton in the White House are hardly subtle. Vice
President Gore and his Democratic rival, Bill Bradley, have been
going out of their way to present themselves as candidates of sound
moral character, men who would never disgrace the office they seek
as Clinton had.
</P>
<P>
   With political symmetry, the main Republican contenders for the
presidency, Governor George W. Bush of Texas and Senator John
McCain of Arizona, have been campaigning for their party's
nomination by taking their distance from the party's congressional
leadership. The impeachment imbroglio is certainly not the only
reason for Bush and McCain to present themselves as conservatives
who are not to be confused with Richard Armey, Tom DeLay, or Trent
Lott. Nevertheless, the behavior of those legislative leaders
during the Punch and Judy show of impeachment left a legacy that
Bush and McCain wisely want to reject.
</P>
<P>
   Even after Clinton's congressional pursuers had published the
salacious narrative of independent counsel Kenneth Starr's report
and after the House had voted for two articles of impeachment, only
38 percent of Americans told pollsters they favored impeachment.
Those who opposed impeachment were not indulgent toward Clinton's
irresponsible and dishonest actions. What DeLay, Armey, and the
Republicans on the House Judiciary Committee refused to accept was
that most Americans did not regard Clinton's actions as a threat to
the nation's constitutional order.
</P>
<P>
   If America was able to recover swiftly from its impeachment
fever, it was because of the good sense of citizens. They concluded
that both parties to the spat had lost the ability to distinguish
what is important from what is not.
</P>
<P>
   Chastened lawmakers early this year let the independent counsel
statute lapse largely because the voters had seen Starr abuse the
extraconstitutional powers available to his office and wanted to
make sure such abuses would not be repeated. The legislators were
doing what the people wanted them to do. They were correcting an
error the way a system of accountable self-government is supposed
to correct errors.
</P>
<P>
   Because journalists tend to present even a constitutional crisis
as a personal conflict between politicians or a saga of one
politician's mythy trials, the impeachment story was too often told
as if it were Clinton's psychodrama. It was not. It was a test of
America's political system that Clinton and Congress should never
have imposed on the public.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever the psychological effect on Clinton, his brush with
impeachment had a lasting effect on his presidency. After a series
of blunders over Kosovo that he never should have made, he retained
enough power to bomb the roads, bridges, and factories of Serbia
but was never able to achieve the backing of Congress for any
further action if that had become necessary. Vestigial bitterness
over impeachment may have played a role in his bungled campaign to
get ratification of the Comprehensive Nuclear Test Ban Treaty. He
has become the mother of lame ducks.
</P>
<P>
   Long after impeachment passions have disappeared into the mists
of history, Clinton will be remembered for prodigious gifts that
were too often squandered but also for presiding over a golden age
of peace and prosperity. Until then, the public's fatigue both with
Clinton and the congressional zealots who pursued him lingers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 0055EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0020 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 00:57 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2546 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u k BC-EDITORIAL-CHAVEZ-BOS &LR;      12-18 0392
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDITORIAL-CHAVEZ-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STORMY WEATHER IN VENEZUELA 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (For release Monday, December 20, 1999)   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   The torrential floods and mudslides sweeping away shantytowns in
Caracas this week were inevitably compared to Wednesday's
overwhelming vote for a new constitution that President Hugo Chavez
sold to voters as a democratic tide to obliterate Venezuela's
corrupt political system.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez, with his mixture of democracy and demagoguery, raises
crucial questions not only about the future of oil-rich Venezuela
but about other corrupt and mismanaged countries in Latin America
and the rest of the world.
</P>
<P>
   Appealing to patriotism, religious symbols, and revolutionary
rhetoric, Chavez persuaded 72 percent of voters to approve his new
constitution. Venezuelans assented to the radical revision of
institutions Chavez calls a ``peaceful revolution'' because they
were disgusted with the old order.
</P>
<P>
   Despite their country's oil wealth, four-fifths of Venezuelans
are living in poverty. Their political parties and courts had
become notoriously corrupt. The combination of poverty, egregious
inequality, and a blatantly rigged system prepared the way for
Chavez and his promises to sweep away all the old rotten
structures.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with their new constitution, Venezuelans have voted for the
possibility of an elected dictatorship. Chavez himself will be able
to run for two six-year terms. The army will be released from
civilian control and will become a base of political power, the
equivalent of a ruling party. Hundreds of new judges and new court
officers will be appointed. The old Senate will be eliminated.
</P>
<P>
   The crucial test for this new order will not be political,
however, but economic. In the year since Chavez took office, there
has been a massive flight of capital from Venezuela _ nearly $4
billion. This represents a telling vote of no confidence in the
statist economic programs Chavez has tried to pursue with funds
from rising oil prices.
</P>
<P>
   Chavez may be able to charm voters with his invocations of Simon
Bolivar, but markets cannot be charmed by anything other than sound
fiscal and monetary policies. Sooner or later, Chavez will have to
do what it takes to reverse the flight of capital. In the meantime,
democracy is the loser.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 0057EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0021 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 00:59 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2548 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-NASCAR-ART-950(2TA     12-18 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NASCAR-ART-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK CAR RACING SETS ITS SIGHTS ON THE NEW YORK REGION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Pa.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT3 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By IVER PETERSON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASCAR has the answer, and it is that stock car racing is coming
to the New York region, and the closer to the Manhattan skyline,
the better.
</P>
<P>
   The 17 million people who live in New York's vast archipelago of
city and suburb may still be contemplating the question: Are people
this far north ready for the foot-stomping,
Confederate-flag-waving, rebel-yelling, hard-charging world of
stock car racing? Will Manhattan sophisticates, Greenwich
stockbrokers, Hoboken artists and the general run of suburban
homebodies really want to jam the front-row seats to exult at the
sting from bits of tar, tire tread and unburned hydrocarbons as the
big cars go shrieking down the straightaway?
</P>
<P>
   The country's two biggest promoters of National Association for
Stock Car Auto Racing events are certain that enough people in the
New York region want to do that to justify building a $200 million
speedway somewhere in the region, most likely in New Jersey. To
them, the New York market represents a $2 billion racing industry's
final step onto the national stage as oval-track racing grows up
and away from its Southern roots, where moonshiners first developed
a taste for cars that looked showroom-normal, or ``stock,'' but
that could be souped up to outrun the revenue agents.
</P>
<P>
   Speeding through the piney woods gave way to racing on the sands
of Daytona Beach, Fla., and from there racing moved onto dozens of
oval tracks, four fast left-turns to the lap, that spread
throughout the South.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the market saturated in NASCAR's Southern birthplace
and as auto racing proves its pull at the gate and among television
viewers nationally, the promoters are building 200,000-seat
superspeedways near Kansas City and Chicago and, soon, in Denver.
But New York, the promoters say, would be the crown.
</P>
<P>
   ``We'd love to build a track where we could see the New York
City skyline,'' said Jim Talley, a spokesman for the International
Speedway Corporation of Daytona, the country's biggest race
operator. ``That skyline. That would be the ultimate!''
</P>
<P>
   ISC, as it is known, last March signed no less than Donald
Trump, the real estate developer, as its partner in a search for a
New York regional site for a superspeedway, so called because it
would be able to handle the fastest cars.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Speedway Motor Sports of Charlotte, N.C., a pioneer
at packaging motor speedways with hotels, resorts and convention
centers, has been looking for a place to race around New York City
as well. ``We are committed to the region, and we've looked at
various sites in and around New York City,'' said Laurie Wilks,
Speedway Motor Sport's general counsel.
</P>
<P>
   In New York City?
</P>
<P>
   ``In, out and around New York City,'' Ms. Wilks said. ``I really
can't be more specific.''
</P>
<P>
   The very scent of high-octane gas and burning rubber in the
local air has inspired a group of South Jersey elected officials
and business people to lobby speedway promoters for a track near a
World War II airfield at Millville, in Cumberland County, below
Atlantic City. Donald DiFrancesco, president of the state Senate,
and Jack Collins, speaker of the Assembly, either one of whom could
be New Jersey's next governor when Gov. Christie Whitman's term
ends next year, have endorsed putting a track in the sandy soil of
the state's economically depressed southern reaches.
</P>
<P>
   O. Bruton Smith, chairman of Speedway Motor Sports, has visited
the state five times since 1992, officials associated with the
South Jersey effort said, and has met with Whitman and other state
officials, without reaching a deal.
</P>
<P>
   Trump, however, has already rejected the South Jersey site, as
well as a location in Suffolk County on Long Island, but local
promoters hope he will change his mind. Trump's group, ISC,
apparently favors a site closer to the New York skyline. The New
Jersey Meadowlands offers such a skyline view, and Whitman is said
to favor a site that would help the financially ailing Meadowlands
Authority, which now requires a huge annual state subsidy.
</P>
<P>
   But a modern superspeedway along with its attractions and
amenities takes about 1,000 acres of land, Talley said, and the
Meadowlands, with Giants Stadium, the Meadowlands Racetrack and
Continental Airlines Arena already on it, has only 759 acres.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's not an appropriate use of the Meadowlands,'' DiFrancesco
told the New Jersey Conference of Mayors in September. The
Meadowlands Authority, after confirming earlier in the week that it
had been in contact with race promoters, has since gone mum.
</P>
<P>
   ``We cannot comment on whether we had a meeting with NASCAR,''
said Dan Emmer, a spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   There may be other problems to overcome before people in the
region see their first checkered flag. Speedway developers are
accustomed to large public subsidies to help build their tracks _
taxpayers contributed $146 million of the $228 cost of ISC's new
track outside Kansas City. But that level of tax support for sports
promoters is a tougher sell in both New York and New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Speedway supporters like Donald Fauerbach, executive director of
the New Jersey Conference of Mayors and a NASCAR racing team owner
himself, say that the state that wins a speedway would have to put
in no more than the usual access roads and sewer lines, which New
Jersey has done for Atlantic City casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, plenty of people could not care less whether NASCAR
moves north. ``I don't understand the mentality of people who pay
good money to watch those cars go around and around,'' said Eric
Mihan, a retired Princeton haberdasher. ``But then those people
will probably say they don't understand the mentality of people who
go and watch someone hit a tennis ball back and forth.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But Fauerbach said people here would pay $50 to $90 for three
hours of racing because NASCAR racing had grown up. ``NASCAR racing
is not just a bunch of rednecks anymore,'' Fauerbach said. ``It's
champagne helicopter executives who come in and follow this sport.
It's Fortune 500 captains of American industry wining and dining
themselves and their employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly NASCAR racing has changed with the boom in television
coverage. The sport known for custom-made muscle cars that are
festooned with advertising logos used to be nearly entirely
dependent on products you had to be 18 or 21 to buy: snuff,
cigarettes and beer.
</P>
<P>
   Now, although the Winston Cup series and the Busch (beer) series
are still the premier events in NASCAR racing, federal and state
tobacco suit settlements have reduced tobacco's role in NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco settlement has sharply curtailed the kinds of
advertising tobacco companies may do at NASCAR events, forbidding,
for example, a display of tobacco logos on the race cars
themselves. Just as the restrictions on tobacco companies
increased, however, NASCAR promoters started looking beyond the
Southern males who were the sport's first and most devoted fans.
</P>
<P>
   According to NASCAR, 39 percent of the most dedicated fans are
women, and more than a third report incomes of more than $50,000.
Advertisers now include the likes of Proctor &AMP; Gamble's Tide, Home
Depot, Visa and Perdue chickens.
</P>
<P>
   Now only National Football League games earn a higher television
rating than NASCAR's premier races, and race attendance has grown
65 percent since 1990, to 6.3 million people last year. Last month,
NASCAR signed a six-year, $400 million television package with Fox,
NBC and Turner Sports.
</P>
<P>
   But will they come? There are NASCAR-sanctioned tracks in
Flemington, N.J.; Pocono, Pa., and at Watkins Glen, in upstate New
York. None are the 1.5-mile, steeply banked ovals that are used for
top events like the Winston Cup, however.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Kuhl is the co-promoter, with his father Paul, at
Flemington Speedway, in central New Jersey. It is a short-track
course, where racing speeds stay below about 85 mph, compared with
speeds approaching 200 miles at superspeedways, and Kuhl has seen
his business fall off as NASCAR developed its new generation of
supertracks.
</P>
<P>
   Kuhl charges $14 admission, compared with an average price of
$90 per admission to a Winston Cup series race. But he thinks the
national promoters have little to worry about in trying to break
into the New York market. ``You're talking millions and millions of
people in the New York area, and all they need is 150,000 people to
be interested,'' Kuhl said. ``They'll find them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 0059EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0023 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 01:00 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2554 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-NY-NASCAR-ART-950(2TA     12-18 1022
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-NASCAR-ART-950(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STOCK CAR RACING SETS ITS SIGHTS ON THE NEW YORK REGION 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Pa.)  (ART ADV: Photo NYT3 has been sent to NYT photo clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
