the New Jersey Conference of Mayors and a NASCAR racing team owner
himself, say that the state that wins a speedway would have to put
in no more than the usual access roads and sewer lines, which New
Jersey has done for Atlantic City casinos.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, plenty of people could not care less whether NASCAR
moves north. ``I don't understand the mentality of people who pay
good money to watch those cars go around and around,'' said Eric
Mihan, a retired Princeton haberdasher. ``But then those people
will probably say they don't understand the mentality of people who
go and watch someone hit a tennis ball back and forth.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   But Fauerbach said people here would pay $50 to $90 for three
hours of racing because NASCAR racing had grown up. ``NASCAR racing
is not just a bunch of rednecks anymore,'' Fauerbach said. ``It's
champagne helicopter executives who come in and follow this sport.
It's Fortune 500 captains of American industry wining and dining
themselves and their employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly NASCAR racing has changed with the boom in television
coverage. The sport known for custom-made muscle cars that are
festooned with advertising logos used to be nearly entirely
dependent on products you had to be 18 or 21 to buy: snuff,
cigarettes and beer.
</P>
<P>
   Now, although the Winston Cup series and the Busch (beer) series
are still the premier events in NASCAR racing, federal and state
tobacco suit settlements have reduced tobacco's role in NASCAR.
</P>
<P>
   The tobacco settlement has sharply curtailed the kinds of
advertising tobacco companies may do at NASCAR events, forbidding,
for example, a display of tobacco logos on the race cars
themselves. Just as the restrictions on tobacco companies
increased, however, NASCAR promoters started looking beyond the
Southern males who were the sport's first and most devoted fans.
</P>
<P>
   According to NASCAR, 39 percent of the most dedicated fans are
women, and more than a third report incomes of more than $50,000.
Advertisers now include the likes of Proctor &AMP; Gamble's Tide, Home
Depot, Visa and Perdue chickens.
</P>
<P>
   Now only National Football League games earn a higher television
rating than NASCAR's premier races, and race attendance has grown
65 percent since 1990, to 6.3 million people last year. Last month,
NASCAR signed a six-year, $400 million television package with Fox,
NBC and Turner Sports.
</P>
<P>
   But will they come? There are NASCAR-sanctioned tracks in
Flemington, N.J.; Pocono, Pa., and at Watkins Glen, in upstate New
York. None are the 1.5-mile, steeply banked ovals that are used for
top events like the Winston Cup, however.
</P>
<P>
   Rick Kuhl is the co-promoter, with his father Paul, at
Flemington Speedway, in central New Jersey. It is a short-track
course, where racing speeds stay below about 85 mph, compared with
speeds approaching 200 miles at superspeedways, and Kuhl has seen
his business fall off as NASCAR developed its new generation of
supertracks.
</P>
<P>
   Kuhl charges $14 admission, compared with an average price of
$90 per admission to a Winston Cup series race. But he thinks the
national promoters have little to worry about in trying to break
into the New York market. ``You're talking millions and millions of
people in the New York area, and all they need is 150,000 people to
be interested,'' Kuhl said. ``They'll find them.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
