<SLUG> BC-NY-REPUBLICAN-FUNDRAISER-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FUND-RAISER DENIES WRONGDOING 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By WILLIAM K. RASHBAUM   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ A businessman who has raised tens of thousands of
dollars for the campaigns of Gov. George Pataki and other
Republicans pleaded not guilty Friday to federal charges that he
promised favorable state parole rulings to the families of three
convicted violent felons in exchange for $36,000 in campaign
donations.
</P>
<P>
   The businessman, Yung Soo Yoo, 63, was released on $100,000 bond
after his arraignment in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn before
Magistrate Judge Robert M. Levy. A nine-count indictment unsealed
on Wednesday charged Yoo with conspiracy, obstruction of justice,
violating campaign finance laws and making false statements.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to asserting that he promised favorable parole
decisions for campaign contributions, the indictment accuses him of
soliciting $40,000 from a South Korean yogurt maker and illegally
funneling about $15,000 to Alfonse D'Amato's unsuccessful 1998
Senate re-election campaign. The indictment also alleges he
collected $20,000 for the 1996 GOP presidential campaign of Bob
Dole. But the indictment says Dole never received the money because
a fund-raising dinner was canceled.
</P>
<P>
   The U.S. attorney in Brooklyn, Loretta E. Lynch, said in a
statement on Wednesday that there was no evidence that the
governor, D'Amato or Dole took part in, or had knowledge of, any of
the crimes charged in the case. The Pataki administration has
denied wrongdoing by its officials, and after the indictment it
cited Ms. Lynch's statement as support of its position.
</P>
<P>
   Yoo's lawyer, Nicholas M. De Feis, said that his client
``promised nothing to these people and he received nothing
personally.'' And he dismissed suggestions that the Pataki
administration would trade a felon's freedom for money.
</P>
</TEXT>
