<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 01:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2565 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-FBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN     12-18 0798
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-HERSKOWITZ-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Bowden a natural as Bryant candidate
<TEXT>
<P>
   By MICKEY HERSKOWITZ
</P>
<P>
   Houston Chronicle
</P>
<P>
   Bobby Bowden will never have to say, ``I coulda been a
contender,'' as Marlon Brando's character grumbled in the movie
classic On the Waterfront.
</P>
<P>
   Bobby is the only coach in history whose team finished among the
top four in the wire service polls for 12 straight years. This
means he has been a contender for half of his 24 seasons at Florida
State, and now for the second time since 1993 his Seminoles are
undefeated with a chance to win the national title.
</P>
<P>
   They did just that on the New Year's night of '94, with a
tumultuous 18-16 victory over mighty Nebraska in the Orange Bowl.
Now the scene shifts to the Sugar Bowl, and a date with a
Cinderella team, Virginia Tech, on Jan. 4. The timing seems a bit
odd, except for those who enjoy the tradition of Tuesday Night
Football. Perhaps they are trying to avoid the Y2K bug, whatever
that is.
</P>
<P>
   But where and when become minor details when teams are playing
for the national championship. It is simply about ringing out the
old, ringing in the new.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, the Bear Bryant Coach of the Year Award is up for
grabs and Bobby Bowden is baaaack.
</P>
<P>
   When Bobby appeared in Houston at the end of 1993 as one of the
four finalists, the evening had a special twist. He brought his kid
with him. Terry Bowden had coached Auburn to a perfect record in
his rookie year, 11-0, which is just about as good as coaching
gets. And wouldn't you know it, Terry upstaged his old man and
walked off with the Bryant trophy.
</P>
<P>
   Against this background, the Bryant dinner, kicking off the year
2000, is shaping up as the most compelling of them all. It takes
place in Houston, for the benefit of the American Heart
Association, two nights after the Nos. 1 and 2 teams face off for
the title in New Orleans.
</P>
<P>
   The National Sportscasters and Sportswriters Association
announced the seven semifinalists this week and, besides the elder
Bowden, the list includes five newcomers. One of them is Mike
DuBose, of Alabama, who played and coached under Bryant Himself,
and who made _ along with his team _ one of the season's most
notable comebacks. He went from the brink of being fired to 10 wins
and a conference title.
</P>
<P>
   The other first-timers are Wisconsin's Barry Alvarez, who did
most of his coaching on crutches after knee replacement surgery;
Frank Beamer of Virginia Tech; June Jones, who did a total
renovation at Hawaii, not previously known as a football factory;
and Bob Pruett, who guided Marshall to a 12-0 record and then held
the University of Houston job for nearly 24 hours.
</P>
<P>
   It might not qualify as a homecoming for Pruett, who is prepared
for some good-natured kidding over his flip-flop. Pruett wasn't
taking any calls from Houston until he learned it had to do with
the Bryant Award. He answered the phone with a sheepish laugh.
</P>
<P>
   The other repeater is Glen Mason, nominated once before at
Kansas and returning this time as the salvage master at Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm going to keep coming,'' Mason said, ``until I win the
thing.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones is no stranger to the city, having coached for the Oilers
under Jerry Glanville and Jack Pardee, when the run-and-shoot was
as popular as Christmas lights.
</P>
<P>
   For the first time in memory, there are three undefeated
finalists _ Bowden, Beamer and Pruett.
</P>
<P>
   Former President George Bush, who once played first base for
Yale and in sports and politics has set a standard for
sportsmanship, will be the keynote speaker. A lifetime achievement
award will be presented to Darrell Royal, who becomes more of a
legend the longer he stays out of coaching.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to Bobby Bowden, the game's current
patriarch. There is no intention here to lobby for any candidate,
but the Florida State coach has an advantage. A country boy from
Alabama, he knew Bryant and had a long and enduring friendship with
him.
</P>
<P>
   ``When I was coming up,'' Bowden says, ``he was the guy. Bear
came to Alabama in 1958. In '59, I got the job at Howard College, a
little Baptist school 50 miles from Tuscaloosa. So I'd drive down
there and watch and learn. Gene Stallings was a graduate assistant
then.
</P>
<P>
   ``My first year at Howard we went 9-1. I was getting my name in
the Birmingham papers. So I wrote Bear a letter, said I wish I
could work for him. He wrote me back, `I appreciate that, but if I
hired you I'd have every Baptist in the state mad at me.' A nice
way of saying no.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was always good to me. Bear would give me a list of kids he
didn't want; he already had all he needed. He'd say, `Pick out the
ones you want and I'll call 'em.' I used to get a lot of my players
from him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
