<SLUG> BC-HKN-STARS-OILERS-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
STARS LOSE HATCHER FOR 6-8 WEEKS IN TIE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By JENNIFER FLOYD 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   EDMONTON, Alberta _ The Stars salvaged a 2-2 tie with the
Edmonton Oilers last night at the SkyReach Centre but lost captain
Derian Hatcher for at least six to eight weeks and center Joe
Nieuwendyk indefinitely. Hatcher left the game midway through the
second period after suffering a calf laceration that cut through
the muscle. He'll be on crutches for at least four weeks. Hatcher
was on crutches and heavily iced and taped after the game.
Nieuwendyk left not long after Hatcher with cartilage damage in his
chest. The game, the Stars could afford to lose. It's one of 82 in
the course of the season. The players they could not. ``That'a a
big blow for us; they had been our two best players,'' Stars coach
Ken Hitchcock said. Hatcher has been the Stars' best player for
most of this season, mounting a Norris Trophy-like season. He has a
pair of goals and 14 assists while ranking among the NHL leaders in
ice time at almost 30 minutes per game. Nieuwendyk, meanwhile, was
centering what had been the Stars' most productive line recently.
He has 10 goals and 12 assists this season. Hatcher had to be
helped off ice with 9:56 remaining in the second period. He had
been skating behind the Stars' net when Edmonton winger Todd
Marchant tried to check him into the boards. Marchant missed, but
Marchant's skate clipped Hatcher in the back of his right calf.
</P>
<P>
   Hatcher immediately dropped to all fours. He was taken directly
to the locker room and wasn't able to put any weight on his right
leg. He didn't return. ``You could see the blood coming out of
Hatch's sock as he was coming off the ice so you knew it was bad,''
Mike Modano said. Trainer Dave Surprenant had been attending to
Nieuwendyk on the bench when Hatcher went down. Nieuwendyk
attempted to come out for another shift but quickly followed
Hatcher into the locker room. The loss of their best defenseman and
one of their leading scorers further handicapped a Stars team that
had been struggling offensively all night. Their loss was felt
almost immediately. The rest of the second period was spent just
trying to escape with a 1-all tie still intact. The score didn't
last long into the third period, though. Stars winger Jamie
Langenbrunner and Oilers defenseman Tom Poti opened the third
period with a fight. Langenbrunner, however, had a two-minute minor
for roughing added to his five minutes for fighting, and the Oilers
went on the power play. With 19 seconds remaining with a man
advantage, the Oilers scored. Edmonton winger Ryan Smyth tried to
center a pass from behind the Stars goal. The puck went off Stars
goalie Ed Belfour's stick and into the net 128 seconds into the
third period. Whatever momentum the Stars had begun with was
officially gone, lost until 15:33 of the third period when Stars
winger Chris Murray grabbed it back with his second goal of the
season. He poked the game-tying goal past Oilers goalie Tommy Salo
after a wild scramble in front. The Stars opened the first period
with all of the good chances and the only goal. Defenseman Brad
Lukowich scored on a wraparound at 17:59 of the first period. He
beat Salo, who was slow to close off the post. The Stars outshot
the Oilers, 13-8. If their power play had been working, the Stars
could have put the game out of reach in the first period. They had
four power plays, failing to score on any of them and failing to
record a shot on three of them. But while the first period belonged
to the Stars, the second was all Oilers. They outshot the Stars,
17-3, including the game-tying goal by Poti at 6:41. The 17 shots
in a period tied the Oilers previous high this season. The period
could've been a lot worse for the Stars if not for Belfour and an
ineffective Edmonton power play. The Oilers failed to capitalize on
three power plays, including two that were back-to-back and 14
seconds with a two-man advantage.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
