</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS ARE PASS PERFECT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   MINNEAPOLIS _ That steadily rising mountain of wins is testament
enough to the Lakers' strength this season, but a closer inspection
of the terrain reveals a team that is, dare we say, bordering on
the unstoppable.
</P>
<P>
   There's proof enough in the scoring averages of Shaquille
O'Neal, Kobe Bryant and Glen Rice. But anyone with a passing
interest can see the more deadly underside of that threesome.
</P>
<P>
   Or, more to the point, their interest in passing.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers' triumvirate accounted for 75 points in a 97-88
victory over the Minnesota Timberwolves at Target Center on Friday.
Bryant led the way with 28, followed by O'Neal's 24 and Rice's 23.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the figures that leapt off the page were the career-high 12
assists by Bryant and the season-high-tying seven by O'Neal as the
team combined for 28.
</P>
<P>
   So much for that ``selfish'' label tacked to the Lakers' stars.
</P>
<P>
   And so much for double-teaming them into turnovers and miscues.
The Lakers' new weapon is definitely the pass. It was the key to
winning their fifth straight game (12th of their last 13) while
sending the slumping Timberwolves to their eighth straight defeat.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were just trying to dissect them,'' said Bryant, whose
assist total was also the highest for any Laker in the last two
seasons. ``We just wanted to take our time and really pick them
apart. We were able to do that. We were able to cut them up in
certain parts of the game.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal distributed the ball nicely out of the low post. Bryant
penetrated and kicked, often feeding O'Neal for the easy score.
Even as the Lakers flogged themselves for letting a 20-point lead
dwindle to single digits by late in the fourth, they took pride in
the way they earned the cushion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Three amigos do it again,'' O'Neal said. ``We got three
weapons on this team. Nice to have.''
</P>
<P>
   For Bryant, who missed seven weeks with a broken hand, the
passing performance was a sign that he's getting comfortable again
with his teammates and a new offense.
</P>
<P>
   ``My (court) vision is coming back,'' he said, and the result
has been some nifty passing to O'Neal. ``That kind of comes from
playing with each other. . . . We're still getting to learn one
another, but we're getting better at it. Like I knew he was going
to be there before I made the move to the baseline (in the fourth
quarter).''
</P>
<P>
   That play, an O'Neal hook shot, netted Bryant his 11th assist
and helped the Lakers push the lead back to 12 with 4:35 to go.
Bryant also scored seven points in the last 5:18 of the game as the
Lakers held off the Timberwolves' charge.
</P>
<P>
   Minnesota had pulled within six points by the 2:07 mark, but a
Bryant 6-foot jumper (assist, Rice) and a pair of O'Neal free
throws followed, sealing the win. Bryant then capped the night with
his 12th assist on a Rice 15-foot jumper that made it a 10-point
game with a minute to go.
</P>
<P>
   Of course, it shouldn't have come down to such a dramatic
finish.
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers worked their offense to precision and dominated the
rebounding game 31-12 as they took a 56-38 lead by halftime. But
then Kevin Garnett, Terrell Brandon and Rasho Nesterovic got loose.
Garnett got eight of his team-record 21 rebounds in the third
quarter, Nesterovic zipped past O'Neal for eight quick points in
the period, and Brandon added eight of his own on the way to a
22-point night.
</P>
<P>
   The lead was reduced to seven by the time the fourth quarter
arrived.
</P>
<P>
   ``I thought the game was played sporadically, if anything,''
Lakers coach Phil Jackson said. ``It was a poorly focused effort by
the Lakers in the second half, although you have to give the
Timberwolves some credit for scrapping. . . . They got back in the
ballgame just purely on hustle.''
</P>
<P>
   Jackson is pleased enough that his team has won the first two
games of the four-game road trip, but he's still looking for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very unusual, strange game. We just blew it open in
the second quarter and then sat on a lead in the third quarter and
were willing to play when we had to play. That's not the way I like
a team to play basketball, so we had a discussion after the game
about that.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
