<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 01:11 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2568 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HOMELESS-CITY-COLUMN-     12-18 0780
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMELESS-CITY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BIG CITY COLUMN: ALLOWING SOME LEEWAY OUT IN PUBLIC 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By JOHN TIERNEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Down and Out in Nyack and Chappaqua, Chapter II.
</P>
<P>
   At last someone has taken pity on me. In my recent foray posing
as a bum in suburbia, recounted in Wednesday's column, I was
prevented from lounging on the pavement outside the houses of Rosie
O'Donnell and Hillary Rodham Clinton. But now Norman Siegel has
come to the rescue.
</P>
<P>
   ``You should have called me from Nyack,'' said Siegel, executive
director of the New York Civil Liberties Union, after reading about
my ejection from the sidewalk in front of Ms. O'Donnell's house.
Unshaven and unkempt, I'd spent a frigid hour huddled next to Ms.
O'Donnell's wall until Officer J.M. Coyle ordered me to move on or
face arrest.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have gotten in the car,'' Siegel said, ``and gone up
immediately to defend you. As long as you weren't obstructing the
sidewalk, they had no authority to make you leave.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe I was on solid legal ground, but I wasn't sure I wanted to
win this case. Never mind the law. Should anyone be allowed to lie
down on the sidewalk in front of someone else's home?
</P>
<P>
   I tried putting the question to Ms. O'Donnell and Mrs. Clinton,
with no luck. ``That's a hard question,'' was the best I could
extract from Ms. O'Donnell's spokeswoman, Lois Smith.
</P>
<P>
   Howard Wolfson, Mrs. Clinton's spokesman, dodged the question by
reiterating her desire not to arrest people ``whose only offense is
that they have no home.'' Her sentiments were echoed this week by
Andrew M. Cuomo, the secretary of Housing and Urban Development,
who accused Giuliani of ``criminalizing'' the homeless.
</P>
<P>
   But no one wants to arrest anyone for being homeless. No one
denies the right of homeless people to be in public spaces. The
question is what they or any other New Yorkers can do there.
</P>
<P>
   ``We faced these same accusations of criminalizing homelessness
when we started the quality-of-life campaign in the subways,'' said
George L. Kelling, a professor of criminal justice at Rutgers
University and co-author of the famous ``broken-windows'' theory of
preserving social order. He trained the police in the subway to
enforce bans on panhandling and to prevent passengers from lying
down.
</P>
<P>
   ``They said we were taking the subways away from the poor and
giving them to the rich,'' he said, ``which was a cruel joke on the
poor and the working class people who had to use the subway. They
deserve hassle-free public spaces just as much as the suburbanites
in Nyack and Chappaqua.''
</P>
<P>
   But how do you legally distinguish ``disorderly'' behavior? A
lemonade stand would probably take up more of the sidewalk than my
sprawled body did. But the neighborhood would gladly tolerate the
children's obstruction.
</P>
<P>
   The simple libertarian solution would be to privatize sidewalks,
as in gated communities. If Rosie O'Donnell and her neighbors owned
the sidewalks, they could kick me off and allow the lemonade stand
without being taken to court. The libertarian approach is
essentially what Mrs. Clinton followed in moving to a cul-de-sac in
Chappaqua with no sidewalks or other public spaces for a bum like
me to rest.
</P>
<P>
   But private sidewalks don't seem terribly realistic for today's
New York City. A more practical approach would be a law like the
one in Seattle, which bans people from sitting or lying on
sidewalks in commercial districts during business hours. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``A law much broader than Seattle's could be passed here and
probably be upheld in court,'' said Dennis Saffran, executive
director of the Center for the Community Interest, a group based in
New York that helps municipalities draft and defend quality-of-life
laws. ``What you would want to do is give police authority, but
also encourage them to be flexible on a case by case basis.''
</P>
<P>
   Kelling also stressed flexibility. ``You can't nail everything
down in a law,'' he said. ``It all depends on the time and place.
One person sleeping in a park at night is no big deal; with 10, you
have problems. Two people begging outside a busy subway station at
8 a.m. is no problem. If they're accosting an elderly woman by
herself at 10 p.m., it can be extortion. The police need to
exercise discretion.''
</P>
<P>
   That philosophy seemed to be guiding Coyle when he ordered me
off Ms. O'Donnell's sidewalk. ``If you need to sleep, go to a
park,'' he said. ``You won't bother anyone, and we won't bother
you.''
</P>
<P>
   Maybe, according to a strict interpretation of the law, I had
just as much right to sleep on the sidewalk as in the park. But at
the moment Coyle's interpretation seemed a lot more sensible.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
