<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 WINNIE MANDELA DELAYED AT AIRPORT OVER VISA 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Winnie Madikizela-Mandela arrived for a visit in the
United States Friday with two bodyguards but no visa, setting off
an early morning boomlet of excitement that entangled federal
agencies, congressional offices and her New Jersey hosts in an
effort to liberate her from Kennedy International Airport.
</P>
<P>
   The intervention worked.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Mandela, politically prominent as a longtime anti-apartheid
leader and the former wife of Nelson Mandela but ineligible for a
visa because of a criminal conviction in South Africa, received
State Department permission to enter the country after a three-hour
enforced wait in an airport office.
</P>
<P>
   She is scheduled to speak at a dinner Saturday in Newark that
has been organized by a group called Black Cops Against Police
Brutality.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. DeLacy Davis, an East Orange, N.J., police officer who is
president of the group, said he learned of Mrs. Mandela's detention
when he arrived at the airport with a welcoming committee and a
women's choir that was set to regale her with the South African
national anthem.
</P>
<P>
   Instead, armed with cell phones, he and his committee mobilized
black police officers all over the Northeast to call and complain
to every elected official they could reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were on the telephone and moving in eight states,'' said
Davis, who turned up the heat by alerting newspapers and television
stations to Mrs. Mandela's situation. ``We called every black
official.''
</P>
<P>
   When she was released, he put her in a limousine and headed for
Newark immediately. ``I just want to get her onto New Jersey
soil,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Mandela, who was in the limousine, declined to comment.
</P>
<P>
   In 1991, Mrs. Mandela was convicted of the assault and
kidnapping of a 14-year-old boy who was later murdered in Soweto.
Because of the conviction, she is not eligible for a visa unless
she requests and receives a specific waiver.
</P>
<P>
   A State Department spokesman said that Mrs. Mandela had received
waivers from the U.S. Embassy in South Africa in the past. ``She
did not do so this time,'' the spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   He would not say who at the State Department granted the waiver
for Mrs. Mandela after she arrived at the airport.
</P>
<P>
   One of the two guards traveling with Mrs. Mandela also arrived
without a valid visa. He also received permission to enter the
country.
</P>
<P>
   Mrs. Mandela's traveling arrangements have caused a fuss before.
She was criticized in South Africa earlier this year when it was
learned that she was traveling on a diplomatic passport, although
she may not have been entitled to one.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
