r s BC-BBN-BELTRE-LADN     12-18 0605
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BBN-BELTRE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PENDING DECISION NOT END OF BELTRE STORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By BRIAN DOHN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Even though the decision from the commissioner's
office is slated for early next week, the saga regarding the
Dodgers and third baseman Adrian Beltre may be months from being
settled.
</P>
<P>
   It was reported Thursday night that baseball would fine the
Dodgers but not grant Beltre free agency, which is what he and his
attorney, Scott Boras, are seeking. Officials from the Dodgers and
Major League Baseball said they heard that decision discussed, but
the Dodgers haven't heard from the commissioner's office.
</P>
<P>
   Two sources said the fine for illegally signing Beltre as a 15
year old would be as much as $500,000. It's also expected the
Dodgers will be banned from signing foreign-born players for a
specified time.
</P>
<P>
   An official from Major League Baseball said the announcement
would come Monday or Tuesday. Sandy Alderson, executive vice
president of baseball operations for the commissioner's office, met
with commissioner Bud Selig on the matter Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Alderson didn't return phone calls Friday, and baseball
officials said no decision has been made.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, the story isn't over.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not a hearing, this is a procedure,'' Boras said.
``This a procedure conducted by baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Gene Orza, associate general counsel of the players union, said
during the recently completely winter meetings that a grievance
would be filed if Beltre's request to be a free agent was denied.
Once a grievance is filed, there will be a hearing and an
independent arbitrator will make a binding decision after hearing
testimony from both sides.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, it takes a month before a grievance goes to the
arbitrator; from there a decision could take weeks.
</P>
<P>
   While the Dodgers refused comment on the Beltre issue Friday,
general manager Kevin Malone said earlier in the week that the club
would move forward on the free-agent market based on baseball's
decision.
</P>
<P>
   Boras already sent documents to New York to begin the grievance
process. A source said Boras will be in New York on Monday when
baseball makes the expected decision.
</P>
<P>
   According to reports, baseball will rule that the statute of
limitations expired because Beltre signed more than five years ago.
The rule states a player has a year from the claim date to file a
complaint. While Beltre signed with the Dodgers in 1994, Boras said
Beltre didn't know about the rule and didn't learn of it until last
March.
</P>
<P>
   The grievance procedure could buy the Dodgers more time to
ultimately keep Beltre because it would allow them to renegotiate a
contract. If an agreement is reached, Beltre could then drop his
grievance and remain with the Dodgers, sources said.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers were fined $200,000 during the season as punishment
for illegally scouting and signing minor leaguers Juan Carlos Diaz
and Josue Perez out of Cuba. The Dodgers were also banned from
signing foreign-born players until Dec. 26.
</P>
<P>
   Beltre, through Boras, asked to be declared a free agent after
it was learned the Dodgers signed him at the age of 15. The Dodgers
listed Beltre as being born in 1978, while Beltre said he was born
in 1979.
</P>
<P>
   Boras obtained Beltre's personnel files from the Dodgers last
month and said it contained two birth certificates _ one with the
year 1979 whited-out and 1978 typed over it _ and several work
visas confirming Beltre was born in 1978.
</P>
<P>
   Boras also claims that Beltre was signed in April. Clubs aren't
allowed to sign players before July 1.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 0113EST &QL; 
