A2577 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-MERCY-PLEA-LADN     12-18 0806
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MERCY-PLEA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
VICTIM'S MOM WANTS MERCY FOR SON'S KILLER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Donna Huffaker  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- Sona Demirchyan knelt Friday over the flowers,
candles and Christmas teddy bear on her 15-year-old son Avo's grave
at Forest Lawn Memorial-Park near downtown Los Angeles and read the
poems she has written in her grief.
</P>
<P>
   It has been her daily ritual for the 15 months since a bullet
allegedly fired by a close friend during a student melee near
Hoover High School in the Los Angeles-area city of Glendale claimed
Avo's life.
</P>
<P>
   With his friend, Artiom Badalyan, facing sentencing next month,
Demirchyan has joined 15 other people who wrote letters to Pasadena
Superior Court Judge Victor Person asking that the 19-year-old be
spared jail.
</P>
<P>
   ``For Artiom to be in jail would not ease my sadness at all,''
Demirchyan says in the letter to be read at sentencing Jan. 10.
</P>
<P>
   ``(Artiom) wouldn't wish for my son Avo's loss. And also my son
wouldn't want Artiom to be jailed,'' Demirchyan said in the court
document filed Thursday.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, Badalyan, 19, pleaded no contest to involuntary
manslaughter in the death on Sept. 10, 1998. Charges were reduced
from murder because the shooting was unintentional and there was
confusion in witnesses' statements, prosecutors said.
</P>
<P>
   It is still unclear what actually happened that afternoon on
School Street, said Mark Geragos, Badalyan's attorney.
</P>
<P>
   It was only three days into the school year when an argument
arose during lunch between Avo and another student. The two
students agreed to settle the dispute after school and each arrived
on School Street with a group of friends.
</P>
<P>
   The groups got into a fistfight, a gunshot sounded and Avo fell
to the ground with a bullet in his stomach. He died two days later.
</P>
<P>
   The groups scattered after the gunshot. Some witnesses testified
Badalyan had a gun in his waistband while others said they saw
nothing. Police issued an arrest warrant for him but the teen-ager
did not turn himself in for 29 days.
</P>
<P>
   Police found the handgun tossed under a bush in Brand Park on
Sept. 16.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know that we'll ever really know what happened,''
Geragos said. ``All we know is this is a tragedy for everybody.''
</P>
<P>
   Geragos on Jan. 10 will ask that Badalyan receive probation,
given the fact the 19-year-old served more than a year in Los
Angeles County Jail.
</P>
<P>
   Deputy District Attorney Patricia Wilkinson will ask that
probation be denied and that Person sentence Badalyan to six years
in state prison half of the maximum sentence
</P>
<P>
   because of his
</P>
<P>
   Although Wilkinson declined to comment until the case is closed,
court documents said Badalyan should receive six years because his
conduct exposed the entire group of students to the risk of serious
injury or death.
</P>
<P>
   She pointed out that Badalyan, who attended Allan Daily
Continuation High School, had been arrested as a juvenile on
suspicion of battery and disruption of school.
</P>
<P>
   ``The defendant ... does have a record evidencing violent
behavior and now he has engaged in conduct that has resulted in
death,'' Wilkinson said in court documents.
</P>
<P>
   ``Violence'' isn't a word Sona Demirchyan would have ever linked
to her son or his friends, she said, flipping through a three-ring
binder packed with poems, sketches and a stack of sympathy letters
addressed to her and her husband from Hoover High students.
</P>
<P>
   It is because of those students, Avo's friends, and her own
prayers that she has risen from her bed every day for the last 15
months. On Dec. 9, the day that would have been Avo's 17th
birthday, Demirchyan baked a cake and invited her son's friends
into her Raymond Avenue home.
</P>
<P>
   The students gave her a booklet stuffed with more drawings and
prayers. On the cover is a picture of Avo and the words: ``We have
lost an angel but we have not forgotten him. In our hearts and
souls forever.''
</P>
<P>
   Demirchyan, who emigrated with her husband and sons from Armenia
in 1992, said Avo preferred being at home with his family unless he
was playing sports. Seated under one of three photographs of her
youngest son, Demirchyan looked around her tidy living room and
said Avo would always do the dusting and cleaning. He liked things
spotless, she said.
</P>
<P>
   So now, Demirchyan returns the favor.
</P>
<P>
   Every day when she visits her son, she pulls a cloth from her
bag and polishes his grave marker. She wipes away any grass
clippings, even getting between the engraved letters.
</P>
<P>
   On Friday, wearing all black as she does most days, Demirchyan
knelt on the ground and kissed her son's picture goodbye. She would
be back the next day, she assured -- the cemetery is her second
home, she said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now he is in a place where there is no violence,'' Demirchyan
said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 0116EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0035 </DOCNO>
