<HEADER>
A2578 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-HELSTOSKI-ART-NY     12-18 0599
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-HELSTOSKI-ART-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HENRY HELSTOSKI DIES AT 75; SERVED 6 TERMS IN CONGRESS 
</HEADLINE>
   (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.)  
 (af)  
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Henry Helstoski, a former New Jersey congressman whose bright
career in government all but ended in 1976 when he was indicted _
but never tried or found guilty _ on charges of accepting a bribe,
died on Thursday at a hospice in Wayne, N.J. He was 75.
</P>
<P>
   The cause was prostate cancer, said his son, Henry Helstoski Jr.
of Boonton, N.J.
</P>
<P>
   In 1976, Helstoski, a Democrat who served six terms in the House
of Representatives representing the Ninth Congressional District in
Bergen County, was charged with taking more than $8,000 for
introducing legislation allowing several Chileans to immigrate to
the United States.
</P>
<P>
   Helstoski said he was framed by political opponents. The
charges, which included obstruction of justice, led to defeat in
his bid for a seventh term in 1976. But the charges were dropped in
1980, when the United States Supreme Court ruled that legislation
could not be used as evidence.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wheels of justice grind slowly,'' Helstoski said in 1980.
``When all this nonsense started, I said it was without merit, but
it has taken all this time to set the record straight.''
</P>
<P>
   Despite the vindication, by 1980 Helstoski's political career
was permanently damaged; he failed to regain his seat in 1978 and
in 1980. In an interview in 1991 with The Record in Hackensack,
N.J., he expressed bitterness toward Washington and the
prosecutorial system.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got a dim view of politics, what people do to advance
themselves,'' Helstoski said. ``You certainly get a good
perspective of what human nature is; the extent of greed, ambition,
the standards and morality of the people.''
</P>
<P>
   Helstoski was born on March 21, 1924, in Wallington, N.J. He
received a bachelor's degree from Paterson College and a master's
degree from Montclair State College. He also served in the Army Air
Forces during World War II.
</P>
<P>
   His first civilian jobs were in education; he worked as a
teacher, principal and school superintendent in East Rutherford,
Cedar Grove and Wallington before serving as a councilman and then
mayor of East Rutherford between 1956 and 1964.
</P>
<P>
   He was elected to Congress in 1964 and was a member of the House
Ways and Means Committee. He was considered a supporter of
anti-pollution laws before they became popular in Washington. He
also sponsored legislation that increased life insurance and
pensions for veterans.
</P>
<P>
   In 1969 he ran unsuccessfully for the Democratic nomination for
governor in New Jersey.
</P>
<P>
   Helstoski was an early critic of American military involvement
in Vietnam. And he was one of the first congressmen to call for the
impeachment of President Richard Nixon.
</P>
<P>
   After his final unsuccessful bid in 1980 to win back his seat in
Congress, Helstoski became a grants administrator in Bergen County.
In 1988, he was a substitute English teacher in Passaic, N.J., and
later a full-time teacher in Irvington.
</P>
<P>
   He was also the publisher of The Passaic Citizen, a weekly
newspaper, and an accountant. For the last decade he had been
mostly retired.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his son, he is survived by his wife, Victoria;
two daughters, Andrea Cahill of Woodridge and Renata Helstoski of
Rutherford; a stepson, Kenneth Baldanza of Wayne; a brother, Robert
J. Helstoski of Saddle Brook; a sister, Lillian Helling of Denver;
and two grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 0116EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
