<HEADER>
A2584 &Cx1f; taf-z
u k BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-BUSH-NY     12-18 0828
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-OBSERVER-BUSH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EDITORIAL OBSERVER: DIVIDING UP THE MONEY FROM THE BUSH TAX CUT 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By MICHAEL M. WEINSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Gov. George W. Bush of Texas projects genuine sympathy when he
talks about the single mother earning $20,000 a year and struggling
to move her family into the middle class. The identification with
salaried workers is a key ingredient of the ``compassionate
conservatism'' that he says can remake the image of the Republican
Party. For that reason, Bush says, his plan, which would cost $480
billion over five years, focuses ``on low- and moderate-income
families,'' and provides the ``greatest help for those most in
need.'' In fact, Bush's plan is fairer than the 10-year, $800
billion plan passed this year by the Republican-controlled Congress
and vetoed by President Clinton. It would have tilted dramatically
in favor of wealthy families, throwing financial crumbs to nearly
everyone else.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush's description of his own plan's distribution of
benefits exaggerates the benefits to low-income people. Given the
mathematics of revenue collection, the poor cannot come away the
big winners. High-income families pay an overwhelming share of all
income taxes. Sweeping cuts of the sort designed by Bush have to go
to many of those privileged families. On the other hand, many
low-income families pay no tax, so even a whopping tax cut does
them not a penny's worth of good.
</P>
<P>
   Bush does try to mitigate the regressive impact of income tax
cuts by proposing to cut the bottom rate by a third, to 10 percent
from 15 percent, and doubling the credit for each child to $1,000.
His plan would thereby remove millions of low-income families from
the income tax rolls entirely, a clear benefit to those families.
But the amounts involved would be modest compared with the big
prizes Bush's plan would hand to the country's wealthiest families
through eliminating the estate tax and making more high-income
families eligible for tax breaks that are now limited to less
wealthy families.
</P>
<P>
   On net, low-income families wind up paying only a slightly
smaller share of total income taxes under the Bush plan. Wealthy
families come away with the biggest prizes. The Center for Tax
Justice, a liberal research group that uses standard economic
models to study tax incidence, estimates that the bottom 60 percent
of taxpayers would get only about 10 percent of the Bush tax-cut
money. By contrast, the wealthiest 1 percent of taxpayers would get
almost 40 percent of the money. The average tax cut for the bottom
20 percent of taxpayers would be less than $50 a year; for the top
1 percent it would be over $50,000.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's supporters defend the plan by reciting a tired mantra:
The rich pay an overwhelming share of the income tax, so it is fair
that they reap an overwhelming share of any tax cut. But nothing
forces Bush to rely entirely on income taxes to fulfill his
tax-cutting pledge. He could have proposed cutting payroll taxes
instead. Perhaps two-thirds of all families pay more in payroll
taxes _ the roughly 15 percent of wages and salaries that employees
and their employers pay into the Social Security and Medicare trust
funds _ than income taxes.
</P>
<P>
   That makes payroll taxes far more burdensome on low-income
families. The bottom 40 percent of families pay less than 1 percent
of income taxes, but about 4 percent of payroll taxes. Said another
way, the top 1 percent of taxpayers pay almost 40 percent of all
income taxes but less than 5 percent of all payroll taxes. Had Bush
chosen to cut payroll taxes, poor families would reap substantially
larger savings.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, Bush's plan is doubly unequal. By cutting a tax that
poor people do not much pay, Bush would force Congress to reduce
spending by between $1 and $2 trillion over 10 years. The programs
almost certainly destined to absorb the largest reductions _
housing, education and other nonmilitary programs _
disproportionately help low- and middle-income families.
</P>
<P>
   Bush promotes his plan with the startling claim that ``roughly
$3 out of every $6 returned to taxpayers would finance changes that
help low-income families gain access to the middle class.'' This
boast is misleading. It invites voters to believe that half of the
cash goes to poor families. Bush is counting the entire cost of the
provisions to cut the lowest tax rate to 10 percent and to double
the tax credit for children as helping the poor escape poverty. But
upper-income families also take advantage of these two provisions,
and in fact they reap most of the benefits. Bush counts the cost of
making rich families even richer as a benefit for the poor.
</P>
<P>
   On balance, then, Bush exaggerates how much his plan favors the
poor. But it is also true that his plan goes further in that
direction than anything else the Republicans have proposed. With
more careful design, he could put even more compassion into his
conservatism. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
