<SLUG> BC-SNOW-GIFT-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ICE COMPANY DELIVERS CHILLED CHEER
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Harrison Sheppard  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- The mercury topped 80 degrees, but it was a white
Christmas at Kristie McLean's house Friday, thanks to some ice men
with warm hearts.
</P>
<P>
   With her mother suffering from cancer, McLean was hoping to
throw an extra-special Christmas party for her and her suburban Los
Angeles neighborhood this year, topping it off with a blanket of
snow on the lawn like they remembered from growing up in Ohio.
</P>
<P>
   Pete DeGrandis and Tony Floria from Union Ice Co. in the Van
Nuys area of Los Angeles heard her pleas for help on the radio, and
came to her rescue. Friday, the company sprayed roughly seven tons
of artificial snow on her front lawn for free, a service that would
normally cost upward of $800.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh my, I'm in snow heaven!'' shouted a grateful McLean as a
neighborhood girl charged at her with a handful of the white stuff.
</P>
<P>
   Floria, the company's route superintendent, said he heard McLean
on station STAR 98.7 (KYSR-FM) Wednesday talking about how she
wanted to make her mom happy, but another ice company refused to
give her a discount.
</P>
<P>
   ``I said, We gotta get a hold of them,'' Floria said. ``We'll do
it for free, just out of a good heart for the holidays.''
</P>
<P>
   The company, which normally makes artificial snow for movie
studios and provides ice for restaurants, fed 48 blocks of ice,
weighing 300 pounds each, into a snow machine and spritzed it all
over her once-green lawn. Neighborhood children watched in awe,
just waiting to roll around in it.
</P>
<P>
   The moment they finished, the kids went to work, rolling around
on the ground making snow angels, throwing snowballs at each other
and the adults, and just giggling their heads off.
</P>
<P>
   ``I love it,'' said 7-year-old Madison Reeb, as she rolled up
what she described as ``the perfect snowball that's so big that I
can hit anyone.''
</P>
<P>
   McLean throws the party for her neighbors on Bloomfield Street
every year, a tradition she picked up from her mother. Neighbors
say she has brought together a community that didn't talk that much
before she moved in a few years ago. She goes all-out in putting
the parties together, including renting a horse-driven sleigh to
parade down the street, but paying for the snow was simply too
much, she said, especially with her mother's condition.
</P>
<P>
   McLean's mother, Gwen Allen, whom her daughter describes as
``everybody's mama and everybody's grandma'' said she was thrilled
with the ice men's generosity. She gingerly walked out to the front
yard and tossed a few snowballs at some of the kids with a broad
smile on her face.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, isn't this something,'' she said. ``I was just enjoying
watching the kids play. Isn't this great?''
</P>
<P>
   Allen, 70, developed cancer about three years ago, and had a
successful operation. But the disease returned last month. She
undergoes weekly chemotherapy treatments, which leave her tired,
but she remains optimistic.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sort of drains you,'' she said. ``Because by the time you
recover from one weekly treatment, it's time to do another. But I'm
blessed. I beat it once, I'm gonna do it again.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
