u k BC-EDIT-PANAMA-CANAL-NYT     12-18 0616
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EDIT-PANAMA-CANAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CENTURY ENDS IN PANAMA 
</HEADLINE>
   (af)  
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The New York Times says in an editorial Saturday, Dec. 18: &QL;
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It may be emblematic of our headlong, high-tech rush into the
next millennium that a chance to reflect on one of the signal
achievements of the American Century _ and one of its less noble
subplots _ passed this week with hardly a ripple. The United States
handed over the Panama Canal to Panama in a ceremony so bereft of
American interest that neither President Clinton nor a single top
official in his administration bothered to attend. It was a shabby
way to treat a monumental human achievement created at the dawn of
this century. Further, it slighted a profound and welcome evolution
of American power as the century comes to a close.
</P>
<P>
   The creation of a water passage across Panama linking the
Atlantic and Pacific oceans was a phenomenal undertaking, the moon
shot of its time. It relied on an ingenious ``lake-and-lock''
scheme whereby ships as long as the Empire State Building is tall
were hoisted 80 feet into vast freshwater lakes created by dams and
fed by torrential rains, connected by a cut through the Isthmus of
Panama. But it was achieved at great human cost. Between 1904 and
1915 more than 5,600 lives, mostly Barbadian, were lost to disease
and accidents.
</P>
<P>
   The canal represented a coming of age for the United States as
an assertive global power, better and worse. Theodore Roosevelt
famously personified America's turn-of-the-century can-do ideal
when, as the first United States president to travel overseas, he
posed at the controls of a 95-ton Bucyrus shovel. But that zeal was
inherently coercive, and over the decades it took on a neo-colonial
dimension. Not a few United States armed interventions in Central
America were aimed largely at protecting the canal from hostile
powers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There is no Panama Canal! There is an American Canal
(italics)at(end italics) Panama,'' ran the slogan of opponents of
the 1977 treaties signed by Jimmy Carter and Gen. Omar Torrijos
that authorized a phased handover of the canal to Panama by 2000.
Carter, who led the United States delegation at this week's
handover, wisely persevered with a deal that signaled a more equal
partnership between the United States and the nations of Latin
America and removed the onus of maintaining a colonial enclave in a
country whose people opposed it. Reflecting a belated respect for a
small nation's sovereignty and pride, the world's only remaining
superpower has voluntarily given up an immensely valuable asset.
</P>
<P>
   One reason Americans can shrug off the deal is that the canal is
no longer strategically or economically essential to American
interests. Supertankers, aircraft carriers and nuclear submarines
cannot pass through the canal, and software does not need to. Few
doubt that Panamanians possess the wherewithal to make a seamless
transition, but there remain legitimate fears of corruption and
patronage in a country with little history of transparent
government. Conservative critics of the deal have questioned
Panama's decision to award port concessions to a Hong Kong company
they say has Chinese military ties. But the treaties explicitly
permit United States intervention if the canal's security is
threatened.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton's lamentable reluctance to risk conservative
ire by attending this week's transfer merely underscored the
courage shown two decades ago by Carter and his Senate allies, who
at great political cost forged an agreement that recognized how
America's long-term interests in that important region were best
served by partnership rather than domination.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 0118EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0042 </DOCNO>
