<SLUG> BC-HKN-RANGERS-CAPITALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CAPITALS BEAT RANGERS IN OVERTIME, 3-2 
</HEADLINE>
  (mk) 
 By JASON DIAMOS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ The Rangers' season-high, five-game unbeaten streak
ended Friday night, and the villain was Washington Capitals
goaltender Olaf Kolzig.
</P>
<P>
   Kolzig stopped 16 third-period shots _ and at least a half-dozen
outstanding scoring opportunities _ to enable the Capitals to force
overtime. In the extra session, Calle Johansson blasted a slap shot
from the top of the right circle over Mike Richter's left shoulder
and into the top right corner of the goal only 31 seconds into the
session to give the Capitals a 3-2 victory.
</P>
<P>
   The goal was set up by a cross-ice pass by Adam Oates from the
bottom of the right circle and through the slot.
</P>
<P>
   Oates had a goal and an assist, and overshadowed two goals by
Adam Graves and two assists by Theo Fleury as the Rangers were
saddled with their first loss since Dec. 1. Thanks to the new
National Hockey League rules, however, the Rangers were able to
salvage a point in the standing.
</P>
<P>
   Over their last six games, the Rangers are 4-1-1 with one
regulation tie, giving them 10 out of a possible 12 points.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitals were without two of their top goal scorers, Peter
Bondra (knee) and Jan Bulis (groin). The Capitals play the trap,
and most of the scoreless first period resembled a football game
played between the 30-yard lines.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
