<SLUG> BC-DREYERS-FLAVOR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GIRL'S CREATION WINS STATE'S ICE CREAM CONTEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Chris Sieroty  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- I scream. You scream. We all scream for Gold
Miner's Dream ice cream.
</P>
<P>
   After a three-month taste-off, the frozen creation of
11-year-old Elysa Hill of Woodland Hills in suburban Los Angeles
has been named the official flavor of the California
Sesquicentennial.
</P>
<P>
   Hill's ice cream will be in stores from Eureka to San Diego in
Dreyer's famous half-gallon barrel beginning in mid-January, said
Dreyer's Grand Ice Cream spokeswoman Jennifer Howard.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is really cool,'' said Elysa, a fifth-grader at Woodlake
Avenue Elementary School in Woodland Hills, who presumably had no
pun intended.
</P>
<P>
   Gold Miner's Dream also will be served at a number of state
functions next year, including at California's 150th birthday party
Sept. 9 in Sacramento. Elysa's mom, Doreen Hill, said, ``The family
has been told to keep that date open and intends to attend as many
events next year as we can.''
</P>
<P>
   Added Elysa: ``It's going to be an opportunity to see a lot of
different things.''
</P>
<P>
   Elysa's winning ice cream is made of mountains of chocolate and
vanilla swirl blazoned with trails of rich milk chocolate and
caramel with hidden toffee nuggets.
</P>
<P>
   Earlier this year, Union City-based Dreyer's ran a contest to
pick the official ice cream of California. All entries had to
include a creative name and description of the flavor, somehow
based on how the flavor represents the state of California. And it
had to be a flavor the company could produce on a mass scale.
</P>
<P>
   Elysa developed the unique flavor after her teacher at Woodlake,
Verdell Gurnee, passed out entry forms to her class, which had been
studying the California Gold Rush.
</P>
<P>
   After several elimination rounds, Gold Miner's Dream beat out
Hurray for Hollywood by a margin of 56 percent to 44 percent in the
three-month, statewide taste-off to take the crown as California's
official ice cream. ``It's not very often an 11-year-old wins a
contest in which 8,000 people entered,'' Howard said.
</P>
<P>
   There's been an extra side benefit to Elysa's victory. Since her
daughter won the contest, Doreen Hill said, ``I no longer feel
guilty when I eat ice cream.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
