<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CELTICS-SPURS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPURS BEAT CELTICS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN ANTONIO _ There's not much suspense these days with the
Celtics. With two starters ailing, there simply is not a lot of
wiggle room. Whatever room they might have had Friday night
disappeared quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The world champion Spurs finally played the role for most of the
evening and emerged with a 103-94 victory before 17,264 at the
Alamodome. San Antonio took control of things in the middle
quarters and turned it over to the reserves, who almost Heathcliff
Slocumbed it away. Fortunately for the Spurs, Tim Duncan &AMP; Co. had
provided a safe cushion.
</P>
<P>
   Duncan played long enough (35 minutes) and well enough (30
points, 17 rebounds, 5 blocks) to do most of the damage. David
Robinson (12 points, 5 rebounds) sat out the last 16 minutes and
Avery Johnson watched the final 19; the Spurs play Saturday night
in Denver. The victory was the ninth straight over Boston here and
the 11th in the last 12 meetings between the teams.
</P>
<P>
   The loss was Boston's eighth straight on the road and fourth in
a row overall. The Celtics are now 10-12 with one roadie left
Saturday night (Houston) in what is turning out to be a week from
you-know-where. Things even got a little testy, when Antoine Walker
and Malik Rose jawed too much for ref Joe Crawford and were tossed
with 5:23 left.
</P>
<P>
   The way Walker was going (2 of 13), he should have blown the
notoriously short-fused Crawford some kisses instead of some
naughty words. He said the matter ``was no big deal'' and ``it's
bound to happen over the course of 82 games.'' Rick Pitino said he
wasn't sure what had transpired, but added, ``You can't do that
with Joe Crawford.''
</P>
<P>
   Walker, however, had company in the misery department. Eric
Williams was 3 of 14 and said, ``This was a rough night. I might
not have 30 games like this in my whole career. I got great
looks.'' The Celtics were under 40 percent shooting while the game
was remotely competitive; they finished at 41.1 percent. They did
manage to cause some angst among the Spurs _ Duncan had to go back
in for the final 73 seconds _ when they got to within 6.
</P>
<P>
   But all that really did was unnecessarily lengthen the game (the
fourth quarter took 48 minutes) and succeed in delaying the start
of the epic tilt between Brownsville Pace and Corpus Christi Tuloso
Midway.
</P>
<P>
   ``They were kind of desperate,'' said Duncan, who was 7 of 14
from the field and 16 of 18 from the line. ``But to finish a game
like that, you do what you have to do.''
</P>
<P>
   The Spurs didn't break much of a sweat in this one. Coach Gregg
Popovich, who has been critical of the team's ragged play of late,
said, ``The guys played great defense. It was one of our better
games.''
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio had a 46-35 rebounding advantage, an 8-3 advantage
in blocked shots, and took 54 free throws (22 in the fourth) to
Boston's 22.
</P>
<P>
   ``They dominated us inside,'' Pitino said. ``But our effort was
A-plus and our attitude was A-plus. It's just hard when you get
behind on the road. You have a hard time winning.''
</P>
<P>
   Dana Barros led Boston with 18, scoring 10 in the fourth as the
Celtics' helter-skelter style forced six turnovers. Tony Battie had
16 and Walter McCarty 15. Adrian Griffin had 13, but came out for
good with 6:45 left after bruising his left knee. He said he'd be
able to go Saturday night.
</P>
<P>
   San Antonio put this one away in the third quarter. The Spurs
led by 10 at the break, thanks mainly to Duncan, who had a 22/7
first half. They led, 58-47, in the third when Robinson started and
finished what turned out to be a game-deciding 10-2 run. He had 6
in the spurt as the Celtics fell behind by 19. It was a 15-point
spread entering the fourth.
</P>
<P>
   It was still a 15-point game with 3:13 left. But the Celtics
kept at it and ripped off an 11-3 run in the next two minutes. It
was now a 7-point game and back came Duncan, who had left with 8:10
remaining.
</P>
<P>
   ``We didn't want to lose the game trying to get practice, so we
put Tim back in,'' Popovich said.
</P>
<P>
   The same thing had happened when the teams met last month in
Boston. The Celtics threatened. The Spurs' big guys came back and
ended the threat. Duncan returned this time to score 4 more points,
grab two more rebounds, and that was that.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
