<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-UCLA-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA WOMEN BEAT FULLERTON
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By LEE BARNATHAN  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   FULLERTON _ A pulse beats within the UCLA women's basketball
team. It has been faint at times, but Friday, it became stronger.
</P>
<P>
   Vital signs are becoming more normal now that point guard Erica
Gomez has returned.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez, playing for the first time since undergoing surgery to
repair a torn labrum, breathed life into her inconsistent team in
sixth-ranked UCLA's 108-75 victory Friday over Cal State Fullerton
before 518 fans. It was the team's highest total since scoring 128
in January 1994.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez played 15{ minutes and scored 10 points, had eight assists
and two steals. But it was the confidence teammates showed that
made the difference.
</P>
<P>
   In recent games, UCLA (5-2) has had trouble starting fast
against mediocre-to-bad teams like Pepperdine and Fullerton (0-7).
This time, however, Gomez sparked an 8-0 run with three assists and
a basket later in the first half, and UCLA never led by less than
eight again.
</P>
<P>
   Six Bruins scored in double figures, led by Maylana Martin's 22,
Michelle Greco's 18 and Marie Philman's season-high 17.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was hard to sit on the bench. We looked kind of flat,''
Gomez said. ``I felt really good. I've been anxious to come back,
to get ready for the East Coast trip.''
</P>
<P>
   That would be upcoming games at nationally ranked Rutgers on
Tuesday and No. 1 Connecticut on Thursday. UCLA struggled in its
last two games against ranked teams, so Gomez's return is
fortuitous.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez said Wednesday she couldn't play until she reached her
surgeon in New York, David Altchek. She succeeded in tracking him
down by telephone Thursday night and found him willing to clear
her.
</P>
<P>
   ``He asked how I felt and he asked about my range of motion,''
Gomez said. ``I said I felt fine and I've been going all out for a
long time. He said, `Well, if you're practicing in full, I can't
hold you back.' ''
</P>
<P>
   A couple of faxes later, Gomez's return became official.
</P>
<P>
   She entered the game with 9:53 remaining in the first half and
the Bruins struggling to pull away from a Fullerton team with no
one taller than 6-foot-1.
</P>
<P>
   Gomez's first-half totals: Seven minutes, 10 points, four
assists. While she was in there, UCLA outscored the Titans 26-16
and led 54-45 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   She was just beginning. After entering with 12:44 left in the
second half, Gomez had LaCresha Flannigan, Janae Hubbard, Ayesha
Rembert and Natalie Jarrett on the floor with her.
</P>
<P>
   It's not a lineup that will inspire fear on the coming road
trip, but in 40 seconds, Gomez had three assists and a steal as
part of an 8-0 run.
</P>
<P>
   ``It didn't look like she missed a beat,'' said UCLA coach Kathy
Oliver, who also noted that team also had a slow start from UCLA to
Fullerton because five players had finals that lasted until 2:30
p.m. ``She brings a lot of leadership to her team. As good as she
is, we were a good basketball team that will be a great team with
her.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
