u a BC-EPA-AIR-POLLUTION-2ND     12-18 0602
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-EPA-AIR-POLLUTION-2NDLD-WRITETHRU-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EPA ORDERS POWER PLANTS TO CUT EMISSIONS TO REDUCE SMOG IN EAST 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: W.Va., Ohio, N.C., Pa., Md., Va., Mich., N.J., Ky., Del.
N.Y., Ind.)   (CORRECTS spelling of Carol in 7th graf) 
 (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling (888)
603-1036 or (888) 346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By MATTHEW L. WALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ The Environmental Protection Agency on Friday
ordered 392 plants in a dozen states, mostly electric generating
stations, to cut in half emissions of chemicals that drift with
winds and add to smog along the Eastern seaboard.
</P>
<P>
   The federal regulators acted at the request of New York,
Connecticut, Massachusetts and Pennsylvania, which said they needed
help to meet national smog standards.
</P>
<P>
   The plants are in 12 states, as far west as Indiana and as far
south as North Carolina. Agency officials said they might soon
issue similar orders for plants in Illinois. Most of the plants
meet existing federal limits on the chemicals, nitrogen oxides, and
are in areas that do not exceed smog standards, but now the EPA is
tightening the limits.
</P>
<P>
   The 12 states are West Virginia, Ohio, North Carolina,
Pennsylvania, Maryland, Virginia, Michigan, New Jersey, Kentucky,
Delaware, New York and Indiana. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The states that requested the action are among a group on the
East Coast that had already agreed among themselves to impose the
stricter standard on nitrogen oxide emissions within their borders.
The areas that would for the first time be forced to take action
under Friday's order are in the South and Midwest.
</P>
<P>
   The areas covered by the action must reduce emissions by 2003 by
a total of about half a million tons a year, all in the summer smog
season, the federal regulators said. The EPA said that compliance
would cost companies, which include Ford, General Motors, Dow
Chemical and most power providers in Ohio, West Virginia and
Pennsylvania, about $950 million a year.
</P>
<P>
   Carol Browner, the EPA administrator, said the order would raise
the cost of electricity by about 1 percent above what it would
otherwise have been, but that because of deregulation of the
industry, costs to consumers are still expected to decline.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in several industries, though, said Friday that they
were not sure what compliance would cost. Many executives and state
officials from areas covered by the order denounced it, saying that
they already met strict standards, that Eastern smog was little
affected by Midwestern emissions and that the EPA would ultimately
be rebuffed by the courts.
</P>
<P>
   Owners of some of the plants are already in court to block
tighter limits on nitrogen oxide emissions that the EPA proposed
last spring.
</P>
<P>
   The EPA's track record in court has been poor in the last few
months. In May, the U.S. Court of Appeals for the District of
Columbia Circuit barred the agency from enforcing a stricter
standard on smog levels, one calculated over an eight-hour period
instead of the current one-hour. In a separate decision, it blocked
the EPA from requiring the states to order a new round of
reductions in nitrogen oxide emissions from sources within their
borders.
</P>
<P>
   So now the EPA is trying a third means.
</P>
<P>
   But Ms. Browner said Friday in a conference call with reporters,
``Our commitment is to solve the long-distance ozone-transport
problem.''
</P>
<P>
   ``We're going to get there, one way or the other,'' she said.
``We are going to get there. We are going to get people clean
air.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   The EPA did not rank the plants cited on its list Friday. David
Cohen, a spokesman for the EPA, said the four states that filed the
petitions provided information based on computer modeling and ``we
looked at the broad categories to verify the fact that the sources
were contributors.''
</P>
<P>
   In Michigan, one of the states with plants covered by the order,
Russ Harding, director of the Department of Environmental Quality,
said: ``I think it's highly inappropriate for the administrator to
be doing this. It may make good headlines, but it's not going to
solve clean-air issues. She's just creating more lawsuits, wasting
more taxpayer dollars.''
</P>
<P>
   He said that Michigan had already been planning to publish new
regulations next month putting stricter controls on nitrogen oxide
emissions, but not as strict as the ones ordered Friday.
</P>
<P>
   At First Energy, the parent company of Ohio Edison, Ralph
DiNicola, a spokesman, said, ``The EPA's own studies have indicated
that under heavy ozone- loading days the Midwest plants contribute
to less than 5 percent of the problem in the industrialized
Northeast cities.''
</P>
<P>
   DiNicola said that in the East, people could see stone statues
eroding, another effect of nitrogen emissions, as they stood next
to roads with ``12 lanes of stalled traffic.''
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a little hard to then take a look at plants 500 miles
away and claim they are the cause of it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Browner, the EPA administrator, was not able to say Friday how
many fewer days of ozone violations the East would record with the
new controls in place.
</P>
<P>
   The order uses a procedure outlined in the Clean Air Act
amendments of 1990 under which the states can petition the EPA to
take action against specific smokestacks beyond their borders. The
EPA set out to use the procedure in April, when several states
petitioned, saying they could not meet the strict new ozone
standards the agency had promulgated. But then the appeals court
here held up the new eight-hour standard, and the states withdrew
the petitions, to rewrite them based on the older ozone standard.
Then several industries sued on the basis of the original
petitions. One issue was how much difference a smokestack in
Cincinnati or Detroit could make to the air in Philadelphia or New
York.
</P>
<P>
   But New York, Connecticut and Pennsylvania cited vast swaths of
states near and far, and categories of plants within those areas
Massachusetts, the other state whose petition was approved Friday,
named individual plants, some as far away as Michigan. Another four
jurisdictions filed petitions later that are still under review,
including New Jersey, Maryland, Delaware and the District of
Columbia.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in the complaining states hailed the order. ``The EPA
has come to the realization that we have come to a long time ago,
that trans-boundary pollution exists, and that there are specific
facilities outside New York's borders that are seriously affecting
quality of air here in New York,'' said William Cahill, New York's
commissioner of environmental conservation.
</P>
<P>
   In 30 years of determined work, government regulators have
forced extensive changes in cars, fuels, power plants and even
hairspray to reduce emissions of chemicals that cause smog. But
paired with 30 years of economic growth, they have not succeeded in
eliminating violations.
</P>
<P>
   At the Clean Air Task Force, a nonprofit group, David Wooley, a
lawyer, said that the federal limit for smog was 120 parts ozone
per billion parts of air, and that often in the summer, air
drifting into densely populated areas of the Northeast was already
at 90 parts per billion. Health damage occurs even below 120 parts,
Wooley said, so any reduction would be helpful.
</P>
<P>
   Others were skeptical. In Marshall, Mich., a town of less than
7,000, situated 100 miles west of Detroit, Maurice Evans, the city
manager, said he doubted that his town's municipal electric plant
could be affecting air in New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have a small electric utility,'' Evans said. ``We've got
very little pollution that's coming out of that plant.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
