<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 02:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2637 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT     12-18 0571
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-CLIPPERS-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLIPPERS EDGE WARRIORS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The Clippers, who've been going low enough to
eliminate a dachshund at high-stakes limbo, needed a heroic hoop
from Lamar Odom to avoid spinal disaster and survive Friday's date
with the Golden State Warriors.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game definitely was on the line,'' said the rookie Odom,
who persevered through unreasonably cold shooting to produce 23
points, 13 rebounds and 7 assists. ``Somebody had to make a play.''
</P>
<P>
   And because the NBA says so, somebody had to win.
</P>
<P>
   In a scheduled NBA event that was every bit as compelling as a
spitball fight between Third World nations, the Clippers rang up a
92-91 victory in front of 11,217 at Staples Center.
</P>
<P>
   Both teams began the evening 5-17, making it almost impossible
to notice they weren't at full strength. The Warriors had three
injured starters - Mookie Blaylock, Antawn Jamison and Adonal Foyle
- back in Oakland, while the Clips matched them on the grief index
with ankle injuries for Derek Anderson and Brian Skinner.
</P>
<P>
   In terms of style, the event lived down to its billing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It wasn't a pretty game,'' said Clippers coach Chris Ford, who
ranks as an authority on the subject. ``We got some breaks.
Christmas came early.''
</P>
<P>
   Let's start at the 1:11 mark of round four.
</P>
<P>
   That's how much time remained before the Clippers followed
Tuesday's mighty Laker clouting by coughing up a loss against the
weakened Warriors, who held a 91-84 lead.
</P>
<P>
   But Golden Stater Chris Mills acquired a double-technical when
Odom was fouled on one of his kamikaze drives to the hoop. ``If I
had it to do again, I hopefully wouldn't do it the same way
again,'' Mills said.
</P>
<P>
   Troy Hudson (20 points) drilled both technical free throws. Odom
- who missed 13 of 20 field-goal attempts and 6 of 15 free throws -
nailed his final two from the line, cutting the deficit to three.
</P>
<P>
   Odom stole a pass on the Warriors' next possession, fed Tyrone
Nesby for a hoop, then finished Golden State's collapse with an
8-foot runner with 11 seconds to play.
</P>
<P>
   ``He put the team on his back and made some plays,'' Ford said
of Odom, who's been fighting an 11-game funk. ``At the end, he was
magnificent.''
</P>
<P>
   Maurice Taylor (26 minutes, 10 points, 6 fouls), who was a few
miles south of magnificent thanks to the flu, said such sensations
are in Odom's job description.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's supposed to do that,'' Taylor said. ``He'll be doing that
here for a long time.''
</P>
<P>
   Some guy named Tony Farmer scored 19 points to lead the
Warriors, who were limited to 39.4-percent shooting by the nasty
Clipper defense. Michael Olowokandi had 16 points and 9 rebounds
for the Clips, who led by 11 in the first quarter and had the
advantage after each quarter.
</P>
<P>
   Odom took it upon himself to make sure they led after the
fourth.
</P>
<P>
   ``He had the guts to make the big plays,'' Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   Said Odom: ``It's just the way basketball has to be played.''
</P>
<P>
   Notes: The Clippers placed Skinner (ankle sprain) on the injured
list Friday and signed journeyman Marty Conlon. The 31-year-old,
6-foot-11 Conlon is in his ninth NBA season and has career numbers
of 6.5 points and 3.5 rebounds per game. He began this season on
the Boston Celtics' roster, but remained on their injured list
(sprained toe) until getting waived Dec. 13.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 0236EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0065 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 02:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2640 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r s BC-HKN-DUCKS-WRITETHRU-L     12-18 0702
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DUCKS-WRITETHRU-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUCKS WIN THIRD STRAIGHT
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By GREG CHRISTENSEN  
 San Gabriel Valley Tribune  
<TEXT>
<P>
   ANAHEIM _ The Mighty Ducks have been huffing and puffing most of
the 1999-2000 season. No matter how hard they tried, it seemed like
.500 was their lot in life.
</P>
<P>
   But it's amazing how three consecutive wins can lift a team's
spirits and standing.
</P>
<P>
   Five times Anaheim had tried, and failed, to win a third
consecutive game this season, but the Ducks overcame that obstacle
Friday night with a 2-0 victory over the Chicago Blackhawks in
front of 12,632 at the Pond.
</P>
<P>
   ``This team is hungrier than at the beginning of the year, we
want it more,'' Teemu Selanne said. ``It's not enough to win, lose,
win, lose. We are harder on each other.''
</P>
<P>
   But the Ducks have been more than willing to come to each
other's defense in recent games. Friday, a frustrated Tony Amonte
made questionable hits on Paul Kariya and Pascal Trepanier and both
times he had to answer to Selanne of all people.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whatever you have to do,'' the winger said with a grin when
asked about his enforcer role.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the guys coming together as a team,'' Ducks coach Craig
Hartsburg said. ``They are standing up for each other and they
actually seem to like these kind of games. This group won't back
down.''
</P>
<P>
   The victory wasn't especially artistic, but the Ducks and goalie
Guy Hebert _ who posted his 25th career shutout _ were never really
threatened by the lowly Blackhawks. Once Niclas Havelid's point
shot deflected off Chicago defenseman Sylvain Cote's stick and
broke the spell of goalie Jocelyn Thibault at 12:35 of the second
period, the outcome seem inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   The second power-play unit chipped in with a goal by Ruslan
Salei three minutes later and just like that the Ducks are tied
with Dallas, trail Phoenix and the Kings by only two points, and
are within three of San Jose in the Pacific Division.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't talk about it, but we are on the right track and know
we can make a push for a top-four playoff spot,'' Hartsburg said.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim's 37 points is its best total after 33 games. The Ducks
had 34 points in the first 33 games last season.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks came into the game tied for fifth in the league in
defense _ allowing 2.25 goals per game. They had given up two or
fewer 20 times, but their offense was averaging only 2.6 goals and
had been limited to two goals or fewer in 18 games.
</P>
<P>
   Anaheim was 4-12-2 in those games, so Friday's contest was very
much up for grabs when the teams were scoreless after 30 minutes
and Thibault was on his game.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the Ducks got some motivation with just under nine
minutes to play in the second period when Amonte and Trepanier came
together and the Ducks defenseman hit his head hard on the ice.
After Trepanier fell, Amonte skated by and pushed his head into the
ice for good measure. Trepanier left looking dazed and did not
return.
</P>
<P>
   The play certainly raised the ire of the small crowd, one member
of which was ejected for heckling a Chicago player.
</P>
<P>
   Thibault was brilliant all game, stopping 28 of 30 shots, but
the Ducks finally broke through with a combination of hard work and
good luck. Steve Rucchin won a faceoff, Kariya battled to get the
puck back to Havelid at the point and the defenseman's shot bounced
off Cote's stick and trickled in.
</P>
<P>
   Thibault had no chance on Anaheim's second goal. Matt Cullen did
some good work on the boards to keep the puck in, got a return pass
from Ted Donato and then set up Salei for a shot from the base of
the left circle.
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks improved to 13-0-0 when leading after two periods
thanks to a scoreless third.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe we could score more goals, but whatever it takes to
win,'' Selanne said. ``We should never lose when we allow two goals
or less.''
</P>
<P>
   The Ducks outshot the Blackhawks only 8-7 in the first period,
but Anaheim had the best of the scoring chances. The best come off
a rebound of a hard shot by Kariya that bounced off Thibault's
shoulder. Selanne was looking at a wide-open net, but the puck
bounced over his stick and Thibault was able to get back in
position to stop a shot by Salei.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
