<P>
   Here are today's top news stories from The New York Times News
Service for AMs of Sunday, Dec. 19:
</P>
<P>
   &UR; INTERNATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``i'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   MACAU-CHINA (Macau) _ Five hundred years of European colonialism
in Asia sputters to a close here this weekend on a desolate,
rain-swept waterfront dredged out of Macau's once-beguiling harbor.
At the stroke of midnight on Sunday, China will reclaim this tiny
enclave from Portugal, raising its red flag over another patch of
Chinese soil and setting the stage for what it hopes will be
eventual reunification with Taiwan. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-ELECT (Moscow) _ The race to elect Russia's third
parliament since the end of the Soviet Union has been suffused with
slander, manipulation and unvarnished peculiarity. It is in keeping
with the surreal nature of Sunday's election for the lower house of
parliament, the Duma, that no one sees the Communists _ who are
once again predicted to capture a plurality of the 440 seats at
stake _ as potential victors, or even much of a force. By Michael
Wines.
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-CHECHNYA (Moscow) _ Russian paratroopers have cut the
road between Chechnya and Georgia in an effort to block the
southern escape routes for Islamic rebels. By Michael R. Gordon.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-TERROR-THREATS (Washington) _ Without knowing where, when or
whether something terrible might happen, U.S. government officials
are trying to prepare for the threat of violence at the millennium,
whether at home or abroad. By Tim Weiner.
</P>
<P>
   IRAQ-U.N. _ Iraq formally rejected the new arms inspection plan
adopted by the Security Council on Friday, and sent demonstrators
into the streets of Baghdad on Saturday to protest what the
government called ``another trick'' perpetrated by the United
States and Britain. By Barbara Crossette.
</P>
<P>
   RWANDA-TRIBUNAL (Arusha, Tanzania) _ Little has been tidy or
efficient in the last four years here as an international court has
wrestled with the incomprehensible: how to mete out blame for at
least 500,000 deaths in Rwanda in 1994. Maybe that is no surprise.
But a furor over the order by appeals judges to release a top
suspect because the tribunal had held him too long before charging
him has made the last few weeks more than difficult for the
International Criminal Tribunal for Rwanda. By Ian Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   VENEZUELA-CATHOLICS (Caracas, Venezuela) _ Since voters swept
him to power 12 months ago, President Hugo Chavez has quarreled
with and berated nearly every part of the establishment here:
political parties, business leaders and intellectuals. So it was
probably inevitable that he would also end up feuding with the
Roman Catholic Church. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   CANADA-QUEBEC (Montreal) _ With popular support for Quebec's
independence in remission, Prime Minister Jean Chretien of Canada
made a bold gamble with his country's future last week by
introducing legislation that lays out Canada's first road map for
national division, but one so littered with obstacles that he bets
the separatists will never follow it. By James Brooke.
</P>
<P>
   KOREA-POLITICS (Seoul, South Korea) _ Frustrated by months of
mudslinging, corruption scandals and legislative gridlock, South
Koreans are demanding an end to the rivalry between the governing
and opposition parties that has mired the political system for
nearly a year. By Calvin Sims.
</P>
<P>
   ITALY-POLITICS (Rome) _ Italian Prime Minister Massimo D'Alema
was widely expected to resign after a ``back me or sack me'' speech
following a call from a small coalition partner for the center-left
to dump him as leader. By Alessandra Stanley.
</P>
<P>
   (THIS STORY IS TENTATIVE AND WILL ONLY RUN IF DEVELOPMENTS
WARRANT A STORY.)
</P>
<P>
   &UR; NATIONAL &LR;  (Moving in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   POET-BOOK-BATTLE _ Billy Collins is the most popular poet in
America. And now this very popularity has provoked one of the odder
publishing battles of recent memory, pitting a huge commercial
publisher against a small academic press over a literary poet. By
Bruce Weber. (With photo.)
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-COMPUTER-CODE (Waltham, Mass.) _ The government and most of
corporate America have declared that virtually all of their
critical systems will function normally when Jan. 1 arrives. But
because only a portion of most computer code is actually tested to
make sure the year ``00'' will be correctly interpreted, even the
most confident computer managers anticipate at least minor flaws
that cannot be indefinitely ignored. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   MD-BOOTCAMP-CLOSING (Baltimore) _ In the face of a looming
scandal, Maryland shut down its once ballyhooed boot-camp regimen
for juvenile offenders last week, providing further evidence of
grave second thoughts across the nation about the ``get tough''
camps avidly favored by politicians during the last decade. By
Francis X. Clines.
</P>
<P>
   HOMELESS-PROFILE (San Francisco) _ Every morning when Kathleen
Gray leaves for work, she worries that her van will be gone when
she gets back. And then where will she be? The van is her home. How
Ms. Gray ended up homeless is a complicated story. Such stories
usually are. But in one crucial respect, her case is like those of
many homeless people she meets: She got in a bind, and had no way
to get out of it. No money. No help. By Evelyn Nieves. (With
photo.)
</P>
<P>
   GLOBAL-WARMING _ Last month was the warmest November in 105
years of record-keeping in the contiguous 48 states, and the
fourth-warmest in the Northeast. The trend continued into December
in most of the country; as of Friday, the average temperature for
the month in New York, for example, was 5.7 degrees Fahrenheit
above normal. But that is almost the least of it. Federal
scientists reported last week that in the contiguous 48 states and
on other global land masses, 1999 is certain to join 1998 as one of
the two warmest years on record, continuing a long-term trend
toward a warmer climate. By William K. Stevens.
</P>
<P>
   MA-BIKEPATH-DISPUTE (Williamsburg, Mass.) _ A
two-and-a-half-mile abandoned rail corridor in this Connecticut
Valley hill town of 2,500 residents is at the center of a heated
dispute between champions of privacy and community. Opponents of a
bike path planned for the corridor where the New Haven &AMP;
Northampton Railroad once ran cast the debate as a property rights
issue. Supporters see narrow-minded self-interest blocking a
project that could preserve the environment, promote health and
help people connect.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; POLITICS &LR;  (Moving in ``p'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   BUSH-CAMPAIGN (Manchester, N.H.) _ A look at divisions within
the Bush campaign. By Richard L. Berke.
</P>
<P>
   CAMPAIGN-TV _ For politicians the close-up, one-on-one approach
(say a ``60 Minutes'' feature or a ``Meet the Press'' format) can
present a much different image than sound bites from speeches and
debates, and also reaches far more people. By Caryn James.
</P>
<P>
   POLITICAL-BRIEFS _ Short items on politics from around the
nation. By B. Drummond Ayres Jr.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WASHINGTON &LR;  (Moving in ``w'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   VA-HOSPITALS (Washington) _ A look at medical mistakes and
mishaps in the last two years at veterans hospitals around the
country. By Robert Pear.
</P>
<P>
   STARR-SUCCESSOR _ A few years ago, Robert W. Ray was one of
dozens of young federal prosecutors in New York who spent their
days trying to put drug dealers and organized crime figures in
prison. So when he replaced Kenneth Starr as independent counsel in
the investigation of President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton
in October, it represented a remarkable journey from relative
obscurity to sudden prominence and enormous power. By Benjamin
Weiser and Neil A. Lewis. (With photo.)
</P>
