Post-Intelligencer, States News Service and the New York Times
Regional Newspapers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 1135EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0071 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 11:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2654 &Cx1f; tta-z
u a BC-POET-BOOK-BATTLE-ART-     12-18 1040
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-POET-BOOK-BATTLE-ART-980(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN CROSSING LITERARY BRIDGE, POET RUNS INTO A ROADBLOCK 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.Y., Pa.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Nonsubscribers
can make individual purchase by calling 888-603-1036 or
888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By BRUCE WEBER    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ At the podium in a makeshift lecture hall at Brooklyn
College recently, Billy Collins was not exactly a commanding
figure. A balding 58-year-old with crows' feet around the eyes, he
looked like the college professor he is, a little weary after
almost 30 years of teaching English at Lehman College in the Bronx.
It was hard to imagine him holding the attention of the 150 high
school students, squirming a bit as they waited to hear him read
his poems.
</P>
<P>
   But that is what happened. Reading in a voice that leavens
gravitas with a hint of mischief _ about a barking dog and
Beethoven or how and why the three blind mice became blind _
Collins had the students in his thrall for nearly an hour. It was
the kind of winning performance that has characterized his
appearances on National Public Radio and that has built a rare
bridge of admiration for his work between serious literary folk and
poetry novitiates.
</P>
<P>
   John Updike is a fan. So are the poets Edward Hirsch and Richard
Howard, and numerous other people as well. It can be argued that
with his books selling briskly and his readings packing them in,
Collins is the most popular poet in America.
</P>
<P>
   And now this very popularity has provoked one of the odder
publishing battles of recent memory, pitting a huge commercial
publisher against a small academic press over a literary poet. It
is an argument about money, with a distinct David-and-Goliath plot,
but it is also about publishing ethics and the right of an author
to determine the direction of his own career.
</P>
<P>
   This year, Random House, the trade publishing giant, signed
Collins to a six-figure contract for his next three books _ an
expression of confidence virtually unheard of in commercial
publishing for a serious poet. The first of the three books, a
collection of new and selected poems called ``Sailing Alone Around
the Room,'' was, until this month, set for publication in February.
Bound galleys have already been printed.
</P>
<P>
   The problem is that the University of Pittsburgh Press, the
publisher of Collins' previous three books, has denied Random House
permission to reprint the 61 older poems that have been requested
for the new volume.
</P>
<P>
   The reason, said Cynthia Miller, director of the Pittsburgh
Press, is that Collins' books are moneymakers, a relatively rare
occurrence for any academic press that like Pittsburgh is a
nonprofit arm of a university. The press publishes 45 to 50 titles
a year, mostly of scholarly and regional interest (and seven books
of poems), earning revenues of about $1.5 million.
</P>
<P>
   Its three books by Collins _ ``The Art of Drowning'' (1995),
``Picnic, Lightning'' (1998) and ``Questions About Angels,'' a 1991
book from William Morrow that Pittsburgh reprinted last year, have
sold more than 50,000 copies. Ms. Miller said she thought the
Random House collection would include too many poems too soon after
their publication and would diminish Pittsburgh's sales. Citing her
financial obligation to the university, she said that allowing
Random House to proceed would be irresponsible.
</P>
<P>
   ``Putting those sales at risk would be quite wrenching for us,''
she said, after informing Random House last week that the
negotiations were closed. ``We certainly value Billy's work, but
publishing is a collaborative effort. We put a lot of time and
effort into making our books successful, and I don't think it's
unreasonable to get some kind of return on that investment.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins and Random House dispute the contention that the new
book would threaten sales of the old ones; to the contrary, they
say that all of Collins' books would benefit from the marketing
muscle of a large commercial publisher.
</P>
<P>
   Still, to address Ms. Miller's concerns, Collins has offered to
take a reduced royalty if the sales of his Pittsburgh books dip,
and Random House was willing to include the Pittsburgh titles in
its advertising. Random House has offered between $20,000 and
$40,000 for the rights. No one will confirm the exact figure, but,
said Chris Calhoun, Collins' agent, it is still a pittance compared
with the sum Ms. Miller has proposed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pittsburgh asked for a price that was more than double the
advance for Billy's entire three-book deal,'' Calhoun said. ``And
two complimentary review copies.''
</P>
<P>
   By comparison, the University of Arkansas Press, which published
Collins' first book, ``The Apple That Astonished Paris,'' in 1988,
contributed 15 poems to the Random House collection for $751.50.
</P>
<P>
   It is not an infrequent occurrence that an author from an
academic press will attract the interest of a trade publisher. When
that happens, several publishing executives said, it is more or
less expected that the academic presses will make the best deal
they can but not unduly stand in the way of an author's success _
and wishes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here at Random House this is an anomalous hurdle,
unprecedented for poetry,'' said Mary Barr, the associate publisher
of the Random House imprint. ``It would have been beyond prophetic
for us to predict that Pittsburgh would be this obstinate.''
</P>
<P>
   Collins does not stand to lose his contract. Random House will
publish his three next books, and one of them is likely to be a
``new and selected'' volume, said his editor, Daniel Menaker.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Miller said that down the line, Pittsburgh would be more
likely to relent because its own books would be older and a
collection could draw on more books. But the already completed book
now seems likely to be canceled, an affront to Collins, who says he
feels he has already earned what is generally considered the
special honor of having a ``new and selected'' volume published.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's a sense of timeliness in terms of my own career,'' he
said. ``I have four books to draw on, I'm a poet of a certain age
and a `new and selected' is a kind of milestone.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   An unprepossessing but droll man, a lover of jazz and good
whiskey in the manner of a 1950s-style hip intellectual, Collins
lives in Westchester County with his wife, Diane, an architect. The
son of an electrician from Lowell, Mass., he was born in 1941 in a
small New York hospital, where, he likes to say, William Carlos
Williams worked as a pediatrician.
</P>
<P>
   He went to parochial schools and Holy Cross College, then earned
a doctorate in romantic poetry at the University of California at
Riverside. For many years, writing was a sidelight in a teaching
career that began ``with this idea I had of myself as a
scholar/gypsy, teaching at Caribbean College and the University of
South Hawaii,'' he said. But he settled in at Lehman in the early
1970s.
</P>
<P>
   His poems appeared first in obscure journals like Flying Faucet
Review, and Oink, names he loves to recite (``especially Oink,'' he
said). Later he was published in university publications.
</P>
<P>
   Two years after his first book was published by the University
of Arkansas, his manuscript ``Questions About Angels'' was selected
by the poet Edward Hirsch as a winner of the annual National Poetry
Series competition. It was published by Morrow. That began
establishing his literary reputation.
</P>
<P>
   ``He has a remarkably American voice,'' said Richard Howard, a
translator, poetry editor and poet, ``that one recognizes
immediately as being of the moment and yet has real validity
besides, reaching very far into what verse can do''
</P>
<P>
   It was after ``Questions About Angels'' that the University of
Pittsburgh Press approached him. ``And I went with them for two
reasons,'' Collins said. ``First, the Pitt Poetry Series is well
known, with a real litany of first-rate authors. And second because
they have a reputation for always keeping books in print as long as
they are selling.''
</P>
<P>
   The crucial moment for Collins came in early 1997. Pittsburgh
brought out ``Picnic, Lightning'' in January, and within a few
weeks, Garrison Keillor, who had read several of Collins' poems
during the ``Writer's Almanac'' feature on National Public Radio,
invited him to appear on his show, ``A Prairie Home Companion.''
Shortly after that, Collins was interviewed by Terry Gross, the
host of the NPR show ``Fresh Air.''
</P>
<P>
   His book sales spiked sharply; since then, requests from schools
and colleges for his readings have multiplied.
</P>
<P>
   Of Collins' four books, three are among the 16 top-selling
poetry titles at the online bookseller Amazon.com, wedged among
those by writers like E.E. Cummings, Robert Frost and Walt Whitman
(not to mention Jewel and Jim Morrison).
</P>
<P>
   ``As I'm writing, I'm always reader conscious,'' Collins said,
explaining the quick connection to his work experienced by many
readers encountering him for the first time. ``I have one reader in
mind, someone who is in the room with me, and who I'm talking to,
and I want to make sure I don't talk too fast, or too glibly.
Usually I try to create a hospitable tone at the beginning of a
poem. Stepping from the title to the first lines is like stepping
into a canoe. A lot of things can go wrong.''
</P>
<P>
   Asked if there was a theme to his work, he continued: ``I think
my work has to do with a sense that we are attempting, all the
time, to create a logical, rational path through the day. To the
left and right there are an amazing set of distractions that we
usually can't afford to follow. But the poet is willing to stop
anywhere. The ur-poem for this is Frost's `Stopping by Woods on a
Snowy Evening.' There's no reason to stop there; the horse knows
that. But the human is willing to stop for some reason that is
beyond the comprehension of the horse. And it's that willingness to
slow down and examine the mysterious bits of fluff in our lives
that is the poet's interest.''
</P>
<P>
   The strategy was on display at his recent Brooklyn College
reading, from the very first poem, ``Another Reason Why I Don't
Keep a Gun in the House.''
</P>
<P>
   Narrated in the first person, it is about a neighbor's
incessantly barking dog. For two stanzas it is literal and
descriptive, about how annoying the barking is, how the narrator
puts on a Beethoven symphony full blast to shut it out.
</P>
<P>
   ... but I can still hear him muffled under the music
</P>
<P>
   barking, barking, barking.
</P>
<P>
   Then comes the crucial moment, as the poem takes a fanciful leap
that turns its tone toward a gently rueful anxiety.
</P>
<P>
   ... and now I see him sitting in the orchestra,
</P>
<P>
   his head raised confidently as if Beethoven
</P>
<P>
   had included a part for barking dog.
</P>
<P>
   The effect on the students was palpable: a perking of the ears
at the invention, a straightening of the posture as the image
resonated, appreciative laughs as though they had been surprised by
an unexpected invitation.
</P>
<P>
   ``Man, those were the funniest poems I ever heard,'' one
17-year-old said to the poet afterward. To which Collins, alert to
the context of the compliment, replied: ``Oh yeah? How many
readings have you been to?''
</P>
<P>
   The boy smiled. ``I don't know,'' he said. ``Two?''
</P>
<P>
   The new book from Random House, Collins said, would be an
opportunity to reach readers more efficiently.
</P>
<P>
   ``There's so much hand-wringing from cultural quarters about the
sad size of the audience for poetry,'' he said. ``But here I am,
writing poetry that is getting out there, and we've reached this
impediment. It's really frustrating. I'd like to forget all about
rights and permissions and royalties and get back to writing
poems.''
</P>
</TEXT>
