<HEADLINE>
SOUTH KOREANS FRUSTRATED BY POLITICAL SQUABBLING 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By CALVIN SIMS    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEOUL, South Korea _ Frustrated by months of mudslinging,
corruption scandals and legislative gridlock, South Koreans are
demanding an end to the rivalry between the governing and
opposition parties that has mired the political system for nearly a
year.
</P>
<P>
   Not long ago, traffic on the Sogang Bridge, a major transit link
here, ground to a standstill as motorists watched an unidentified
man scale the main supports and unfurl a banner that called for
reforming political system.
</P>
<P>
   A few weeks earlier on a street corner, a group set up an ice
sculpture that depicted the National Assembly Building and offered
mallets to passers-by who readily smashed the ice to protest the
frozen state of relations in the legislature.
</P>
<P>
   ``This has got to be the most vicious political fighting that
I've ever seen,'' Moon Jung-in, a professor of political science at
Yonsei University, said of the governmental gridlock. ``The worst
part is that there seems to be no compromising, no politics of
negotiation. Our current politicians have turned the possible into
impossible.''
</P>
<P>
   At the center of the crisis is a no-holds-barred battle between
President Kim Dae-jung's party, the National Congress for New
Politics, and the Grand National Party, the main opposition, for
votes in a parliamentary election scheduled for April.
</P>
<P>
   Few Koreans would argue that either party has behaved properly.
Each has hurled accusations against the other, followed by libel
charges and countercharges. In the last month, the rival parties
have filed eight defamation suits against each other.
</P>
<P>
   Among the most tantalizing scandals was the so-called furgate
affair, in which prosecutors have accused the wife of an insurance
tycoon of having tried to influence government policy by giving fur
coats and other expensive clothes to the wives of top officials.
</P>
<P>
   A former justice minister, Kim Young-jae, was arrested recently
and charged with illegally altering a secret government report on
his wife's involvement in the scandal. The opposition has contended
that a cover-up goes all the way to the president's office.
</P>
<P>
   ``At the beginning, the story was a simple corruption scandal,''
said Lee Shim-bom, an opposition legislator and frequent critic of
Kim. ``But now it's Watergate.''
</P>
<P>
   With all the fury, the legislative session has been deadlocked,
and decisions on important bills on the national budget, political
reform and other issues have been delayed. But the assembly
steering committee managed to pass a bill that raises assembly
members' salaries 14.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   ``Interparty squabbles have been going on for some time in
Korea, but today's verbal battles are so fierce that they are
keeping the legislature from passing important reforms,'' said Kim
Mi-young, a staff member of the Citizens' Legislative Committee, a
watchdog group. ``The legislators don't seem to have the ability to
put the public interest above their own selfish aspirations.''
</P>
<P>
   A central figure in the jousting has been Chung Hyung-keun, an
assemblyman from the Grand National Party who is widely viewed here
as having made unfounded statements for political gains. At an
outdoor rally, Chung set off a furor when he accused the president
of using Communist guerrilla-style tactics in dealing with
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   The governing party has accused Chung, a former senior officer
for the National Security Planning Agency, of operating, from his
office, a private intelligence team that consists of former
colleagues. At an assembly session in November, Chung released a
report that accused the government of trying to censor newspapers
critical of the administration.
</P>
<P>
   In an interview, Chung denied using former intelligence agents
to investigate officials from the governing party. He said he had
acquired much information on corruption from disgruntled employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``I believe that the recent scandals reveal the true face of the
Kim Dae-jung administration, which had been covered under a veil
until now,'' Chung said. ``Today in Korea, it's very difficult to
differentiate between the true proponents of human rights and
democracy and those leftists who have covered themselves under a
mask.''
</P>
<P>
   Political analysts said that scandals uncovered by the
opposition in recent months had damaged Kim's credibility and that
his coalition government could lose its majority in the assembly in
April. The president has publicly said he wants the corruption
allegations to be fully investigated.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Korean people had a lot of expectations when President
Kim's `people's government' was launched two years ago,'' Kim of
the watchdog group said. ``But in reality the promises that the
president made have failed to materialize, and this has led to a
lot of disappointment.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
