<SLUG> BC-TEENS-DRUGS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DRUG USE AMONG ADOLESCENTS LARGELY UNCHANGED IN 1999 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By CHRISTOPHER S. WREN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   After receding modestly for two years, the use of marijuana and
other illicit drugs by American adolescents remained largely
unchanged in 1999, according to the latest findings in an annual
national study that is the leading barometer of teen-age substance
abuse.
</P>
<P>
   The White House director of national drug policy, Gen. Barry R.
McCaffrey, said the study was encouraging because its findings
confirmed that a resurgence in drug use since 1992 had been
reversed.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is now the third year in a row where a well-focused
education campaign has moved youth attitudes and behavior,''
McCaffrey said on Friday at a news conference in Washington, where
the results of the study were announced. ``We now appear to have a
trend line where the period of increased drug use is over.''
</P>
<P>
   The study, he noted, is the first to be conducted since the
government began its $195 million media campaign earlier this year
to discourage young Americans from experimenting with illicit
drugs.
</P>
<P>
   The only significant increase involved Ecstasy, a synthetic drug
with a niche at nightclubs and dance parties. Eight percent of the
high school seniors surveyed said they had tried the drug, compared
with 5.8 percent last year.
</P>
<P>
   McCaffrey expressed alarm at the use of steroids by teen-age
boys, which rose to 2.8 percent of sophomores, from 1.9 percent
last year, and to 2.5 percent of eighth-graders, from 1.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   The study drew upon confidential questionnaires that 45,000
students from around the country filled out earlier this year.
Lloyd D. Johnston, who conducts the annual study at the University
of Michigan's Institute for Social Research, analyzed the responses
with his colleagues, Jerald G. Bachman and Patrick M. O'Malley.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 14,100 high school seniors polled, 54.7 percent
reported having tried an illicit drug, which was slightly more than
the 54.1 percent in 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Among the 17,300 eighth-graders asked, 28.3 percent said they
experimented with an illicit drug, a decline from 29 percent last
year. The drop in drug use reported by eighth-graders is considered
a potential indicator that drugs may be losing their attraction for
the newest group of teen-agers.
</P>
<P>
   Marijuana remained the drug primarily used by adolescents. Among
high school seniors polled, 49.7 percent said they had tried
smoking marijuana, while 40.9 percent of sophomores and 22 percent
of eighth-graders said they had done so.
</P>
<P>
   In a more precise indicator of current use, 25.9 percent of
seniors surveyed said they had smoked marijuana in the last 30
days, an increase of three-tenths of 1 percent from last year.
Monthly marijuana use among eighth-graders remained unchanged, at
9.7. percent.
</P>
<P>
   Alcohol remained far more popular among adolescents, with 62.3
percent of seniors, 48.9 percent of sophomores and 24.8 percent of
eighth-graders reporting that they had been drunk at least once.
</P>
<P>
   Binge drinking, defined as consuming five alcoholic drinks in a
row, was a particular problem. Thirty-one percent of the seniors,
26 percent of the sophomores and 15 percent of the eighth-graders
sampled said they had been binge-drinking within the previous two
weeks.
</P>
<P>
   While this reflected a slight rise among sophomores and
eighth-graders, the prevalence of binge drinking has remained
fairly constant since 1996.
</P>
<P>
   Experimentation with cocaine rose slightly, to 9.8 percent of
seniors from 9.3 percent last year, and for sophomores, to 7.7
percent from 7.2 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Heroin use remained flat for the third consecutive year, with
2.3 percent of sophomores and eighth-graders but only 2 percent of
seniors saying they had tried heroin.
</P>
<P>
   The use of inhalants continued a decline that started in 1996.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
