<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-GORE-CAMPAIGN-(TRIM)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GORE PUSHES BRADLEY BACK IN THE NEW YORK RACE 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
(See also BUSH-CAMPAIGN) 
 By KATHARINE Q. SEELYE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ He pronounces Israel as ``Iz-rul,'' and plays a bit
of the country rube.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just shakin' hands with ya and talkin' briefly to each one of
ya reminded me of what a diverse group this is, what a powerful
group this is.''
</P>
<P>
   Al Gore is mixing it up, in his own way, on the Upper East Side.
He is talking to about 75 people who are forking over $1,000 each
for his presidential campaign. They are all crammed into the living
room of John and Margo Catsimatidis, the Red Apple supermarket
chain family and a force in the Greek-American community.
</P>
<P>
   The aw-shucks foot-shuffling and grand generalities help Gore
avoid the kind of specifics that have landed Hillary Rodham Clinton
in such hot water locally. And his charm offensive is helping him
smooth over some of the campaign's rough edges.
</P>
<P>
   As a result, Gore has pulled off a minor New York miracle. He
has united virtually all of the state's Democratic establishment
behind him, with the notable exceptions of Sen &UR; . &LR;  Daniel Patrick
Moynihan and Rep &UR; . &LR;  Jerry Nadler of Manhattan. And after months of
being clobbered in the polls here by former Sen &UR; . &LR;  Bill Bradley of
New Jersey, Gore has pulled statistically even with him. The latest
poll, conducted by Quinnipiac College and released last week, put
Gore at 42 percent and Bradley at 39 percent. This reversed the
findings in November, which had Bradley at 47 percent and Gore at
38.
</P>
<P>
   New York, where he was swamped in 1988 by fierce ethnic
rivalries and lost a searing primary that shredded his presidential
aspirations, still seems to have the vice president a little off
balance. This time, as he seeks the Democratic presidential
nomination, his approach is diffident. He reverts mentally to the
hog-slopping days of his Tennessee summers.
</P>
<P>
   While he takes on local issues elsewhere _ he has faced down
angry Microsoft employees in Seattle with his support for antitrust
laws _ here in New York he tends to offer platitudes and avoid
specifics. He is content to extol the virtues of the shining lamp
that America lifts to immigrants.
</P>
<P>
   Gore has carefully sidestepped some of the pitfalls that Mrs.
Clinton, who is running for the Senate, has plunged into. He has
refused to say what he thinks of President Clinton's grant of
clemency to a group of Puerto Rican nationalists, even though a
White House memo suggested that the clemency could help Gore with
Hispanic voters.
</P>
<P>
   A few days ago, at a fund-raiser at the Brooklyn home of Abe
Biderman, a former city official prominent in the Orthodox Jewish
community, Gore fudged a question about whether the president
should pardon Jonathan Pollard, the Israeli spy, whom Israel wants
to serve out his time in Israel. Gore also skirted a question about
moving the U.S. Embassy now in Tel Aviv to Jerusalem. (He did,
however, express his opposition to school vouchers, a position he
is advertising in a commercial in New Hampshire and one that would
have been hard to duck.)
</P>
<P>
   Andrew Cuomo, the secretary of housing and urban development and
one of Gore's closest advisers, as well as the son of the former
New York governor, Mario Cuomo, beams when discussing Gore's ginger
steps. ``Better you tiptoe through the tulips now than you step on
a land mine,'' Cuomo said.
</P>
<P>
   But, he added, Gore knows that soon enough he will have to
become more specific on matters like the homeless, immigration and
various ethnic policies that are not priorities in the early voting
states of Iowa and New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   Until recently, Gore's New York campaign was widely acknowledged
to be disorganized and inept, with too many power brokers fighting
for a piece of the action. He was openly criticized by the likes of
Rep. Charles Rangel of Manhattan, who supports him, for failing the
basics of New York Politics 101 _ touching bases and assuaging the
egos.
</P>
<P>
   Gore was also hurt by the terrain. New York is Bill Bradley's
home court and, along with New Hampshire, represents one of
Bradley's best states. Bradley is relying on decades of exposure as
a star player for the New York Knicks and as a senator from
neighboring New Jersey to ignite support from New York voters. He
has delivered policy speeches here, and he staged his splashiest
fund-raising event of the season at Madison Square Garden.
</P>
<P>
   But recently, Gore upended his national campaign and became a
more aggressive candidate, pointedly deconstructing Bradley's
health care and budget plans as budget busters that would undermine
the nation's Medicare and Medicaid systems and force a tax
increase.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   Some Bradley supporters, like Nadler, think the numbers have
flipped because Bradley has appeared lax in responding to Gore.
Nadler says Bradley needs to be more aggressive, even at the risk
of undermining his above-the-fray image. ``Bradley has answered the
attacks factually, but not politically,'' Nadler said.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Nadler says that the reason he supported Bradley over
Gore in the first place remains valid _ that Bradley has a better
chance than Gore of capturing New York against a Republican next
fall. And the polls that match each of the two Democrats against
George W. Bush bear him out.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, for the first time, the campaign was holding
simultaneous rallies in eight cities across the state to spur
volunteers to help Gore qualify in all of the state's 31
congressional districts.
</P>
<P>
   Leading the pep talks were Karenna Gore Schiff, the candidate's
daughter, in Syracuse; Robert F. Kennedy Jr., an environmental
lawyer and son of the late senator, in Rochester, and Rangel in
Harlem.
</P>
<P>
   Raising money in New York has not been the problem for Gore that
some predicted it might be with Mrs. Clinton also competing for New
York dollars. In fact, both he and Bradley have raised more money
from the Upper East Side _ specifically ZIP code 10021 _ than they
have anywhere else in the country.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   When his campaign hit the rocks earlier this year, Gore had been
coasting on a message aimed at suburban swing voters, bemoaning the
hassles confronting two-career couples and warning about suburban
sprawl. Now he is talking to the base of the Democratic Party,
sounding the alarm that Bradley would cut Medicaid, disregard
public education and raise taxes.
</P>
<P>
   ``Gore is de-emphasizing his suburban strategy,'' said Lee
Maringhoff, director of the Marist Institute for Public Opinion.
``What he needed to do was establish some Democratic party roots.
Now he's proposing federal intervention into education. It's a long
way from where he was six months ago.''
</P>
<P>
   This has not gone unnoticed in the Bradley campaign. ``Gore is
trying to do what organizational Democratic candidates do _ go hard
and singularly at the traditional Democratic constituency,'' said
Michael J. Del Giudice, a co-chairman of Bradley's New York
campaign.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 1238EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0084 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 12:46 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2679 &Cx1f; taf-z
u w BC-STARR-SUCCESSOR-ART-9     12-18 1038
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-STARR-SUCCESSOR-ART-970(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AGGRESSIVE PROSECUTOR ENTERS LIMELIGHT AS STARR'S SUCCESSOR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036 or (888)
346-9867.) 
(mk) 
 By BENJAMIN WEISER and NEIL A. LEWIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A few years ago, Robert Ray was one of dozens of young federal
prosecutors in New York who spent their days trying to put drug
dealers and organized crime figures in prison, with little apparent
prospect of a coveted change of assignment to one specializing in
white-collar crime.
</P>
<P>
   So when he replaced Kenneth Starr as independent counsel in the
investigation of President Clinton and Hillary Rodham Clinton in
October, it represented a remarkable journey from relative
obscurity to sudden prominence and enormous power.
</P>
<P>
   In his new role, Ray, a 39-year-old lawyer with no obvious
political predilections, will have the last say on whether either
of the Clintons should be indicted. In addition, he will be the
ultimate editor of the final report of the investigation, a
document that could have a profound effect on Mrs. Clinton's Senate
campaign in New York.
</P>
<P>
   Lawyers familiar with the operations of the Office of the
Independent Counsel said Ray was working against an undeclared but
firm deadline of Aug. 1 to make those and other major decisions.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike Starr, who had never been a prosecutor or tried a case,
Ray is a member of that distinct species in the law _ career
prosecutors, people steeped in a culture aimed at bringing down the
bad guys while valuing zeal tempered with discretion.
</P>
<P>
   In that role, Ray built a reputation in New York as an
aggressive prosecutor with an enviable rate of success. But he was
also on occasion scolded by federal judges who warned him that he
had come close to the line in his eagerness to put people in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   In 1992, for example, Ray and a colleague were admonished by
Judge Louis Freeh, now the director of the FBI, for their use of a
witness whose testimony was questionable. Another judge once
complained angrily that Ray had improperly tried to trick a witness
into giving information.
</P>
<P>
   But in his six-year tenure as a federal prosecutor, Ray also won
many admirers. In one complex heroin case, he was responsible for
the conviction of 48 defendants. The judge, Leonard Sand, recalled
that the case went smoothly under Ray. ``He was unflappable, no
histrionics,'' Sand said. ``From a professional standpoint, it was
a pleasure having him before me.''
</P>
<P>
   He came to Washington in 1996 to handle the trial work for
Donald Smaltz, the special prosecutor investigating Mike Espy,
Clinton's first agriculture secretary. There is wide agreement in
the legal world that the Espy case was a trouble-filled
prosecution. Espy was acquitted of all charges concerning
accusations that he accepted gifts from people in the industries he
was regulating, while some lesser figures were convicted. Defense
lawyers complained and a judge agreed that one of the cases was
wrongfully brought in California rather than in Washington, simply
to avoid a mostly black jury.
</P>
<P>
   Ray's role in those matters remains unclear. ``I respect Bob
Ray,'' said Elliot Peters, a former federal prosecutor in New York
who represented one of the defendants in the Espy investigation.
``But the Smaltz thing was a very ugly and unproductive exercise
and cannot be a positive in his resume. I think it's a vehicle to
question his judgment.''
</P>
<P>
   William Jeffress Jr., who represented Archibald Schaffer, a
Tyson's Food executive who was convicted of a crime similar to the
one with which Espy was charged, complained that the prosecution
lacked even-handedness. ``The whole thing is topsy-turvy.
Prosecutors don't ordinarily proceed that way,'' Jeffress said.
</P>
<P>
   ``Prosecutors make judgments all the time,'' Ray said in
response. ``People are always saying, `Why are you picking on
me?''' He said the fact that Espy was acquitted and Schaffer
convicted is out of the hands of the prosecutor. ``Ultimately it's
up to the jury.''
</P>
<P>
   A judge recently granted Schaffer a new trial.
</P>
<P>
   Ray joined the U.S. attorney's office in February 1989 after
being offered the job by the U.S. attorney at the time, Rudolph
Giuliani, now the mayor of New York and a probable candidate for
the Senate against Mrs. Clinton. But Ray never worked under
Giuliani, who left the office before Ray reported for work.
</P>
<P>
   Some of Clinton's associates jumped on the nominal association
with Giuliani to question Ray's fitness for the job.
</P>
<P>
   ``The idea that I came to Washington with a mission to get the
Clintons is mistaken,'' Ray said in an interview, angrily
dismissing that speculation. ``It's just baloney.''
</P>
<P>
   Robert William Ray was born on April 4, 1960, in Frankfurt,
Germany, the son of a colonel in the Army. After graduating from
Princeton he went to Washington and Lee law school in Virginia. His
first job after working as a clerk for a federal judge in New York
was as an assistant U.S. attorney in New York.
</P>
<P>
   In an environment in which Ivy League-educated prosecutors are
thrown together with street cops and federal agents, Ray was
someone who was thoroughly comfortable in both worlds.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of those prosecutors can't relate to what's going on in
the street,'' said Joe Walsh, an FBI agent who worked with Ray on
several cases. ``But Bob was raised the right way. He's our kind of
guy.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, few expected that he would follow in the job held by such
legal heavyweights as Starr and Robert Fiske Jr., a former U.S.
attorney in Manhattan who was the first Whitewater prosecutor.
</P>
<P>
   ``Bob was a solid assistant,'' said Paul Shechtman, chief of the
criminal division of the U.S. attorney's office from 1993 through
1995 when Ray was there, ``but I'm not sure one would have guessed
that we'd start with Bob Fiske and end with Bob Ray.''
</P>
<P>
   Ray accepts his former colleagues' surprise gracefully. He said:
``A lot of life is about being at the right place at the right
time. Some would question whether or not this is the place one
would want to be.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In six years as an assistant U.S. attorney, prosecuting hundreds
of defendants, Ray went to trial dozens of times. One of his
biggest cases was ``Operation Horse Collar,'' a 2 1/2-year wiretap
investigation in which 48 people were charged with narcotics
trafficking in the Bronx and Westchester County.
</P>
<P>
   Gerard Lynch, chief of the criminal division in 1990 and 1991,
said that Ray managed a crushing amount of paperwork and technical
details even before the trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``Here was this relatively junior guy and doing this kind of
monumental thing,'' said Lynch, now a law professor at Columbia
University.
</P>
<P>
   In another major case, Ray oversaw the investigation of a gang
called the 142nd Street Lynchmob, in which 10 members were indicted
in 15 murders, a string of armed robberies and a
multimillion-dollar narcotics ring on the East Coast.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes Ray's approach got him into trouble, a review of court
records shows. In a 1992 cocaine-trafficking case, a defense lawyer
accused Ray of crossing the line by springing a surprise question
on a defendant who had been called in to provide a tape recording
of her voice, so that it could be compared to others heard on
wiretaps.
</P>
<P>
   After Ray asked her to repeat a few innocuous phrases onto the
tape, he asked her whether she knew another defendant in the case.
</P>
<P>
   She had answered yes, and her lawyer later complained that the
statement, which could tie her to the crime, was improperly
elicited and should not be used against her.
</P>
<P>
   Judge Kevin Duffy agreed. ``What the blazes were you playing
games like that for?'' he asked as he disallowed the statement.
``That stinks.''
</P>
<P>
   The difficult moment before Freeh occurred in a 1992 narcotics
trial when one of Ray's witnesses had testified that she had
recognized a voice on a wiretapped phone call as that of a certain
defendant conducting a crack cocaine sale, then later told him and
a co-prosecutor that she was mistaken.
</P>
<P>
   Ray did not raise the problem with the court until the next
morning, leading to defense charges that he had allowed the jury to
go home that night believing the tainted testimony was true.
</P>
<P>
   After questioning Ray and his colleague, the judge blamed
``absolutely poor and inadequate preparation by the government''
for the matter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't find that Ray intentionally or willfully misled the
court,'' Freeh said, adding that Ray should have raised the problem
as soon as he learned of it. The judge repeated his criticism of
``incredibly poor preparation'' by the government.
</P>
<P>
   Ray said he was willing to take ``fair responsibility'' for his
decision. ``You live and learn,'' he said. ``In retrospect and with
the benefit of hindsight,'' he said, ``maybe the better course
would have been simply to say, `Look judge, we may have a problem
here.'''
</P>
<P>
   But in another case, Ray was praised for revealing that a
government witness had lied in a trial. ``Indeed, the candid and
forthright disclosures of the assistant U.S. attorney followed the
highest traditions of that office,'' wrote Judge Robert Patterson.
</P>
<P>
   While a prosecutor, Ray ran unsuccessfully in nonpartisan races
for a local school board from Brooklyn, in 1993 and 1996, after
obtaining permission from his office.
</P>
<P>
   The first race took place during a raging debate in New York
over the ``rainbow curriculum'' and the teaching about gays to
children in elementary school.
</P>
<P>
   Election board records in New York show that Ray was part of a
group of candidates who called themselves ``the children's slate,''
and who fiercely opposed the ``rainbow curriculum.''
</P>
<P>
   He wrote to a Brooklyn newspaper that while gays had the right
to press their demands in the political arena, they had ``no right
to use first-graders as a vehicle for acceptance of a lifestyle
that was objectionable to many parents.''
</P>
<P>
   ``This does not mean that anyone is seriously interested in
bringing God back into the public classroom or that a rigid code of
behavior is being advocated,'' he added. ``Indeed, a public school
is fundamentally about tolerance and acceptance of all.''
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, he told friends that he was seeking an opportunity to
leave the U.S. attorney's office. He was worried that he would
remain in the drug and organized crime unit for years, unable to
move to another specialty and grow.
</P>
<P>
   He decided, he recalled, that he needed some experience with
white-collar crime ``to round me out as a prosecutor.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said that he had never expected to be in Washington for
so long. His family still lives in Rumson, N.J., meaning that he
has established a routine in which he leaves his home before 6 a.m.
each Monday to preside over the office's 9 a.m. weekly meeting.
During the week he stays with his parents and sleeps in his boyhood
bedroom at their suburban Virginia home before heading back to New
Jersey late on Friday night.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
