<TEXT>
<P>
   The Los Angeles Daily News plans to move the following general
stories for use by NYTimes News Service clients, AMs and PMs of
Dec. 19 and thereafter. For questions about stories, contact the
Daily News, (818) 713-3705.
</P>
<P>
   SOLSTICE-MOON (Los Angeles) _ In a rare confluence of celestial
events. the last full Moon of the millennium Tuesday night also be
will be the brighest since 1930 and overlap with the shortest day
of the year, the winter solstice. Between sundown Tuesday and dawn
Wednesday, tides will be exceptionally high and low, the Moon will
be bright enough to cast shadows at night and police and mystics
expect people to witness the tie between lunar and loonacy. ``Those
lunar tide pulls seem to enhance the inclination of people to break
the law,'' said Los Angeles police Sgt. Lisa Phillips. By Robert
Monroe (Will move on the ``n'' California and ``a'' national news
wires.)
</P>
<P>
   RIORDAN-BESTYEAR (Los Angeles) _ By all accounts, 1999 was the
most successful political year for Mayor Richard Riordan as he
pushed through a new majority on the Los Angeles Board of Education
and a new City Charter while the economy continued to imrpove and
crime continued to drop. Yet, in an example of unintended
consequences, the mayor also has continued to fuel the seeds of
discontent because of rising expections with new calls for a
breakup of the Los Angeles Unified School District and widening
discontent with how the city of Los Angeles operates. Riordan
discusses this and his plans for 2000. By Rick Orlov (Will move on
the ``n'' California and ``a'' national news wires.)
</P>
<P>
   EVICT-COUPLE (Palmdale, Calif.) -- On the day before
Thanksgiving, Glen and Norma Jean Rambo were ordered by a sheriff's
deputy out of the house her father had bought 35 years before. The
elderly couple, beset by medical bills, had fallen behind on
mortgage payments. They spent two weeks living in a motel. But now
they are back at home, thanks to a local investment company that
bought the house and is renting it to the couple for less than
their mortgage payments. By By John Sanders (Will move on the ``n''
California and ``a'' national news wires.)
</P>
