<HEADER>
A2683 &Cx1f; ttc-z
r a BC-RIORDAN-BESTYEAR-LADN     12-18 0982
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RIORDAN-BESTYEAR-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
L.A. MAYOR COUNTS 1999 AS HIS BEST
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By Rick Orlov  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES -- By his own account, Los Angeles Mayor Richard
Riordan sees 1999 as the most politically successful and personally
satisfying year he has spent in office since being elected six
years ago.
</P>
<P>
   And most of it had nothing to do with City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   ``We did God's work,'' Riordan said. ``By far the most important
thing I've ever done in my life is changing the Board of Education
and the culture of the Los Angeles Unified School District.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is the future of society, of our city. It will turn young
people from a life of crime to one with a future.''
</P>
<P>
   As he has done in the past, Riordan worked around the political
establishment by going directly to voters to change the school
district.
</P>
<P>
   It was Riordan who recruited candidates to challenge three
incumbent members of the Board of Education and then he used his
own personal wealth and that of friends to finance a $2 million
campaign to see those seats won.
</P>
<P>
   While the school district has been in near-constant turmoil
since then, Riordan professes it is an uncomfortable byproduct of
the revolution that was needed and will ease once a new
superintendent is in place permanently.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have a different board there and a different mentality,''
Riordan said. ``You have people who believe in reform, a strong
board that will hopefully pick a strong superintendent.''
</P>
<P>
   It was far from his only political success this year.
</P>
<P>
   Riordan also helped finance the campaign for passage of a new
City Charter that expands the power of the mayor, and the election
of two new City Council members _ Alex Padilla and Nick Pacheco _
whom he had backed.
</P>
<P>
   Relations with the City Council also were smoother this past
year than in other years as his $4 billion budget sailed through
with only token opposition, although some members attributed that
to the mayor's involvement with the school board and charter
reform.
</P>
<P>
   ``To be polite, I'd have to say he's been disengaged with most
of the city matters,'' said one council member, who asked not to be
identified. ``You don't see him or his people down here like they
used to be, lobbying the council for something. He and his office
just don't seem that involved with the day-to-day running of the
city.''
</P>
<P>
   As might be expected, the mayor rejects that notion.
</P>
<P>
   ``This city is running much better,'' Riordan said. ``We
generally have good strong general managers and I much prefer to be
in a position of macro-managing as opposed to micro-managing.''
</P>
<P>
   Riordan has benefited from the improving local economy and the
steady drop in crime across the city, even as the Los Angeles
Police Department faced difficulties in the hiring of officers and
civilians.
</P>
<P>
   At the same time, the administration has been hampered by the
ongoing corruption scandal at the LAPD's Rampart Division and the
growing secession movement across the city, most recently fueled by
the decision to reopen the Sunshine Canyon Landfill.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Rampart situation started a long time ago and we are doing
all we can to resolve it,'' Riordan said. ``We have a police chief
who will not tolerate this sort of thing. What people forget is it
was the department that found this out and is investigating it.''
</P>
<P>
   As for the secession drives, Riordan acknowledged they are
partly an unintended consequence that he himself might have fueled
with higher expectations from the city and his campaigns against
the city institutions.
</P>
<P>
   ``In some ways, that is true,'' Riordan said. ``Once you see you
can solve some problems, you expect more problems to be solved.
People are looking at that. They know things can get done by having
more involvement.''
</P>
<P>
   One aspect of the new charter which Riordan did not favor was
the concept of advisory neighborhood councils.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if they work on quality-of-life issues and interact with
departments, it could head off some of that,'' Riordan said. ``If
they spend all their time on land-use issues, they won't be
effective.''
</P>
<P>
   What concerns Riordan and other city officials is what the
neighborhood councils would do on issues such as the Sunshine
Canyon Landfill by joining forces to become a political force and
take power from City Hall.
</P>
<P>
   To outside observers, Riordan had an up-and-down year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think you'd have to say it was a roller-coaster kind of year
and the jury is still out on what happens with all the changes he's
forced,'' Democratic consultant Richard Lichtenstein said. ``Now
that you have a new school board and a new charter and a new
council, it could be five or 10 years before we know the full
impact of all these.
</P>
<P>
   ``What we say in 10 or 15 years will be far different from what
we're saying now. Change does not come overnight.''
</P>
<P>
   Political analyst Sherry Bebitch Jeffe said that the mayor might
be in the position of regretting what he wished for.
</P>
<P>
   ``He said he wanted reform and he's getting it, and you could
say the secession movement is also a reform,'' Jeffe said. ``No one
really knows the depth of the anger and if it will last.''
</P>
<P>
   What concerns her, however, is the low profile the mayor has
taken after instituting change.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was this whole debate over whether or not to keep
(Ruben) Zacarias as superintendent and you barely heard a peep from
the mayor,'' Jeffe said. ``It's like he started this change and
disappeared.''
</P>
<P>
   Riordan shrugs off the criticism and insists he has remained
involved and continues to look forward in his job.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things I'm proudest of is what we are doing on the
quality of life and improving neighborhoods,'' Riordan said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think, if the city continues as it has, there will be a
strong middle class in every part of the city.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
