<SLUG> BC-EVICT-COUPLE-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
FINANCE COMPANY RESCUES EVICTED COUPLE
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By John Sanders  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   PALMDALE, Calif. -- Glen and Norma Jean Rambo didn't think
things could get any worse after they learned their house was in
foreclosure.
</P>
<P>
   That is, until Norma Jean suffered a stroke the day the Rambos
were ordered out of the house.
</P>
<P>
   But over the past month things have begun to look much brighter
for the couple.
</P>
<P>
   Norma Jean, 62, is recuperating and the couple is back in the
house where they have lived the past 10 years, thanks to a real
estate company, the Leona Valley-based Fernwood Group, that bought
their home from the mortgage company and allowed them stay at a
lower rent than their mortgage payments.
</P>
<P>
   ``The only thing that kept me going was my Bible, trusting the
Lord,'' Norma Jean said. ``I kept reading Psalm 34 and Psalm 137
and 138, and Romans 8.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rambos moved into their house off 3rd Street East in
Palmdale, about 62 miles north of Los Angeles, about 10 years ago
so that they could take care of Norma Jean's father, who was will.
Her father passed away in 1994 and left them the house, which had
already been paid off.
</P>
<P>
   But the Rambos soon found out that Norma Jean's father owed
money for taxes and bills. They were forced to take out a second
mortgage worth about $33,000 to help pay the debt.
</P>
<P>
   But then Norma Jean was hospitalized with a broken hip and they
got behind in their payments, then $518 a month.
</P>
<P>
   The week before Thanksgiving, they were evicted.
</P>
<P>
   Glen, a retired builder, contacted Palmdale officials, who
directed him to South Antelope Valley Emergency Services, a food
bank that also helps people find shelter during the winter.
</P>
<P>
   The couple packed up some belongings and moved into the Heritage
Hotel on Palmdale Boulevard, leaving behind their furniture and
three cats at the house.
</P>
<P>
   That night, Norma Jean suffered a stroke and went to a hospital.
Glen spent the first couple of nights alternating between the hotel
and the hospital visiting his wife. He was allowed back at the
house only to feed the couple's cats.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even though we're thankful for that room over there, that's
not like home,'' Glen said. ``Without that (room) I don't know what
we would have done because we has nowhere to go.''
</P>
<P>
   The Rambos spent a total of 29 days in the Heritage Hotel.
</P>
<P>
   Before they were evicted, Glen had called Lloyd Cook, co-owner
with Alexis Upton-Knittle of the Fernwood Group, after picking up a
Fernwood Group business card advertising that the firm helps
homeowners in foreclosure.
</P>
<P>
   Actually, the house had been foreclosed on six days earlier,
Cook said.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked him what he wanted us to do,'' Cook said. ``He said,
`We just want to be able to stay in the house.' ''
</P>
<P>
   With the help of Suburban Realty owner Pete Dattilo, Cook and
Upton-Knittle spent three months negotiating with the mortgage
holder. Finally, a couple days after the Rambos were evicted, the
Fernwood Group's purchase offer was accepted. Cook said he tried to
do a 10-day escrow but it dragged into three weeks.
</P>
<P>
   The Rambos moved home Dec. 10 with an option to buy and rent at
$400 a month, less than their mortgage payment.
</P>
<P>
   ``One of the things we do is to help people in foreclosure,''
Cook said. ``Some investment companies are in it for the money. We
are too, but we have hearts. ... I think we all fell pretty good
about this.''
</P>
<P>
   Both Glen and Norma Jean are happy that everything worked out in
the end and both are happy be back in their home.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm so glad to be back home. It's such a blessing and a joy,''
Glen said.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's such a relief and my animals are so happy,'' Norma Jean
said. ``It was all the Lord.''
</P>
<P>
   X X X  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
