<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ELECT-ADS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE AD CAMPAIGN 
</HEADLINE>
  (With RUSSIA-ELECT) 
(js) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Russia's rough-and-tumble parliamentary election campaign has
been shaped by the major parties' aggressive television
advertising. Here are samples of ads broadcast in the campaign's
final days by three parties: the Union of Right Forces, a
Western-oriented free-market faction; the Communist Party; and
Fatherland-All Russia, a centrist anti-Kremlin party headed by
former Prime Minister Yevgeny Primakov and the mayor of Moscow,
Yuri Luzhkov.
</P>
<P>
   The Communist Party: Holding Fast to a Well-Worn Theme
</P>
<P>
   THE SCENE: A muscular worker's arm in a plaid shirt slams a hard
hat on a table atop a copy of a Communist newspaper. An arm attired
in a white shirt with gold cuff links and a Rolex watch follows,
depositing a mobile phone on the table. Sleeves rolled up, the two
begin to arm wrestle. As years flash on the screen _ 1991, 1993,
1995 _ the white-shirted arm slowly presses the worker's arm
downward. By 1997, the worker begins to come back, and the
white-shirted figure tries to overcome him with both hands. But as
1999 flashes by, the worker wins.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCRIPT: A Soviet war medal appears on the screen, and to the
sound of a war anthem, an announcer intones: ``For victory! The
Communist Party of the Russian Federation!''
</P>
<P>
   ANALYSIS: The class-warfare message has not changed in a
century.
</P>
<P>
   Union of Right Forces: A Call to Shake Up the Privileged Class
</P>
<P>
   THE SCRIPT: In a cartoon, two men working at a computer hear a
siren. They wheel about, saying ``What?'' ``Where?'' ``Look,
here!'' and see a huge cockroach crawling toward them, a flashing
blue light on its back.
</P>
<P>
   One man rolls a newspaper to swat the roach. The other whispers
nervously into his ear, ``You know what he is?'' The first man
hesitates, then shouts ``WHAM!'' and smashes the roach.
</P>
<P>
   The Union of the Right Forces emblem appears on the screen with
the slogan ``FOR ABROGATION OF DEPUTIES' IMMUNITY''
</P>
<P>
   ANALYSIS: To Muscovites' enduring irritation, legislators and
other privileged types tool about in black sedans with sirens and
blue lights, weaving through traffic and even driving the wrong way
down busy streets. The spot uses that image to stress the party's
message that it wants to shake up the privileged class, starting by
ending legislators' immunity from criminal prosecution.
</P>
<P>
   Fatherland-All Russia: In Unsettled Time, a Pledge of Stability &QL;
</P>
<P>
   THE SCENE: A man reads a newspaper, then turns to his computer.
</P>
<P>
   Images appear on the screen: a demonstration; a stock exchange;
new 100 ruble notes; angry crowds at a closed bank; protesting coal
miners; riot police officers. Finally, the party leader, Yevgeny
Primakov, is seen speaking to the parliament. The camera returns to
the man; the words I TRUST DEEDS and the party emblem appear on the
screen.
</P>
<P>
   THE SCRIPT: An announcer: ``They promised a land of milk and
honey, but they brought the country to the brink of economic
disaster. Now we need someone who has already hit his stride, who
can accomplish the most important thing: to maintain stability in
the state, preserve concord in the society.''
</P>
<P>
   Newspaper reader: ``I trust only deeds.''
</P>
<P>
   ANALYSIS: Primakov's image as a trustworthy, stable leader is
the party's strongest suit. The ad tries to contrast his reputation
with the tumult of the Yeltsin years.
</P>
</TEXT>
