<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0094 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 13:24 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2705 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-2TAKES-     12-18 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S NEW HAMPSHIRE ALLIES SAY HE'S VULNERABLE THERE 
</HEADLINE>
  (EXCLUSIVE; 4 p.m. ET EMBARGO for print media; 7 p.m. ET EMBARGO
for electronic media.) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ Many of Gov. George W. Bush's allies in New
Hampshire are blaming his Texas-based campaign for early lapses
that they say have left him unnecessarily vulnerable against Sen.
John McCain in the state that holds the first presidential primary
in only six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of aloofness and overconfidence, they say, led
advisers unfamiliar with the peculiarities of New Hampshire's
politics to let Bush adopt a sound-bite style that voters here
disdain, and to forgo the time-honored approach of personal
campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   After months of appearing unstoppable elsewhere, Bush has seen
his lead in the New Hampshire polls evaporate, and some surveys
show McCain is continuing to surge. Several of Bush's top advisers
now concede that he could lose the primary on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, Bush would still be the clear favorite for the
Republican nomination. He holds a commanding lead in polls in every
other battleground state and sits atop a daunting treasury.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire may no longer be the make-or-break state it once
was for presidential aspirants. Still, no matter what happens, many
Bush supporters in New Hampshire said the campaign should never
have put itself in jeopardy. Their recrimination underscores a
tension _ one that many strategists say was inevitable _ between
the campaign's tightly run high command in Austin, Texas, and its
supporters on the ground in this tiny state.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Stephen E. Merrill of New Hampshire, who ran Bob
Dole's campaign here in 1996 and backs Bush, spoke out for the
first time in an interview about his qualms about the governor's
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bush campaign believed it was the front-runner in New
Hampshire,'' said Merrill, who did not seek re-election in 1996.
``There's no such thing as the front-runner in New Hampshire. You
simply become the biggest target. This state demands personal
attention _ and is not easily impressed by either money or poll
numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Emphasizing his belief in Bush himself, Merrill added: ``I love
this guy. He'd make a great president. That's what's so
frustrating. There is no inevitability in any presidential primary.
The great irony is that the candidate understands that. I'm not
sure everybody else does.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many of Bush's backers in New Hampshire argued that the
governor's top national advisers did not grasp the idiosyncratic,
even quaint, requirements for stumping in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, they complained that Bush, seeming to take his
lead for granted, did not spend nearly enough time in the state and
passed up early debates with his rivals. When he did venture here,
they said, Bush staged mostly large events where the voters had
little chance to quiz him, a cherished state tradition.
</P>
<P>
   He also took pains not to engage McCain directly, and Bush's
supporters said he did not develop a crisp message early on to
answer the Arizona senator's call for campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   And they said he has been slower than Vice President Al Gore in
trying to shed his entourage, as the vice president did when former
Sen. Bill Bradley mounted an unexpectedly vigorous challenge here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they understand New Hampshire; they don't get
it,'' said Jane E. O'Hearn, a state representative from Nashua, in
the south of the state, who endorsed Bush in May. ``I don't think
they are complying with the way New Hampshire has done things. They
are treating every state probably the same way _ it's sound bites
in every state.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. O'Hearn, who is so exasperated she is toying with the idea
of defecting to McCain, added: ``George Bush's sound bites are all
the same. I don't think he's coming across with the depth he needs
to reach the people of New Hampshire. The man is good, he is
sincere, and just needs an opportunity to show that. And I hope the
Bush campaign allows that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Ed Dupont, a former state Senate president from Concord who is a
member of Bush's state steering committee, said it had been a
nightmare trying to set up an appearance in September at the
international speedway here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent two days with Texas Rangers and advance staff for a
two-hour event,'' he said. ``He couldn't ride in a golf cart, had
to have a closed vehicle.'' In the end, Bush had to scrap the event
because of a shooting in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain swooped in with almost no advance planning. ``They
stuck him in a golf cart and drove him down to the infield and he
shook 400 hands,'' Dupont recalled. ``That is part of what the
McCain message has been: throw your jacket over your shoulder and
go ahead and do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dupont echoed many Bush backers who had nothing but praise for
how McCain has mounted his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this race started, it was Bush's to lose and McCain was
clearly the underdog,'' he said. ``But when McCain wraps the United
States flag around himself, people want to salute. And he's
deserving of that. He's definitely caught on in New Hampshire. The
Bush campaign certainly has the ability to even this thing up in
New Hampshire and win. But time is running short.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Corrigan, a commissioner in Coos County in northern New
Hampshire who is a town chairman for Bush and has been active in
politics for three decades, said: ``The people from the Concord
office were getting their orders from Texas. They had their methods
set even before they came to New Hampshire. We had strangers coming
in trying to run a campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   But Karl Rove, Bush's chief strategist, said many of the
decisions were made jointly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do the mechanical stuff here,'' he said. ``The TV ads are
produced here, but they are carefully vetted there. For all the
volunteer activity on the ground, and decisions about where does
Bush go, they come up with a plan that they discuss with us. What
does Bush say? It's a mutual discussion between them and us.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers insist that they are not rattled now that they
are threatened by a potent rival in the Granite State. But their
calm exteriors belie several steps they have taken in recent weeks
to be more competitive.
</P>
<P>
   After saying he would not take part in any debates until
January, Bush participated in three this year, and the first was in
New Hampshire. He has significantly stepped up his travel schedule
to the state. And at events here he now allows far more time for
questions and answers from residents than in most other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, the front-runner always has a rough patch in the road
somewhere,'' said Rove. ``And the way to plow your way though is to
stay disciplined and to stay focused _ make alternatives and keep
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Rove said he was doing other things to become more competitive,
but would not describe them ``because it would be showing our
cards.''
</P>
<P>
   A victory by McCain in New Hampshire could fortify the Arizona
senator's entire operation as the campaign moves into a fast-paced
schedule of contests. And there is always the possibility _ remote
as it may seem _ that a humiliating defeat could unhinge the entire
Bush operation.
</P>
<P>
   Some Bush supporters said McCain's rise was inevitable, because
it is political custom for there to be an intense skirmish here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not shocked or stunned or anything like that,'' said Rep.
Charles Bass, R-N.H., one of the Bush campaign's top lieutenants
here. ``Frankly, I don't think Bush is either. I've been pounding
this every time I've been with him: `We're going to be behind and
don't worry about it.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Todd Harris, the McCain campaign's spokesman in New
Hampshire, said the Bush campaign ought to be worried. ``Their
definitive victory line in the sand keeps getting pulled back
further and further every day,'' he said. ``It used to be, we'll
defeat them here in New Hampshire. Now, they're talking about a
firewall in Michigan.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Joel Maiola, the Bush campaign director in New Hampshire, argued
that McCain's rise had come about because the Arizona senator drew
new support each time one of the other alternatives to Bush dropped
out of the race earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he thought many Bush supporters had publicly
criticized the candidate's operation, Maiola said: ``In New
Hampshire, there's a lot of agendas and a lot of reasons for saying
different things. In New Hampshire, you can never get enough of a
candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides also defended their operation by arguing that
McCain is concentrating his effort in New Hampshire, completely
bypassing the Iowa caucuses a week before and skimping in other
states as well. By contrast, Bush is running a full-fledged
national campaign. As of Saturday, Bush had spent 19 days in New
Hampshire this year; McCain had been here 42 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our object is to compete everywhere and to win everywhere,''
Rove said. ``You can't claim to be a national candidate worthy of
the nomination of the Republican Party if you say you're going to
pick and choose every contest.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhona Charbonneau, who is chairman of the Bush campaign in
Hillsborough County, said she had been worried that the candidate
did not spend enough time here. ``I don't think they understood New
Hampshire politics,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But she said she had become more confident because the candidate
was coming here more _ and because she was being overwhelmed by
people who wanted to attend a reception for Bush at her house on
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to be hanging from the ceilings,'' she said.
``I've got 180 people coming to my home, and I've had to turn
people away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 1324EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0096 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 13:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2708 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-CAMPAIGN-TV-975(2TAKE     12-18 1002
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CAMPAIGN-TV-975(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CRITIC'S NOTEBOOK: COZY FORMATS PUT CANDIDATES' BEST FACES
FORWARD 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By CARYN JAMES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the Republican debate in New Hampshire early this month,
Gov. George W. Bush looked so squinty-eyed and ill at ease on
camera that it was easy to visualize him as a cartoon figure with
wheels slowly cranking inside his head.
</P>
<P>
   But last Thursday on ``Larry King Live'' he was a political
consultant's dream: He was at ease joking about baseball and
flattering the host; his eyes widened with sincerity when he talked
about the ``heavy heart'' he had when Karla Faye Tucker, who had a
religious conversion while on death row in Texas, was executed. It
was suddenly possible for a viewer to comprehend the charm that
people who have seen him in person have noted, but that had been
conspicuously missing from his television appearances.
</P>
<P>
   Before that, pop quizzes about foreign leaders and reading lists
had caused him to send a panicky look into the camera; during an
hour-long interview with Tim Russert on ``Meet the Press'' he had
seemed prepared and cogent, though mostly in comparison to the low
expectations he had carried along.
</P>
<P>
   This improvement is not only about Bush's evolution as a
television performer, and it is certainly not about policies. In
each event, from the formal debate to the rigorous ``Meet the
Press'' appearance to the puffball interview on ``Larry King,'' the
camera became less formal, the format cozier, the candidate's image
more positive.
</P>
<P>
   The same pattern exists on the Democratic side. Former Sen. Bill
Bradley, who early in his campaign sounded lofty in sound bites,
has seemed far wittier and more engaging up close. He has had his
own dream interviews. He shot baskets at Madison Square Garden with
Ed Bradley for a ``60 Minutes'' profile that resonated with the
glory of his basketball fame. Sitting on the court for an interview
with Wolf Blitzer on CNN's ``Late Edition,'' he said pleasantly
that he would not discuss his religious beliefs, as if that were
the most ordinary position in the world rather than an anomaly
among candidates.
</P>
<P>
   In the last weeks, even days, the campaign has gone through a
range of televised events, from archaic debates to the fake
intimacy of town hall meetings with questions from an audience to
the genuine scrutiny of one-on-one interviews. And it has become
clear that the camera and the format can make a single candidate
seem like several different people.
</P>
<P>
   The three Republican debates have shown that form to be a
throwback to a time when stump speeches and oratorical skill
mattered more than sound bites. Though the candidates stood on
stage and made mini-speeches, during the Arizona debate on CNN it
was plain that the format had been outstripped by technology. When
Sen. John McCain answered a question, it was impossible to tell
that he was actually in New Hampshire, his image carried by
satellite. Against a blue background that matched that on stage, in
close-up he was visually on an equal platform with his five rivals
standing in a row in Arizona. (Lined up that way, Steve Forbes,
Gary Bauer, Alan Keyes and Sen. Orrin Hatch looked like uneasy
backup singers just waiting for Bush to step out and sing the
lead.)
</P>
<P>
   Bush had been heard of but not widely seen on television until
last month, and he had the most to gain or lose from his suddenly
increased exposure. The formal debates made him defensive, working
overtime to counter the charge that he was a smirking intellectual
lightweight. But on ``Larry King,'' with flowers in the background
and the host cheerfully reminding viewers they were at the
Wildhorse saloon in Tennessee, the smirk factor disappeared (except
briefly, when Bush refused once more to talk about possible drug
use in his past). There was no sense that the wheels in his brain
were cranking, but then the questions didn't require much mental
machinery. ``It takes a lot of ego to say I want to be president
and I'm the best person to run the country. That's what you're
saying, right? Is that hard to say?''
</P>
<P>
   A close-up camera and a friendly question are worth only what a
candidate makes of them, of course. McCain, appearing on ``Good
Morning America'' on Thursday, lost a perfect opportunity when
Diane Sawyer asked him why campaign finance reform mattered to
viewers ``brushing our teeth and getting the kids ready for
school.'' Though she handed him a chance to make his central
campaign issue relevant to voters' everyday lives, he resorted to
familiar abstractions about the evil influence of big-corporation
money on legislation.
</P>
<P>
   With his straightforward manner, McCain usually makes more of a
close-up situation. His relaxed, post-debate interviews offset the
frozen smile and prepackaged laugh lines that at times undermined
him on the debate stage. But compare his campaign-finance remarks
on ``Good Morning America'' to Bush's on ``Larry King'' about the
need for free trade with other countries. Bush said he understood
``a mom or a dad'' from Mexico crossing the border for the higher
wages that would allow them to feed their children, demonstrating
which candidate has mastered the art of the soft sell.
</P>
<P>
   And softly selling the candidate's image is what the campaign is
about for most people at this point. With campaign commercials
running in just a handful of primary states, images are very slowly
seeping into the national consciousness. Catching a glimpse of a
candidate while brushing your teeth is the reality behind the
image-making right now. Political junkies may watch the debates,
but many more voters see profiles on ``60 Minutes'' and ``20/20.''
</P>
<P>
   Those fluffier forms may not give the most cogent information,
but they reach the most people. ``Good Morning America,'' for
example, reaches about 3 million people, roughly twice the number
watching each of the Republican debates.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bradley did his own ``town hall'' on ``Good Morning America''
last week, focusing on health care. He talked about specifics, but
easily exuded a concern that offset the dry details. It helped that
he could get up and walk around the small studio space, with a
Christmas tree in the background to warm the atmosphere.
</P>
<P>
   The so-called town hall meetings have become staples of
``Nightline'' as well as ``Good Morning America.'' Combining
elements of the debate and the one-on-one interview, the town hall
is the most flexible form, and also television's loose cannon.
During Friday's flabby, unilluminating ``Nightline'' meeting,
Bradley and Vice President Al Gore talked at, rather than to, each
other. Ted Koppel nearly begged them to keep their answers short.
During an earlier town hall on CNN two months ago, answers were
limited to 90 seconds, and the result was less windy and more
productive. But time was only part of the problem on Friday. A
bigger element was the strangely cautious way the candidates sniped
at each other without really engaging in a discussion.
</P>
<P>
   Of all the candidates, Gore has the least to gain or lose from
such television appearances because he is already the most
familiar. But he suffers because he displays so little difference
between speeches, town hall meetings and sit-down interviews. There
is the same forced naturalness whether challenging Bradley about
financing health care or chopping wood on his farm in Tennessee for
the benefit of Lesley Stahl and ``60 Minutes.''
</P>
<P>
   Gore and Bradley are set to appear together again Sunday morning
on ``Meet the Press.'' Russert has been promoting the meeting as
one that evokes the Lincoln-Douglas debates, though there doesn't
seem to be any good reason. In the seven Lincoln-Douglas meetings,
one candidate spoke for an hour, the next for an hour and a half,
and then the first gave a 30-minute rebuttal. Those two would never
have survived a television campaign, especially at a time when
``the character issue'' has become a buzzword for an appealing
personality, and playing to the camera counts for more than any
policy proposal.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
