<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 13:42 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2715 &Cx1f; tta-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-ELECT-2TAKES(7     12-18 0795
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ELECT-2TAKES(760)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA VOTING AFTER RANCOROUS CAMPAIGN, BUT IT'S JUST A   PRELUDE
TO NEXT YEAR 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RUSSIA-ELECT-ADS) 
(js) 
 By MICHAEL WINES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ The race for Russia's third parliament since the end of
the Soviet Union and more than 70 years of Communism was less a
campaign than a barroom brawl, a chairs-over-the-head affair
suffused with slander, manipulation and unvarnished peculiarity on
all sides.
</P>
<P>
   Yet it was also a race that the public took seriously, despite
its disgust at the tactics. Between the opening of the first
polling booths at 8 a.m. Sunday in Russia's Far East and the
closing of the last, 11 time zones away, in Kaliningrad on the
Baltic Sea 23 hours later, as many as 80 percent of the 107 million
eligible voters are expected to cast ballots for the Duma, the
lower house of parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Eight years after the Soviet Union collapsed in 1991, the
Communists are once again expected to emerge with a plurality of
the 450 seats at stake. But it is a measure both of the surreal
nature of the campaign, and of the Duma's weight compared with the
far more powerful presidency, that almost no one perceives the
Communists as the potential victors in this contest.
</P>
<P>
   The focus is on two parties that are effectively straw men for
the Kremlin clique around President Boris Yeltsin and for its most
powerful opponents, who are led by former Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov and the mayor of Moscow, Yuri Luzhkov.
</P>
<P>
   Neither of the parties that represent these two camps existed a
year ago. But the outcome of their struggle, for second and third
place in the parliamentary vote, will determine who has a
psychological leg up in the next round of even more bare-knuckled
campaigning, the run-up to the election of a successor to Yeltsin
next summer.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently in an attempt to cast this weekend's vote as a true
forerunner of that real tussle for power, Primakov announced on
Friday that he would run for president. His probable opponent in
Yeltsin's Kremlin camp is Prime Minister Vladimir Putin, the former
KGB agent who so far has captivated the electorate by running a
seemingly brisk if brutal war in Chechnya and thus projecting the
image of a strong and decisive leader.
</P>
<P>
   ``The parliamentary election is just a sideshow to this whole
thing,'' said Michael McFaul, a Russia scholar at the Carnegie
Endowment for International Peace, referring to the battle between
the Kremlin and the Primakov-Luzhkov alliance.
</P>
<P>
   As for the score or so other parties competing in the
parliamentary elections, he said, ``they're just sort of white
noise in the background.''
</P>
<P>
   In truth, for all the noise and fury in this election, it is
hard to tell yet what it signifies beyond a rearrangement of
Russia's political furniture before the presidential vote. The
results of the voting will not be fully known until at least Monday
evening in Moscow.
</P>
<P>
   One of the great powers of the current parliament, a
Kremlin-backed party called Our Home Is Russia, is expected to fade
from the scene almost without a whimper. Its leader, Viktor
Chernomyrdin, was prime minister and a Yeltsin favorite when the
last parliament was elected in 1995. Now he is out of the political
game.
</P>
<P>
   The new pro-Kremlin faction, variously called Unity and Medved _
the Russian word for bear _ did not exist six months ago and, like
Chernomyrdin's party four years ago, has little visible ideology
beyond a desire to retain power.
</P>
<P>
   The Primakov-Luzhkov alliance, called Fatherland-All Russia,
also sprang to life this year without much of a philosophy beyond
claiming the Kremlin for itself.
</P>
<P>
   The only constants are the Communists and the West-leaning
Yabloko party, two iconoclastic and ideological factions whose
refusals to compromise have left them proud but on the edges of
power.
</P>
<P>
   If this does not sound like the liberal democracy many
envisioned when the Soviet Union broke up and Russia gained
independence in 1991, it is not. Some experts say Sunday's vote
signals Russia's drift away from a checks-and-balances political
system toward the strongman form of government that has held sway
for most of the last 1,000 years, and for which many
crisis-fatigued Russians now openly long.
</P>
<P>
   But it still is a democracy, and in some ways a robust one.
Predictions of the turnout for Sunday's vote range from 60 percent
to 80 percent of eligible voters, figures that would put Americans
to shame. And the political debate here _ ragged, raw, state- and
tycoon-controlled, libelous and frequently funny _ is far more
heartfelt and ubiquitous than in jaded American or West European
electoral districts.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   As evidence, consider this exchange on national television last
week: Grigory Yavlinsky, leader of the Yabloko party, called
Anatoly Chubais of the Union of Right Forces ``a former keeper of
the president's chamber pot.''
</P>
<P>
   Chubais, who ran Yeltsin's 1996 presidential campaign and is
widely despised in Russia for the way he introduced capitalism in
the early 1990s, likened Yavlinsky to ``a pure, honest, immaculate
and incorruptible bride, with only one flaw: the bride is already
going on 60.''
</P>
<P>
   The two men are actually, in a sense, ideological allies,
leaders of the only two pro-Western liberal parties. Between
enemies, such exchanges actually get personal.
</P>
<P>
   Pollsters have long been laying out the general outlines of the
outcome: the Communist Party, which dominated Russia for more than
70 years of Soviet rule and benefits from a disproportionately
higher turnout of older voters, could collect as much as 25 percent
of the national vote, compared with 22.3 percent in the last
election in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Its ideological opposites, the parties led by Chubais and
Yavlinsky, will probably split about 15 percent _ illustrating the
rough extent of the ardent supporters here of a Western style of
politics and economic order.
</P>
<P>
   The struggle will be for the middle, where the Kremlin's Unity
party and the Primakov-Luzhkov Fatherland faction will be dividing
as much as 30 percent of the electorate.
</P>
<P>
   While many reports suggest that the Unity party has surged
lately, experts still disagree over which of the two will claim the
larger share.
</P>
<P>
   In a way, it doesn't matter. Almost everyone agrees that the two
parties' leaders differ philosophically only by shades.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is just fighting over splitting the pie,'' said Leonid
Radzikhvsky, the political correspondent for the Moscow daily
newspaper Segodnya. ``That's why people go blithely from one party
to another; that's why these parties fall apart and rise with each
new election, and that's why it's possible to put on ideological
masks like liberal, socialist, Communist. They're just completely
average people.''
</P>
<P>
   In the real fight _ over the presidential race, not ideology _
Unity, Fatherland and almost everyone else have been going at it
fang and nail.
</P>
<P>
   As in the West, much of the war has been fought on television,
where the airwaves have been stuffed with commercials pitching
various parties' strengths.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the West, the real battle has been waged on news programs
and talk shows, where broadcasters under politicians' control have
sought nothing less than to destroy their candidates' rivals by
freely airing the most outlandish accusations, often on the
flimsiest of what passes for evidence.
</P>
<P>
   After Primakov went abroad for back surgery this fall, programs
on Kremlin-controlled state television reported breathlessly that
he was terminally ill. Luzhkov, who controls an empire of
city-owned businesses and joint ventures in near dictatorial _ and
highly secretive _ fashion, has been repeatedly tied in television
news reports to the notorious killing of an American businessman
several years ago.
</P>
<P>
   A recent Sunday evening expose included film from a helicopter
flight over Luzhkov's sprawling country estate outside Moscow,
showing rows of mansions and tennis courts that the program implied
were built for his top aides.
</P>
<P>
   An especially notorious program, broadcast on a network
controlled by the tycoon Boris Berezovsky, a Kremlin ally, tied
Primakov to an assassination attempt on the president of Georgia,
Eduard Shevardnadze.
</P>
<P>
   Luzhkov, who is running for re-election as mayor, has not pulled
any punches. A network allied with his municipal empire has aimed a
stream of invective at the Kremlin and Berezovsky.
</P>
<P>
   City police and inspectors have taken an unusual interest in
Luzhkov's Kremlin-backed opponent in the mayoral race, the former
Prime Minister Sergei Kiriyenko.
</P>
<P>
   Kiriyenko's campaign posters have been banned from public
transit as a potential source of confusion and disturbance; police
officers carrying assault rifles raided the Kiriyenko campaign
headquarters this month, demanding campaign-related documents and a
copy of the campaign's office lease.
</P>
<P>
   Dirty tricks are hardly limited to attacks on the presidential
contenders. The government has been unusually selective in
enforcing campaign laws, at one point disqualifying completely the
Liberal Democratic Party because one of its leaders did not report
owning a home. Most observers surmised that the Kremlin hoped that
the party's followers would move to its Unity faction.
</P>
<P>
   The leader of the Liberal Democrats, the outrageous
politician-singer-sex-book author-nationalist Vladimir Zhirinovsky,
eventually won the right to run under another banner. But even
though his billboards proclaim bluntly that his new bloc is just
another name for Liberal Democrat, he seems unlikely to retain the
significant presence he holds in the current parliament.
</P>
<P>
   In the meantime, Yabloko's Yavlinsky escaped any sanction from
the commission although he failed to report $3,000 in income on a
financial-disclosure form.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the entire question of money and politics seems to have
been given a pass by regulators this year, perhaps because
virtually everyone is guilty of violating whatever laws are on the
books.
</P>
<P>
   The richest party, Unity, reports receiving only about 40
million rubles in donations _ some $1.5 million _ and spending
barely half that on a national campaign with heavy television
advertising. Zhirinovsky and the Communists are only a few rubles
behind.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
