the constitutional powers granted its governor.
</P>
<P>
   ``The imagined office is much greater than the real office,''
said Richard Murray, a political science professor at the
University of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The result is a quirky paradox: The job offers a bully pulpit
with national reach, yet it has fewer institutional powers than,
say, the governor of Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   The Texas governor has no formal cabinet, because those
positions are held by elected officials with their own political
bases. The governor controls appointments to powerful state
regulatory boards, but often the appointments are staggered from
previous administrations.
</P>
<P>
   And the governor is far less influential in the writing and
administering of the budget, which is dominated by the Legislature
and the lieutenant governor, compared with governors like Christie
Whitman in New Jersey and George Pataki in New York. (The New York
governor's office is considered the most powerful in the nation.)
</P>
<P>
   Unlike New York, where governors have risen to the presidency
(Franklin D. Roosevelt, Theodore Roosevelt), tried and failed (Al
Smith and Nelson Rockefeller), or thought about it a good bit
(Mario Cuomo), the Texas job has not served as springboard, at
least not yet.
</P>
<P>
   John Connally, regarded as the state's most successful modern
governor, sought the Republican presidential nomination but lost
badly. The state's two presidents, Lyndon Johnson and George Bush,
did their apprentice work in Washington, not Austin.
</P>
<P>
   The job's inherent restrictions have always made it hard for
even an ambitious Texas governor to accomplish the sort of big
things that can launch a presidential run.
</P>
<P>
   Connally managed to pass sweeping reforms and improvements to
the state's higher education system in 1965. But he benefited from
flush times and widespread public sympathy (his arm was in a sling
from injuries he suffered while riding with John F. Kennedy on the
day Kennedy was assassinated).
</P>
<P>
   Gov. Mark White later passed reforms to public schools, but with
significant help from Ross Perot, who spent untold amounts of money
lobbying for the measure.
</P>
<P>
   What, then, of George W. Bush?
</P>
<P>
   Does a weak office mean that Bush has been a weak governor?
</P>
<P>
   Few academics or lawmakers in Texas would argue that.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the nature of the office has in many ways helped shape
what some observers regard as the split personality of Bush's style
of governing.
</P>
<P>
   Upon taking office in 1995, Bush seemed to understand that he
could succeed only with the good will of the Legislature.
</P>
<P>
   He established a chummy, back-slapping tone, paying unexpected
courtesy calls to flattered legislators in both parties and
ingratiating himself with the two leading Democrats _ Lt. Gov. Bob
Bullock and House Speaker Pete Laney.
</P>
<P>
   ``It seems to be more of a love fest with Bush,'' said state
Rep. Steven Wolens of Dallas, one of many Democratic legislators
who speak warmly of the governor. ``He is very, very accessible.
And he is pal-sy.''
</P>
<P>
   The result was that the 1995 Legislative session was regarded as
a ringing success for the new governor.
</P>
<P>
   He had set out four broad issues during the campaign _ juvenile
justice, welfare reform, tort reform and education _ and
legislation was enacted on all four.
</P>
<P>
   None of it represented seismic change, and some observers
complained that Bush hadn't led so much as jumped, in Clinton-esque
fashion, in front of a parade that was already under way.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, all four issues were popular with voters and in the
legislative pipeline before his election. But Bush was seen as
effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have to coerce, cajole and convince these people to do
what you want to do,'' said Bush's close friend, state Sen. David
Sibley, a Republican from Waco, in explaining the influence exerted
by the governor.
</P>
<P>
   Two years later, emboldened by his popularity and eager to
burnish his legacy and his presidential ambitions, Bush proposed a
sweeping overhaul of the state's unwieldy tax structure. Doing so
might have ranked Bush with John Connally, who is credited with
significantly improving the state's system of higher education.
</P>
<P>
   But Bush failed.
</P>
<P>
   His plan promised to lower property taxes and stabilize school
funding while raising sales taxes, but an alternative bill was
passed with the governor's blessing, only to die in the Senate at
the hands of his fellow Republicans.
</P>
<P>
   Bush did win a $1 billion tax cut that many regarded as a
consolation prize.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, Bush was taking the Legislature where it was already
heading. But his tax plan in 1997 represented a political risk for
lawmakers, and he could not muster the support to get the deal
done.
</P>
<P>
   More important, in the eyes of some observers he failed to
effectively use his bully pulpit _ perhaps the greatest tool of his
weak office _ to rally public opinion.
</P>
<P>
   Bush could have spoken out for his program before it was killed
in the Senate, said Bruce Buchanan, a political scientist at the
University of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``That would have been the point where he could have gone public
and mobilized the public, and he chose not to,'' Buchanan said.
Others credited the governor for taking a huge political gamble,
even if he did fail.
</P>
<P>
   Political observers were interested to see which Bush would
greet the 1999 legislative session: the more cautious, if more
successful, governor of 1995 or the bolder, if less successful,
model of 1997.
</P>
<P>
   There was no clear answer; Bush was widely regarded as playing
defense as friendly lawmakers killed any bills that might present
embarrassments during the presidential campaign.
</P>
<P>
   The lessons that Bush has taken from his office seem mixed.
Legislators describe him as flexible and hardly an ideologue.
Several lawmakers, including Democrats, credited the governor with
projecting a genuine sense of non-partisanship in his dealings with
legislators.
</P>
<P>
   Whether this talent is transferable to the presidency is
uncertain. President Jimmy Carter's problems with the Georgia
Legislature during his years as governor there seem now to have
foreshadowed his later struggles with Congress.
</P>
<P>
   President Clinton, however, had apparently learned the art of
massaging legislative egos as governor of Arkansas, yet his
relationship with Congress has often been poisonous.
</P>
<P>
   ``Does the ability to reach across party lines and work with
people translate to Washington?'' asked state Rep. Paul Sadler, an
influential East Texas Democrat. ``The answer is `I don't know.'''
</P>
<P>
   But others said Bush's collegial approach does not always work
for a leader, even a popular leader, as seen in his tax failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``His approach has kept him from being bold, because it's an
approach that depends on the goodwill and friendship of others,''
Buchanan said. ``It means not stepping on toes.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
