<HEADER>
A2723 &Cx1f; var-z
u v BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT &LR;      12-18 0923
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-REVIEW-BUDGET-NYT </SLUG>
  
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Editors: The following items from The N.Y. Times Week in Review
for Sunday, December 19, will move Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   On the dress page:
</P>
<P>
   MILITARY-GAYS-REVIEW (Washington) _ The denunciations of the
military's ``don't ask, don't tell'' policy, triggered by Hillary
Rodham Clinton and quickly followed by President Clinton and Vice
President Al Gore, don't tell Americans that the policy will be
tough to change and don't ask why it hasn't worked. By Eric
Schmitt.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   TEXAS-BUSH-REVIEW (Houston) _ In a campaign in which both his
intellect and his experience have come under attack, Gov. George W.
Bush is reminding voters of two things: that he alone among the
Republican contenders for president holds executive office, and
that governing Texas is a big job, not unlike governing the nation.
Yet Texas actually has one of the weakest gubernatorial offices in
the country, a legacy of a Reconstruction-era constitution that was
written to curb executive power. By Jim Yardley.
</P>
<P>
   (Story has moved in ``a'' news file.)
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `a' category:
</P>
<P>
   PEANUTS-BASEBALL-REVIEW (Undated) _ For 50 years, Charles Schulz
tortured Charlie Brown through a number of devices _ never letting
him kick the football, entangling him in the kite-eating tree,
paralyzing him with fear before the little red-haired girl. Yet
none captured Schulz's fondness for futility more deliciously than
those involving baseball. Schulz, 77, who will end his ``Peanuts''
strip Jan. 4 to focus on treatment for colon cancer, has called
baseball his favorite motif of all. By Alan Schwarz.
</P>
<P>
   TWINN-DOLLS-REVIEW (Undated) _ The My Twinn doll, personalized
from a menu of skin tones, eye shades and matching moles, has been
around for about six years. News articles have raised concerns that
the dolls may be inspiring narcissism, creating a plastic race of
Stepford dolls and, worst of all, stifling the imagination of
children by giving them clones for imaginary friends. By Doreen
Carvajal.
</P>
<P>
   GOVERNMENT-WAGES-REVIEW (Undated) _ That deafening silence you
hear is the sound of presidential hopefuls debating whether
government should intervene in the wage-setting process to help
people afford a better life. Today, it seems, everyone agrees that
the market does this best. By Louis Uchitelle.
</P>
<P>
   RELIGION-POLIITCS-REVIEW (Undated) _ Religious language has
always played a role in American political life, on rare occasion
achieving a profound resonance, as it did in Lincoln's Second
Inaugural Address. But politicians who speak publicly about
religious belief, lacking Lincoln's eloquence, usually talk in
general terms. The political statements made in recent days fly in
the face of that tradition. By Gustav Niebuhr.
</P>
<P>
   DRUG-TRIALS-REVIEW (Undated) _ In recent weeks a wide array of
insurance companies have agreed to pay for experimental cancer
treatments administered to policyholders who participate in
clinical trials sanctioned by federal health agencies. It is a
development that experts described as momentous. By Gina Kolata and
Kurt Eichenwald.
</P>
<P>
   MENTAL-ILLNESS-REVIEW (Undated) The nation is suffering from a
veritable epidemic of mental illness, according to a report last
week by the surgeon general of the United States, which asserted
that ``22 percent of the population has a diagnosable mental
disorder.'' But how is mental illness defined? There seem to be
some large gray areas in which ordinary life-adjustment problems
and vexing behaviors are classified as mental illnesses requiring
clinical treatment.
</P>
<P>
   THISWEEK-REVIEW (Undated) _ Some highlights of the week.
</P>
<P>
   _ Also moving in the `i' category:
</P>
<P>
   RUSSIA-POLITICS-REVIEW (Moscow) _ Just six months ago, veteran
Russia watchers were predicting the disintegration of Russia's
central authority, pulled apart by centrifugal forces that were
moving power away from the Kremlin. Now, they are not quite so
sure. At the close of Sunday's parliamentary elections, which are
widely seen as a test run for the presidential race next June, the
political picture looks quite different. By Celestine Bohlen.
</P>
<P>
   PANAMA-CANAL-REVIEW (Panama City) _ Ever since Balboa sighted
the Pacific Ocean from a hill here in 1513, this has been one of
the world's great geopolitical battlegrounds. The competitors may
have changed, but the link between control of the isthmus and
dominance in world trade has remained constant. Now, with the
United States having formally handed the canal over to Panama last
week, a new phase of that Great Game is beginning. By Larry Rohter.
</P>
<P>
   SCANDANAVIANS-CHILDREN-REVIEW (Oslo, Norway) _ Anette Sorensen,
the Danish mother arrested for leaving her baby unattended on a
sidewalk outside an East Village restaurant in 1997, wept openly
last week when a federal jury rejected her multimillion-dollar
false-arrest claim against New York City. But sympathy for the
young actress in her homeland has all but evaporated. By Walter
Gibbs.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; QUESTIONS OR RERUNS: (888) 346-9867 &LR;
</P>
<P>
   Weekends, Tim Hilchey (e-mail, hilchey(at)nytimes.com).
</P>
<P>
   Phone: (888) 346-9867
</P>
