NYT-12-18-99 1348EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0113 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 13:52 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2725 &Cx1f; tib-z
u k BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT &LR;      12-18 0713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOWD-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
COMMENTARY: NO FANCY SPOKEN HERE 
</HEADLINE>
  (th) 
 By MAUREEN DOWD    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WASHINGTON _ Trying to plan for the future without a sense of
history, the historian Daniel Boorstin said, is like trying to
plant cut flowers.
</P>
<P>
   So how do we judge whether those who would tend our national
garden are planting cut flowers? We should give them more quizzes!
And make them give longer answers!
</P>
<P>
   That's the opinion of the noted historian David McCullough.
</P>
<P>
   In a campaign where John McCain and Bill Bradley seem to have
cornered all the combustion with their allegedly plain-spoken,
putatively maverick and vauntedly Trumanesque politics, I asked the
author of ``Truman'' how we can tell who's faking authenticity.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the way candidates for the Foreign Service have to pass a
foreign language test,'' he says, ``we should make presidential
candidates pass a test'' on history, both personal and global.
</P>
<P>
   McCullough, who is writing a book on John and Abigail Adams and
so spends his days with the extraordinary individuals who created
the Republic, is chagrined that we have devolved to the point where
the burning issue of the day is whether George W. Bush read a book
about Dean Acheson, or any book at all.
</P>
<P>
   The historian observes that we need to know much more about
people before we put them in the Oval Office. He would test for
``groundedness,'' and include these questions:
</P>
<P>
   ``Who is your favorite president, and why?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Which figures in world history interest you most?'' (Aside
from Jesus.)
</P>
<P>
   ``If you could drive from here to St. Louis with any one of
these people, whom would you pick: Andrew Jackson, Abigail Adams,
Thomas Edison or Eugene O'Neill?''
</P>
<P>
   ``If you could spend half an hour with someone who occupied the
presidency in the past, whom would you pick?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Did you ever see a movie or read a book that genuinely changed
your life?'' (Aside from the Bible.)
</P>
<P>
   ``What's your favorite poem?''
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the best speech you ever heard?''
</P>
<P>
   McCullough sees the appeal of the designedly scrappy campaigns
of Bradley and McCain.
</P>
<P>
   ``People are craving something that isn't a contrivance,'' he
says. ``It's terribly disconcerting to think that every single
thing we're sold by commerce or politics is somehow a con. It's not
just authenticity we want. It's backbone and common sense. We have
been exposed to so much political behavior that's lewd and sordid
and contrary to common sense.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think McCain and Bradley are grandstanding or
posturing,'' he says dryly. ``But if this is posturing, let's have
more of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are so marinated in hypocrisy and untrustworthiness. When I
read that the president took a poll to figure out whether to tell
the truth about Monica Lewinsky, that's more unsettling than the
fact of his not telling the truth.''
</P>
<P>
   He said he found the joint effort by Bradley and McCain to fix
campaign finance reform ``emblematic of a larger desire to reform
and improve the system.
</P>
<P>
   ``William Clinton's presidency was all about him. Real leaders
look outward. Clinton wanted to build a bridge to the future. That
doesn't mean anything. That's a bridge that runs off into the air.
He was never willing to risk his political life for something he
believed in.''
</P>
<P>
   Whether or not McCain is Truman, the historian thinks that Bush
is Dewey. ``Their campaign strategy is similar,'' he says. ``Don't
rock the boat. We've got it wrapped up. Don't do anything dumb or
controversial. Stick with platitudes and you'll come in with the
tide.''
</P>
<P>
   He has no patience for Donald Trump and Steve Forbes and the
rest of the rich and famous and vain who would be president.
``They're all clowns and bozos and show-offs with awful,
embarrassing egos,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The more he studies American history, the more convinced he is
that human nature matters for history. ``What's so fascinating is
to see how often the ups and downs of history derive from that
mysterious ingredient called personality,'' he says. ``It's not a
coincidence that the best presidents had a genuine sense of
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``They don't see themselves as the be-all and end-all of
creation, but simply as part of a long-running chain going all the
way back to George Washington.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
