<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-CHECHNYA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIA TRIES TO BLOCK ROUTE FROM CHECHNYA INTO GEORGIA 
</HEADLINE>
  (See also RUSSIA-ELECT) 
(mk) 
 By MICHAEL R. GORDON   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ In an effort to block the southern escape routes for
Islamic rebels in Chechnya, Russian paratroopers have cut the road
between the breakaway region and Georgia, its neighbor to the
south.
</P>
<P>
   Georgian officials reported that Russian helicopters had dropped
bombs on the Georgian side of the border in an apparent effort to
seal the border, and President Eduard Shevardnadze of Georgia vowed
a response. The paratroopers were flown in by helicopter and have
taken up positions inside Chechnya, but near the Georgia border.
</P>
<P>
   ``This operation could change the whole picture of the
counterterrorist operation in the North Caucasus,'' Prime Minister
Vladimir Putin said, providing an encouraging account of the war as
Russians prepared to vote in weekend elections for the lower house
of parliament, the Duma.
</P>
<P>
   During the three-month war, Russian troops have attacked from
the north, the west and the east, but there had been no Russian
forces blocking the Georgian border.
</P>
<P>
   The operation to seal that frontier has a long history. The
Russians initially sought to persuade Georgia to let Russian troops
on to the Georgian side of the border. Georgia refused, afraid that
it would be drawn into the war.
</P>
<P>
   The move underscores that Russia is determined to win a
decisive, if bloody, victory over its foes. Islamic rebels in
Grozny, Chechnya's capital, are already surrounded. Now, Russia
appears to be trying to encircle a separate group of rebels in the
south.
</P>
<P>
   Grozny was the scene of more bombing Friday night, and fighting
between Russian troops and rebel forces on the city's outskirts.
All told, about 50 strikes were carried out through Chechnya by
planes and helicopters during the past 24 hours, Russian officials
at the Mozdok air base near Chechnya said.
</P>
<P>
   The attacks have produced an outcry in Western capitals. On
Saturday, the European Union signaled that it was drawing up a list
of sanctions as a result of Russia's military campaign. Chris
Patten, the external affairs commissioner for the European Union,
said the organization could not carry out ``business as usual''
with Russia while it wages war.
</P>
<P>
   The Russians began bombarding and encircling Chechnya after
Islamic rebels based there made incursions in August into the
Russian-ruled republic of Dagestan to its east. After the rebels
were driven back, explosions in apartment buildings in Russia and
in Dagestan killed almost 300 people. Russian authorities blamed
Chechen rebels. The status of Chechnya _ officially a Russian
republic _ was left in limbo after a 1994-96 war in which thousands
of Russian soldiers were killed.
</P>
<P>
   In Moscow, there has been virtually no criticism of the war, and
Putin's running of the conflict is very popular. In Sunday's
parliamentary elections, he has endorsed the pro-Kremlin Unity
party, led by Sergei Shoigu, the minister for emergency situations,
increasing its ratings substantially from virtually nil.
</P>
<P>
   Shoigu has sought to exploit the war politically by highlighting
his efforts to rescue civilians from Grozny, although they have not
so far led to any large outpouring of civilians from the city,
which is thought to contain as many as 45,000 civilians.
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, the Russian public has been presented with a
reassuring version of the campaign. Putin said Saturday that
civilian casualties ``could be counted on one's fingers'' and
denounced reports of heavy civilian casualties as a ``propaganda
and a lie.''
</P>
<P>
   The Russian account of civilian casualties, however, is
grievously understated. The civilians remaining in Grozny, many of
them ethnic Russians, have endured hunger, cold, marauders and
indiscriminate bombing. And tens of thousands of others have been
caught in the fighting in other towns and cities.
</P>
<P>
   Spokesmen for the Chechen rebels assert that several thousand
civilians have been killed, although these figures, too, cannot be
confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   According to Russian spokesmen, Russian military casualties have
been held to a minimum. Official figures state that 404 Russian
soldiers and 129 Interior Ministry troops have been killed, high by
the standards of the American military but low compared with the
earlier war.
</P>
<P>
   The figures given for Russian military casualties do not include
soldiers who are ``missing in action,'' but are almost certainly
dead.
</P>
<P>
   Reporters working for foreign news media who have disclosed
failed military operations _ like the destruction last week of what
was apparently a Russian reconnaissance force of more than 100
soldiers in Grozny _ have been denounced as agents for foreign
powers who dispense Chechen disinformation.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
