<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 14:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2737 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-HOMELESS-PROFILE-ART-     12-18 0951
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HOMELESS-PROFILE-ART-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A HOMELESS PORTRAIT: TWO JOBS, AN ANCIENT VAN AND BLEAK PROSPECTS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (ART ADV: Photo is being sent to NYT photo clients. Non-subscribers
can make individual purchase by calling (888) 603-1036.) 
(jw) 
 By EVELYN NIEVES   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   SAN FRANCISCO _ Kathleen Gray bought the van brand new in 1978.
It took half a year of waiting tables to make the $1,300 down
payment. But it was well worth it. A Volkswagen pop-top camper!
</P>
<P>
   The day she drove it home, she spread her sleeping bag in the
cab, popped open the roof and lay under the built-in tent,
daydreaming of a life on the road.
</P>
<P>
   That life on the road did not work out as planned. Yet now, with
its engine as loud as a helicopter when it agrees to work, the
musty green van is more precious than ever. Every morning when Ms.
Gray leaves for work, she worries that the van will be gone when
she gets back. And then where would she be? The van is her home.
</P>
<P>
   She and her boyfriend, David Aquino, began living in the van
almost two years ago. Before the van became home, the couple lived
for three months in a tent in an encampment at Golden Gate Park.
Before that, both unemployed, they had been evicted from the house
where Aquino grew up. Before that seems like a long time ago.
</P>
<P>
   How Ms. Gray became homeless is a complicated story. But in one
crucial respect, Ms. Gray's case is like those of many homeless
people she meets: She got in a bind and had no way to get out of
it. No money. No help.
</P>
<P>
   Even now, six months into working two part-time jobs that
together pay her nearly $1,200 a month, she cannot say when she
will be able to stop using a ratty blanket for a bed or a pickle
jar for a toilet. Not with landlords asking for three months' rent
up front, her boyfriend still not working and past-due bills
waiting to attach themselves to her paycheck.
</P>
<P>
   It is especially hard to be homeless in these days of giddy
prosperity. For Ms. Gray, it is like having her nose pressed
against the glass of a big party where money flutters in the air
like confetti. San Francisco, flush with Silicon Valley
professionals, has become so expensive that a six-figure income is
considered middle-class, and basic items like a gallon of regular
gas ($1.60) cost more than anywhere else in the country.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gray has never been rich. Her parents divorced when she was
12. In her senior year of high school, she abandoned plans for
college to support herself and her mother, who had cancer.
</P>
<P>
   But she never thought she would have to count pennies at 44, in
the prime of life. People she meets who are not homeless are always
surprised to learn that she is; she defies the stereotype.
</P>
<P>
   The Census Bureau survey of homeless people, released this
month, showed that most were ill, physically or mentally. Ms. Gray
is healthy. She does not drink or use illegal drugs. She does not
come from welfare poverty. She is not a single mother.
</P>
<P>
   Until three years ago, when she quit a job as a concessions
manager at a Renaissance fair in Marin County to attend a school
for prospective travel industry employees, she had worked nonstop
since graduating from high school in Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   Until she had to do it herself, she says, she always looked at
the people living on the streets with something like revulsion.
</P>
<P>
   ``Now I know it's a lot harder to get out of the fix than to get
in it,'' she said with a laugh, her usual punctuation, as she
stopped at an Anderson's supermarket the other day on her way to
work. By 7 every morning, after a round of catch with Kaya, a
pit-bull mix she and Aquino adopted last year, they arrive at the
supermarket to wash up. Then they buy the breakfast they can
afford: large coffees, light and sweet.
</P>
<P>
   Sometimes, Ms. Gray has no good answer when people ask why she
does not go somewhere easier to live.
</P>
<P>
   Living in a vehicle is illegal in San Francisco. Even in a
desolate, wind-whipped neighborhood hard by the ocean, the police
regularly shine lights into the van in the middle of the night.
Once, when the van was towed for a parking violation, it took
several days and $700 of scrounged and borrowed money to get it
back.
</P>
<P>
   Inside, the van is as dark and crowded as a storage closet. Good
clothes, like his pin-striped interview suit and her pink down
jacket, hang on a rod. Clean clothes are piled in his and her's
stacks. Laundry sits in plastic grocery bags. Kaya's water and food
dishes are by the driver's seat. Jars used as portable urinals are
discretely lined up on the floor by a stack of boxes.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gray, who is tall and broad-shouldered, with a long red
braid, a curtain of bangs and wire-rimmed glasses, often laughs,
loudly, at her daily tribulations. ``We have to use a bathroom
where we can find one,'' she said, laughing, making a beeline for a
veterans' hospital near a park where they exercise Kaya.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's Ramen noodles for a week,'' she will say, laughing if she
splurges on a $5 lunch.
</P>
<P>
   ``The police call me a habitual, known offender for sleeping in
the van,'' she says, laughing. ``And it's true: I sleep every
night.''
</P>
<P>
   On weekdays, she works at the Coalition on Homelessness, a
nonprofit advocacy organization. On weekends, she helps run showers
for homeless people at the Mission High School. Her job perks
include invitations to church potlucks and one long hot shower a
week.
</P>
<P>
   No one notices if her hair needs washing or she wears the same
turquoise T-shirt two days in a row.
</P>
<P>
   She and the short, bushy-haired Aquino often borrow the
coalition's van, which they use to push Ms. Gray's van from one
street to the next when it refuses to run.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   They met playing darts at a pub. At the time Aquino, who will be
46 this month, had recently left an 11-year job as a sorter for the
Postal Service. He says he quit in anger over a $20,000 bill he
received for interest and penalties on child support (for a
daughter, now in her 20s), which he thought he had paid.
</P>
<P>
   Three months after they met, after a falling out with her
roommate, Ms. Gray moved in with Aquino, who was living with his
grandfather. Divorced from his daughter's mother, he had vowed he
would never marry again, but Ms. Gray said, ``We were going to.''
</P>
<P>
   But her wanderlust, whetted by six years as a waitress and
bartender in Maui (where she bought her van), was not satisfied.
She enrolled in the travel school, hoping for a job on a cruise
ship. ``It had this highfalutin title for what I wanted,'' she
said. ``Destination management.''
</P>
<P>
   Within months, Aquino's grandfather died. The house became the
property of Aquino's estranged father and uncle, who evicted the
couple so they could sell it. Neither Ms. Gray, with her savings
gone and credit cards at their limits, nor Aquino, with his debts,
was in a position to land on their feet.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, of course, I wouldn't have quit my job if I knew all
this was going to happen,'' Aquino said, as he sipped an Anchor
Steam ale outdoors on a recent afternoon. ``People just have no
idea how hard it is to get out of the hole of homelessness. You
spend your days surviving. You don't have room for much else.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gray is convinced that if she and Aquino had been getting
along at the time his grandfather died, they could have fought the
eviction. Instead, they were busy fighting each other. It was so
consuming, she said, that she dropped out of travel school, twice.
She had Aquino arrested for assault after he broke a telephone on
her head. A judge ordered him to attend an anger-management class.
</P>
<P>
   Aquino prefers not to discuss that period. One day, when they
were retracing their descent to the streets, Ms. Gray, laughing,
said, ``Well, things got really hairy when I had David arrested.''
</P>
<P>
   Aquino took his baseball cap off, tapped her on the head with it
and said, ``Hey, you stop that.''
</P>
<P>
   The day they were evicted, Ms. Gray invited Aquino to stay with
her in her van until he found somewhere else. Throughout their
ordeals, they have never separated.
</P>
<P>
   She says she tried to leave, alone, before they were evicted.
With both parents gone and her two brothers (one a minister in
Oregon, the other a computer programmer in Southern California),
out of touch, she called an old friend of her mother's and asked to
borrow $5,000. The friend said she could not spare it.
</P>
<P>
   These days, Ms. Gray and Aquino get along fairly well. Their
dog, who is obsessed with chasing tennis balls, is their therapy,
Aquino says.
</P>
<P>
   But they disagree over how to improve their situation.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Gray says it is best to take any job to begin repairing
their broken credit. Aquino says it is not worth getting a job that
pays less than $10 an hour, because it would be impossible to save
money making less. He still receives $345 a month as part of a city
program that tries to steer assistance recipients into solid jobs.
(He once cleaned buses for his stipend.) He says he hopes to become
a truck driver.
</P>
<P>
   While Ms. Gray is still not used to being homeless, she says her
worst moment occurred at the beginning, when she and Aquino were
living in Golden Gate Park. (Ms. Gray's van was in a friend's
driveway in Marin County, refusing to run). Ms. Gray had just
started workfare two days a week for the Parks and Recreation
Department for $345 a month. One day, the parks department was
ordered to sweep all the homeless camps from the park. Ms. Gray, as
part of the crew, was forced to dump her own meager possessions.
</P>
<P>
   ``I remember at the time, thinking well, I was guilty,'' she
said. ``I was living in the park, Now, I see things so differently.
With these sweeps, the city was _ and is _ systematically
destroying people's personal property. Blankets, prescription
medicine, glasses, documents. And I watched as bosses looked the
other way while workfare workers were allowed to keep _ to steal _
things.''
</P>
<P>
   She and 10 other homeless people sued the city in small claims
court for the illegal destruction of their property and won. She
received $500 in damages.
</P>
<P>
   ``Working at the coalition has really taught me how to stand up
for myself,'' she said. ``And now, I think I'll always have a
social conscience.''
</P>
<P>
   Lately she has been worried about how to help a quadriplegic
homeless woman in her 30s. The woman spends nights on the ground,
crawling to her chair in the mornings. By the end of the week, when
Ms. Gray helps the woman take a shower, her body and clothes are
soaked in feces and urine.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think two things when I see her,'' Ms. Gray said one morning
in the van. ``First, I think, How can we allow this to happen?
</P>
<P>
   ``Then,'' she said, letting her head fall back against a
tattered window curtain, ``I think, boy, am I lucky. I am just so
lucky.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
