<HEADLINE>
TO DENMARK, SOMETHING IS ROTTEN 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By WALTER GIBBS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   OSLO, Norway _ Anette Sorensen, the Danish mother arrested for
leaving her baby unattended on a sidewalk outside an East Village
restaurant in 1997, wept openly last week when a federal jury
rejected her multimillion-dollar false-arrest claim against New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   But sympathy for the young actress in her homeland has all but
evaporated.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sorensen's cultural defense _ that Danish mothers leave
their babies outside in strollers all the time _ initially struck a
chord in Denmark and neighboring Norway. Scandinavians are proud of
their relatively safe cities and they relish comparison with New
York City.
</P>
<P>
   But a half dozen young parents who were interviewed admitted
that they would never leave a baby on a Copenhagen sidewalk for an
hour while drinking inside, as Ms. Sorensen was alleged to have
done in Manhattan. Even the Scandinavian habit of parking a
stroller outside for a few moments while posting a letter or buying
a pastry is rapidly fading into nostalgia.
</P>
<P>
   ``In the countryside and even in minor towns you could maybe
still do that, but Denmark has changed,'' said Per Schultz
Jorgensen, chairman of the Denmark's Council for Children.
``Copenhagen is a city of 1 million people, with many strangers and
lots of people passing on the streets. No, no, parents have to take
much more care.''
</P>
<P>
   Last weekend, Copenhagen was roiled by a child kidnapping inside
a shopping mall. While the mother shopped, a two-year-old girl was
snatched by an unknown woman. Twenty-four hours later the toddler
was released in a park by a man in a black car.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sorensen, 32, lost support among her countrymen not only by
overplaying the culture card but by filing her false-arrest
lawsuit.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everyone thinks she is greedy,'' said Arno Viktor Nielsen, a
professor who also writes widely read newspaper columns on Danish
culture.
</P>
<P>
   Scandinavians have had difficulty understanding Ms. Sorensen's
disappointment over Tuesday's verdict, which still awarded her
$66,400 in damages on a technicality stemming from the failure of
police to inform her of her right to call the Danish Embassy. The
amount converts to nearly half a million Danish kroner, an
astronomical sum by Scandinavian legal standards.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Sorensen, eyes puffy, landed on the cover of Copenhagen
tabloids Wednesday under mocking headlines such as, ``Crying over
half a million.'' The respected national newspaper Jyllands-Posten
editorialized: ``Seen through Danish eyes, the damage amount is out
of all proportion, and we hope that we (in Denmark) will never come
to the point where people can demand compensation for making a fool
of themselves.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 1431EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0124 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 14:38 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4147 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-PANAMA-CANAL-REVIEW-A     12-18 1092
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PANAMA-CANAL-REVIEW-ART-1040(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ASIA MOVES IN ON THE BIG DITCH 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Japan, S.Korea, Taiwan, China)  (ART ADV: Graphic is being sent to NYT graphic clients.
Non-subscribers can make individual purchase by calling
888-603-1036 or 888-346-9867.) 
(js) 
 By LARRY ROHTER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   PANAMA CITY _ Ever since Balboa sighted the Pacific Ocean from a
hill here in 1513, this has been one of the world's great
geopolitical battlegrounds. The competitors may have changed, as
the colonial rivalry of Spain and England gave way in the 1800s to
a struggle to build the Panama Canal that pitted France against the
United States, but the link between control of the isthmus and
dominance in world trade has remained constant.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the United States having formally handed the canal
over to Panama last week, a new phase of that Great Game is
beginning. This time it is the trading powers of East Asia that are
emerging as players _ reflecting the waterway's diminishing
importance to U.S. commerce and its growing strategic value to
export-dependent economies on the far side of the Pacific.
</P>
<P>
   Before the canal was built, the United States, emerging as a
world power, envisioned it as the best way to get people and goods
between its Atlantic and Pacific coasts and to unify a new
two-ocean Navy. But today, not only are aircraft carriers too big
to fit through the canal (and missile submarines normally too
secretive to use it), but U.S. companies increasingly prefer
overland routes or air freight for shipping goods between their two
coasts.
</P>
<P>
   For Asians shipping exports across two oceans, however, the
canal is now indispensable. The United States remains its largest
user, but the big trading nations of Asia are catching up fast.
China, Japan, Korea and Taiwan are all in the top 10, and a typical
cargo nowadays is likely to be soybeans from Brazil or oil from
Venezuela on their way to East Asia in exchange for automobiles or
electronic goods destined for the Colon Free Trade Zone here.
</P>
<P>
   The result has been a conspicuous burst of Asian investment
here. Taiwanese and Korean consortiums are building separate
industrial parks, and a pair of Chinese shipping tycoons with
competing political loyalties are now solidly installed in the
ports that command both approaches to the canal: Chang Yung-Fa, a
Taiwan loyalist, and his Evergreen Maritime Corp. in Colon at the
Caribbean entrance; and Li Ka-shing, of Hong Kong's Hutchison
Whampoa Ltd., who is cozy with Beijing, in Balboa at the Pacific
entrance.
</P>
<P>
   ``Panamanians have an easier time relating to U.S. businessmen
than Chinese or Japanese because culturally they feel more at ease
with Americans,'' said Roberto Eisenmann, a prominent business
leader here who advises President Mireya Moscoso. ``But the
governments of Asia have been much more aggressive than the United
States'' in seeking opportunities here.
</P>
<P>
   In Washington, only the conservative Republicans who opposed the
Panama Canal Treaties in 1977, and who now fear that the People's
Liberation Army is sneaking in as the Southern Command moves out,
seem interested in Panama these days. Former Secretary of Defense
Caspar Weinberger warned this month that China is seeking ``a
foothold in one of the world's three major chokepoints,'' while the
Senate majority leader, Trent Lott, fears that ``U.S. naval ships
will be at the mercy of Chinese-controlled pilots and could even be
denied passage through the canal.''
</P>
<P>
   Supporters of the turnover counter that such a focus on the
military ignores the fact that the United States is the only
country with a treaty right to intervene should such an unlikely
scenario occur.
</P>
<P>
   More interestingly, perhaps, a narrow emphasis on the military
plays down the underlying mercantile factor; it is, after all, by
expanding its economy that China has the best chance of becoming a
global power in the next few decades rather than by challenging the
United States militarily in the Western Hemisphere.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps the most significant contest developing here, according
to Ricardo Arias Calderon, a former vice president of Panama, is
``an intense competition between Taiwan and the People's Republic
of China to advance a broad array of interests'' that are
fundamentally political and economic.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the Chinese have learned the lesson of 19th-century
England, which understood that it had influence in the
Mediterranean to the extent that it commanded the entrance and
exit'' at Gibraltar and Suez, he added. ``China and Taiwan are
already competing in the South China Sea, and now both are seeking
a presence at the exit on the other side of the Pacific.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, power and influence today can be exercised in a more
subtle manner than by establishing colonies or sending in the
fleet, as the British so often did. Neither Chinese state is in a
position _ or even appears to want _ to supplant America's role as
protector of the canal. So their rivalry has centered on the
commercial facilities in and around the canal and on penetrating
Latin American markets.
</P>
<P>
   Japan, too, is bidding for influence and profit here. It has
underwritten a feasibility study for construction of new canal
locks and is offering to finance a new bridge on extraordinarily
generous terms.
</P>
<P>
   Yet neither Panama, which abolished its armed forces following
the U.S. invasion to overthrow Gen. Manuel Antonio Noriega 10 years
ago, nor the Asians can guarantee the security of the canal. That
has historically been a U.S. responsibility _ just as it is America
that guarantees that the sea lanes remain open in Asia. But
defending the canal is a role that has changed enormously in the
last century, if only because the nature of war has changed.
</P>
<P>
   Panamanians say there is virtually no possibility of building a
foolproof military shield these days, a point U.S. military
planners concede privately.
</P>
<P>
   Flying over the canal in a helicopter with Nicolas Ardito
Barletta, the director of the Inter-Oceanic Regional Authority, the
Panamanian government agency that oversees the former Panama Canal
Zone, and looking down on the network of dams and locks that hold
back the man-made Gatun and Madden Lakes, the waterway's
vulnerability in the missile age is evident. If they were to be
blown up, ``the canal would be shut down for two years,'' Barletta
acknowledged. That is why, he added, ``the best guarantee for the
canal is its neutrality.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
</TEXT>
