<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4152 &Cx1f; var-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-REVIE     12-18 1050
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-POLITICS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN RUSSIAN ELECTIONS, THE KREMLIN IS STILL AHEAD 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 By CELESTINE BOHLEN    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ It was just six months ago that veteran Russia watchers
were predicting the disintegration of Russia's central authority,
pulled apart by centrifugal forces that were moving power away from
the Kremlin _ to the country's wayward regions and to an
increasingly emboldened parliament.
</P>
<P>
   Now they are not quite so sure. At the close of Sunday's
parliamentary elections, which are widely seen as a test run for
the presidential race next June, the political picture looks quite
different.
</P>
<P>
   To loud applause at home, Russia has gone to war in Chechnya to
regain control of its unruly southern border. The Kremlin has
fractured and humiliated its once cocky opposition, all the while
promoting the presidential chances of its preferred heir, Prime
Minister Vladimir Putin.
</P>
<P>
   And the considerable powers of Russia's superpresidency are
intact and waiting for the Kremlin's next occupant. Which, it turns
out, is what a majority of the Russian people have wanted all
along.
</P>
<P>
   ``The opposition overestimated the public consensus in favor of
redistributing the powers of the presidency,'' said Sergei Markov,
director of the Moscow-based Institute of Politics. ``Most people
don't want to shift more power to the parliament. They want a
stable government, and that means one subordinate to the
president.''
</P>
<P>
   A recent poll by the Regional and Political Research Agency
found that 44 percent of the respondents said Russia would always
need a ``strong hand.'' Another 22 percent thought it needed a
strong hand in these troubled times. Only 17 percent thought that
putting power into one set of hands was a bad idea.
</P>
<P>
   In this atmosphere, few observers now expect to see the
anti-Yeltsin opposition try to limit the power of the presidency,
by pressing ahead soon with changes to the 1993 Constitution.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, some experts now predict that Russia's regional
governors, who have been enjoying the role of kingmakers in this
election year, may find that their days of near-autonomy are now
numbered.
</P>
<P>
   Markov, for one, predicts a move to curtail their regional
powers and to end the special treatment that some ``national''
regions have enjoyed. ``I think this time will come, but not until
after the presidential elections,'' he said. ``Before the
elections, no candidate will be brave enough to challenge the
regional authorities.''
</P>
<P>
   The almost-feudal power of some governors over their regions has
been evident in these elections, as national politicians have
shamelessly vied for their support in hopes of receiving large
chunks of their local electorate.
</P>
<P>
   But Nikolai Petrov, a political expert at the Carnegie Endowment
for International Peace, said: ``It seems to me that what we see
now is the last blossoming of the regional leaders' separatism. It
is their last role in this play.''
</P>
<P>
   Power in Russia is still a winner-take-all proposition. Nine
years of democracy have changed the rules of the game, but not its
essence, and Sunday's elections are a case in point.
</P>
<P>
   The contest is not, as it was four years ago, between Yeltsin
and his Communist opposition. It is between two different clans
from the same ruling elite _ much like the old struggles between
feuding members of the Communist Party Central Committee. Except
that this fight is fought openly through the ballot box, and not,
as Kremlinologists used to say, under a rug.
</P>
<P>
   A turning point in the fight came last summer, when a
center-left coalition headed by former Prime Minister Yevgeny
Primakov joined the Communists in challenging the Yeltsin
administration. At the time, Yeltsin's authority was weakening,
undermined by his poor health, by scandals and by his unpredictable
behavior.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout his presidency, Yeltsin's use of his considerable
authority has been erratic. ``There hasn't been decentralization
and federalism, there has been a weakening of authoritarian
institutions,'' said Petrov. ``But the authoritarian institutions
remained in place; they just haven't been utilized.'' Until, he
added, this latest election campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Challenged by Primakov's coalition, the Kremlin and its
political operatives have waged a bitter and ugly political war,
replete with media tactics that smacked of old-style Soviet
propaganda, electoral technicalities and a mustering of loyalists
for a crash counteroffensive.
</P>
<P>
   Some critics even charge that the Kremlin team, in its greed to
hold onto power after Yeltsin leaves office, launched the real war
in Chechnya, which is largely responsible for propelling Putin to
the top of the polls.
</P>
<P>
   Putin is not a candidate in the parliamentary elections, but his
spectacular rise in the polls has boosted the chances of a
brand-new pro-Kremlin alliance, known as Unity and nicknamed Bear,
which was created specially to take votes away from its rivals.
</P>
<P>
   The key to the Kremlin's strategy was its understanding of the
mentality of a Russian political elite that is always on the
outlook for the next winning bandwagon.
</P>
<P>
   When Primakov was riding high last summer, local officials and
powerful businessmen eagerly jumped on his team, hoping to pick up
jobs, favors, contracts and other perks. Now that it looks as
though Putin, not Primakov, will be the next president, some of
those hangers-on are having second thoughts. ``They joined not to
be in the opposition but to be in the party of power,'' Markov
said.
</P>
<P>
   According to some experts, the rise of Putin, and the Kremlin's
success in weakening Primakov's team, will once again leave the
Duma toothless and divided _ a parliament slavishly attuned to
Putin's popularity ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Michael McFaul, a Russia scholar at the Carnegie Endowment for
International Peace, evoked the retreat from the French Revolution
recently at a seminar held in Moscow: ``Thermidor is ending,
Napoleon has arrived.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 1445EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0135 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 14:45 </DATE_TIME>
