</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RELIGION-POLITICS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GOD AND MAN AND THE PRESIDENCY 
</HEADLINE>
  (EDS: Abraham Lincoln quote appears as epigraph to text) 
(The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(js) 
 By GUSTAV NIEBUHR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``Both read the same Bible and pray to the same God, and each
invoked His aid against the other. It may seem strange that any men
should dare to ask a just God's assistance in wringing their bread
from the sweat of other men's faces, but let us judge not, that we
be not judged. The prayers of both could not be answered. That of
neither has been answered fully. The Almighty has His own
purposes.'' _ Abraham Lincoln
</P>
<P>
   Religious language has always played a role in American
political life, on rare occasion achieving a profound resonance, as
it did in Lincoln's Second Inaugural Address, in which he expressed
his awe at an ultimately mysterious God in the passage above, and
called on the nation to bind up its wounds after the Civil War.
</P>
<P>
   But politicians who speak publicly about religious belief,
lacking Lincoln's eloquence, usually talk in general terms,
referring to the value of faith and asking God to bless America,
yet leaving ample space for their audiences to fill in the
specifics according to their individual beliefs.
</P>
<P>
   The political statements made in recent days fly in the face of
that tradition. They are all the more remarkable because of their
venue: Four presidential candidates chose national television to
declare their belief in Jesus Christ. For many viewers, the
declarations were unexpectedly personal, and for some they were
disturbing because they seemed to cross a boundary that
distinguishes a general affirmation of faith from specific and
intimate belief. The risk is that for every voter gained, another
is lost. Although the candidates all come from within the broad
tent of Christianity, America is more pluralistic than ever, with
growing religious minorities.
</P>
<P>
   First, it was Vice President Al Gore, the leading Democratic
contender, who described himself as a born-again Christian in a
``60 Minutes'' interview on Dec. 5. He spoke openly about his
beliefs, Gore said, because he wanted ``to be forthright and
candid'' about who he is.
</P>
<P>
   Then on Monday at the Republican debate in Iowa, Gov. George W.
Bush of Texas, the Republican front-runner, said he, too, shared an
evangelical Protestant experience of personal conversion. Asked
whom he regarded as his favorite philosopher, Bush said, ``Christ,
because he changed my heart.'' Fellow Republicans Gary L. Bauer and
Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah followed with statements about their
devotion to Christ.
</P>
<P>
   Jimmy Carter, a devout Southern Baptist who taught Sunday school
during his White House years, delivered an inaugural address that
the religious historian Martin E. Marty said was probably ``the
least religious'' by a recent president. ``In the public realm, he
was very careful,'' Marty said of Carter. So, too, was Ronald
Reagan, Marty added, despite his political courtship of religious
conservatives.
</P>
<P>
   In their caution, those presidents had plenty of precedents.
Dwight D. Eisenhower, for example, once described himself as ``the
most intensely religious man'' he knew, but he reached toward the
universal when speaking about God and faith.
</P>
<P>
   The end of the Cold War may be partly to blame. The fall of the
Soviet state removed the external threat of Communism and its
atheistic doctrine. Randall Balmer, a professor of religion at
Barnard College, said that during the darkest days of the Cold War,
declarations like Gore's and Bush's would have been unheard of
because the spirit of the era emphasized ``a united front against
the perils of Communism.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I think what we're seeing is a return toward particularity,''
Balmer said. ``Then that begs the question as to how that works in
the political arena.'' The candidates, he said, may be taking ``a
calculated risk that Americans are looking for people with
definition and conviction, even if that conviction differs from a
particular voter, or blocs of voters.''
</P>
<P>
   If that's the trend, it follows the rise in political and
cultural influence of evangelical Protestants, which began with
Carter's election in 1976 and has been marked by groups like the
Christian Coalition, the success of Christian pop musicians and the
emergence of ``mega-churches'' with huge congregations. ``There's a
whole lot more self-confidence now,'' said Balmer, whose new book,
``Blessed Assurance'' (Beacon), is about evangelicals.
</P>
<P>
   Conrad Cherry, director of the Center for the Study of American
Religion and Culture at Indiana University-Purdue University,
agreed. ``My guess is that this is an illustration of the impact of
evangelical Christianity on the culture as a whole,'' he said. ``I
can only assume that these politicians are tuned into that.''
</P>
<P>
   Cherry said he doubted that the candidates' statements would be
universally well received in his state. Central Indiana, like other
regions in the country, has a growing Muslim population and its
Jewish presence is well established. He wondered ``how attuned''
the candidates were to that kind of religious pluralism.
</P>
<P>
   That question also concerns Abraham Foxman, national director of
the Anti-Defamation League of B'nai B'rith, who said he felt a
sense of ``alienation'' after hearing some of the candidates in the
Iowa debate, even though, he said, as a ``believing, traditional
Jew,'' religion is important to him. The statements crossed a
``certain line'' in civic life, he said, but probably reflected the
candidates' attempts to connect with a public looking for answers
amid a sense that a ``crisis of values'' exists in the country,
especially after the school shooting last April in Littleton, Colo.
</P>
<P>
   ``I guess somebody's telling them that it's OK,'' Foxman said.
``It's as if somebody's made a decision to ignore the Jews, the
Muslims, the Hindus, the Buddhists, and here we are a country
that's moving more and more into'' a religiously diverse direction.
</P>
<P>
   It is as if two conflicting trends are occurring at once, Marty
said. ``We're more pluralistic and more particular at the same
time,'' he said. ``Figure out that paradox.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 1446EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
