<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0138 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2747 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-TWINN-DOLLS-REVIEW-55     12-18 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWINN-DOLLS-REVIEW-555&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FACE DEFINITELY LOOKS FAMILIAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., N.Y.)  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 By DOREEN CARVAJAL    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Earlier this month my 3-year-old daughter's body double arrived
in a UPS box, resplendent in a midnight-blue velour dress,
patent-leather shoes and dark coffee-bean eyes selected from a
range of 26 colors.
</P>
<P>
   At $150, it was the most money I had ever spent on a doll, so I
opened the cardboard box labeled ``My Twinn'' with some
apprehension. Inside rested my daughter's toy mate _ a 23-inch
figure swathed like a mummy in pink tissue, secured at the neck
with a rose ribbon tied in a bow.
</P>
<P>
   This was the ``one-of-a-kind personalized to look like your
child'' doll that I ordered for Christmas, but the customized
replica, with her unblinking eyes, gave me an eerie jolt.
Instinctively, I loosened the bow to let her breathe and hid her in
a closet.
</P>
<P>
   The My Twinn doll, personalized from a menu of skin tones, eye
shades and matching moles, has been around for about six years. It
was created by John Kudirka, a California emergency physician who
believed that replica dolls could build a child's confidence and
self-esteem.
</P>
<P>
   In 1995, he sold his business to the Flagship Group, a privately
held Colorado mail-order company that also runs a doll hospital
where exacting owners can return My Twinns for plastic surgery to
fix misplaced freckles or restyle bad haircuts.
</P>
<P>
   News articles have raised concerns that the dolls may be
inspiring narcissism, creating a plastic race of Stepford dolls
and, worst of all, stifling the imagination of children by giving
them clones for imaginary friends.
</P>
<P>
   Despite the cringe factor _ or perhaps because of it _ the dolls
continue to flourish as media creatures. In November, the dolls
appeared on ``The Oprah Winfrey Show'' in a segment called
``Oprah's favorite things'' that is scheduled to be rebroadcast on
Dec. 23.
</P>
<P>
   My Twinn dolls have actually appeared at least 200 times on
television and hundreds of times in newspaper articles, said David
Liggett, a company spokesman. ``Every year our business
increases,'' he said. ``One reason is the publicity, obviously.
Another reason is because a lot more people have our dolls, and
their friends and neighbors are finding out about it.''
</P>
<P>
   Liggett said he was unfazed by the cringe factor. ``It's obvious
in a market like this that if you think the doll is narcissistic,
you're not going to buy it.''
</P>
<P>
   People are clearly buying _ and sending in unsolicited letters
with photographs and effusive tributes. The testimonials come from
customers ranging from a 76-year-old Indiana grandmother, Opal
Patterson, who has created a tea party tableau of three dolls
matched to resemble her daughter and grandchildren at the age of 4,
to Jenny Vekich, a 31-year-old homemaker in Middleport, N.Y., who
bought a doll to mirror the look and periwinkle cotton dress of her
5-year-old daughter, Ryanne, on her first day of kindergarten.
</P>
<P>
   ``It looks so real that sometimes there are split seconds that I
walk into the living room and feel a slash of terror because I
think someone is in the house,'' said Mrs. Vekich. ``I've done it
four or five times and then I think _ `It's the doll.'''
</P>
<P>
   ``In a way I look at the doll as a gift to myself,'' she added.
``Ryanne is my oldest. I had my children close together and life
was such a whirlwind. And by the time I started slowing down, she's
going to school. So losing her was more traumatic for me.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   If dolls and toys reflect contemporary society, what do
personalized mates say about their times?
</P>
<P>
   In the history of play, toys are used as a ``socializing process
and a way to recreate the world and have control,'' said Eugene
Provenzo Jr., an education professor at the University of Miami who
studies toys and culture. ``Toys are also a way to practice life.
For example, in the colonial period dolls were used in mock
funerals with doll caskets'' because the mortality rate of children
was so high. ``In a certain sense,'' he said, ``children were
rehearsing to attend the funerals of their own friends.''
</P>
<P>
   My Twinn dolls are a reflection of today's sophisticated
technology, said Provenzo, but at the same time they may say more
about cultural values that emphasize the self, including an
``excessive interest in sculpting the body or working out or being
fit.''
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Provenzo said, it is better for a child to play with a
My Twinn doll than with one designed to talk or walk. He cited a
new doll that is programmed to repeat hundreds of expressions.
``What toy makers are doing there is controlling the play space,
and it's probably better for children to play with a simple doll.''
</P>
<P>
   Of course, there are certain questions when children play with
their replicas. To start with, what do you call your new friend?
(In the Vekich home, the parents used their daughter's middle name,
Naomi.)
</P>
<P>
   Then there is a broader question: Who gets to keep the doll when
the children grow up and leave home? When asked about this, Mrs.
Vekich responded with a long pause and an unfinished sentence
indicating that she didn't know: ``I think when she leaves home
...''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 1447EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0139 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 14:47 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4154 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-TWINN-DOLLS-REVIEW-55     12-18 0930
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TWINN-DOLLS-REVIEW-555&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE FACE DEFINITELY LOOKS FAMILIAR 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Ind., N.Y.)  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
