<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2748 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-PEANUTS-BASEBALL-REVI     12-18 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEANUTS-BASEBALL-REVIEW-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A 50-YEAR STREAK IN A GAME OF FAILURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 By ALAN SCHWARZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charlie Brown had just given up yet another home run when his
fussbudget right fielder, Lucy Van Pelt, walked in to the pitcher's
mound.
</P>
<P>
   ``I wonder why I do this,'' Charlie Brown grumbled. ``I wonder
why I stand out here day after day losing all these ball games. Why
do I do it?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Probably because it makes you happy,'' Lucy said. To which a
perturbed Charlie Brown yelped, ``You always have to be right,
don't you?''
</P>
<P>
   For 50 years, Charles Schulz tortured Charlie Brown through a
number of devices _ never letting him kick the football, entangling
him in the kite-eating tree, paralyzing him with fear before the
little red-haired girl. Yet none captured Schulz's fondness for
futility more deliciously than those involving baseball. Schulz,
77, who will end his ``Peanuts'' strip Jan. 4 to focus on treatment
for colon cancer, has called baseball his favorite motif of all.
</P>
<P>
   No pitcher yielded more homers and no manager squandered more
games than Charlie Brown, the game's most lovable loser. Line
drives disrobed him. Fastballs baffled him. He didn't need a tape
measure for his team's home runs because ``Our hits can be measured
quite adequately with an 18-inch ruler.''
</P>
<P>
   While New York Yankee fans complain about the error-prone Chuck
Knoblauch, imagine Charlie Brown's double-play combo: a beagle
catching balls in his mouth and spitting them _ ptui! _ to his
security-blanketed second baseman. His catcher knew more about
Beethoven than baseball. The team routinely got pounded 40-0,
123-0, even 200-0. But Charlie Brown always came back for more.
</P>
<P>
   ``I could draw baseball strips every day,'' Schulz said in a
1995 interview. ``It really is funny. Baseball is ideal because
little kids do play it at that age, and they aren't very good. But
they do suffer at it.''
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Brown got so tired of his team's losing that one day he
ran a classified ad, searching for a new managerial job. He
received one reply _ from his own team.
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Brown's favorite player, Joe Shlabotnik, once got
demoted to Stumptown of the Green Grass League after hitting .004.
(Shlabotnik was later fired as a manager because he called for a
steal of home with the bases empty.)
</P>
<P>
   Charlie Brown got so consumed with his baseball failures that
the sun, and soon his own head, turned into a baseball. He asked
his psychiatrist, ``Is this the last of the ninth?''
</P>
<P>
   In one of Schulz's more sadistic moments 30 years ago, he had
Charlie Brown's love for baseball betray him at what could have
been his finest moment. In his class spelling bee, he was asked to
spell ``maze.''
</P>
<P>
   ``M-A-Y-S.''
</P>
<P>
   AAAAUUUGGHHH!
</P>
<P>
   ``It's funny because it isn't happening to us,'' Schulz
explained.
</P>
<P>
   It has been said that this is a nation of failed baseball
players, and Schulz is no exception. His own persona as the hapless
underdog was cast when he was growing up in St. Paul, Minn., as a
good-field, no-hit catcher and third baseman. His team actually did
lose a game 40-0. Later, as a sergeant stationed in Germany during
World War II, Schulz got one of the thrills of his life simply by
playing a pickup game.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was so flattered that these guys should like some unknown
guy from Minnesota to be on their team,'' Schulz recalled. ``Isn't
that funny? Something as totally meaningless as that, really, in
the history of mankind and baseball, a game played in an unknown
area that didn't mean a thing, and yet it meant so much to me.
That's what sport does for us.''
</P>
<P>
   The first cartoon Schulz sold after the war displayed a little
boy and girl with the caption, ``Judy, if your batting average was
just a little higher I could really fall in love with you.''
</P>
<P>
   He began ``Peanuts'' in October 1950 and infused Charlie Brown
with his own struggles. Even as his strip became the world's most
popular, there was never a shortage of new material. This is a man
who, after being told by a fan how much she loved the strip, was
asked to draw Popeye. And even last Tuesday, after he announced his
retirement, the headline in The Portland (Maine) Press Herald read,
``George Schulz ....'' Good grief!
</P>
<P>
   Schulz made Charlie Brown fail at every turn because most
readers could relate better to losing than to winning. ``Victories
are fleeting,'' he said, ``but losses we always live with.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Schulz did get a little sentimental over the years, though _ in
part because of age, which he claimed he first felt when he
couldn't bend over to field a ground ball. In 1993, he finally let
Charlie Brown hit a game-winning home run. It turned out that the
pitcher threw one down the middle only because she felt sorry for
him.
</P>
<P>
   As America's ``We're No. 1!'' culture evolved around him, Schulz
provided a clubhouse, a 5-cent psychiatry booth, for all the No.
2s. Baseball, say the pros who actually can hit the ball three
times out of 10, is a game of failure. But Charlie Brown knew
failure more than anyone _ pure,
slink-back-home-with-your-bat-dragging failure _ and exuded it to
his fans' delight.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't realize how many Charlie Browns there were in the
world,'' Schulz said. ``I thought I was the only one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 1449EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0141 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 14:49 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A4155 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-PEANUTS-BASEBALL-REVI     12-18 0941
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-PEANUTS-BASEBALL-REVIEW-720&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A 50-YEAR STREAK IN A GAME OF FAILURE 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 By ALAN SCHWARZ   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charlie Brown had just given up yet another home run when his
fussbudget right fielder, Lucy Van Pelt, walked in to the pitcher's
mound.
</P>
