<SLUG> BC-POLITICS-BRIEFS-785(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICAL BRIEFS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Iowa, N.H., S.C., Ariz., La., Mich., Mass., Utah)  (jw) 
 By B. DRUMMOND AYRES Jr.    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   IOWA: INVISIBLE MAN CASTS A LONG SHADOW
</P>
<P>
   DES MOINES, Iowa _ For months, Sen. John McCain, R-Ariz., has
been insisting that he will not participate in Iowa's
first-in-the-nation caucuses next month. He says he has only
limited resources for his presidential quest and that in the early
going he will concentrate on New Hampshire, South Carolina and
Arizona.
</P>
<P>
   He has no organization in Iowa, has run no ads and has been in
the state only twice this year, once in April to hold a
congressional hearing on air fares (hardly a campaign appearance)
and again last Monday to participate in a debate with the other
Republican contenders (it was televised nationally, not just in
Iowa).
</P>
<P>
   So, as he says, he is not running in Iowa.
</P>
<P>
   And yet he is here.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his physical absence from the state, he was running a
strong third in one recent Iowa poll, closing fast on Steve Forbes,
who is spending a fortune, literally, to hang on to the No. 2 spot
as he chases the front-runner, Gov. George W. Bush of Texas.
</P>
<P>
   Further, reports of McCain's campaigning in other states show up
daily in Iowa newspapers and on Iowa television, and McCain bumper
stickers and placards can be spotted here and there. Periodically,
too, there have been reports that calls have been made around the
state on his behalf, though there is no evidence that he sanctioned
them.
</P>
<P>
   And then there was that closing remark in Monday's debate after
McCain had pinned a boondoggle label on the federal energy program
that subsidizes production of ethanol, a fuel additive made from
corn, a lot of it Iowa corn.
</P>
<P>
   In what was almost an aside, but not quite, he called for a
``hardy band of brave souls'' to turn out and vote for him on
caucus night, Jan. 24.
</P>
<P>
   What's going on here?
</P>
<P>
   A delicate political dance, as many Iowa political pros see it.
</P>
<P>
   The way they analyze the senator's acts and words, he is trying
to set up a win-win situation in which he keeps his profile as high
as possible in Iowa, but at the same time does not become so
involved in the state that he raises undue expectations about how
he will fare on caucus night.
</P>
<P>
   Or, as Dennis Goldford, a political scientist at Drake
University, put it the other day, if McCain should finish in the
top three in the caucuses without genuinely competing, he would be
entitled to ``some bragging rights'' on the eve of the next crucial
nominating test, the New Hampshire primary.
</P>
<P>
   But why the head-on McCain attack on ethanol in the nation's
leading corn-producing state?
</P>
<P>
   ``Two plausible reasons,'' says David Yepsen of The Des Moines
Register, the dean of the state's political reporters. ``One,
agriculture accounts for just 20 percent of the new,
much-diversified Iowa economy. Two, the Iowa vote is now more
diverse too, and a maverick reformer like McCain could have a
certain appeal here, as elsewhere around the country.''
</P>
<P>
   One thing more:
</P>
<P>
   He'll be back shortly for another debate.
</P>
<P>
   IOWA, LOUISIANA: THE BATTLE OF THE FIRST CAUCUS ENDS
</P>
<P>
   Speaking of the Iowa caucuses ...
</P>
<P>
   Election officials here need no longer worry that Louisiana
Republicans will try to slip in and hold their caucuses first, on
Jan. 15.
</P>
<P>
   The governing central committee of the Louisiana Republican
Party has decided to scrap that plan and instead hold a primary on
March 14. But the change didn't come without a bitter fight.
</P>
<P>
   The push for caucuses was led by leaders of the state's
Christian right, along with the party chairman, Mike Francis. They
figured that while the party's moderate wing, led by Gov. Mike
Foster, was probably more powerful, the Christian right wing was
better organized and more committed and thus could dominate the
caucuses.
</P>
<P>
   But in the end the Foster forces out-organized the Christian
right forces and last weekend the party's central committee voted
down the caucus proposal, 92-77.
</P>
<P>
   The governor, a Bush ally, declared after the vote that
``reasonable people made a reasonable decision, and I'm proud of
the Republican Party.'' He had been warning for weeks that the
caucuses would turn into an embarrassing political disaster because
most candidates would shy away from campaigning in Louisiana lest
they anger Iowa voters. And, in fact, only Gary Bauer, the family
values advocate, Alan Keyes, the conservative radio commentator,
and Sen. Orrin Hatch of Utah agreed to participate.
</P>
<P>
   Francis charged after the proposal was defeated that caucus
supporters, many of them strong backers of outspoken anti-abortion
candidates, such as Forbes and Bauer, had been ``intimidated and
threatened.''
</P>
<P>
   Four years ago, when Louisiana first tried to steal Iowa's
first-in-the-nation thunder, the caucuses were a political bust.
Most of the top candidates stayed away.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   MICHIGAN: SANTA TAKES SIDE IN SENATE RACE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Michigan is one of those states in which neither Democrats nor
Republicans consistently stay on the top of the political heap. So
it should come as no great surprise that next year's race for U.S.
Senate is tight.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, the race, in which Rep. Debbie Stabenow, a
moderate-to-liberal Democrat from Lansing, is trying to unseat the
conservative Republican incumbent, Spencer Abraham, is shaping up
as one of the most competitive congressional contests. And also one
of the most expensive.
</P>
<P>
   A new poll indicates that the race is a statistical tie.
</P>
<P>
   As for campaign spending, Abraham, who is seeking a second term,
is talking about spending upwards of $9 million and Ms. Stabenow,
first elected to the House in 1996, says she is confident she can
raise close to that amount.
</P>
<P>
   Abraham is considered a vulnerable target by Democrats as they
seek to reclaim control of the Senate not only because he is a
freshman legislator in a state that tends to be a swing state but
also because, according to pollsters, voters view him as a rather
subdued politician who in five years in office has failed to
establish a strong bond with them. He has pushed a conservative
agenda, including popular tax cuts, but many voters say they know
little about him.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Stabenow is a much more outgoing politician. But Abraham
says that however outgoing she may be, she nevertheless is too
liberal for the state.
</P>
<P>
   Recently he began running ads that accuse her of ducking tough
law-and-order issues, specifically for failing to condemn President
Clinton for granting clemency to Puerto Rican nationalists serving
time for terrorist acts.
</P>
<P>
   But last week the tables were turned and Abraham is now the
target of some ads as the race builds an ever bigger head of steam.
</P>
<P>
   In one that began running on Monday, sponsored by the Michigan
Democratic Party, a Christmas elf and Santa Claus decide that the
senator has been ``very, very naughty'' this year because of some
of his votes on health care.
</P>
<P>
   As Santa and the elf tell it, Abraham voted to protect health
maintenance organizations that make serious medical mistakes,
failed to push for cuts in drug prices and got ``lots of presents''
from insurance companies in return for helping them ``put profits
ahead of patients.''
</P>
<P>
   Santa: Meanwhile, he's been giving Michigan families a big lump
of coal.
</P>
<P>
   Elf: So no toys for Senator Abraham?
</P>
<P>
   Santa: Not unless he starts voting better. His votes on health
care are making everyone have a blue Christmas.
</P>
<P>
   Elf: Paid for by the Michigan Democratic Party.
</P>
<P>
   MASSACHUSETTS: HATCH DOES BETTER WITH DEMOCRATS
</P>
<P>
   Sen. Orrin Hatch was the last candidate to jump into the
Republican presidential contest. And in many polls he continues to
run exactly where he started _ last, sometimes pulling so little
support that pollsters put a zero next to his name.
</P>
<P>
   Such was the case when the Boston Globe last sampled Republicans
in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   But take heart, senator.
</P>
<P>
   When the Globe asked Democrats whom they would go for should
they decide to vote Republican, 1 percent chose Hatch.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
