<HEADER>
A2751 &Cx1f; var-z
u a BC-DRUG-TRIALS-REVIEW-NY     12-18 1091
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DRUG-TRIALS-REVIEW-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INSURERS COME IN FROM THE COLD ON CANCER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: N.J., Va.)  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(mk) 
 By GINA KOLATA and KURT EICHENWALD   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   During the six months when her 66-year-old father was dying from
cancer, Carolyn Aldige relied completely on doctors at Eastern
Virginia Medical Center for information. But, she says, none of
them ever mentioned the possibility that he might take part in a
clinical trial.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't even know what the words clinical trial meant,'' said
Ms. Aldige, who after that experience in the 1980s went on to found
the Cancer Research Foundation of America. ``I was just clueless.''
</P>
<P>
   Few doctors ever tell cancer patients about the option of
clinical trials _ research involving human subjects that remains
the only scientifically valid method of finding safe and effective
new treatments.
</P>
<P>
   Usually, participation in such trials seems impossible,
especially since the costs for tests and hospital stays can be
prohibitive. And historically, insurance companies have refused to
pay, saying that experimental treatments are not covered by their
policies.
</P>
<P>
   Now that is changing.
</P>
<P>
   In recent weeks a wide array of insurance companies have agreed
to pay for experimental cancer treatments administered to
policy-holders who participate in clinical trials sanctioned by
federal health agencies. It is a development that experts described
as momentous.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a very important step,'' said Dr. Henry Simmons,
president of the National Coalition on Health Care. ``Finally we've
recognized that you need a source of sufficient funding for
experimental therapy.''
</P>
<P>
   For almost two decades, cancer researchers in this country have
been fighting over inadequate federal payments for clinical trials.
As a result, they have often relied on money from drug companies,
which would only pay for experimental medications while often
leaving patients stuck with the related hospital and lab costs. But
the recent moves by the insurers now bring to the table a
potentially large source of cash and test subjects _ coming from a
third party with no vested interest in which treatment is best.
</P>
<P>
   This should improve what had been a situation in which just 3
percent to 5 percent of adult cancer patients enrolled in clinical
trials _ a dire circumstance that has actually impeded the search
for cures. Worse, doctors often independently sell experimental
procedures, siphoning off potential trial subjects.
</P>
<P>
   Programs intended to solve these problems are now catching on
across the country.
</P>
<P>
   In New Jersey, Gov. Christie Whitman announced on Thursday that
a coalition of insurers had agreed to pay for cancer patients to
receive experimental treatments in federally sanctioned clinical
studies.
</P>
<P>
   Even as that program was being developed, Coventry Health Care,
a managed care company with 1.4 million members in the Midwest,
South and mid-Atlantic regions, began a pilot program that also
pays for patients who enroll in valid studies testing new cancer
treatments. Earlier in the year, a similar program was begun by
United Healthcare, which covers 13 million Americans.
</P>
<P>
   Experts say the New Jersey initiative is the most significant.
There, for the first time, the insurers will work hand in hand with
state government, doctors and patient groups to spread the word
that patients can now participate in medical research at little to
no personal cost.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is probably the most important program in the nation
right now,'' said Dr. Robert Comis, the president of the National
Coalition of Cancer Cooperative Groups, the association of research
centers that conducts federally sanctioned trials. ``It's really
the first time that all the needed and required forces have come
together to address the problem.''
</P>
<P>
   Until now, relations between groups involved in experimental
procedures have been nothing short of adversarial.
</P>
<P>
   Doctors would offer the treatments outside of clinical trials.
</P>
<P>
   Insurance companies would refuse to pay, citing decades-old
precedents.
</P>
<P>
   Patients were caught in the middle, angry at their insurance
companies and unable to pay their doctors.
</P>
<P>
   Faced with desperate patients, courts and state legislatures
began to require the insurers to pay for experimental therapies,
regardless of whether they were being offered as part of a
sanctioned research study with the potential to advance medical
knowledge.
</P>
<P>
   Only in pediatric cancer research did doctors, insurers and
patient advocacy groups work together to make sure that children
could enroll in clinical trials. As a result, most of these
children do participate in research studies so that doctors can
quickly determine whether treatments work or not. That has
contributed to a significant decline in death rates for children
with cancer in the last few decades.
</P>
<P>
   Now, with the New Jersey initiative, medical experts believe
that a system is being put in place that could potentially bring
the successes seen in pediatric cancer to the adult world.
</P>
<P>
   The program could face some challenges.
</P>
<P>
   Not every patient will qualify to participate in research
programs, which could spur renewed trips to the courthouse. Only
this time, the insurance companies _ with support from doctors and
patient groups _ will be able to argue that their new policies
serve a broad societal interest, one that could allow promising
therapies to be tested quickly and made widely available.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, insurance industry executives said, the financial
consequences to the companies are negligible. Since the industry
has been forced to pay for experimental procedures offered outside
of trials, the costs of that coverage has already been incorporated
in their rate structure. That is one reason insurers expect to
offer this new benefit at no additional premium.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey initiative is already attracting national
attention. Insurers believe that if the effort there proves
successful it will only be a matter of time before similar programs
become a common feature of the American health care landscape.
</P>
<P>
   ``Other states are starting to call already,'' said Comis, who
is working with the New Jersey group. ``New Jersey will lead the
country.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 1452EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
