<P>
   CHINA-MACAU _ MACAU _ The checkered history of this indolent old
Portuguese enclave is about to end, and few are weeping as China
prepares to take over. Four hundred years ago Macau was far richer.
Portuguese traders dined on plates of gold because for a century
Portugal had a world monopoly on trade in silk, gold, porcelain and
silver with Japan and China. Twelve years ago, China and Portugal
had no trouble agreeing that the Portuguese should end their
occupation just before the millennium. Both sides have stuck to
this pact with little friction. And so on the evening of December
19, 2,500 guests from Portugal, Macau and China are due to gather
here just before midnight to toast the end of nearly 450 years of
Portuguese occupation. When the clock in the Macau cathedral
strikes 12 times, Portugal will lower its flag on the last and
oldest Western enclave in Asia. (Kunstel/Albright, Cox News
Service). WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
