<P>
   VPHISTORY _ WASHINGTON _ During a television interview this
fall, Democrat Bill Bradley was confronted with the weight of
history: no sitting vice president, his interviewer asserted, had
ever been defeated for his party's nomination. Not true, Bradley
responded. Vice President George Clinton lost to James Madison to
succeed President Jefferson _ in 1808. A far better historical
precedent, Bradley said, was the fact that George Bush was the
first vice president to win the presidency in 150 years. Bradley,
trying to wrest the nomination from Vice President Gore, was both
right and wrong. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
