<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2754 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-MA-BIKEPATH-DISPUTE-N     12-18 0961
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MA-BIKEPATH-DISPUTE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
TOWN DIVIDED BY PLAN TO REPLACE RAILS WITH TRAILS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Calif.)  (mk) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   WILLIAMSBURG, Mass. _ A two-and-a-half-mile abandoned rail
corridor in this Connecticut Valley hill town of 2,500 residents is
at the center of a heated dispute between champions of privacy and
community.
</P>
<P>
   Opponents of a bike path planned for the corridor where the New
Haven &AMP; Northampton Railroad once ran cast the debate as a property
rights issue. Supporters see narrow-minded self-interest blocking a
project that could preserve the environment, promote health and
help people connect.
</P>
<P>
   The battle mirrors others being waged nationwide.
</P>
<P>
   Of the estimated 300,000 miles of tracks laid in the United
States starting in the 1830s and peaking around 1920, about 160,000
miles are no longer used, said Craig Della Penna, a New England
representative of the Rails-to-Trails Conservancy. His
organization, based in Washington, envisions a web of
``rail-trails'' using these rights of way to connect communities
and eventually create a coast-to-coast bicycle route.
</P>
<P>
   Congress, recognizing that lost rail corridors would be
difficult to reconstitute if needed again, passed the Rail Banking
Act in 1983, effectively giving local and state governments the
first right to abandoned beds. Since then Congress has appropriated
close to half a billion dollars for trail construction.
</P>
<P>
   So far, 11,000 miles of trails have been built nationwide, and
19,000 more miles are in development, Della Penna said.
</P>
<P>
   But property rights advocates regard this transformation of
abandoned railroads as theft, because the properties were often
originally taken by eminent domain or the railroads were granted
easements.
</P>
<P>
   Nels Ackerson, a Washington, D.C., lawyer whose firm represents
opponents of the Williamsburg project, testified before Congress
two years ago that many beds assumed to be owned by railroads in
fact belonged to individuals along the lines and should revert to
them when the trains stop running.
</P>
<P>
   ``Trails proponents see opportunities for recreational uses and
often view my clients as greedy or disgruntled neighbors, rather
than as the owners of the land that is to be taken for the trail,''
Ackerson said.
</P>
<P>
   His firm represents 27 people in Williamsburg who claim title to
pieces of the proposed trail.
</P>
<P>
   Massachusetts Electric Co. purchased the corridor, thinking it
might be useful for power lines after train service ended in 1962.
</P>
<P>
   But Michael Pill, a local lawyer hired by Ackerson's firm, said
after researching the deeds that the utility purchased property the
railroad did not own. ``They bought the Brooklyn Bridge,'' Pill
said.
</P>
<P>
   Della Penna said it is unusual for opposition to such plans to
be as virulent as it is here.
</P>
<P>
   Many residents were taken aback, for example, when the
anti-trail group, Railtrail Impact Committee for the Hilltowns,
sent a letter this fall to everyone who signed a petition
supporting the project. The letter suggested that recipients might
be held liable for costs associated with the project if they did
not remove their names from the petition.
</P>
<P>
   Jean Hemenway, who was a member of the town's governing board
from 1970 to 1988, said she liked the idea of a bike path when it
was first raised 13 years ago, thinking it would be nice for
children to ride from one part of town to another without having to
use a state highway.
</P>
<P>
   A member of an early bike path committee, the author Tracy
Kidder, recalled the opposition from neighbors of the rail corridor
who feared that a paved trail would bring crime and debauchery into
their back yards. Kidder said one objection was that elderly women
would be subjected to the spectacle of spandex-clad men pedaling
past their windows.
</P>
<P>
   Planning was shelved because of difficulties securing federal
grants, Ms. Hemenway said, but it resumed four years ago after the
success of the nine-mile Norwottuck trail linking the college towns
of Amherst and Northampton, which neighbors Williamsburg.
</P>
<P>
   Three years ago, opponents of the project contacted the National
Association of Reversionary Property Owners for advice. NARPO, a
clearinghouse for rail-trail opponents around the country, is led
by Dick Welsh, a retired airline pilot who lives in La Quinta,
Calif.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet domain name of one NARPO chapter
(www.railtrail.org) is similar to that of the Rails-to-Trails
Conservancy (www.railtrails.org). The NARPO chapter's Web site
refers to bike path supporters as ``eco-nuts'' and communists and
contains a link to an article co-written by Welsh that offers
instruction on fighting trail projects.
</P>
<P>
   Acting on Welsh's suggestions, opponents of the Williamsburg
project videotaped meetings of the town's governing board for more
than two years while raising legal and procedural questions about
the project.
</P>
<P>
   The question of ownership is scheduled to go to mediation
between the corridor's neighbors and Massachusetts Electric in
January, but the town voted overwhelmingly in November to go ahead
with the project. Officials have said they want to go ahead, even
if that means using eminent domain to seize the land.
</P>
<P>
   The larger issue the dispute raises, Della Penna said, is
whether Americans want to isolate themselves or rekindle the sense
of community ``we used to have when we had places with sidewalks
and houses with front porches.''
</P>
<P>
   Rail-trails are ``America's new front porch,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Those sentiments do not sway Linda Rowley, who gave up a nursing
job to work full time fighting the bike path, which is right
outside her kitchen window.
</P>
<P>
   ``At what point does their opinion supersede my right to own my
property in peace and quiet?'' Ms. Rowley asked.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 1453EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0149 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 14:53 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2755 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-WOODWARD-OBIT19-COX     12-18 1764
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-WOODWARD-OBIT19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    SouthernBy Tom Bennett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ C. Vann Woodward, 91, the greatest living Southern
historian, died Friday at his home in Hamden, Conn., reportedly
suffering complications from a recent heart operation.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward had been retired from the Yale University faculty since
1977. He was a graduate of Atlanta's Emory University and began his
teaching career at Georgia Tech in the '30s.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward was ``the dominant force in Southern historiography,''
wrote biographer John Herbert Roper. Woodward was ``the one
historian whose works must be mastered and reckoned with by serious
students of Southern history,'' declared another biographer,
Elisabeth Muhlenfeld.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward's 1938 book, ``Tom Watson: Agrarian Rebel,'' is the
definitive work about the former Georgia senator and one of this
state's most important historical volumes, according to Judson C.
Ward Jr. of Emory University.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward's 1951 book, ``Origins of the New South, 1877-1913,''
won the Bancroft Prize for history-writing. It best states his
revisionist view of post-Reconstruction Southern history since the
Civil War and is universally regarded as his most important
scholarly contribution, according to Muhlenfeld.
</P>
<P>
   The most popular of Woodward's works, ``The Strange Career of
Jim Crow,'' was published in 1955 and traces the history of Jim
Crow segregation laws, including Atlanta's prior to the 1960s. With
more than 600,000 copies sold, the book has been called ``the
single most influential ever written on the history of American
race relations'' by James M. McPherson of Princeton University.
</P>
<P>
   Martin Luther King Jr. read from ``The Strange Career of Jim
Crow'' on the steps of the Alabama Capitol at the culmination of
the 1965 Selma march _ an epic protest in which Woodward himself
participated. King called Woodward's book ``the historical Bible of
the civil rights movement.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodward edited ``Mary Chesnut's Civil War,'' which won the 1982
Pulitzer Prize for history. He and Muhlenfeld edited ``The Private
Mary Chesnut: The Unpublished Civil War Diaries'' in 1984.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward debunked a host of myths about Southern history,
including:
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Redemption'' in the Compromise of 1877. According to
Woodward, the Southerners who agreed to support Rutherford B. Hayes
for president in exchange for his promise to remove federal troops
were not ``Redeemers,'' as they have been called, but ``greedy
opportunists'' anxious to make the South like the North through
industrial and commercial development.
</P>
<P>
   _ ``Historical continuity'' in the South through a return to
power in 1877 of antebellum leaders, maintaining an unbroken social
and economic order. In fact,. Woodward argued, prewar Whigs gained
power and thereafter ``New South'' politics was at odds with the
region's dominant agricultural economy.
</P>
<P>
   _ A ``Solid South,'' of one mind politically. In fact, the
populism that arose in the 1890s, and which had its principal
spokesman in Watson, demonstrated a diverse political environment.
</P>
<P>
   _ Jim Crow segregation laws were ancient and ingrained in
Southern life. Not so, said Woodward. Whites and blacks had
occupied train cars together and attended the same political
functions until the 1890s. Segregation laws were mainly the product
of a single generation.
</P>
<P>
   The influence of Woodward's books was so great, and his
arguments so convincing, that no rival historian challenged him for
decades. Then the challenges were minor, for example that he
neglected psychological insights in his Watson biography.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward was Sterling professor of History at Yale from 1961
until his retirement in 1977. He was a member of a triumvirate of
Southern literary greats there; the others were writer and poet
Robert Penn Warren _ who lured Woodward from Johns Hopkins _ and
literary critic Cleanth Brooks.
</P>
<P>
   Living a good deal of his life outside the South gave Woodward a
platform from which to view and comment on his native region. His
iconoclastic books disturbed many, but he made no apologies.
Looking back on his career, he wrote in 1986: ``I am on the whole
undismayed by the experience, and quite unrepentant.''
</P>
<P>
   Youth
</P>
<P>
   Comer Vann Woodward was born Nov. 13, 1908, in Vanndale, Ark., a
town near Memphis, Tenn., that is named for one of his maternal
ancestors. He grew up in Morrilton, Ark., 40 miles north of Little
Rock.
</P>
<P>
   His father, Hugh A. Woodward, was Morrilton school
superintendent and a leader in the Methodist church, and his mother
was Bess Vann Woodward.
</P>
<P>
   The future author studied for two years at Henderson Brown
College in Arkadelphia, Ark., intending to become a chemist.
However, in 1929 his father became associate dean of
Emory-at-Oxford, an affiliate of Atlanta's Emory University. The
young Woodward enrolled at the latter.
</P>
<P>
   He was ``a bright student and social nonconformist,'' according
to an alumni magazine profile. An uncle, an eminent socologist,
introduced Woodward to Will Alexander, chairman of the Commission
on Interracial Cooperation, later the Southern Regional Council.
Alexander introduced Woodward to black educators at crosstown
Atlanta University. One of the latter, J. Saunders Redding, was
``the first black man with whom I ever broke bread and exchanged
views as an equal,'' Woodward wrote.
</P>
<P>
   At an AU dance, Woodward asked a black girl to dance. ``I
embarrassed her and caused myself a good deal of notoriety and
distrust,'' he wrote later. ``Had I to do it over again, I'm not
certain I would.''
</P>
<P>
   He graduated from Emory with a degree in philosophy in 1930 and
got a job teaching English at Georgia Tech; an engineering school,
it also has liberal arts courses. At the same time, Woodward
studied at Columbia University in New York, and received a master's
degree in political science in 1932.
</P>
<P>
   While in New York, he knew black poet Langston Hughes and had a
role in a play in Harlem. In the summer of 1932, he traveled in
France, Russia and Germany. He was struck by Europeans' strong
feelings against the American South because of its treatment of the
``Scottsboro Boys,'' nine black Alabama youths convicted of raping
two white girls.
</P>
<P>
   At odds with Tech superiors
</P>
<P>
   Back in Atlanta in 1933, Woodward was a party to two events that
placed him at odds with his Georgia Tech superiors.
</P>
<P>
   The University System of Georgia reasoned that teachers taught,
and thus should be paid, only 10 months of the year. Woodward and
M.W. Blanton, another faculty member, filed a legal test of the
system in Superior Court and won. ``The case of Woodward and
Blanton v. Regents has become a landmark decision dealing with the
obligations of states and state agencies,'' according to lawyer
Hamilton Lokey.
</P>
<P>
   The second event of a combative year came when Woodward served
as vice-chairman of a defense committee for Angelo Herndon, a black
Communist sentenced to 18 years on a chain gang in 1933 for
distributing on the steps of the Fulton County Courthouse a
Communist Party leaflet calling for an end to segregation and
unemployment.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward ``left the Herndon committee ... disillusioned by
internal bickering and by Communist manipulation of the case for
propaganda purposes,'' according to Muhlenfeld. Woodward was fired
from his teaching position at Tech. He was ``admonished'' for
supporting Herndon, Woodward wrote, and officially fired because of
budget cuts. ``I left much the wiser,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   He looked around for a book subject who ``represented everything
I abhorred in the public life of the South.'' He found it in
Watson.
</P>
<P>
   After a year's research, Woodward ran out of money and sought a
fellowship. ``The logical place to go was the University of North
Carolina, which had Watson's private papers,'' he wrote. At UNC,
Woodward was taught and strongly influenced by Howard K. Beals, a
proponent of a progressive interpretation of history_that change
results from the conflict of economic interests. ``Tom Watson:
Agrarian Rebel'' was Woodward's thesis for Beals.
</P>
<P>
   Woodward received his doctorate in 1937. It is rare for a thesis
to be published in book form, but Woodward's was the following
year, when he was 29.
</P>
<P>
   During World War II, he was a naval officer who wrote three
classified books about battles. One of them, ``Battle of Leyte
Gulf,'' was declassified and published by Macmillan, and is
considered a definitive work on the naval battle.
</P>
<P>
   `Delusions, temptations and obsessions'
</P>
<P>
   Union Seminary's Reinhold Niebuhr, author of ``The Irony of
American History,'' was another scholar who influenced Woodward. In
the 1950s, as his native South braced to fight school integration,
the historian ``sought out the aging Niebuhr to address those
contemporary American delusions, temptations and obsessions that
absorbed and alarmed me.''
</P>
<P>
   He was one of a group of social scientists and historians who
aided the 1952-53 preparations of briefs and papers for the
historic school desegregation suit, Brown v. Board of Education of
Topeka. For the NAACP lawyers arguing the case, Woodward prepared a
paper on the Reconstruction era and how idealistic goals of the
period ``gave way to pragmatism of Northern and Southern whites,''
according to author Richard Kluger.
</P>
<P>
   In 1953, ``to distance myself and get perspective on the
South,'' Woodward lectured at the University of Tokyo. In 1954-55,
he was Harmsworth professor of American History at Oxford
University in England.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Strange Career of Jim Crow'' is the text of a series of
lectures that Woodward delivered at the University of Virginia in
1954. He was in England when the book was published. At first,
sales were so-so. As the civil rights revolution gained momentum,
``what had originated as a modest communication to a Southern
academic audience had swelled into a mass paperback publication of
vast numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Woodward has critical passages in the book about the city where
he spent his undergraduate days, began to teach, and was at odds
with his Tech employers. For example, Woodward describes a 1940
Atlanta ordinance segregating city parks that did not apply to ``so
much of Grant Park as is occupied by the zoo.'' Thus, Woodward
said, ``Only in the presence of the lower anthropoids could
law-abiding Atlantans of different races consort together.''
</P>
<P>
   He married Glenn MacLeod in 1937. She died of cancer at 71 in
1982. Their son, Peter, died of melanoma at 26 in 1971.
</P>
<P>
   There are no immediate survivors.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
