<HEADER>
A2767 &Cx1f; taf-z
u v BC-OUTLOOK-BIZ-BUDGET-2T     12-18 1713
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OUTLOOK-BIZ-BUDGET-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
  
(jt) 
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; FOR USE MONDAY, DEC. 20 AND THEREAFTER &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   EDITORS: The New York Times News Service plans the following
stories from the year-end Business Outlook section of The Times,
which is being published Monday, Dec. 20:
</P>
<P>
   (The stories and accompanying artwork will move beginning Sunday
afternoon in the ``f'' news file. This material replaces the Monday
Business section of The Times.)
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-INTERNET-ECONOMY (Undated) _ Historians say the Internet
should be viewed mainly as the latest advance in communications, a
successor to the telegraph and the telephone, more a technological
step than a leap forward. Still, whether labeled a revolution or an
evolution, the Internet's impact on the economy seems destined to
become greater and greater. By Steve Lohr. (With graphic showing
business investment in computers, peripherals and software.)
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-REFLECTIONS (Undated) _ When eight well-known executives
were asked to sum up the most important characteristics of the last
100 years in an epitaph for the 20th century, they invariably
talked about the powerful impact of technology in all its myriad
forms: the airplane, television, computers and the Internet. By
Reed Abelson.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-READER-VISIONS (Undated) _ Asked for proposals to
improve the human condition in the next century, people were
generous with their ideas. Many visions fell into broad categories
like health, nutrition, education and transportation. This article
offers a sampling of responses.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-DEMOGRAPHICS (Undated) _ Five years into a booming
economy, America is ``depleting its pool of available workers'' _ a
warning often heard from Alan Greenspan. But beyond the pool of
known recruits lies another mass of untapped labor that can supply
an expanding work force _ and sustain a robust economy _ into the
new decade. This labor in reserve consists mainly of women and
potential immigrants. By Louis Uchitelle. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-FED (Undated) _ A look at the past and future of the
Federal Reserve, which has risen from virtual obscurity to near
omnipotence. By Richard W. Stevenson. (With graphic showing GDP for
the last 100 years.)
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-CURRENCY (Undated) _ The history of money and its
future. The century began with a universal money _ gold _ and ends
with gold all but eliminated. In its place are national currencies,
some floating, some fixed to major currencies and one supernational
currency, the euro. A look at what lies ahead. By Floyd Norris.
(With graphic showing the value of the U.S. dollar since 1900.)
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-BIOTECH (Undated) _ For several years, the big quest in
biotechnology has been to determine the complete sequence of human
DNA, the genetic code of life. Now, however, that task is nearing
completion, and the biotechnology industry is facing an even
tougher job _ deciphering that code so that new drugs and
diagnostic tests can be developed. By Andrew Pollack. (With graphic
on biotech stocks.)
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-AGRICULTURE (Undated) _ Agribusiness leaders are as
confident as ever that the need to feed a growing world population
makes it both essential and inevitable that biotechnology will play
a central role in 21st century farming. But for now it looks like
the industry may be pulled over by consumers and fined by investors
for recklessly speeding toward such a future. By Barnaby J. Feder.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-HEALTH (Undated) _ Americans who have complaints about
the health care system may soon be in luck _ or maybe not. Many
health care professionals expect the medical system in the United
States to be overhauled so remarkably during the next two decades
that many patients will not be able to recognize it. By David J.
Morrow.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-AUTOS (Jackson, Mich.) _ A look at how the car-buying
experience may change in the coming decades. By Keith Bradsher.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-AIRCRAFT (Washington) _ Aviation, which enters its
second century in 2003, is still far from a mature industry, and
for the next decade it seems likely to move in two directions at
once. By Matthew L. Wald.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-OIL (Undated) _ Of all the pressures on the oil industry
as the century turns, the one most likely to transform it over the
next two decades, industry experts say, will be the fervent
campaign to improve the environment. By Kenneth N. Gilpin. (With
graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-BANKS-REED (Undated) _ As a young Citicorp executive
more than 20 years ago, John S. Reed earned a reputation as a
technology guru. Reed is now co-chief executive of Citigroup, the
country's largest financial services concern and the creation of
last year's merger of Citicorp and Travelers Group. But for all his
interest in technology, Reed admitted in an interview that the
impact and importance of the Internet escaped his attention until
recently. By Timothy L. O'Brien.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-BANKS (Undated) _ In the wake of the historic changes
made by Congress this year in laws that separated commercial banks,
investment banks and insurance companies, a wave of consolidation
is expected among financial services companies, creating more
conglomerates like Citigroup, the first company in the United
States to combine an insurer with a commercial bank, an investment
bank and a securities brokerage firm, the experts say. By Patrick
McGeehan. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-SHOPPING (Undated) _ The changes remaking retailing come
not only in the medium shoppers use to make their purchases but in
what they expect their dollars to buy _ which is a lot more than
they did even five years ago. In the end, it is less the Internet
that is transforming traditional retailing as this century closes,
than one giant discounter: Wal-Mart Stores. By Leslie Kaufman.
(Graphic showing Wal-Mart vs. online retailers.)
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-HOTELS (Undated) _ A look at trends that will take the
hotel industry profitably into the next decade. By Edwin McDowell.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-BLOOPERS (Undated) _ A look at the century's biggest
business blunders. By Floyd Norris. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-SCAMS (Undated) _ A look back at the century's major
scandals. By Diana B. Henriques.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-COMPUTERS (Undated) _ If using the Internet rather than
spread sheets and word processors is driving the growth of the
personal computer industry, then mobile access to the Internet is
likely to dominate in short order. Who could possibly argue that
surfing the Web while trapped sitting in a chair at a desk is
natural or inevitable? The one flaw in this argument is that PC
sales are not shrinking. By John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-INTERNET-DAD (Undated) _ The Internet has many fathers,
but few deserve the label more than Robert W. Taylor. In 1966, as a
director of the Pentagon's Advanced Research Projects Agency
Information Processing Techniques Office, Taylor came up with the
idea for the Internet's precursor, the ARPAnet. An interview. By
John Markoff.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-WEB-SOFTWARE (Undated) _ If 1999 was the year everyone
started saying that Internet-based software would replace
conventional programs, 2000 will surely be the year the transition
begins in earnest. By Lawrence M. Fisher.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-INTERNET (Undated) _ Future developments in the Internet
regarding business should come in waves. Those who are studying the
relationship between business and the still-primitive and slow
Internet say that in five or 10 years those waves could well
reshape the way business is conducted. This transformation will
happen because, very basically but profoundly, the Internet permits
ease and breadth of communication, provides newfound mobility and
allows complex transactions to take place among numerous parties in
far-flung regions. By Matt Richtel.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-E-COMMERCE (Undated) _ Ten years ago, Internet
prognosticators sounded overzealous when they suggested that a
network of computers would recast every facet of society. Some of
the most futuristic and utopian predictions may never play out, of
course. But the Net does seem to be bringing irrevocable change to
one part of life: buying stuff. The E-commerce column. By Bob
Tedeschi.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-COMMUNICATIONS (Undated) _ Over the last decade,
cellular telephones have evolved from oddity to indulgence to
everyday accessory. Discuss the future of wireless technology with
leading communications executives, and the words ``phone'' and
``telephone'' may not be used at all. That is because they see the
future of wireless technology as having little to do with talking
and everything to do with putting the Internet into pockets and
purses around the world. By Seth Schiesel.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-PATENTS (Undated) _ The patents column: The debate, and
resulting litigation, over the importance of patents in the
Internet's development. By Teresa Riordan.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-NEWSPAPERS (Undated) _ Challenged to recreate themselves
both online and in print, newspapers _ and their advertisers _ have
a greater appetite for information about their appeal, their
audiences and their competition than ever, according to both those
who gather data on the Internet and those who use the data. By
Felicity Barringer.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-AD-COLUMN (Undated) _ Shakespeare's exclamation ``O
brave new world'' is an appropriate way to begin an examination of
what advertising will be like when years no longer begin with 19.
It is even more appropriate that those words are from ``The
Tempest'' because the changes facing Madison Avenue in the next
decade will be nothing if not tumultuous. By Stuart Elliott. (With
graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-MOVIES (San Francisco) _ Throughout the entertainment
industry, from the major studios to Internet start-up companies,
people are attempting to figure out how the rapidly emerging
digital technology will affect the movies people see and the ways
they see them. By Rick Lyman.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-TELEVISION (Undated) _ Although executives in the worlds
of television and entertainment are not entirely certain about the
details of the convergence of television, computers and broadband
cable systems, all agree that the experience of watching television
will prove extraordinarily different in 26 years from today's
viewing. By Bernard Weinraub.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-WALLSTREET (Undated) _ Electronic trading is driving new
market structures, so Wall Street is approaching the new millennium
the way superstitious pilots approach the Bermuda Triangle _
fearing the worst, hoping for the best but prepared for just about
anything. By Diana B. Henriques. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-MARKETS (Undated) _ The upward march of the stock market
indexes has become so inexorable in recent years that most
strategists no longer weigh whether the market will rise next year.
Instead, they speculate on just how much higher it will go. By
Gretchen Morgenson. (with graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-INTERNET-INTERVIEW (Undated) _ Last month, with about
six weeks left in the century, Mary Meeker, head of the Internet
research team at Morgan Stanley Dean Witter, and Jeff Camp, who
follows Internet data services for the firm, sat down to talk about
the future of Internet stocks. By Kenneth N. Gilpin.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-MUTFUNDS (Undated) _ Are the mutual fund industry's best
days behind it? Sales gains are slowing. Fund company stocks are
lagging. Some fund investors have taken their big gains and cashed
in. And challenges from cheaper institutionalized money managers,
online brokerage firms and other new competitors have led some
analysts to predict that the industry is only starting to see tough
times. By Richard A. Oppel Jr. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-COMMODITIES (Undated) _ If the decade of the '90s was
the greatest ever for stock prices, it was one of the poorer for
commodity prices. But as the decade ends, there are signs of life
in commodities. By Jonathan Fuerbringer. (With graphic showing the
CRB Index since 1990.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-INTEREST-RATES (Undated) _ Inflation is calm. The
Federal Reserve is vigilant. And the Federal budget deficit has
disappeared. So conditions should be right for long-term interest
rates finally to fall decisively below 5 percent, a level they have
seen only briefly in the final third of the century about to end.
Maybe. By Jonathan Fuerbringer. (With graphic showing interest
rates since 1900.)
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-WORKPLACE (Undated) _ Across the country, thousands of
people who tried working from home part time during the 1990s have
returned to the office full time. It is enough to make one wonder
whether the workplace of the early 21st century will in fact
resemble a traditional office much more than was once thought. Do
not be fooled, workplace experts say, contending that in reality
this is the lull before the telecommuting storm. By David
Leonhardt.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-CORPORATIONS (Undated) _ For five years a klatch of
management scholars and forward-looking executives has met at the
Sloan School of Management at the Massachusetts Institute of
Technology to ponder a question: What will be tomorrow's model for
business success? By Fred Andrews.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-GLOBAL (Washington) _ A decade ago it would have been
hard to imagine that at the end of the century the world economy
would mix unparalleled American ascendancy with such pervasive
global anxiety, or that free-marketeers would be celebrating the
triumph of market capitalism while so many around the globe
questioned the cost of its victory. By David E. Sanger. (With
graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-JAPAN (Tokyo) _ To almost everyone's surprise, the
Japanese economy showed remarkable _ and remarkably diverse _ signs
of life this year. But there are many contradictions in the
economy, making it difficult to be either optimistic or pessimistic
when it comes to Japan's prospects as the century turns. By
Stephanie Strom.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-CHINA (Beijing) _ When negotiators from China and the
United States clinked their champagne glasses here last month to
celebrate a trade agreement between the two countries, nobody
exulted more than China's Internet entrepreneurs. The deal, which
opens the door to China's entry into the World Trade Organization,
will also allow foreign companies to own stakes of up to 50 percent
in Chinese Internet companies by 2006. By Mark Landler.
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-RUSSIA (Moscow) _ After weathering a year of debt
defaults, a currency crash, an absentee president and governments
that change with the seasons, Russians have one piece of good news:
The economy has not collapsed. By Neela Banerjee. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-EUROPE (Frankfurt, Germany) _ Europe enters the new year
and the new millennium on a mission of staggering scale: an
expansion of the European Union by 13 countries and some 170
million people. By Edmund L. Andrews. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-LATIN-AMERICA (Rio de Janeiro, Brazil) _ On the theory
that things cannot get much worse, Latin America is looking to the
start of the new decade with anticipation. The past year has been a
difficult one, more onerous even than the crisis that followed the
Mexican meltdown in December 1994: It began with a currency
collapse in Brazil, included a bond default in Ecuador and, with
the numbers now toted up, is concluding with most of the region's
large economies struggling to emerge from recession. By Larry
Rohter. (With graphic.)
</P>
<P>
   OUTLOOK-ASIA (Singapore) _ Southeast Asia's battered economies
have bounced back this year, and the most serious concern in the
year 2000, economists say, will not be the region's enduring
banking mess but the possibility that things could unexpectedly
turn ugly in the United States or Japan. By Wayne Arnold. (With
graphic.)
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
