</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-THISWEEK-REVIEW-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HIGHLIGHTS OF THE PAST WEEK 
</HEADLINE>
  (The Week in Review) 
(NOTE TO INTERNATIONAL CLIENTS: For use by special arrangement
only. Asian and European points: Call Karl Horwitz in Paris for
details and prices, phone: 47 42 17 11; fax: 47-42-80-44). Latin
American points: Call Olivia Vasquez in Los Angeles, phone:
310-996-0075; fax: 310-996-0089). 
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   After coexisting uneasily for 50 years in a state of war and for
the last four years in cold silence, Israel and Syria have agreed
to agree. President Clinton announced that the two countries would
begin intensive and accelerated peace talks Jan. 3 at a site near
Washington, to be determined.
</P>
<P>
   ``Over the past 48 hours, Israel and Syria have taken critical
steps in the journey toward peace,'' Clinton said at the White
House, flanked by Prime Minister Ehud Barak of Israel and Foreign
Minister Farouk al-Sharaa of Syria. ``The journey will be a
difficult one. But with courage and perseverance on both sides, the
result will be deeply rewarding to the people of Israel and to the
people of Syria.''
</P>
<P>
   No deadline was set for reaching agreement on issues that
include borders, security, terrorism, water rights and economic
relations.
</P>
<P>
   New York Escapes a Strike
</P>
<P>
   For days, a contract dispute involving New York City's transit
workers had shaped up as a heavyweight bout between Mayor Rudolph
Giuliani and Local 100 of the Transport Workers Union. The mayor
threatened to hit the union with huge fines if it went on strike.
But minutes after the strike deadline passed, union and transit
officials agreed on a tentative contract that would increase the
pay of bus and subway workers by more than 18 percent over three
years.
</P>
<P>
   Giuliani boasted that his forceful leadership had averted a
strike. And Willie James, the union's president, declared that
after a decade of concessions and austerity he had won the most
generous contract received by the city's public-sector workers
since the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   _ STEVEN GREENHOUSE
</P>
<P>
   Finger-Pointing on Rwanda
</P>
<P>
   In a scathing report that he commissioned, Secretary-General
Kofi Annan and other high-ranking U.N. officials were described as
weak and ineffectual in stopping the genocide in Rwanda in 1994.
Annan is a former head of the U.N. peacekeeping department.
</P>
<P>
   The report found that the United Nations was unable or unwilling
to prevent attacks by Hutu militias on Tutsi and moderate Hutu that
left at least 800,000 people dead. But the inquiry commission also
blamed members of the Security Council, mainly the United States,
saying they played down warnings and failed to authorize a strong
response to the genocide.
</P>
<P>
   _ BARBARA CROSSETTE
</P>
<P>
   Monsanto Sued Over Seeds
</P>
<P>
   Monsanto Co., which has vowed to create sustainable agriculture
through the use of genetically engineered crops, was hit with a
class-action lawsuit by antitrust lawyers who claim that Monsanto
rushed genetically engineered corn and soybean seeds to the
marketplace without testing them for safety.
</P>
<P>
   The suit, filed on behalf of a group of small farmers and
environmental groups, also charges Monsanto with leading an
international cartel that has fixed prices in the seed market and
stifled competition in the market for bioengineered crops. Monsanto
executives denounced the suit and said its products are entirely
safe.
</P>
<P>
   _ DAVID BARBOZA
</P>
<P>
   San Francisco Keeps a Mayor
</P>
<P>
   It took a run-off election, perhaps $2 million in political
action committee money and $3 million from his campaign coffers,
but the irrepressible mayor of San Francisco, Willie Brown, finally
won his bid for re-election _ and did so in a landslide.
</P>
<P>
   Brown, the city's first black mayor, and his opponent, Tom
Ammiano, the gay president of the board of supervisors, were billed
as Liberal and Liberal-er. In the end, Brown said, his appeal to
more conservative Asian voters and homeowners won the day.
</P>
<P>
   _ EVELYN NIEVES
</P>
<P>
   Setback for Linda Tripp
</P>
<P>
   When Linda Tripp first approached federal prosecutors saying she
had tapes showing that President Clinton had a affair with an
intern named Monica Lewinsky, she knew she might have violated
Maryland's law against secret taping.
</P>
<P>
   She asked the federal prosecutors for immunity and received it,
but a state judge has ruled that this did not protect her from
prosecution in Maryland.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the week, after Ms. Lewinsky testified that the
taping was done without her consent, Mrs. Tripp moved closer to
facing a criminal trial next month.
</P>
<P>
   _ NEIL A. LEWIS
</P>
<P>
   Nazi Slave Fund Created
</P>
<P>
   More than a half-century after the defeat of Hitler, German
corporations and the government have agreed to create a $5.2
billion fund to compensate slave laborers in Nazi Germany and other
victims of the Holocaust. The agreement followed difficult
negotiations with U.S. Jewish groups and class-action lawyers, who
have filed lawsuits against scores of German companies and
financial institutions. A big challenge lies ahead: actually
getting the money to surviving workers, most of whom live in
central Europe and Russia.
</P>
<P>
   _ EDMUND L. ANDREWS
</P>
<P>
   Support for Ritalin Use
</P>
<P>
   A landmark study found the drug Ritalin to be the most effective
form of treatment for children with attention deficit hyperactivity
disorder. In a study of 579 children in six communities, Ritalin
was found to be more effective than intensive behavior-modification
therapy and standard treatments in the communities.
</P>
<P>
   Ritalin has been a subject of debate for decades, prompted by
concerns that the drug could cause addiction or violence. The fears
were unfounded, the researchers said.
</P>
<P>
   _ HOLCOMB B. NOBLE
</P>
<P>
   Weapons Scientist Held
</P>
<P>
   A former scientist at Los Alamos National Laboratory was held
without bail after pleading not guilty to charges that he had
illegally transferred and copied vast amounts of classified
information related to the U.S. nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials say that Wen Ho Lee, who was arrested Dec.
10, transferred secret data from a classified computer network at
Los Alamos into an unsecure system, and then copied the information
onto computer tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Lee is known to have copied nuclear secrets onto 10 high-volume
computer tapes, and seven of those tapes are still missing, the
government said.
</P>
<P>
   _ JAMES RISEN
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Home Improvements for Gore
</P>
<P>
   Over the last six years, Democratic donors have contributed more
than $1 million to make improvements in Vice President Al Gore's
official residence _ everything from new landscaping to a hot tub,
a steam shower and a billiard table. Gore's 33-room Victorian home
in Washington is supported by tax dollars, but the additional
contributions pay for things that the government does not cover.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Public Integrity, a Washington nonprofit group,
reported that donations came from such corporations as Coca-Cola
and General Motors, while individuals gave cash or gifts worth up
to $30,000, far above the amounts they could give directly to
Gore's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   _ LESLIE WAYNE
</P>
<P>
   Police Inquiry in Los Angeles
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, a city where drama is often ripped from the
headlines, the headlines seem stolen from drama in a widening
investigation into police corruption. So far, more than a dozen
officers have been dismissed or suspended from duty after one of
them confessed to shooting, and then framing, an unarmed suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and public defenders now say that as many as 3,000
cases may need to be reviewed for possible false testimony by
officers.
</P>
<P>
   _ TODD S. PURDUM
</P>
<P>
   Sentencing in Louima Case
</P>
<P>
   The former police officer convicted of torturing Abner Louima in
a police station-house bathroom in 1997 was sentenced to 30 years
in prison. Justin Volpe, 27, could have received life behind bars
without the possibility of parole. Under the sentence imposed by
Judge Eugene Nickerson in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn, N.Y., he
could be freed in 25 years if he behaves well in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe apologized to Louima for ramming a stick into his rectum,
inflicting severe internal injuries, after arresting him in a
street brawl. Nickerson called the assault a ``barbarous misuse of
power.''
</P>
<P>
   _ JOSEPH P. FRIED
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 1527EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
