   A former scientist at Los Alamos National Laboratory was held
without bail after pleading not guilty to charges that he had
illegally transferred and copied vast amounts of classified
information related to the U.S. nuclear arsenal.
</P>
<P>
   Government officials say that Wen Ho Lee, who was arrested Dec.
10, transferred secret data from a classified computer network at
Los Alamos into an unsecure system, and then copied the information
onto computer tapes.
</P>
<P>
   Lee is known to have copied nuclear secrets onto 10 high-volume
computer tapes, and seven of those tapes are still missing, the
government said.
</P>
<P>
   _ JAMES RISEN
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Home Improvements for Gore
</P>
<P>
   Over the last six years, Democratic donors have contributed more
than $1 million to make improvements in Vice President Al Gore's
official residence _ everything from new landscaping to a hot tub,
a steam shower and a billiard table. Gore's 33-room Victorian home
in Washington is supported by tax dollars, but the additional
contributions pay for things that the government does not cover.
</P>
<P>
   The Center for Public Integrity, a Washington nonprofit group,
reported that donations came from such corporations as Coca-Cola
and General Motors, while individuals gave cash or gifts worth up
to $30,000, far above the amounts they could give directly to
Gore's campaign.
</P>
<P>
   _ LESLIE WAYNE
</P>
<P>
   Police Inquiry in Los Angeles
</P>
<P>
   In Los Angeles, a city where drama is often ripped from the
headlines, the headlines seem stolen from drama in a widening
investigation into police corruption. So far, more than a dozen
officers have been dismissed or suspended from duty after one of
them confessed to shooting, and then framing, an unarmed suspect.
</P>
<P>
   Prosecutors and public defenders now say that as many as 3,000
cases may need to be reviewed for possible false testimony by
officers.
</P>
<P>
   _ TODD S. PURDUM
</P>
<P>
   Sentencing in Louima Case
</P>
<P>
   The former police officer convicted of torturing Abner Louima in
a police station-house bathroom in 1997 was sentenced to 30 years
in prison. Justin Volpe, 27, could have received life behind bars
without the possibility of parole. Under the sentence imposed by
Judge Eugene Nickerson in U.S. District Court in Brooklyn, N.Y., he
could be freed in 25 years if he behaves well in prison.
</P>
<P>
   Volpe apologized to Louima for ramming a stick into his rectum,
inflicting severe internal injuries, after arresting him in a
street brawl. Nickerson called the assault a ``barbarous misuse of
power.''
</P>
<P>
   _ JOSEPH P. FRIED
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 1528EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0158 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 15:28 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2771 &Cx1f; taf-z
u p BC-NJ-BRADLEY-900(2TAKES     12-18 0939
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NJ-BRADLEY-900(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
POLITICIANS AT HOME REMAIN COOL TO BRADLEY CANDIDACY
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By DAVID M. HALBFINGER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   TRENTON, N.J. _ Robert Menendez remembers the first time he went
to bat for Bill Bradley, defying the Hudson County political
machine in 1978 to support a retired basketball star who had never
held elective office.
</P>
<P>
   Menendez, who is now one of a number of prominent Democrats in
New Jersey who have publicly rebuffed Bradley and endorsed Vice
President Al Gore in the presidential race, even guided the
candidate through a political tour of the county that took place on
the day that Menendez's father died of a heart attack.
</P>
<P>
   And he remembers what happened when he asked Bradley to go to
bat for him 14 years later. Menendez, who went on to become Union
City's mayor and later a state assemblyman and state senator, was
making his own run for Congress. But when he asked Bradley to
support him in the Democratic primary, he was turned down.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a very disappointing moment,'' said Menendez, who
nonetheless won election to the House, where he continues to
represent the 13th District. ``I asked him to support me in the
primary, and he would not. He said it was his policy not to get
involved in races where Democrats were fighting each other. I said,
`Two things: You don't know him, and remember what I did for you.
And, if I didn't have a primary opponent, I wouldn't need your
endorsement.'''
</P>
<P>
   The pain in Menendez's voice sounds undiminished by the
intervening years as he tells this story, though he has been
telling it often lately. And when Sen. Frank Lautenberg, D-N.J.,
campaigned in New Hampshire with Gore on Friday it was a vivid
reminder that Bradley could not count on political support from his
home-state colleagues.
</P>
<P>
   Considering Bradley's popularity during his three terms in the
Senate, one might have expected to find Democrats throughout the
state uniting behind the first New Jerseyan to take a credible shot
at the White House since Woodrow Wilson. But while the roster of
Bradley's supporters in his home state includes dozens of officials
at the local and county levels eager to attach themselves to the
coattails of a favorite son, there are striking omissions _ and not
one member of the delegation in which he served for 18 years.
</P>
<P>
   Lautenberg, who endorsed Gore months ago, drew attention to his
support before Friday night's debate between Gore and Bradley. Rep.
Frank Pallone of Long Branch, who does not speak ill of Bradley,
nonetheless is backing Gore. And Rep. Donald Payne of Newark, who
has not formally endorsed Gore, has praised the vice president
while describing Bradley as somewhat distant.
</P>
<P>
   Still, Bradley's popularity among New Jersey's voters is widely
acknowledged, and he would be expected to beat Gore easily in the
state's Democratic primary in June, although backers of both men
believe the race will be decided well before then.
</P>
<P>
   But aides to Gore suggest that Bradley's problems in New Jersey
are reminiscent of Sen. John McCain's frosty relations with his
fellow Republicans in Arizona, among them Gov. Jane Dee Hull, who
has endorsed Gov. George W. Bush of Texas for president. Her
remarks about McCain's temper set off a wave of speculation about
his emotional fitness.
</P>
<P>
   In Bradley's case, however, what seems to have alienated many
New Jersey Democrats, or at least left them with mixed feelings
about him, is not so much a perceived character flaw as some of the
same choices, convictions and experiences that he has tried to turn
into selling points for a national audience.
</P>
<P>
   Bradley makes much in his campaign speeches of his three-year
hiatus from politics, for example, when he traveled the country
giving speeches, consulting and teaching. But his absence from the
political scene won him few friends at home. Victor Scudiery,
chairman of the Monmouth County Democratic Committee, recalled
asking Bradley to attend a party function after his retirement from
the Senate. ``He stated to me that he doesn't do those things
anymore,'' Scudiery said. ``Those are the exact words, and they
still ring in my ears.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody talks about our favorite son,'' he added. ``My
father said, `If you leave the nest and the family, you better
start apologizing when you come back.'''
</P>
<P>
   One longtime friend and supporter in state politics who has
endorsed Bradley for president said: ``With Bill Bradley, a lot of
the time it's a one-way street. That's just Bill.''
</P>
<P>
   Bradley's aides and allies in New Jersey respond to such
criticisms by calling Bradley's lack of interest in logrolling with
local politicians a virtue. ``John Kennedy wasn't the greatest
senator for Massachusetts,'' said state Sen. John Lynch. ``He
wasn't part of the club, and he didn't play inside baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Richard Codey, the state Senate minority leader, said: ``Bill
was not the stereotypical pol at all. Among some politicians, that
could be a weakness. He's not going to stay at the bar and make
some deals on federal judgeships. That's not him. And that's a
strength.''
</P>
<P>
   And Emma Byrne, a longtime adviser to Bradley, noted that he had
invested heavily in the machinery of politics, helping to build the
first statewide voter database in New Jersey, for example. ``Bill
has always believed in investing in the institution of the party,
not about being a political boss,'' she said. ``We have state
chairmen for that. It wasn't like he neglected or walked away from
the party, or from trying to help elect Democrats.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Sen. Robert Torricelli, D-N.J., who has not yet
taken sides in the presidential campaign, said Bradley, whom he
succeeded, was always ``a little bit different.''
</P>
<P>
   ``The most revealing comment I've heard about Bill Bradley was
from Bill Bradley _ when he said the people he most admired were
Jimmy Carter, Woodrow Wilson and Mikhail Gorbachev,'' he said. ``It
was a telling moment, because none of those people had good local
political skills or worked well within the institutions of their
time. But each was a visionary, each set important goals and made a
contribution. I can see that's a list where Bill Bradley would be
comfortable.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, Bradley delivered in his own way for New Jersey
residents; one of his final achievements in office, for instance,
was to preserve Sterling Forest, the largest remaining tract of
unprotected woodlands along the New York-New Jersey border. But the
vice president has cultivated important politicians in the state
throughout his seven years in office, Democratic officials say _
working with Menendez on dredging the shipping channel to create
jobs for longshoremen, for example, and with Mayor Sharpe James of
Newark on demolishing high-rise housing projects.
</P>
<P>
   The New Jersey official who has been most critical of Bradley,
in fact, is James, who questioned Bradley's political skills and
even his sincerity, the most essential element of his largely
image-driven campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was good for the Senate, because he challenged them
on issues,'' James said. ``But to be the chief executive, where you
have to make rapid decisions, you have to know the art of
compromise, you really have to have sensitivity to people, where
you really want to shake people's hands. He doesn't have that
warmth and sensitivity. He's now on a mission of charade.''
</P>
<P>
   James, who recounted several events at which, he says, Bradley
snubbed him in recent years, was one of Bradley's earliest
supporters; the two shared a campaign office in 1978, when James
was running for re-election as city councilman from Newark's North
Ward. ``I was with him from beginning to end,'' he said. ``I even
read his mail.''
</P>
<P>
   But he said his opinion of Bradley began to change when the
senator at first refused to travel to Chicago to support Harold
Washington's candidacy for mayor in 1983. ``All the Democratic
caucus was going, but Bill Bradley would not go,'' James said. ``He
said, `I'm not into local politics.' He was about theory. He didn't
want to deal in the nitty-gritty. But I screamed and shouted, and
finally he went, and felt good about it, and we felt good about him
being there.''
</P>
<P>
   But for all the high-profile defections to Gore, Bradley retains
the loyalty of many local officials, particularly in the southern
third of the state. On Dec. 8 in East Brunswick, Bradley raised
$750,000, and hundreds of admirers crushed in around him, waiting
for a chance to be photographed with him.
</P>
<P>
   And while the New Jersey State Federation of the AFL-CIO has
endorsed Gore, longtime union leaders like Charles Marciante, who
retired as president of the federation in 1997, say they harbor no
ill will toward Bradley.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an independent guy,'' Marciante said. ``He's his own man.
He wasn't like a party hack, if you know what I mean. Just as many
senators are in Washington, they're pretty independent _ the nation
comes first. He was one of those. And that did not hurt him one
bit. Who can hate him for that? As long as the people and the
nation came first.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
