<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 15:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2782 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u i BC-RUSSIA-ELECTION-BOS &LR;      12-18 1220
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-RUSSIA-ELECTION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUSSIANS GO TO POLLS AMID CYNICAL BACKDROP 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By DAVID FILIPOV  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   MOSCOW _ Few influential Russians avoid publicity the way the
oil baron Roman Abramovich has. The 33-year-old head of Sibneft,
one of Russia's largest oil companies, avoids interviews, rarely
makes appearances, and stays out of public politics.
</P>
<P>
   Abramovich keeps such a low profile that when he was identified
last spring as a close confidant to President Boris N. Yeltsin's
family, it took the Russian media weeks to find a photo of him.
Little is known about his positions on any issue.
</P>
<P>
   It might seem strange that such a man is running for public
office. But when Russians elect a new lower house of parliament
Sunday, Abramovich will be the candidate to beat in the frozen and
impoverished far east region of Chukotka, a place he visited for
the first time just a month ago. Chukotka is across the Bering
Strait from Alaska.
</P>
<P>
   Abramovich's candidacy in Chukotka is symbolic of the broader
meaning of the elections for the State Duma. For many of those
running, the race is not about issues or ideology, it is about
self-interest. Abramovich is one of a number of candidates asking
not what they can do for Russia, but what the Duma can do for them.
</P>
<P>
   The central problem for Russia's political and business elites
is how to guarantee their positions when the Yeltsin era that saw
their rise to prominence ends with next summer's presidential
elections.
</P>
<P>
   ``At stake are vast financial resources, political power, and,
ultimately, the Russian presidency after Boris Yeltsin retires next
year,'' said Don Jensen, a former US diplomat in Moscow who is
deputy director of Radio Free Europe/Radio Liberty.
</P>
<P>
   That cynical backdrop leaves little room for the ideals that
democratic elections are supposed to stand for _ public debate,
freedom of choice, popular rule through political parties.
</P>
<P>
   Some candidates _ such as Abramovich and another Kremlin
insider, Boris Berezovsky, who is running for a seat in an obscure
North Caucasus district _ seem intent on gaining the immunity from
prosecution granted to members of the 450-seat Duma. They, and
dozens of lesser-known businessmen, feel they need immunity just in
case Russia's next rulers decide they profited from political ties
to gain their holdings illegally.
</P>
<P>
   The larger battle is between two coalitions of politicians,
business and regional leaders over who will succeed Yeltsin.
</P>
<P>
   One coalition, known both as Unity and ``The Bear,'' is centered
on the Kremlin and backed by popular Prime Minister Vladimir Putin;
the other, Fatherland-All Russia, known by its Russian initials
OVR, draws its power from former prime minister Yevgeny Primakov
and Moscow Mayor Yury Luzhkov.
</P>
<P>
   Although several other parties are expected to place candidates
in the Duma, and the Communists are expected to win the most seats
with a quarter of the vote, they are seen as almost irrelevant in
the race for the presidency.
</P>
<P>
   Polls indicate the Communist leader, Gennady Zyuganov, has no
chance to win a presidential vote. The clear favorites are Putin,
who has seen his approval rating rise to more than 70 percent as
the architect of Moscow's popular campaign against Islamic rebels
in Chechnya, and Primakov, who announced his long-expected
candidacy for Russia's top post Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Throughout the Duma campaign, Kremlin-controlled state media,
including Russia's most-watched television network, have launched
daily attacks against Primakov and Luzhkov aimed at making sure OVR
does not top the ballot.
</P>
<P>
   Analyst Michael McFaul of Stanford University said the
Unity-Bear bloc was created by Berezovsky and other Kremlin
strategists with the purpose of providing them with a loyal
following in the Duma. The Bear's top three candidates are
Emergencies Minister Sergei Shoigu, who has a leading role in
Russia's campaign in Chechnya; Olympic wrestling champion Alexander
Karelin, who lacks the charisma of his American counterpart,
Minnesota Governor Jesse Ventura, but has not lost a wrestling
match in nine years; and retired general Alexander Gurov, a former
top crime-fighting official.
</P>
<P>
   This image, which McFaul called ``a Russia that fights,''
appears to have appealed to the public. Against the backdrop of the
popular war in Chechnya and Russia's increasingly confrontative
stance toward the West, Unity's rating has risen dramatically.
Polls now suggest the bloc will win about 18 percent of the vote
for a strong second-place showing behind the Communists; OVR has
slipped to a distant third.
</P>
<P>
   Unity-Bear has no party program, no grass-roots membership, and
no unifying principle other than the need to place second in this
election. Shoigu has said he will not serve in the Duma, and
Karelin is most likely to take leave of his parliamentary duties to
compete in next summer's Olympics.
</P>
<P>
   Abramovich is only loosely connected to the Unity-Bear bloc. He
is running in one of the 225 single-candidate districts spread
across the country's nine time zones, where half the Duma's seats
are being contested (the other 225 seats will be divided among
parties that win more than 5 percent of the vote.)
</P>
<P>
   Election and security officials said a large number of
candidates who allegedly have committed illegal acts or have ties
to organized crime are seeking election in the single-candidate
districts. Political analyst Sergei Markov said many of the laws
created to make the campaign fair, such as rules limiting campaign
financing, ``are violated by almost everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Abramovich has been accused of no crime, though critics question
the murky privatization deal that left him in control of Sibneft.
Luzhkov and Primakov have vowed to investigate such sell-offs and
prosecute wrongdoers. Abramovich may be thinking about how to
protect himself.
</P>
<P>
   In places like Chukotka, which suffers from shortages of food
and fuel in the winter, the main problem for its 43,984 voters is
how to survive. Abramovich's campaign offers to take on this
problem in exchange for a seat in the Duma. Sibneft has reportedly
supplied $5 million in fuel to the region.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are no doubts that he will get his mandate,'' said
Nikolai Petrov, political analyst for Moscow Carnegie Center.
</P>
<P>
   But will Abramovich actually serve as Chukotka's representative
in the Duma?
</P>
<P>
   ``We'll see,'' he said in his first public interview, published
this month in the daily newspaper Vedomosti. Abramovich was asked
whether Chukotka's location, far from the Moscow press, had
anything to do with his decision to run there.
</P>
<P>
   ``In part, yes,'' he replied.
</P>
<P>
   In fact, just getting to Chukotka to cover the Abramovich
campaign is difficult. Commercial flights are sporadic and
frequently canceled for lack of fuel. There are no road or rail
connections.
</P>
<P>
   Because Chukotka is a border zone, Russian authorities require
special permission for anyone who wants to visit. When the Globe
inquired in November, regional officials said a correspondent could
obtain permission to go there in ten days. Later, that was extended
to 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Right now there's no reason to come,'' a local official said.
``Could you please move back your plans . . . until after the
elections?''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 1540EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
