<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 15:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2802 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-ASYLUM-DOCUMENTARY-12     12-18 1251
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ASYLUM-DOCUMENTARY-1200(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DOCUMENTARY SHOWS PITFALLS IN PROCESS OF SEEKING ASYLUM  
 (ATTN: N.J., N.Y.) 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By SUSAN SACHS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   A Chinese man follows the instructions of the smuggler who
brought him to the United States and concocts an improbable story
of fleeing his country's one-child policy, not realizing that the
actual religious persecution he experienced as a Christian in his
homeland would qualify him for asylum here.
</P>
<P>
   A Romanian woman tormented for her membership in the Anglican
Church is asked, as a test of her credibility, to name its top
prelate. The officer hearing her asylum request decides her answer
is incorrect and denies her application. She, not he, is right, it
turns out.
</P>
<P>
   A young Algerian woman describes how Islamic militants
threatened to kill her and members of her politically prominent
family. But her translator relays only the skeletal outlines of her
tale to the official who could, but ultimately does not, grant her
political asylum.
</P>
<P>
   ``Only God knows how it will end _ and them, of course,'' the
woman whispers sadly when the door closes behind her after the
unfortunate interview.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly every day, behind closed doors in antiseptic government
offices around the country, people like these tell their tearful
stories of fear and torture in an attempt to win asylum. Some
accounts are found to be genuine. Others _ indeed most, in the view
of some veteran interviewers _ are contrived.
</P>
<P>
   But the official sifting of truth from lies, of the worthy from
the unworthy and the plausible from the unconvincing, is a process
that the public never sees, and so cannot evaluate.
</P>
<P>
   Now a documentary by two independent New York City filmmakers,
Shari Robertson and Michael Camerini, has opened an extraordinary
window into what happens at the Immigration and Naturalization
Service's asylum offices, where only one in five applicants is
granted sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   The film, called ``Well-Founded Fear'' and scheduled for
broadcast on PBS in June, provides the first close-up picture of a
secretive and discretionary system that can capsize or renew each
applicant's life.
</P>
<P>
   The documentary has been screened so far only for immigration
and human rights lawyers and for INS employees, who have reacted
with consternation and commiseration to its searing picture of how
one of the nation's most sensitive policies is administered.
</P>
<P>
   Filmed in 1998 at the immigration service's New York City and
Lyndhurst, N.J., asylum offices, the documentary reveals for the
first time a process that is based on law and on instinct and that
operates, as one asylum officer puts it, like Russian roulette.
</P>
<P>
   Some applicants, like the fragile-looking Chinese poet who weeps
as he recalls his vicious beatings in prison, sail through the
ordeal, their stories so horribly authentic that officials seem
thankful for the opportunity to offer them asylum. ``I am
humbled,'' says Gerald, the asylum officer who reviews the case of
the poet, Huang Xiang. ``What a life.''
</P>
<P>
   Other applicants, desperate for a chance to remain in the United
States, are failed by their own or government-provided translators,
who, as the filmmakers demonstrate with subtitled translations,
carelessly leave out chunks of their stories.
</P>
<P>
   Or they pay the price of poor preparation or outright
fabrication by the people who prepare their applications.
</P>
<P>
   One Salvadoran man shown in the film comes to the interview
thinking he is applying for a visa extension. A Chinese man,
relaying a story that seems badly memorized, tells an incredulous
asylum officer that he was forcibly sterilized back home and would
be sterilized again if deported back to China.
</P>
<P>
   In the face of what they come to believe is extensive fraud, the
asylum officers interviewed by the filmmakers talk frankly about
their slide from trust to exasperation to hardened cynicism about
the stories they hear, all the while worrying that they have
crossed a line between honest skepticism and burnout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has got their own threshold,'' says an asylum
officer named Peter, who muses that an applicant's chance of
winning asylum depends on who hears the case. ``Everybody's got
their own interpretation of the law. Everybody's got their own
willingness to believe or to suspend disbelief.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people may associate the U.S. asylum program with such
high-profile humanitarian efforts as the airlift of Kosovo refugees
and the open-door policy for Soviet Jews. But the rescue of
refugees is separate from the asylum program, which covers people
who have been able to make it to the United States to ask for
sanctuary.
</P>
<P>
   In the last few years, between 35,000 and 52,000 people have
asked for asylum annually. The numbers fluctuate according to world
events and wars that send people fleeing in search of a haven, but
have dropped significantly since the INS stopped handing out
automatic work permits to every asylum seeker.
</P>
<P>
   To win the prize of asylum, with its benefits and promise of
future citizenship, applicants must show that they cannot return
home because of ``persecution or a well-founded fear of persecution
on account of race, religion, nationality, membership in a
particular social group, or opinion.'' And they must prove that
they cannot count on protection from persecution by their home
government.
</P>
<P>
   (BEGIN OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   The chief decision makers are the asylum officers, although
since 1996 immigration agents at airports and other border points
may decide that asylum seekers do not have a credible fear of
persecution and turn them away. The decisions of both the officers
and the agents are reviewed by immigration judges.
</P>
<P>
   Most people get to make their case. But few _ about one in five,
historically _ are approved.
</P>
<P>
   (END OPTIONAL TRIM)
</P>
<P>
   In the year ending Sept. 30, 1998 _ the latest for which the INS
has statistics _ asylum officers conducted about 42,000 interviews
and granted about 9,900 applications. The remainder were either
denied outright or referred to immigration judges for hearings. The
judges that year granted 35 percent of the referred requests. At
the borders, all but 14 percent of the 3,000 people who asked for
asylum upon arrival were admitted so they could press their claims.
</P>
<P>
   Asylum officers are supposed to depend on State Department human
rights reports, which describe the conditions in an applicant's
country, to determine if the fear of persecution is reasonable.
They are supposed to confirm the identity of the applicant. But at
that point their task shifts to a more subtle plane of intangibles
and gut feelings in determining if someone is credible.
</P>
<P>
   It is a human system, says one asylum officer to the filmmakers,
and reflects the personalities of the people who operate within it.
</P>
<P>
   Doris Meissner, the commissioner of the INS, said she agreed to
the filming to showcase a much-heralded reform of the asylum
process in 1995 that aimed to expand the training of asylum
officers and judges, reduce the backlog of old cases and attack
fraud.
</P>
<P>
   ``The film shows how murky some of these issues are and,
ultimately, how there's almost no black and white,'' said Mrs.
Meissner, who saw the documentary in October and has since shown it
to groups of asylum officers around the country as a training tool.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most things in life,'' she added, ``are in the gray areas.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   (MORE
</P>
<P>
   The asylum seekers shown in the documentary, however, see their
stories as clear-cut. They say they have suffered and will suffer.
Few seem to understand that that is often not enough.
</P>
<P>
   Anna Maria, the Romanian woman who suffered religious
persecution, is frustrated by her interview with the asylum officer
whose questions were meant to establish whether she really was what
she claimed to be: a member of the Anglican Church.
</P>
<P>
   ``What do these asylum officers want?'' she says to her lawyer.
``They want somebody to cry? To beg them?''
</P>
<P>
   Another Romanian, a man named Cristian, says he was a
much-hounded dissident during the reign of the Communist dictator
Nicolae Ceausescu. But while he was waiting for his case to be
heard, the dangerous regime he fled was toppled and an elected
government took its place.
</P>
<P>
   Now, after nearly a decade in the United States, he is an
articulate and successful businessman. But does he still have a
well-founded fear of persecution? The asylum officer says no.
</P>
<P>
   Farida, the Algerian woman, is tripped up by the translator's
failure to explain that her family is specifically targeted for
persecution, and leaves the asylum office totally unaware that the
point was not made.
</P>
<P>
   ``To me the whole thing hinges on whether her family has been
singled out,'' says Gerald, the asylum officer. After the
interview, he is not convinced. ``I don't see what she has to be
afraid of, above and beyond what every poor soul in Algeria has to
be afraid of,'' he says.
</P>
<P>
   The most provocative vignettes captured by the filmmakers focus
on the men and women like Gerald who do the interviews and make the
decisions. Many admit freely that the resentment they feel at being
lied to by some applicants may carry over to subsequent cases.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, another Chinese,'' mutters an officer named Jim, who later
rolls his eyes during an interview with a man who cannot seem to
get his story straight. Others joke about the similarity of
people's tales of persecution. ``You get lots of, `I helped pull
down the statue of the former dictator,''' says one officer.
</P>
<P>
   Kevin, a young asylum officer, says he tries to remember that in
some countries, many people could well have had the same experience
of torture or abuse. Over time, he adds, he has developed a keener
instinct for sniffing out lies.
</P>
<P>
   ``I mean, I hope that's what it is, but it could be the fact
that you're just very jaded,'' Kevin says. ``Then if I admitted I
was jaded, wouldn't I then be saying I shouldn't be doing this job?
So I say that I have a more acute understanding of credibility
issues.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
