<SLUG> BC-VECSEY-COLUMN-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SPORTS COLUMN: MORE NATIONALISM IN THE NEXT CENTURY 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Pa., Mass., Calif., Canada, England)  (jw) 
 By GEORGE VECSEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   Here's a scary thought for you as the century runs out: Sports
could get even more intense in the years stretching ahead of us.
</P>
<P>
   It won't be the money and it won't be the booze and it won't
even be the 'roid rage coursing in fans and athletes alike. It will
be that ancient specter of flags and anthems and national colors
painted across distended faces, celebrating a 21st century
championship.
</P>
<P>
   The future was revealed last year in two most unlikely sports _
women's soccer and men's golf. Americans discovered they could get
to like watching their very own Michelle Akers chasing down a
wayward soccer ball or their very own Justin Leonard tapping a golf
ball into the hole.
</P>
<P>
   Americans have had a taste of jingoism in the arena. We have
been reminded of this at the end of the century as everybody has
compiled lists, most of them gratuitous and arbitrary, but some of
them reminding us of where we have been. Many people agree that the
greatest team of the century was not some perpetual champion like
the New York Yankees or the Boston Celtics or the Montreal
Canadiens or John Wooden's basketball teams from UCLA, but rather
the improbable amateurs who won the gold medal of ice hockey at the
1980 Winter Games, the so-called Miracle on Ice.
</P>
<P>
   That epic upset inspired American men and women to persevere in
a sport that had been seen as the province of Canada and northern
Europe. Men like Mike Richter and women like Cammi Granato dreamed
of winning a gold medal for their country, which, in fact, Granato
would do 18 years later in the first women's medal play in Nagano,
Japan. The amateurs of 1980 paved the way for American men to
realize they could play in the National Hockey League, and also
paved the way for the sprawl of hockey downward into the Sun Belt,
not necessarily the best thing for the Canadian heritage, but
probably inevitable.
</P>
<P>
   Then there was the Dream Team of the 1992 Summer Games, with
Charles Barkley beating up on some poor Angolan, but the Yanks were
so overwhelming in basketball that there was no suspense, and no
carry-over.
</P>
<P>
   As the century ebbed, however, America learned to love its
national teams. Even baseball fans, watching the Phillies torment
the Mets on a sunny afternoon during the September pennant race,
could get the basic mathematics of Ryder Cup golf: Europe had been
ahead, 10-6, but the scoreboard in Philadelphia revealed a
match-by-match turnaround that saw the Americans prevail, 14{-13{.
</P>
<P>
   While it was happening in Brookline, Mass., American fans and
American golfers celebrated so raucously that you could have asked
the question, ``Who do you people think you are, soccer
hooligans?'' _ the ultimate American sporting epithet.
</P>
<P>
   Many golf fans were horrified at the emotions of other fans in
the gallery. Fans hurled insults at the European players, hissed
the universal word ``choke'' at them.
</P>
<P>
   And when the Yanks roared back into contention, even the most
staid American players, who normally contain themselves during
their personal triumphs, danced on the fairways and sprayed
champagne in full view, while Europeans golfers were still trying
to compose themselves for a putt.
</P>
<P>
   It was not pretty, but it was the future. Nationalism sells. The
Olympics are supposed to be about individuals, but tell it to the
fans who tossed national flags to Carl Lewis and Jackie
Joyner-Kersee after their epic events in Los Angeles or Seoul or
Barcelona.
</P>
<P>
   In British soccer, people talk about ``our lads,'' as if the
national team is some village team gone off to play the next
village.
</P>
<P>
   Soccer fans in Brazil and Italy, cricket fans in the West Indies
and Pakistan, rugby fans in Australia and South Africa and hockey
fans in Russia and Canada have long known the peculiar agonies of
nationalist sports. Now, even isolated and insular Americans were
catching on.
</P>
<P>
   Women did as much for nationalism as men. The United States has
always resisted the low scores and the foreign sounds and the
intricate maneuvers of soccer. This is hardly the fault of the game
itself, not when billions of fans all over the world totally grasp
the subtleties.
</P>
<P>
   More to the point was that Americans refused to commit to soccer
because ``our lads'' did not play it very well, by American
standards. When the Yanks came back without a victory from Italy in
1990 and from France in 1998, it was a national version of the film
``The Last Picture Show,'' with the hapless high school football
players being teased by the townspeople.
</P>
<P>
   In 1999, that all changed _ and maybe forever. The American
women were so captivating and so good that they caught America's
attention, at least for a few weeks. The American team finished
ahead of teams from China, Norway, Brazil, Nigeria and Germany. The
play was spirited and physical but far more offensive and positive
than the defensive, bitter tactics of the men's game.
</P>
<P>
   Those were not all soccer insiders packing into the Rose Bowl
and the other top-of-the-line stadiums across the country. They
were Americans with money being attracted by charisma and success.
Even with an African-American goalkeeper protecting the goal, the
team was generally a white and yuppified version of the country,
but that will change.
</P>
<P>
   In a shrinking world, where everywhere is only a click of the
television zapper or the Internet mouse away, nationalism thrived
on elegant fairways and lush soccer pitches. America could learn to
love cheering for ``our girls'' and ``our lads.''  &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 1601EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
