<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0173 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 16:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2810 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-MAYOR-UNIONS-500&AMP;A     12-18 0953
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-MAYOR-UNIONS-500&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UNIONS PREPARE FOR TALKS, BUT NOT INJUNCTIONS
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By ALAN FEUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Less than a week after Mayor Rudolph Giuliani used a
court injunction as one of the major tools in his efforts to avert
a transit strike, leaders of municipal labor unions across New York
called the order excessive and heavy-handed, but declined to
predict whether the city might brandish a similar weapon against
them.
</P>
<P>
   The injunction, issued by Justice Michael Pesce of state Supreme
Court in Brooklyn hours before the transit workers' contract
expired, was remarkable both for its breadth and the severity of
punishment it promised if the union violated the court's order and
the state Taylor Law by going on strike.
</P>
<P>
   It brought what appeared to be overwhelming force to bear
against city transit workers, who were threatening to walk off the
job, providing significant fines against the union's members.
</P>
<P>
   Several municipal labor unions, including the city's largest,
District Council 37, are scheduled to start negotiations with the
city soon. While some of their leaders criticized Pesce's
injunction as overly harsh, none of them said they were actively
preparing to face a similar order in their own negotiations with
the city.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think we're preparing for an injunction, seeing as
we've never gone on strike,'' said Arthur Cheliotes, president of
Local 1180 of the Communications Workers of America, whose contract
covering middle managers expires on March 31.
</P>
<P>
   Nonetheless, Cheliotes said the injunction was typical of
Giuliani, adding: ``The law was there, but he wanted to add to it
and show people how brutal he could be. It's typical that he would
want to overwhelm people.''
</P>
<P>
   Lee Saunders, president of District Council 37, the largest
union of municipal employees, whose contract also expires at the
end of March, said he was preparing for talks with the city, but
added that he hoped the negotiations would not reach the point
where an injunction like the one Pesce issued would be necessary.
``I'm treating this process very seriously and honestly,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Randi Weingarten, president of the United Federation of
Teachers, whose contract is up in November, said she did not expect
to have to fight a similar injunction, but added that lawyers for
the union were nonetheless trying to determine whether it was
constitutional.
</P>
<P>
   ``You already have in place penalties for unions if they go on
strike,'' she said. ``But the mayor's injunction, well before
deadline and before anyone decided to go on strike, sought
penalties that were so overreaching and punitive that they chilled
free speech.''
</P>
<P>
   The thrust of the injunction was to bar the 33,000 members of
the Transportation Workers Union from going on strike under
provisions of the Taylor Law, a state statute that forbids job
actions by public employees. But the injunction also prohibited
transit workers from advocating a strike, and made punishable a
host of preparatory steps, including holding a vote on a strike or
``causing, instigating, encouraging or condoning, or lending
support or assistance of any nature to any strike.''
</P>
<P>
   The order the judge signed was broadly drafted by the city's
lawyers, and worded so that it covered not only members of the
transit union but also anyone else acting on behalf of union
members or in concert with them. It also imposed fines of $25,000
on anyone who violated the order.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   The injunction provided much tougher sanctions than a second one
issued by Pesce the same day, at the request of the Metropolitan
Transportation Authority, which also barred a strike.
</P>
<P>
   The sweeping provisions and penalties of the city's injunction
baffled civil libertarians and union supporters. They asserted that
the right of union members to express their thoughts about a strike
should be constitutionally protected, particularly given that the
union was poised to begin what could be a tough period of internal
debate about the new contract.
</P>
<P>
   Arthur Schwartz, a lawyer for New Directions, a dissident
faction in the union, said the injunction set up a situation in
which people could advocate the overthrow of the U.S. government _
a right protected by law _ but not advocate a strike by subway
motormen and bus drivers.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is an incredibly broad, sweeping prohibition on transit
workers,'' Schwartz said. ``It creates a police state with respect
to the question of supporting public employees.''
</P>
<P>
   Lorna Goodman, a spokeswoman for Michael Hess, the city's
corporation counsel, said she could not discuss whether the
Giuliani administration would consider seeking a similar injunction
as a bargaining tool in upcoming talks with its workers.
</P>
<P>
   But given the apparent success of the strategy in recent
negotiations, some labor experts said they would not be surprised
if the city unsheathed at least the threat of another injunction in
the coming months.
</P>
<P>
   There is no reason why such an order would not be sought again,
said Joshua Freeman, a professor of history at Queens College. ``I
can't think of any equivalently severe restraining order in
decades.''
</P>
<P>
   At least one labor leader, Brian McLaughlin, president of the
New York City Central Labor Committee, seemed somewhat eager for
the mayor to attempt to use a court order in the upcoming
negotiations _ if only for the chance to defeat it.
</P>
<P>
   ``As we look forward to other contracts, you have to realize
that we didn't get to see the whole injunction process played out''
because a strike was averted, he said. He called the order a
decision that could have been challenged.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
