<HEADLINE>
WORKER KILLED AND SEVERAL SICKENED BY FUMES AT TIMES SQUARE CLUB
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Gas fumes in a popular supper club in Times Square
left one night-shift employee dead Saturday and four others
hospitalized, as the police closed off the block, evacuated a
building next door and checked manholes and nearby basements for
evidence of carbon monoxide.
</P>
<P>
   Five rescue workers were also overcome by fumes. Three of them,
who entered the club, were hospitalized and two were treated and
released. Another club employee who had difficulty breathing was
treated at the scene.
</P>
<P>
   Firefighters dragged the five unconscious custodial workers from
the Laura Belle restaurant at 120 W. 43rd St. shortly after 10 a.m.
as the owner and several workers from the day shift stood in the
faint winter sun and wept. The men, believed to have ranged in age
from their late 20s to early 50s, were still wearing their white
janitor uniforms when they were put onto stretchers and raced to
waiting ambulances. One worker, believed to be in his 50s, was in
cardiac arrest and was pronounced dead on arrival at St.
Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center. Another worker was in critical
condition and on a ventilator, a hospital spokesman said.
</P>
<P>
   The incident was probably caused by carbon monoxide from an
unknown source, possibly aggravated by a noxious mixture of
cleaning fluids, including ammonia, window cleaner and bleach, said
Thomas Galvin, a Fire Department division chief. Mixing such
cleaning fluids, sometimes haphazardly, is common practice by
custodial workers around the city, said a fire department
spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   Police detectives said they were also investigating whether
there were any safety violations that might have contributed to the
accident.
</P>
<P>
   The men were first discovered by Gary Marcius, an employee who
arrived Saturday morning to lock up the night club and found the
five workers unconscious on the basement floor, one in a small
office. ``I go downstairs, and all of them lay down,'' Marcius
said, his eyes welling with tears. ``I say, `What is it?' but
nobody talking.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcius said that he then raced upstairs and called 911.
</P>
<P>
   The first fire truck arrived three minutes later, and
firefighters entered the building. When they saw the men, they
immediately called for backup and the street quickly filled with
emergency vehicles.
</P>
<P>
   The men were dragged from the basement and onto stretchers, as
paramedics pumped oxygen into their mouths. Foam bubbled from the
mouth of one worker, his white uniform twisted and half off. A Fire
Department spokesman said that a combination of the gas and the
cleaning solvents might have caused that reaction.
</P>
<P>
   The victims were believed to have been in the building for at
least 11 hours before they were discovered, Galvin said. The level
of carbon monoxide was extremely high, he added. In some parts of
the basement, firefighters recorded levels in excess of 500 parts
per million; a safe level is 35 parts per million.
</P>
<P>
   At St. Clare's Hospital, nursing administrator Lito Bathan said
two of the victims were being transferred to Jacobi Medical Center
in the Bronx for deep oxygen treatment in a hyperbaric chamber. One
victim, in his late 20s, was unconscious but in stable condition.
Another, in his mid-30s, was alert and in good condition, Bathan
said.
</P>
<P>
   Two of St. Clare's emergency medical technicians were briefly
overcome by the fumes, but were treated at the hospital and
released.
</P>
<P>
   Two other emergency medical workers and a police officer were
overcome by fumes and began feeling ill while in an ambulance
taking a victim to the hospital, said Paul Iannizzotto, a Fire
Department spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The two emergency medical workers were taken to New
York-Presbyterian Hospital, where they were hosed down as a
precautionary measure. They were in stable condition with
respiratory problems, according to one of their co-workers. The
Fire Department did not release their names.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Iannizzotto said it was unclear whether the emergency workers
and police officer had become ill from having entered the club.
</P>
<P>
   Outside Laura Belle, a woman who identified herself as an owner,
Joanne O'Connor, looked stunned as she was surrounded by
firefighters and plainclothes officers. ``I left here at 2 a.m.,''
and everything was fine at that time, she said.
</P>
<P>
   Con Edison emergency workers searched the surrounding
underground access points, manhole covers and the basements of
nearby buildings, but detected no natural-gas leaks, emergency
workers at the scene said.
</P>
<P>
   Onlookers and workers from an Airborne Express shipping office
next door, and from other nearby businesses watched yet another
disaster unfolding on what they said was a star-crossed block. ``We
thought maybe 4 Times Square was coming down again,'' said Erik
Sundve, referring to the scaffolding collapse and other accidents
that bedeviled the Conde Nast building while it was under
construction a few doors down.
</P>
<P>
   His co-worker said, ``It's a block of gridlock now.'' At that
moment, the police began to clear the street of onlookers and
Sundve was forced back into his company's docking area and the
metal door of the garage was lowered.
</P>
<P>
   As rescue workers carried out the personal effects of the
workers, emergency workers wearing masks rolled in portable gas
gauges and police officers evacuated the staff of Airborne Express.
</P>
<P>
   One Airborne Express delivery man, William Smith, wheeled a cart
of packages out, shaking his head as he headed up the Avenue of the
Americas. ``The police, they just made us get out,'' he said.
``They said it was poison gas and we had to evacuate the building.
I am too nervous,'' he said. ``I just wanted to get out of there.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
