<SLUG> BC-NY-HEALTHCARE-POLICY-620&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW YORK'S PLAN FOR UNINSURED SENDS NATIONAL MESSAGE
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wis.)   (jw) 
 By JENNIFER STEINHAUER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ By agreeing Friday on a $1 billion plan to provide
health insurance for a third of the state's 3.2 million uninsured,
Gov. George Pataki and legislative leaders sent a message to the
rest of the country that the state was trying to regain its stature
as a leader on health care policy.
</P>
<P>
   At the beginning of the decade, the number of New Yorkers
without health insurance was below the national average; now, at
the end of the decade, it exceeds it. Roughly 20 percent of New
York's residents under 65 do not have insurance; the national
average is 16.3 percent.
</P>
<P>
   Legislative leaders have been locked in a battle with the
governor for most of his term over Medicaid, medical education
costs and, more recently, how to use the state's portion of a
settlement with tobacco companies.
</P>
<P>
   But in an 11th-hour deal a few weeks before the expiration of
state laws governing health care financing, all camps cobbled
together an ambitious plan aimed at the state's uninsured
population _ from poor families with members who work sporadically
to self-employed people who cannot afford premiums to low-income
workers whose employers do not provide insurance but who make too
much to qualify for Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   The plan, believed to be the largest effort in the nation to
help the uninsured, will be paid for in large part through a
55-cent increase in the tax on cigarettes and part of the $500
million in tobacco settlement money over 3{ years.
</P>
<P>
   Officials in other states and in Washington who have been
challenged to deal with swelling ranks of uninsured will be all but
sure to watch New York.
</P>
<P>
   ``By taking such a significant step,'' said James Tallon,
president of the United Hospital Fund, a philanthropy group, ``New
York sends a clear signal to Congress that there is a groundswell
on the state level to get on with taking care of the problem of the
uninsured. It has put the subject back on the agenda.''
</P>
<P>
   Even on Saturday, the final terms of the deal were still being
negotiated. But the plan calls for roughly $600 million _ part of
which is federal matching funds _ to pay for a program to insure
poor families.
</P>
<P>
   The program, Family Health Plus, will be modeled on a state
program for children, Child Health Plus. That program arose from a
move by Congress in 1997 to create the Children's Health Insurance
Program, which provided $24 billion over five years and a total of
$39 billion over 10 years to states to insure children. New York's
program has so far enrolled 415,000 children.
</P>
<P>
   Both the family program and the children's program are, in
essence, a newfangled form of Medicaid in which states subsidize
health insurance and the federal government gives matching money,
but the list of doctors that participants have to choose from is
substantially broader than that of the Medicaid program.
</P>
<P>
   The family program would expand those benefits on an sliding
scale; the poorest of families would pay no premiums and others
would pay premiums based on their income to participate in managed
care plans. Families earning up to 150 percent of the poverty line
_ like a family of four with an annual income of $25,000 or less _
could receive coverage without paying premiums. Childless single
people earning up to 100 percent above the poverty level would also
qualify.
</P>
<P>
   The program is significant in several ways. Most importantly, it
provides coverage for single people and those without children, a
far less politically attractive group of people than mothers and
their young children. At the same time, it raises the likelihood
that more children will be insured, because parents are often
reluctant to enroll their children by themselves or are unable to
maneuver the system.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   ``The best way to get children insured is to get the whole
family insured,'' said Joe Leean, the secretary of Wisconsin's
Department of Health and Family Services. That state's program,
BadgerCare, which started in July, is considered the earliest model
of how states can insure large populations of people. It is a
prototype for New York's plan, although in Wisconsin the number of
uninsured was far lower, at 330,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Often, until a child gets sick, parents don't think their kid
needs insurance,'' Leean said. ``Furthermore, once we have parents
working, it is their own health that secures the family well being.
And if you get them all in, in the same clinic or HMO, it works
much better. We think the success is bearing out.'' The goal was to
reduce Wisconsin's ratio of uninsured residents to 4 percent from 6
percent, but Leean said the goal had already been achieved.
</P>
<P>
   Uninsured Americans are far from homogenous. Many of them work
and therefore do not qualify for Medicaid, but are either not
offered insurance by their employers or opt not to incur the
expense of the premiums. Others are self-employed and either cannot
afford insurance or also chose to not pay for it, crossing their
fingers and praying against calamity instead.
</P>
<P>
   The rise of the working uninsured _ roughly three-quarters of
New York's uninsured _ has resulted from exploding insurance
premiums in recent years and employers' efforts to reign in costs.
The New York plan addresses these people through two components.
</P>
<P>
   It will pay about $220 million to subsidize small businesses
that want to offer insurance to employees, most likely through a
group purchasing plan in which many companies get together to
bargain for a good rate from an insurance carrier. Group purchasing
plans have met with mixed success in other states, depending
largely on the rates that groups are able to negotiate from
insurance companies.
</P>
<P>
   Through another component, the state has earmarked about $180
million to help reduce premiums for people who wish to buy their
own private plans. Those who usually choose to buy individual
plans, which are very expensive, often have chronic illnesses and
know they must incur the cost.
</P>
<P>
   The state has also set aside about $120 million for a pilot
program to insure home health care workers, who often go for long
periods without work assignments and therefore are often uninsured.
</P>
<P>
   The state will be most challenged in its family program in the
enrollment process. Children's health programs nationwide have
suffered low enrollment rates, largely because of complicated
enrollment procedures that stymie those who try to enroll, and poor
outreach. New York officials say that using community groups to
assist people in assessing their eligibility and signing them up
will be a crucial part of the program.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest lesson we learned with children is that creating a
program and expanding eligibility does not ensure by itself that
people are going to get covered,'' said David Sandman, a program
officer at the Commonwealth Fund, a large, private philanthropic
organization in New York. ``It needs to be augmented by intensive
outreach and enrollment efforts. Our research shows that two-thirds
of children who are uninsured do qualify for either Medicaid or
Child Health Plus chips but are not signed up.'' The state recently
announced a $10 million addition to the Child Health Plus program
for community-based groups to help with enrollment.
</P>
<P>
   Further, some critics of government programs worry that they can
backfire _ if too many people sign up for subsidized health
insurance, they argue, businesses may be dissuaded from offering
their employees benefits. As a result, eligibility requirements
must be carefully monitored.
</P>
<P>
   But if New York can make a substantial dent in its uninsured
populace, it may be able to polish its image as a health care
leader, an image much tarnished by bitter labor disputes, exploding
costs and a high number of those without coverage.
</P>
<P>
   ``If New York were to do these things,'' Sandman said, ``it
would be a major step to restoring its position as a leader among
states in ensuring insurance for working adults who have nowhere
else to turn.''
</P>
</TEXT>
