<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAITEMS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Laettner still trying to find his place
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Christian Laettner has felt like an outsider in Detroit,
especially on offense, and he's voiced his concerns, which did not
go over well with the Pistons.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was able to get it going (Tuesday at Phoenix for a
season-high 26 points), but it seems like you have to start yelling
and barking your name to get some plays for you out there,'' he
said, ``and I don't think that's the way it should be. I don't like
feeling like I have to be overly aggressive like, `Give me the
ball, I want the ball,' to get the ball. You shouldn't have to play
basketball like that.''
</P>
<P>
   Laettner has been accused of being nonchalant on the court
before _ in Minnesota and Atlanta. Now, maybe, it seems he has come
to understand that quality players demand the ball when it does not
come their way.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started yelling for the ball and demanding it a little bit.
But I don't believe that and I never bought into that _ that you're
ready to play or you're going to have a good night if you're
demanding the ball. It's never the way I played in college, and
it's still not the way I like to play. It seems like it's the
players' fault because the coaches are giving us a lot of freedom
out there.''
</P>
<P>
   Laettner is averaging 11 shots a game in 30 minutes, compared to
Grant Hill's 20 in 38 minutes and Jerry Stackhouse's 16 in 38.
</P>
<P>
   Coach Alvin Gentry wasn't moved. ``If he wants to use that as a
cop-out,'' Gentry said, ``then let him.''
</P>
<P>
   Nick vs. George
</P>
<P>
   Nick Van Exel thought he had a good relationship with Milwaukee
coach George Karl. Then Karl _ as he is wont to do _ spoke his mind
when asked about the Denver Nuggets guard.
</P>
<P>
   Said Karl: ``He's a talented player when he wants to play. But
he doesn't have an 82-game commitment. He does not have a serious
enough attitude to lead a team to a lot of success. But he can
really play on a given night. He really is good.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I have trouble giving Nick Van Exel $70million and
thinking that's going to motivate him when he hasn't been motivated
in the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Van Exel responded by going for 27 points in Milwaukee as the
Nuggets erased a 16-point deficit to win. Afterward, with a chance
to blast Karl, Van Exel took a surprisingly mature approach.
</P>
<P>
   Said Van Exel: ``For a guy like him to say that after I torched
him in the playoffs before and all those things that we've been
through, and then I go to him and tell him I think he's a great
guy, I think he gets the best out of his players, I think he's a
good coach. I told him that last season.
</P>
<P>
   ``For him to turn around and make those remarks about me is just
typical. It's just typical. I'm not going to say anything bad about
him. I guess that's the way he feels, and I can't do anything about
it.''
</P>
<P>
   First steps
</P>
<P>
   It took a while for straight-out-of-high-school forward Jonathan
Bender to make his NBA debut. But when he did last week against
Cleveland, he impressed none other than his coach, Indiana's Larry
Bird.
</P>
<P>
   Bender, right off the injured list, played 13 minutes, going
4-for-7 with a 3-pointer for 10 points _ an NBA record for a high
school draftee in his first game. He also blocked two shots, and
generally looked comfortable.
</P>
<P>
   Bird saved the game ball, which will be painted and presented to
Bender at a later date. ``I was really surprised by how well he
played,'' Bird said. ``You saw how he's going to be able to score
points in this league.''
</P>
<P>
   Said Bender: ``I had jitters at first, but once I got on the
court and took a couple of steps, it was like practice. I'm not the
type of person to get all excited by stuff. It's a game, you go out
and score, and that's the outcome.''
</P>
<P>
   Thumbs up
</P>
<P>
   To the Lakers' Kobe Bryant. At 21, the spectacular guard
purchased half of the Italian professional team Olympia Milano. It
is the team his father, Joe Bryant, played for in Italy. Bryant's
the first active athlete to buy such a major stake in another pro
team.
</P>
<P>
   Thumbs down
</P>
<P>
   To the Los Angeles Clippers. They score just 19 points in the
first half of a debacle against the Lakers _ an NBA record for
futility. It was so bad the Lakers would not even take credit
afterward for playing quality defense. They pointed to the Clips'
ineptitude.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
