<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Western Conference notes
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Figuring the Grizzlies
</P>
<P>
   The NBA has hired the accounting firm Ernst &AMP; Young to determine
the fair market value of its franchises, at a time when attendance
figures are down in most cities. The results are expected in
mid-January, and then Bill Laurie will be forwarded the league's
new terms as to how and when he can acquire the Vancouver
Grizzlies.
</P>
<P>
   That means the sale of the Grizzlies is very much alive.
</P>
<P>
   Apparently, the league believes the Grizzlies have duped their
fans and the media with inflated turnstile numbers the past few
years, but they could not fool Laurie. There were no surprises in
the Laurie camp when the Grizzlies dropped their charade this fall
and began announcing actual paid attendance without complimentary
tickets and promotional giveaways. Prior to last year's shortened
lockout season, the Grizzlies were padding their attendance numbers
by an average of 2,000 per game.
</P>
<P>
   Rebuilding the Rockets
</P>
<P>
   With Charles Barkley gone and Hakeem Olajuwon on an extended
absence, the Rockets are almost blowing off the rest of the season
as a 60-game training camp. The primary goals now are to rebuild
and find out who on the roster can play.
</P>
<P>
   ``It really just speeds up the process we were going to have to
go through at the beginning of the year when we wouldn't have had
Charles,'' Rockets coach Rudy Tomjanovich said.
</P>
<P>
   Of 16 who played in Houston last season, only Cuttino Mobley,
Bryce Drew and Matt Bullard are on the active roster.
</P>
<P>
   Pippen's nod to Barkley
</P>
<P>
   Here's Scottie Pippen's take on Barkley's farewell. ``I might
send him a plant,'' Pippen said, laughing. ``I feel bad for him,
actually. But I don't know if I plan on doing anything for him. I
may give him a call, just to make him feel better ... or worse, I
don't know. I didn't want to see him end his career like that. I
wanted to see him go out as a fighter and a warrior, the type of
player he's been his whole career. Charles is a legend ... he'll be
remembered like all the great players to play the game.''
</P>
<P>
   Scrape off the rust
</P>
<P>
   Almost two weeks overdue, Mavericks forward Gary Trent suited up
Tuesday for the first time this season. As much as the Mavericks
desperately need Trent's rebounding and low-post scoring,
coach-general manager Don Nelson is worrying about Trent's rusty
game and the effect his return will have on Dallas' fragile
chemistry.
</P>
<P>
   ``He looks awful,'' Nelson said. ``Trent's very rusty.''
</P>
<P>
   Saving his job for now
</P>
<P>
   P.J. Carlesimo was all set to be fired by Golden State last
Sunday but an improbable victory over Minnesota the night before
changed the plan. General manager Garry St. Jean will take over at
some point this season unless the Warriors win something like 60
percent of their remaining games.
</P>
<P>
   Layups
</P>
<P>
   Timberwolves coach Flip Saunders denied that he and vice
president Kevin McHale talked to the Knicks about a trade for
Minnesota guard Terrell Brandon. ``No one's even really talked to
us,'' Saunders said. ... When Steve Smith sank 6 of 11 against
Seattle, he reversed a down trend in which he had gone 28-for-85
over a seven-game span, including 9-for-33 on 3-pointers. Five off
days helped after the ex-Hawk injured his right thumb.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
