<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Skiles private, intense
 &HT;    By Curtis Bunn
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Scott Skiles took over the Phoenix Suns and made a few things
perfectly clear: His business is his business, so when seeking
personal information, don't expect any help from him. And he's
going to work extremely hard.
</P>
<P>
   The former assistant coach who had an undistinguished NBA career
has had enough of his personal life played out in the media, so
he's guarding it now with a passion. It is the same kind of passion
that he brings to the game as a coach, which has industry people
who've seen him in action expecting big things.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was born to coach,'' said Danny Ainge, whose job Skiles
took when Ainge quit Monday to spend more time with family.
</P>
<P>
   Skiles, the youngest coach in the league at 35, views his family
as the job. He was intense as a star in high school and at Michigan
State, and he remains that way. He once kicked a teammate during a
Spartans game when he did not do what Skiles thought he should. He
has cursed referees _ which makes him a prime coaching candidate _
and collected technical fouls.
</P>
<P>
   And he's proud of it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not going to lie, I'm an intense guy,'' Skiles said. ``I
guess my whole life, whatever I'm involved in, I do it all-out. But
I prefer to keep my private life just that _ private. I always
have. I'm a private person.''
</P>
<P>
   So much so that Suns general manager Bryan Colangelo said he
doesn't know Skiles that well. But he does know this much: Skiles
started protecting his privacy a few years ago after a public
divorce, custody battle and paternity case.
</P>
<P>
   His past public transgressions did not send Skiles into cover.
His college career was blemished when he was arrested twice for
drunk driving and once on a drug charge. After violating his
probation, Skiles spent 15 days in jail in his hometown of
Plymouth, Ind., a few days after being named the Big Ten Player of
the Year.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's the statute of limitations on having it not in print
anymore?'' he said. ``I was a college student, young, and I did
some stupid things. And I paid for them in a lot of ways more than
the average college student pays. That's it. I did some foolish
things a long time ago. And now I'm a grown man.''
</P>
<P>
   No one who knows Skiles is concerned about his ability to coach,
and it starts with his playing days. His 10 years in the league
between four teams were not spectacular, but he did set the record
for assists in a game with 30 in 1990 against Denver.
</P>
<P>
   When he played for Washington, he showed his coaching acumen.
``He not only told his teammates where they were supposed to be, he
used to tell the opponents when they were running a play wrong,''
said New Jersey general manager John Nash, who was GM in Washington
when Skiles played there. ``He'd tell a guy on the other team, `No,
you're supposed to cut through and go stand over there.'''
</P>
<P>
   Pat Williams, Magic senior executive vice president, had a
chance to hire Skiles last summer, but chose Doc Rivers instead.
Still, Willliams said: ``His work ethic, his intensity, his
ferocity is unparalleled. The only guy I've come across in my 32
years I can compare him to is (Utah coach) Jerry Sloan.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
