<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NBAEAST19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Eastern Conference notes
 &HT;    By Jeffrey Denberg
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   No message from Ewing
</P>
<P>
   All this silliness about Patrick Ewing and Miami is going
nowhere. The market for 37-year-old centers making $29 million for
this season and next is nonexistent.
</P>
<P>
   Ewing understands that. He simply was venting his frustration
when he suggested he might seek a trade.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not trying to send a message to anybody,'' Ewing said.
``I'm just trying to fine-tune my game. I believe in myself. I know
I have a lot of basketball left in me. I think the more I keep
playing, the more and more my skills will come back.''
</P>
<P>
   Ewing joked previously about being traded to Miami in the past
year, but this was the first time he sounded serious when he said
he possibly would accept a trade to another team.
</P>
<P>
   Heat cools off
</P>
<P>
   Miami ended its six-game road trip on a sour note, with
consecutive losses in Seattle and Golden State, then came home and
lost to Milwaukee. Tim Hardaway has missed 11 games with a jammed
right knee, and a return date remained uncertain heading into the
weekend.
</P>
<P>
   It appears only great games from Alonzo Mourning can keep the
Heat on top. Mourning averages fewer shots per game than any other
player currently ranked in the NBA's top 10 in scoring. Coach Pat
Riley said he wants Mourning to take 20 shots a game.
</P>
<P>
   Tired of that soft stuff
</P>
<P>
   Following a 21-point loss to Utah on Tuesday, in which
Washington led 44-43 at halftime, coach Gar Heard said his team
played soft. This infuriated guard Rod Strickland.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm tired of them putting that out there,'' Strickland said.
``They're putting that out there a little too much for me. There's
nothing soft about me and there's nothing soft about anybody in
here. ... That soft stuff, he can keep that to himself. ... When we
lose we all lose together. It's everybody's fault, just like when
we win. We don't need them making scapegoats of us for them.''
</P>
<P>
   Center Ike Austin paid the price, losing his starting job.
</P>
<P>
   Layups
</P>
<P>
   Larry Bird reiterated he won't change his mind about coaching
the Pacers after this season. But he admits there's one problem:
What to do with all the suits. ``One of my buddies (from Terre
Haute) was here tonight and we were talking about that,'' said
Bird, ``and I told him to come back after the season and he can
have them all.'' ... ``It was pretty tough getting up for a game
with Chicago, but they are an NBA team,'' Pacers guard Travis Best
said. ... Bulls guard Hersey Hawkins said he had 17 messages on his
cell phone when he missed his first game after 527 straight.
``There were a lot of condolences, like I'd passed away.'' ...
Orlando rookie Corey Maggette, on former Duke teammate Elton Brand,
a rookie with the Bulls: ``We talk on the phone all the time. I
think losing is getting to him. He isn't used to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
