<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-AFCNOTES19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tension in Miami blamed on media
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Dolphins coach Jimmy Johnson took some more shots at struggling
quarterback Dan Marino after last week's 28-20 loss to the New York
Jets. Later, Johnson accused the media of creating tension between
him and his quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   ``The biggest problem that I have _ and I don't know that
national people understand quite as much as people who are living
down here _ is that every single word is dissected, is under a
microscope,'' Johnson said. ``I'm asked to analyze the game. And if
I say, 'Well, we turned the ball over and that was the turning
point in the game,' everybody says Jimmy is ripping Dan Marino,
which is not the case at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``When things are written and things are said, it's going to
cause some tension between us,'' Johnson said. ``But for the most
part, over the last four years, I thought that we had a good
relationship.''
</P>
<P>
   After his team's third loss in a row, Johnson pointed to
Marino's two interceptions vs. the Jets as Miami's downfall.
Marino, 38, missed five games this season because of a pinched
nerve in his neck. Since returning, he has thrown eight
interceptions in a three-game span for the first time since 1986.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not worried about the blame part,'' Marino said. ``I'm
just worried about doing my job.''
</P>
<P>
   Heat's on Beathard
</P>
<P>
   San Diego Chargers team president Dean Spanos continues to stand
by general manager Bobby Beathard, despite a growing movement to
fire him or force him to retire. Beathard, who turns 63 in January,
has been criticized for several controversial moves, including the
trade of three draft picks and two players to Arizona for the No. 2
choice in the 1998 draft.
</P>
<P>
   Bearthard used the Cardinals' pick to draft Washington State
quarterback Ryan Leaf, who has been a bust.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've said that before and I will remain consistent. He has all
of my confidence,'' Spanos said. ``In terms of retirement? You
would have to ask him; I have no idea. I have not heard anything
along those lines.''
</P>
<P>
   Beathard, in his 10th season with the team, admits the idea of
retiring crosses his mind. It hit home at a recent lifeguard
reunion, where he saw a large group of his old buddies from his
hometown of El Segundo, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   ``Out of all the guys there, only three of us weren't retired,''
he said.
</P>
<P>
   Extra points
</P>
<P>
   Since former Broncos quarterback Jeff Lewis has played so
sparingly for the Panthers this season, Denver will receive the
minimum compensation for him in April's draft. Had Lewis started
eight games, or played more, the Broncos could have gotten
Carolina's second- or third-round pick to complete last year's
trade. Instead, Denver will get only a fourth-rounder. ... After
spending his first 12 seasons with the Raiders, receiver Tim Brown
could be wearing a different uniform next season. Brown confirmed
that he has a clause in his contract that allows him to become a
free agent after this season. One televised report has Brown
heading back to his hometown of Dallas and signing with the
Cowboys. Dallas inquired about trading for him in each of the past
two seasons. ``I don't know what's going to happen,'' Brown said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
