<SLUG> BC-FBN-ODDS-ENDS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NFL notes
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Off and running
</P>
<P>
   If you want to win games during the playoff chase, you've got to
run the football. In the past five weeks, there have been 33
individual 100-yard performances. The teams with the 100-yard
rushers were 30-3 in those games. The losers were Washington and
Stephen Davis (122 yards vs. Philadelphia), Dallas and Emmitt Smith
(127 yards vs. Arizona) and Minnesota and Robert Smith (118 yards
vs. Kansas City).
</P>
<P>
   Hello again
</P>
<P>
   When the Colts face the Redskins today, it will be the third
father-son combination that Washington cornerback Darrell Green has
played in his 17-year NFL career. In 1984, Green intercepted former
Vikings quarterback Archie Manning, and today he'll face his son,
Colts passer Peyton Manning. Green also played against former
Cowboys running back Tony Dorsett and his son, Titans safety
Anthony Dorsett, and Dallas running back Ron Springs and his son,
Seattle cornerback Shawn Springs. ``I've been thinking about the
privilege it is to play against these guys and their kids,'' Green
said. ``I find myself being more of a fan as I get older.''
</P>
<P>
   He said it
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's saying, `Oh, Oliver Stone directed it? It's got to
be good.' But the only good actor I saw in there was (Al) Pacino.
Dennis Quaid hasn't done anything since 'Innerspace.' And Cameron
Diaz? Sorry, this ain't `There's Something About Mary.' And LL Cool
J? That right there tells you about this movie.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Darrell Russell, Oakland Raiders defensive tackle on Stone's
new football movie, ``Any Given Sunday.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
