<SLUG> BC-BBO-INDIANS-PITCHING-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CLEVELAND'S LONG ROAD FINALLY LEADS TO FINLEY 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Cleveland Indians traveled a long and treacherous road to
sign Chuck Finley. It took them over the ruts and potholes of four
free-agent markets and an endless number of talks aimed at
generating the right trades. They were left behind in the wake of
the movement of pitchers like Roger Clemens, Pedro Martinez,
Orlando Hernandez and Randy Johnson.
</P>
<P>
   Before signing Finley last week, the Indians had struck out in
their pursuit of a string of top-line starting pitchers in the past
four years. The only one they succeeded in obtaining was Jack
McDowell, whom they signed as a free agent in December 1995, and
then he blew out his arm after one season.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a combination of things,'' John Hart, the Indians'
industrious general manager, said. ``Some of it is economics, some
of it that there were more buyers than players. We just haven't
been able to land the guys we wanted.''
</P>
<P>
   The Indians wanted Clemens when he was a free agent following
the 1996 season. They competed for him with the New York Yankees
and the Toronto Blue Jays. The offers were similar. Clemens said at
the time he wanted to play for a team that had a chance to go to
the World Series. The Indians went in 1997, the Yankees in '98;
Clemens, however, signed with the Blue Jays.
</P>
<P>
   That same winter the Indians also pursued Alex Fernandez and
thought they had him. But at the last minute his wife persuaded him
to play in Miami, their hometown, and the Indians lost him, too.
</P>
<P>
   After the 1997 season, the Indians renewed their efforts to get
a top-notch starting pitcher. They discussed a trade with Montreal
for Martinez, but the Expos accepted an offer from the Boston Red
Sox. The Indians then negotiated with a trio of free agents, Wilson
Alvarez, Darryl Kile and Andy Benes, but other teams offered far
more than they wanted to pay.
</P>
<P>
   Straying off the beaten path, they looked at another kind of
free agent that winter, the Cuban defector known as El Duque. They
were one of two or three finalists, but the Indians did not feel
they had enough information to warrant the four-year $6.6 million
contract the Yankees offered him. Hernandez became just another one
who got away.
</P>
<P>
   But the one who really got away was Randy Johnson. It was the
day of the 1998 trading deadline, and the Seattle Mariners were
ready to trade Johnson, who was three months from free agency. The
Indians, thinking they were among the front-runners, were
envisioning Johnson at the head of their rotation, pitching against
the Yankees in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   But the Houston Astros swooped in at the last minute and
snatched Johnson out of the Indians' rotation and placed him neatly
into theirs.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you look at our club traditionally,'' Hart said, ``we've
either developed players or made major trades. Our forays into the
free-agent market haven't been big, except for Robby Alomar last
year.''
</P>
<P>
   Acquiring Johnson would have been a major trade. That the
Indians did not get him was a major disappointment. When he became
a free agent after he pitched for the Astros in the postseason, the
Indians did not make a competitive offer for him. Nor did they for
Kevin Brown, although they liked the thought of having him. But
then, no one made a competitive offer for Brown. The Los Angeles
Dodgers gave him $40 million more than his next highest offer.
</P>
<P>
   Moving back to the trade route last winter, the Indians tried
again to get Clemens but lost out again, this time to the Yankees.
Then last July they made another deadline stab at bolstering their
corps of starters, trying for Finley and Scott Erickson of
Baltimore. Neither was traded.
</P>
<P>
   Last month Andy Ashby was traded, by the San Diego Padres to the
Philadelphia Phillies. The Indians tried for him, too, but they did
not want to relinquish the prospects the Padres wanted.
</P>
<P>
   It was their desire to hold on to their prospects that prompted
them to pay more to sign Finley for what will turn out to be $25
million for three years, bringing an end to their four years of
failure.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were fortunate to land him,'' Hart said. ``I thought we
were out of it at the winter meetings. We were reluctant to go
beyond where we were. But as we examined our club, we kept coming
back to the feeling that Chuck was the guy.''
</P>
<P>
   It also became apparent to Hart at the meetings last week that
he was not going to be able to trade for a pitcher. The Indians
have been one of the best teams in the American League for the past
six seasons. But their experience in the opening round of October's
playoffs was embarrassing.
</P>
<P>
   Finding themselves short of starters, the Indians used two on
three days' rest instead of on the usual four. Bartolo Colon and
Charles Nagy lasted a total of four innings as the Indians
squandered a two-games-to-one lead against the Red Sox.
</P>
<P>
   Finley gives the Cleveland rotation a stronger look, though how
much stronger they will have to see.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're not advertising him as Randy Johnson or Pedro
Martinez,'' Hart said. But at least the Indians have Finley, the
proverbial bird in hand who is worth the two who never made it to
the Indians.
</P>
</TEXT>
