<HEADLINE>
ZEILE LOVES NEW YORK; THE ETHICS DODGERS 
</HEADLINE>
  (lh) 
 By MURRAY CHASS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Does Todd Zeile like New York?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have always wanted the opportunity to play in New York
City,'' the New York Mets' new first baseman said. ``I've always
loved the opportunity to play there when it's been against the Mets
or the Yankees. I've been there three different times in playoff
atmosphere against the Yankees. In the world of sports there's no
place that compares to New York City for an athlete.''
</P>
<P>
   But does he really like New York?
</P>
<P>
   ``I have teammates who are afraid to go out of the hotel when
they get to the city,'' he said. ``I've always loved the city. I
think there's so much to do. I have children I'd love to expose to
the culture. I have great interest in the city as a whole outside
of the game of baseball.''
</P>
<P>
   Did he, like some of those teammates, ever just stay in the
hotel?
</P>
<P>
   ``Absolutely not,'' he said. ``My representatives have been
there a number of years now, so I've been able to see the city and
the personality of the city for much more than what I initially saw
there. Julianne, my wife, who was involved in gymnastics'' _ she
was Julianne McNamara, 1984 Olympic gold medalist _ ``traveled
extensively since she was young. She helped introduce me to
different things about the city. I figured if she had no fear of
the city and there was so much out there to see and experience, I
should do it. I grew to love it. Every time there was an
opportunity to go to New York City, I couldn't wait, and I often
had my family join me there.''
</P>
<P>
   Doesn't he even mind the dreaded news media the city features?
</P>
<P>
   ``I know that media scrutiny is a great part of what people are
afraid of in that city,'' he said, ``but I think if you're honest,
if you tell it like it is, if you don't run from your
responsibilities, what's the problem? The key to this is stand up
and be honest with the people who try to interpret what you do and
why. I welcome the challenge. If you can have success there, it's a
different feeling than anywhere else, at least in athletics.''
</P>
<P>
   THE ETHICS DODGERS
</P>
<P>
   Once upon a time the Los Angeles Dodgers portrayed themselves as
the epitome of a well-run, highly efficient, purest-of-pure
organization. It was only a fairy tale, it seems.
</P>
<P>
   The Dodgers are not the only organization that has signed Latin
players illegally. Nor are they the only one that has been caught.
But the Dodgers were nabbed having scouted players in Cuba and
spiriting them out of the off-limits island, then lying about where
they discovered them, and now they have been caught with a gun that
spews so much smoke the city had to declare a smog alert.
</P>
<P>
   Not only did the Dodgers sign Adrian Beltre, their young third
baseman from the Dominican Republic, a year before he reached the
legal age of 16, but they kept obviously altered documents in their
files.
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner Bud Selig is expected to rule on the matter Monday,
and he may allow the Dodgers to keep Beltre while issuing a heavy
fine and other disciplinary action. And he may extend the
foreign-signing ban imposed on the club in the Cuban matter, which
was supposed to end next Friday.
</P>
<P>
   But if he allows the Dodgers to keep Beltre, thus avoiding an
expensive free-agent pursuit among several clubs, he will almost
certainly trigger a grievance from the players association.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our current inclination is to file if they don't grant him
free agency,'' said Gene Orza, the union's associate general
counsel, ``but I want to read the opinion. It may have something in
it. But it's going to have to be a very persuasive opinion for us
not to file.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
