<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NEILSON19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Neilson an upbeat Flyer
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   He is on a cell phone in a car doing an interview as he is being
driven from one function to another. It has been this way for a
week, ever since Philadelphia Flyers coach Roger Neilson showed his
players a clip from a Monty Python movie to loosen them up, then
broke the news to them and the world: He has cancer.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had no idea there'd be this much publicity over it,''
Neilson said. ``It's really getting a lot more than it deserves.''
</P>
<P>
   When the Flyers arrived in Toronto the other day, a hotel
ballroom was set up for a Neilson news conference. The 65-year-old
coach took one look around and said, ``It reminds me of when I got
fired. Cancer is such a dreaded word. You die and get less
publicity.''
</P>
<P>
   The jokes haven't stopped, nor has Neilson's affinity for loud
ties. But reality will arrive with a cold slap Monday. After
several delays, the Flyers coach is scheduled to begin chemotherapy
treatments for multiple myeloma, an incurable form of bone-marrow
cancer. Dr. Isadore Brodsky, the chief of hematology at Hahnemann
(Pa.) University Hospital, is downplaying statistics that show
patients in Neilson's age bracket generally live five years,
saying, ``I'd put Roger's life expectancy easily beyond five years,
and even 10 or 15 years or longer. People who hear `cancer' or
`leukemia' want to assume it's a death sentence, but that's not
necessarily the case. Georges Pompidou, the premier of France,
lived with multiple myeloma for 20 years.''
</P>
<P>
   Neilson, who hopes to be able to coach Tuesday night in New
Jersey, has received standing ovations at every turn. They stood in
Toronto when the scoreboard read, ``Roger: This cheer's for you.''
They stood in Philadelphia when the video screen showed him behind
the bench at the Flyers' first home game since the announcement. On
both occasions, he was moved to tears.
</P>
<P>
   Two months ago, they were talking about firing him.
</P>
<P>
   Neilson again: ``I've been getting hundreds of calls and
letters, everybody suggesting cures and telling me encouraging
stories about people who have beat cancer. All the support has been
great. It just seems like right now it's never going to end. I'm
looking forward to the time things get back to normal a little.''
</P>
<P>
   Neilson doesn't believe the Flyers' losses immediately following
his announcement was a case of his players being distracted. ``We
only lost three of our last 23 games,'' he said. ``The problem now
is every time we lost, the media is going to say the players are
distracted. That's not the case at all.''
</P>
<P>
   Neilson is scheduled to have a bone-marrow transplant in late
February or early March, which will require a three-week stay in
the hospital and three to four weeks of recovery. He could miss the
first round of the playoffs, prompting him to allude to his past
early playoff problems and joke, ``(General manager) Bob Clarke
pointed out that wouldn't be a bad idea, me missing the first
round.''
</P>
<P>
   As to his future, Neilson said last week, ``I believe God has a
plan for my life and this is part of that plan. If the plan is to
beat it or not beat it, I accept it. At least in the games up in
heaven you won't have to deal with Kris King or Tie Domi.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
