<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLEAST19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NHL East notes
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Is it worth it?
</P>
<P>
   In a marketing ploy between the league and players union, each
team conducts a ``skills competition'' every year, in which players
compete in a variety of areas: skating, shooting, goaltending _ the
usual. But after Florida goalie Trevor Kidd suffered a dislocated
right shoulder last week, sidelining him for at least two months,
some teams are wondering if it's a bad idea. Kidd's injury occurred
during a rapid-fire shooting drill when he went to reach for a shot
by Peter Worrell.
</P>
<P>
   Approximately 6,000 students from 43 South Florida middle
schools watched as Kidd went down to the ice in agony.
</P>
<P>
   ``I started skating away, and he started screaming,'' Worrell
said. ``I thought he was just fooling around. I turned back, and I
realized he was in some pain.''
</P>
<P>
   Kidd is 13-4-2 this year and ranks among the league leaders in
save percentage (.930) and goals-against average (2.08).
</P>
<P>
   The Panthers' Scott Mellanby said, ``It's something we shouldn't
have to deal with. There's enough problems trying to stay healthy.
You want to grow the game and all that, but it's a risky thing.''
</P>
<P>
   What's Bruin
</P>
<P>
   Before Boston ended a six-game winless streak _ after a
nine-game winless streak to open the season _ a Boston newspaper
pointed out that such results often get coaches fired. It would be
hard to imagine the Bruins pushing Pat Burns out. He's probably one
of the five best coaches in the league. But Burns read the
commentary and responded the next day, ``Don't stick a fork in us
yet. The fork's getting ready to (be) stuck in me. We're not dead
yet. This is early in the season.'' The coach also put the onus on
some of his team's struggling forwards, like Jason Allison and Dave
Andreychuk. ``The guys who are going to make you win are your
offensive weapons,'' he said. ``If they don't go, I don't know how
we're going to do it. I don't care if the Lord is behind the bench
and Moses is GM, it's not going to make a difference.''
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Buffalo's Michael Peca continues to struggle with five goals in
31 games and is a minus-eight in plus-minus. Peca, a Selke Trophy
winner as the league's best defensive forward, was on the ice for
all four goals in a loss to Philadelphia. ... The latest from
Sabres goalie Dominik Hasek on rumors that he may reverse his
retirement decision with an injury possibly prematurely ending his
season: ``We'll see.'' ... New Jersey did not raise ticket prices
this season, but it failed to sell out any of its first 16 home
games, and average attendance is down about 2,000. ``The people in
charge have to be a little worried,'' goalie Martin Brodeur said.
``At first we thought it was (because of) the Yankees (competing
for fans' dollars), but the Yankees are long gone. And when you
look and see empty seats for a Rangers game, you think, `Wow,
what's going on?''' ... War of words: Toronto's Tie Domi said he
won't fight Philadelphia's Sandy McCarthy, just to teach him a
lesson for falsely accusing Domi of using a racial slur against
McCarthy in a game last year. Domi on McCarthy: ``I think he draws
pictures, but I don't think he knows how to speak. Actually, the
only words he knows how to say are `fight' and `chicken.'''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
