</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLITEMS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Faceoff with Steve Yzerman
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steve Yzerman, Detroit Red Wings
</P>
<P>
   _ Update: Leads Detroit in scoring with 29 points (through
Thursday), with five of his 14 goals coming on the power play.
Ranks 10th all-time in goals (606), ninth in assists (906). Leads
North American team in voting for All-Star Game.
</P>
<P>
   _ On former N.Y. Islanders star Bryan Trottier: ``He was my
idol. I followed him from the minute he came in the NHL. The
Islanders were an up-and-coming team, so as a young kid I started
to follow them. I just admired the way he played the game and how
he carried himself on the ice. I like the fact that he was pretty
quiet; didn't say a whole lot. I tried to kind of copy a lot of
things he did as far as the kind of helmet he wore; the way he
celebrated a goal; the way he taped his stick. I watched everything
that he did. But most of all I like the way he played.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On playing 17 seasons with one team: ``There were a couple of
occasions where it was possible that I might be traded. I think the
only thing that makes it a little bit more difficult now is a lot
of decisions are going to be based on finance, where in the past, I
don't think that was true because there wasn't such a great range
in salaries.''
</P>
<P>
   _ On Detroit signing Pat Verbeek: ``The best thing he brings to
our team is that he is a hard guy to play against. He's gritty.
He's abrasive. The more guys you can have that are hard to play
against, it's a plus come playoff time. Abrasive guys seem to excel
when it is a tight, close game and there is not a lot of scoring
opportunities and a lot of the soft calls like interference you get
during the regular season aren't called in a tight playoff game
</P>
<P>
   _ On Dallas' post-Cup struggles: ``My feeling is they're going
to get stronger as the playoffs get closer. I don't know how they
felt coming back (after the title). But the way I felt, you've just
been through so much, with the intensity and emotion that you have
in the playoffs, and two months later you've got to turn around and
do it again. Every time a team beats you, particularly when you're
on the road, it's like the Stanley Cup playoff victory for them.
Combined with all the injuries, that's made it difficult for
them.''
</P>
<P>
   Catch this
</P>
<P>
   Some goaltenders believe new restrictions on catching gloves,
which are two inches smaller this year, have left them more
susceptible to injury. There was evidence last week, when four
goalies (Phoenix's Sean Burke, Los Angeles' Stephane Fiset,
Detroit's Chris Osgood and Chicago's Jocelyn Thibault) went out
with hand injuries. ``There's no margin for error anymore,'' said
Toronto's Curtis Joseph. ``If you close your hand too fast and
catch a shot on the end of the glove, you're in trouble.'' Thibault
did precisely that on a blast by St. Louis's Al MacInnis and broke
his ring finger in two places.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
