</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLWEST19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    NHL West notes
 &HT;    By Jeff Schultz
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Windy City rumors
</P>
<P>
   San Jose coach Darryl Sutter did nothing to shoot down rumors
about his candidacy for the coaching job in Chicago after the
season when he spoke about his goals for the future last week: ``To
win a Stanley Cup for San Jose. After that, I don't give a
(expletive).'' So Sharks general manager Dean Lombardi did his best
to cool things, saying, he ``can't imagine'' Sutter and new
Blackhawks director of operations Mike Smith coexisting. ``They're
opposites as people and opposites in philosophy,'' Lombardi said.
``If I know anything about their philosophies, it would be like oil
and water.'' Lombardi said he and Sutter have a ``handshake''
agreement on a new contract, but that it might not be finalized
until after the season. ``He knows we want him,'' Lombardi said.
``I think he wants to be here. With nine (players) without
contracts (for next season), he's in the trenches, and the last
thing he wants is him getting a contract and them not.'' Meanwhile,
Lorne Molleken continues to act as associate coach as he stands
next to VP-GM-coach-retiree-in-waiting Bob Pulford.
</P>
<P>
   Old ways in Dallas
</P>
<P>
   The signing of free-agent forward Kirk Muller (33) and the
acquisition of defenseman Kevin Dean (30) from the Thrashers seem
to indicate Dallas, after a planned youth movement, has returned to
its old ways. But general manager Bob Gainey said, ``I wouldn't say
we've changed our focus or our plan on how we're using our younger
players. We have four younger players in the lineup right now and
had you asked me at the beginning of the season I probably wouldn't
have thought we'd have that many. This gets us more in line with
where we thought we would be as far as veterans go.'' Dean, who
admitted he could not play an expanded role with the Thrashers,
also said he was beaten down by the losing: ``I played in New
Jersey all those years and got used to winning. I thought I'd like
it in Atlanta, but it was horrible. I didn't think losing was going
to be so frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Briefly
</P>
<P>
   Vancouver has played nine rookies this season, leading coach
Marc Crawford to say, ``It's not very often you get an opportunity
to do that. It's not very often you want an opportunity to do it.''
... Stickgate: Colorado had officials check the sticks of two
Anaheim players (Teemu Selanne and Dominic Roussel) and both were
found to be of illegal proportion. The result was a two-man power
play with a goal by Sandis Ozolinsh, but the Mighty Ducks won 4-2.
The reaction from Ducks coach Craig Hartsburg: ``We're also going
to ask the league to investigate this building (the new Pepsi
Center). There is no door to our stick room and it's right next to
their dressing room door. Maybe we cheated with the illegal sticks,
but maybe they cheated in the way they checked our sticks. Let
other teams that come in here beware.'' ... After scoring five
points in his first game back from shoulder surgery, Colorado's
Peter Forsberg had one assist and was a minus-four in his next six
games. ``I get tired kind of easy,'' he said. ``It's something I
kind of knew would happen, but it's real frustrating.'' ...
Nashville sent goalie Thomas Vokoun (0-8-1, 3.54) to the minors and
next they may send him to a sports psychologist. Vokoun was
12-18-4, 2.95 last year. ``Right now, he's like the second baseman
who can't make the throw to first, or the actor who gets stage
fright,'' goalie coach Mitch Korn said.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
