<SLUG> BC-ITALY-POLITICS-400&AMP;ADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ITALY'S PREMIER OUTLINES PLAN TO RESHAPE HIS COALITION 
</HEADLINE>
  (js) 
 By ALESSANDRA STANLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   ROME _ Seeking to avert early elections, Italy's beleaguered
prime minister, Massimo D'Alema, told Parliament Saturday that he
wants to remold his fragile, divided majority into a ``stable and
strong'' center-left coalition.
</P>
<P>
   ``Italy does not need lacerations or a traumatic dissolution of
its legislature,'' he said in a 40-minute speech. ``It needs a
government that operates to its full capacity and that can carry
out the necessary and possible reforms.''
</P>
<P>
   The speech was the culmination of a tumultuous political week,
in which the government's inherently brittle center-left coalition
grew badly frayed from within. Unless Parliament decides to support
D'Alema, the prime minister would have to offer his resignation to
President Carlo Azeglio Ciampi. Ciampi would then consult political
leaders across the board to see if he can give D'Alema a green
light to try to form a new majority, a process that could take
days.
</P>
<P>
   If D'Alema fails, and no other center-left leader succeeds in
forming a majority, then Italy would be plunged into new elections.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday's showdown underscored the fragility of Italy's
political system, which still partly awards seats to political
parties on the basis of their share of the national vote, and thus
allows tiny parties representing few voters considerable power in
forming _ and wrecking _ coalitions. Party loyalty is not a
prerequisite for political office. Since April 1996, 108 members of
Parliament have changed parties, 20 have shifted allegiances twice,
and one has moved four times.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema, who delivered a state-of-the-nation style address that
highlighted the accomplishments of his 14-month administration,
said that Italy had pulled out of ``the black hole'' it found
itself in the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   He urged Parliament to help create a bipolar system that would
be more stable. But efforts to streamline the splintered Italian
electoral system and build a two-party system similar to those that
exist in the United States and Britain have continually broken
down.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly enough, last week's free-for-all did not prevent the
government from passing a budget for next year. Saturday night, the
Senate approved an uncontroversial package that includes small tax
cuts and deficit reduction, and which was passed by the lower house
of Parliament on Thursday.
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   But internal power struggles with the majority came to a head at
the same time, when the Socialists within the coalition infuriated
the prime minister last weekend by saying he should be replaced.
</P>
<P>
   Although the center-left majority is desperate to avoid early
elections, which polls suggest it could lose to the center-right
opposition, there is deep debate within the coalition as to whether
D'Alema is the best choice as leader for elections due in April
2001.
</P>
<P>
   The tension turned dramatic when Beniamino Andreatta, a former
defense minister and a member of Parliament who supports D'Alema,
had a massive heart attack on the house floor late Wednesday night,
and was rushed to a hospital, where he remains in a coma.
</P>
<P>
   Then, things grew ugly when the parliamentarian, Paolo Bampo,
accused another deputy, Luca Bagliani, a member of a centrist party
who is loyal to D'Alema, of seeking to bribe him to support the
prime minister. Bagliani and D'Alema angrily denied the charges,
and the speaker of Parliament set up a special committee to
investigate.
</P>
<P>
   But the vote-buying accusation prompted Francesco Cossiga, a
former president and a maverick centrist who backed D'Alema in
1998, to pull his support. D'Alema began his speech by saying that
vote-buying was ``intolerable,'' but he failed to mollify Cossiga's
party, which announced afterwards that it would request D'Alema's
resignation.
</P>
<P>
   Cossiga, long a thorn in the side of the center-left, announced
Saturday night that he would fly to Tunisia to meet with the former
socialist prime minister, Bettino Craxi, a fugitive from justice
who is ill in exile. The surprise trip seemed less like a sickbed
visit than an attempt to lure Socialists over to his side.
</P>
<P>
   D'Alema, a former Communist who founded a non-Marxist party
after the collapse of the Soviet Union, Democrats of the Left, was
catapulted to power 14 months ago, when his center-left
predecessor, Romano Prodi, lost a confidence vote in Parliament by
one vote.
</P>
<P>
   As with Saturday's drama, that showdown was forced by splits
within the majority. At that time, D'Alema put together a similar
center-left coalition that stretched uncomfortably across the
spectrum, including both Communists and small centrist parties,
like Cossiga's, that sprung up after the Christian Democratic party
collapsed in the early 1990s under the weight of scandals.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
