<HEADLINE>
BISHOP FULTON SHEEN, ON THE LONG ROAD TO SAINTHOOD
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By ROBERT D. McFADDEN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Archbishop Fulton J. Sheen, whose television ministry
in the 1950s reached 25 million viewers _ more than Milton Berle _
and made him the most prominent spokesman of the Roman Catholic
Church in America, could become a candidate for sainthood under a
process begun by a Franciscan friar he inspired as a boy.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Andrew Apostoli, 56, a friar at St. Felix Friary in
Yonkers, has received permission from Cardinal John O'Connor to
begin a study of the life, writings and teachings of the
archbishop, the first of many steps required to canonize the
evangelist, who died in New York City in 1979 at the age of 84.
</P>
<P>
   Apostoli, whom Sheen ordained in 1967, was traveling Saturday
and unavailable for comment, but a spokesman for the New York
Archdiocese, Joseph Zwilling, confirmed that Apostoli and the
Archbishop Fulton Sheen Foundation, based in El Paso, Texas, had
been given permission by the cardinal to began a study that could
lead to canonization.
</P>
<P>
   The study could take five years. If approved by the cardinal's
successor, it would be sent to the Vatican for papal endorsement,
which would be followed by witnesses' testimony and evidence of one
miracle for beatification and two for canonization, or sainthood.
</P>
<P>
   Such miracles are usually healings without medical explanation
in people who appealed to the candidate through prayer.
</P>
<P>
   Known as Bishop Fulton J. Sheen, though he became a titular
archbishop a decade before his death, the evangelist brought a
blend of religion, advice and conservative politics into millions
of homes on his weekly half-hour television show, ``Life Is Worth
Living,'' on the DuMont Network and later ABC from 1951 to 1957.
</P>
<P>
   With high cheekbones and mesmerizing blue eyes so deep-set and
piercing that many thought they were black, Sheen spoke on freedom,
pleasure, war and peace, love and many other subjects, mostly with
a Christian but not specifically Roman Catholic outlook that
appealed to viewers of many faiths. He spoke simply, casually,
often humorously, although he said each talk was carefully prepared
and represented hours of study and rehearsal.
</P>
<P>
   Slotted on Tuesday nights against Milton Berle and Frank Sinatra
on larger networks, he swamped the competition with ratings that
soared, and eventually reached more than 25 million viewers on 123
stations. During his heyday, he was national director of the
Society for the Propagation of the Faith, whose goal was to spread
Catholic teachings.
</P>
<P>
   Bishop Sheen, who won many awards, including an Emmy, had been
well-known on radio long before the television program. He had been
featured in the Sunday evening ``Catholic Hour'' on NBC in the
1930s and in 1940, he conducted the first telecast religious
service.
</P>
<P>
   Many of his talks were controversial. He was stridently
anti-Communist, and during the Spanish Civil War he supported
Franco's fascist-supported insurgency against the government. He
defended corporal punishment in schools, and opposed Freudianism so
strongly that Catholic psychologists protested, fearing that his
polemics might steer the faithful away from needed therapy.
</P>
<P>
   He was famous for his conversions, of ordinary people en masse
and of such celebrities as Fritz Kreisler, Heywood Broun, Clare
Boothe Luce, Henry Ford II and Louis Budenz, the managing editor of
The Daily Worker, the Communist party newspaper in America.
</P>
<P>
   Sheen, who wrote more than 50 books of popular evangelism and a
widely syndicated newspaper column, lived most of his life in New
York City, but was reassigned in 1966 to become bishop of
Rochester, his first pastoral post in 40 years.
</P>
<P>
   He retired in 1969, was given the title of archbishop and moved
back to New York. He is buried beneath the high altar in the crypt
of St. Patrick's Cathedral.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
