<SLUG> BC-CALIF-REDEVELOP-REAL-780(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW DOWNTOWN FOR A LOS ANGELES SUBURB 
</HEADLINE>
  (lb) 
 By MORRIS NEWMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   BREA, Calif. _ This city 30 miles east of downtown Los Angeles
is creating an all new downtown around its busiest intersection in
an effort to restore pedestrian activity and public spaces to a
community that has lacked a downtown for nearly a decade.
</P>
<P>
   The redevelopment effort is notable in this traditionally
suburban community for introducing such urban approaches as parking
garages to encourage patronage of downtown enterprises and loft
apartment buildings with retail space.
</P>
<P>
   ``We are trying to put this downtown back,'' said Shaul Kuba, a
principal of CIM Group LLC, a Los Angeles-based developer that is
constructing 13 buildings, including three with a total of 62 loft
apartments plus retail space here. ``It's basically giving the
heart and soul back to the community.''
</P>
<P>
   The redevelopment project, which is expected to be completed
sometime next year, will contain 400,000 square feet of stores and
restaurants, 22 movie screens, 96 detached houses and 40 town
houses in addition to the loft apartments. The Brea Redevelopment
Agency has built two parking structures with a total of 1,750
spaces.
</P>
<P>
   Brea's effort is part of a larger trend in California in which
existing, mature cities are being retrofitted with walkable,
villagelike downtown areas. Brea is unusual in creating its
six-block downtown out of an empty site, rather than filling in and
refurbishing an existing urban hub. City officials decided against
redeveloping the historic downtown area because it did not have
enough commercial land for the project.
</P>
<P>
   Brea's loss of its original downtown, and the decision to build
a new one, both stem from the city's pro-growth attitude.
</P>
<P>
   In 1898, oil was discovered in Brea (the word means tar in
Spanish, as evidenced by the La Brea Tar Pits, west of downtown Los
Angeles). Soon, wooden derricks spread across the landscape. The
city remained an oil town, and a bedroom community for employees of
the oil industry, into the 1960s.
</P>
<P>
   Surrounded by orange groves, the city was comparatively isolated
until the completion of the Orange Freeway (Route 57) in the early
1970s. The freeway tied Brea more closely to the fast-growing
economy of Orange County.
</P>
<P>
   With the decline of the oil industry, city officials promoted
Brea as a center for both industry and back-office operations,
primarily for insurance and banking concerns. Their efforts seem to
have succeeded, for the city's current daytime population of
100,000 is nearly three times as large as its resident population
of 34,000.
</P>
<P>
   As in many U.S. cities, Brea's rapid growth was paralleled by a
decline in the downtown area. In the early 1970s, when a regional
mall opened several miles away from the traditional town center,
``downtown began to suffer,'' said Susan Georgino, the city's
redevelopment services director.
</P>
<P>
   Further damage to the old downtown occurred in the early '90s,
when transportation officials widened Brea Boulevard, the city's
main street and site of many of older buildings and businesses.
Expanding the boulevard from a four-lane to a six-lane,
140-foot-wide freeway resulted in the loss of a number of older
buildings.
</P>
<P>
   In the course of becoming a vibrant business center, Brea lost
its city center as well as part of its history. ``There is no
community gathering place,'' Ms. Georgino said. ``There is no place
that is Brea.''
</P>
<P>
   Brea has been studying a way of restoring a downtown area since
1987. The redevelopment effort has been an ongoing project
involving several designers and developers.
</P>
<P>
   The first phase of the project was a conventional
200,000-square-foot shopping center and 96 residential ``cottages''
with traditional architectural features, including front porches
and peaked roofs.
</P>
<P>
   In 1997, the city commissioned a new master plan from RTKL
Associates, a Baltimore-based architectural firm, which included
the design of the remaining four blocks of vacant land that the
city had owned for more than a decade.
</P>
<P>
   RTKL's design extended Birch Street into the vacant site, and
surrounded it with entertainment and retail uses. The designers
were also careful to include a number of small public spaces
throughout the site. On the other side of Brea, town houses and
apartment houses are expected to fill three full blocks. Olson Co.
of Seal Beach, Calif., plans to start construction on the housing
next year.
</P>
<P>
   Nathan Cherry, the master-plan architect, said that the project
contained other elements beyond retail, such as a new church,
public art and newly planted trees.
</P>
<P>
   Those elements, he said, provide a ``critical mass of civic
elements that are really going to make the thing authentic.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE _ OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Not all Brea residents were receptive to Cherry's urban-design
ideas, however. He recalled one city councilman saying to him, ``I
don't think that parking structure is going to work,'' because the
stroll from the parking stall to a new restaurant in the area took
three minutes. But Cherry said that many urban designers now
believe that a walking time between parking and destination of five
minutes or less is considered ideal for promoting foot traffic.
</P>
<P>
   The first project to be built under RTKL's master plan was the
Birch Street Promenade, the retail and mixed-use portion undertaken
by CIM Group.
</P>
<P>
   Cooperation between the developer and city government is one
reason for the rapid development of the project, which has taken
little more than two years from the start of design to the
completion of construction, according to Kuba, the developer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Typically a street consists of many properties and it takes a
long time to assemble enough real estate to get a critical mass,''
he said. But in this case, the city assembled the land and the
development process moved forward quickly, he said.
</P>
<P>
   In an effort to give Birch Street a sense of urban variety, CIM
Group hired different architects for each of its buildings. ``We
want the area to look as if it evolved over time, even though it
was actually built all at the same time,'' said John Given, an
urban designer and developer with CIM Group.
</P>
<P>
   Architects designed the buildings not only to be attractive, but
also to play distinct roles in the larger life of the street.
</P>
<P>
   A building with storefronts at street level and loft-style
apartments on upper stories, designed by Koning Eizenberg
Architecture of Santa Monica, is a variation on a building type
that was once nearly universal on shopping streets.
</P>
<P>
   At the end of the street is a flamboyant two-story retail
building with a decorative obelisk built into the facade that
serves as a visual exclamation point for the new stretch of Birch
Street. The architect is Kanner Associates of Los Angeles.
</P>
<P>
   Other buildings are understated, ``background'' buildings such
as the retail building, with loft-style apartments on second and
third levels, designed by Koning Eizenberg. Situated at the center
of the block, the building provides the street with an orderly row
of storefront spaces, without calling undue attention to itself as
a design object.
</P>
<P>
   Although still unfinished, the Promenade is increasingly crowded
with pedestrians, fulfilling the developer's prediction of an unmet
demand for pedestrian-friendly places.
</P>
<P>
   One merchant who is pleased is Sally Waranch, owner of Sarah
Bain Gallery on Birch Street, which moved from nearby Fullerton. In
its former location, visitors to the gallery had to make a special
trip by car, she said, adding that ``there was maybe one walk-in a
day.''
</P>
<P>
   But in the new Brea downtown, Ms. Waranch said, 200 to 300
people show up on weekends. ``We are selling quite a bit of art to
new clientele,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
