<P>
   ATTENTION EDITORS: The following photos are part of tonight's
New York Times Photo Package, moving Saturday, 12/18/99. Photo
clients will automatically receive these photos via AP's
PhotoExpress or may download them from either the Wieck Photo
Database in Dallas at 972-392-0888 or from NYTPhotos on Newscom at
305-448-8411. Non-clients can make individual purchases by calling
(888) 603-1036 or 212-556-4204.
</P>
<P>
   (NYT9) NEW YORK -- Dec. 18, 1999 -- NY-FATAL-FUMES -- Gas fumes
in a popular supper club, ``The Laura Belle'' restaurant in Times
Square, left one night-shift employee dead Saturday morning and
four others hospitalized, one in critical condition, as the police
closed off the block, evacuated a building next door and checked
manholes and nearby basements for evidence of carbon monoxide. Five
rescue workers were also overcome by fumes. Firefighters dragged
the five unconscious custodial workers from the club at 120 W. 43rd
St. shortly after 10 a.m. (Earl Wilson/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT8) NEW YORK -- Dec. 18, 1999 -- OBIT-WASHINGTON-2 -- Grover
Washington Jr., the jazz saxophonist and composer, producer and
arranger of jazz fusion, playing at the Blue Note in 1998.
Washington died Friday night in New York City after taping four
songs for a television show. He was 56. Washington was taken to St.
Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center following his collapse after he
performed the songs for ``The Saturday Early Show'' on CBS. He died
of an apparent heart attack. He released about 30 solo albums, five
of which went gold. Washington won a Grammy Award for best fusion
jazz performance, vocal or instrumental, in 1981 for ``Winelight,''
his platinum album, which included the hit single ``Just the Two of
Us,'' with Bill Withers. (Steve Berman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT7) NEW YORK -- Dec. 18, 1999 -- OBIT-WASHINGTON-1 -- Grover
Washington Jr., the jazz saxophonist and composer, producer and
arranger of jazz fusion, playing at the Blue Note in 1998.
Washington died Friday night in New York City after taping four
songs for a television show. He was 56. Washington was taken to St.
Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center following his collapse after he
performed the songs for ``The Saturday Early Show'' on CBS. He died
of an apparent heart attack. He released about 30 solo albums, five
of which went gold. Washington won a Grammy Award for best fusion
jazz performance, vocal or instrumental, in 1981 for ``Winelight,''
his platinum album, which included the hit single ``Just the Two of
Us,'' with Bill Withers. (Steve Berman/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT6) NEW YORK -- Dec. 18, 1999 -- GLOBAL-WARMING --
Unseasonable warmth is causing a variety of flowers to blossom at
the New York Botanical Garden in the Bronx. Federal scientists
reported last week that in the contiguous 48 states and on other
global land masses, 1999 is certain to join 1998 as one of the two
warmest years on record, continuing a long-term trend toward a
warmer climate that has been especially sharp in the last quarter
of the 20th century. (Suzanne DeChillo/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT5) SAN FRANCISCO -- Dec. 18, 1999 -- HOMELESS-PROFILE-2 --
Kathleen Gray, 44, with her boyfriend, David Aquino, 45, an
ex-postal worker who quit his job, live together in a van on the
streets of San Francisco. Until she became homeless, Gray says she
always looked at people living on the streets with something like
revulsion. ``Now I know it's a lot harder to get out of the fix
than to get in it,'' says Gray. San Francisco, flush with Silicon
Valley professionals, has become so expensive that a six-figure
income is considered middle-class, and basic items like a gallon of
regular gas cost more than anywhere else in the country. (Monica
Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT4) SAN FRANCISCO -- Dec. 18, 1999 -- HOMELESS-PROFILE-1 --
With landlords asking for three months' rent up front, Kathleen
Gray, 44, and her boyfriend, David Aquino, 45, are not sure when
they will be able to abandon the van in which they have been living
illegally for almost two years in San Francisco. Their dog, Kaya,
also lives with them. San Francisco, flush with Silicon Valley
professionals, has become so expensive that a six-figure income is
considered middle-class, and basic items like a gallon of regular
gas cost more than anywhere else in the country. (Monica
Almeida/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT3) WASHINGTON -- Dec. 18, 1999 -- STAR-SUCCESSOR -- Robert
W. Ray, 39, replacement to Kenneth W. Starr, in his Washington
office. Unlike Starr, who had never been a prosecutor or tried a
case, Ray is a member of that distinct species in the law, career
prosecutors, people steeped in a culture aimed at bringing down the
bad guys while valuing zeal tempered with discretion. In that role,
Ray built a reputation in New York as an aggressive prosecutor with
an enviable rate of success. (Paul Hosefros/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT2) NEW YORK -- Dec. 18, 1999 -- POET-BOOK-BATTLE-2 -- High
school students from Brooklyn talking with poet Billy Collins, 58,
center, whose popularity has provoked a publishing battle, pitting
a huge commercial publisher against a small academic press over a
literary poet. It is an argument about money, with a distinct
David-and-Goliath plot, but it is also about publishing ethics and
the right of an author to determine the direction of his own
career. ( Jeff Zelevansky/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   (NYT1) NEW YORK -- Dec. 18, 1999 -- POET-BOOK-BATTLE-1 -- Poet
Billy Collins, 58, whose popularity has provoked a publishing
battle, pitting a huge commercial publisher against a small
academic press over a literary poet. It is an argument about money,
with a distinct David-and-Goliath plot, but it is also about
publishing ethics and the right of an author to determine the
direction of his own career. ( Jeff Zelevansky/The New York Times)
</P>
<P>
   The New York Times News Service
</P>
