<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 18:15 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2884 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-AMERICA-CUP-DEMISE-82     12-18 0860
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AMERICA-CUP-DEMISE-820(2TAKES)-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
SHOCK OF YOUNG AMERICA'S DEFEAT SINKS IN
</HEADLINE>
   (jw) 
 By HERB McCORMICK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   The breeze was building and the seas were stacking up in the
waters off Auckland, New Zealand. It was Nov. 9 and Young America,
the New York Yacht Club's challenger for the America's Cup, had
just begun a race with Japan's Nippon Challenge in the preliminary
trials to determine who would face Team New Zealand in February's
cup finals.
</P>
<P>
   Hours later, the first of Young America's two
multimillion-dollar vessels, USA 53, sustained cataclysmic hull
damage and nearly sank. When Young America was eliminated from the
cup trials last week, USA 53's dramatic accident was cited as the
catalyst for an irreversible downward spiral from which the New
Yorkers never recovered.
</P>
<P>
   Now, everyone involved is grappling to comprehend what happened
to a talented syndicate that began last October's cup season as a
huge favorite to advance at least as far as the six-boat
challenger's semifinals, which start Jan. 2. ``It's hard to
identify a single factor,'' said John Marshall, Young America's
president, after his team was ousted.
</P>
<P>
   Criticism of Young America was swift and direct. ``They arrived
in Auckland with a kind of swagger, the rightful owners of the cup
come to reclaim their property,'' wrote Ivor Wilkins, a New Zealand
journalist. ``But arrogance left them friendless in a hostile
world.''
</P>
<P>
   The Hauraki Gulf was the hostile world on Nov. 9. Young
America's problems actually began just moments after the start,
when a critical piece of deck hardware started to peel away.
``There was some delamination under the tracks for our jib leads,''
said Jerry Kirby, a member of the crew. ``We broke a little
structural piece and had to move the leads outboard. We actually
carried the wrong jib for two legs and we were still beating the
Japanese.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were thinking that even when things don't go perfect for
us, this boat is still fast enough to bail us out.''
</P>
<P>
   But if 53 was fast, it was also flawed. ``Thirty seconds from
the top mark for the last leg, we snapped in half,'' Kirby said.
``Who knows what our future would've been if we'd gotten around
it?''
</P>
<P>
   Kirby says that the delaminated deck was unrelated to the later
incident. But what happened to the carbon-fiber structure remains
unclear, though Russell Bowler of Farr Yacht Designs, the yacht's
designer, has an idea.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was a huge impact when the boat struck a big wave,''
Bowler said. ``The drives for the on-board computers crashed at the
point of impact. We hit this piece of water pretty hard, and this
one area of the boat wasn't ready for it.''
</P>
<P>
   Young America hurriedly substituted its second boat, USA 58, for
the remainder of the round. But they forfeited a race in the
change-over, and lost other races because the new boat wasn't
ready. ``We were sort of flying blind,'' Kirby said. ``Those lost
races took away our points buffer and maybe a little confidence.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Young America controlled its destiny going into the third
qualifying round. Quick losses to Italy's Prada Challenge and
Nippon _ races that USA 58 lost because of questionable strategy _
were crucial, but not fatal. But the losing continued, and it
coincided with a winning streak by Le Defi Francais.
</P>
<P>
   In the latter stages of the round, suddenly Young America needed
outside help from two American teams, Paul Cayard's America One and
Dawn Riley's America True, to sustain their hopes of advancing into
the semifinal fleet of six.
</P>
<P>
   That help was not forthcoming. On Dec. 11, Le Defi beat America
One by 25 seconds. Two days later, the French were awarded a
victory when America True, already qualified for the semis and
fearful of damaging its single boat, withdrew from a scheduled
race. For Young America, it was over.
</P>
<P>
   Though Young America's skipper, Ed Baird, concedes that no
matter what the actions of his competitors, his team would have
advanced had it simply won more races. Still, he remains bitter
about what transpired in the final days of the third round.
Specifically, he feels that Cayard handed his race to the French.
``We lost key races at the wrong time and allowed other teams to
make the choices they did,'' Baird said, ``of letting their races
be won.'' Moreover, many Young America team members believe that
there were America One crewmen who knew the outcome of the race in
advance and placed wagers on the French to win.
</P>
<P>
   Cayard denies both allegations. ``We put forth our best race
against the French,'' he said. ``They aren't slow and it was a
pretty good day for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``As for the betting, that's absolutely not true. We heard the
rumors swirling around so we questioned everyone, and no one on our
team made a bet.''
</P>
<P>
   For Young America, it's clear why other syndicates would want
them eliminated. ``Everyone knows we probably have the fastest
boats down here,'' Kirby said.
</P>
<P>
   Baird added: ``A lot of competitors felt our team was a likely
candidate to win this event. They were nervous to race us.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Of course, if Young America was so powerful, why didn't it win
more races?
</P>
<P>
   Some observers conclude it was simply poor sailing due to a lack
of chemistry in Young America's afterguard, which included Baird,
Tony Rey and Ed Adams, both first-time cup competitors. Had Young
America advanced, sources within the camp said a shake-up was in
the works. One possible plan was for Baird to start the boat and
then hand over the helm to concentrate on tactics.
</P>
<P>
   Others believe that the loss of USA 53 was the devastating blow,
not only because it was a proven performer, but also because it
served as a tuning benchmark for USA 58.
</P>
<P>
   Marshall was open and reflective in defeat. ``The critical
decision that left us vulnerable was made over a year ago, when we
decided to extend the design program,'' he said. ``That cost us
some time on the water.''
</P>
<P>
   Certainly, had his team been sailing months earlier, as was
originally planned, the weakness in USA 53 might have been
discovered earlier, and 58 could have been tuned and ready when the
time came.
</P>
<P>
   Remarkably, 53 has been repaired and is once again ready to
sail. This week, the Young America team members plan to test its
soundness. They will sail alone and unchallenged, finished with the
event before the money round begins. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
