A2892 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-ESCAPE-CAPTURE-KAN &LR;      12-18 0586
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ESCAPE-CAPTURE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
CONVICTED MURDERER, PRISON GUARD ARRESTED IN TEXAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MATT STEARNS and MIKE RICE  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The seven-week flight
of a convicted murderer and the prison guard who authorities say
helped him escape from Crossroads Correctional Center in Cameron
ended Saturday morning with their capture in a rural Texas trailer
park.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Terry Banks, 26, and Lynette Barnett, 27, of Hamilton were
arrested about 7:30 a.m. on the outskirts of Victoria, Texas, about
120 miles southwest of Houston.
</P>
<P>
   The two barricaded themselves in a recreational vehicle parked
next to a trailer for about 30 minutes before their arrests. Police
used a public address system to order them out of the RV.
</P>
<P>
   Banks' father, Charles Banks, was arrested at the scene. A woman
named Roberta Jones and a man named Paul Hoard also were arrested.
Their relationship to the fugitives was unclear Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   Terry Banks and Barnett will be arraigned Monday and face
extradition to Missouri. The two walked out of the correctional
center about 45 miles north of Kansas City on Oct. 29. Banks was
wearing a prison guard's uniform and carrying a fake ID that
authorities believe Barnett made for him.
</P>
<P>
   Banks was serving a life term for the 1992 murder of a man in
Rocky Comfort. Barnett, who was assigned to the food service area
where Banks worked, could face two to five years in prison if she
is convicted of helping him flee.
</P>
<P>
   It was unclear how long the two had been in Texas, or how long
they had planned to stay.
</P>
<P>
   ``There was some concern they were getting ready to load up the
RV and take off,'' said FBI agent Kurt Lipanovich.
</P>
<P>
   The arrest was the result of a tip last week from a viewer of
the television show ``America's Most Wanted,'' which featured a
segment on Banks and Barnett on Dec. 11.
</P>
<P>
   The tip was instantly credible to investigators because the
caller went beyond simply saying he recognized Terry Banks and
Barnett.
</P>
<P>
   ``The person knew that the older guy was using the name
Charlie,'' Lipanovich said. ``He knew something that wasn't on the
show.''
</P>
<P>
   Lipanovich would not say how the tipster came in contact with
the three.
</P>
<P>
   Agents from the FBI, the Texas Department of Public Safety, the
Victoria Police Department and the Victoria Sheriff's Office had
had several spots around Victoria under surveillance for the last
two days, Lipanovich said.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday morning, agents identified the pair in the trailer park
as Banks and Barnett and made the arrest.
</P>
<P>
   Barnett, a redhead, had dyed her hair black.
</P>
<P>
   The first break in the case for investigators came about two
weeks ago, when they found Barnett's pickup truck near Joplin, Mo.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Banks had sold it to a woman there for about $2,000,
Lipanovich said. He then apparently accompanied his son and Barnett
on a route that took them to Texas.
</P>
<P>
   The elder Banks has an extensive criminal record, and
authorities believe the trailer belonged to a friend of his,
Lipanovich said.
</P>
<P>
   Authorities believe that Barnett and Banks were having an affair
behind the bars of Crossroads, a 1,500-inmate maximum security
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Barnett's family insists that Banks coerced the guard's
assistance by threatening her family.
</P>
<P>
   Either way, the family is relieved to know Barnett is safe, said
Lorra Johnson, one of her sisters.
</P>
<P>
   ``The wait's over,'' Johnson said. ``Lynette's still got a lot
to go through, but she can get through it.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
