<P>
   POLITICAL-NOTES _ Mark Sherman's political notes. (Sherman,
Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   VPHISTORY _ WASHINGTON _ During a television interview this
fall, Democrat Bill Bradley was confronted with the weight of
history: no sitting vice president, his interviewer asserted, had
ever been defeated for his party's nomination. Not true, Bradley
responded. Vice President George Clinton lost to James Madison to
succeed President Jefferson _ in 1808. A far better historical
precedent, Bradley said, was the fact that George Bush was the
first vice president to win the presidency in 150 years. Bradley,
trying to wrest the nomination from Vice President Gore, was both
right and wrong. (Foskett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED
</P>
<P>
   NATIONAL
</P>
<P>
   CLINTON-LANDUSE _ GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ With one year left in
office, President Clinton is using the western landscape to carve
his place in history. Before leaving office Jan. 20, 2001, Clinton
has pledged to change the management of millions of acres of public
lands, largely in the West. If successful, the consequences would
range from increased environmental protections to more limits on
access and how the land can be used. (Cleary, Grand Junction Daily
Sentinel) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   LANDUSE-FAMILY _ PAONIA, Colo. _ Logger Ken Smith is living in
the shadow of a proposed federal rule that could mean the endcentury-long livelihood for his family. (Cleary, Grand Junction
Daily Sentinel) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   ARMY-SAFETY _ DAYTON, Ohio _ The U.S. Army's latest annual
aviation accident rate is the highest, excluding Desert Storm, in
17 years, and the Army's top safety official says mistakes are
being made at almost every level. (Carollo, Dayton Daily News)
MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   WOODWARD-OBIT _ ATLANTA _ C. Vann Woodward, 91, the greatest
living Southern historian, died Friday at his home in Hamden,
Conn., reportedly suffering complications from a recent heart
operation. (Bennett, Atlanta Journal-Constitution) MOVED.
</P>
<P>
   AIRPORT-USO _ ATLANTA _ Hartsfield International Airport can be
an overwhelming place every day of the year. This weekend it gets
another big test as thousands of military personnel pass through
its halls en route to holidays at home. The USO will be there to
help them with special lounges, entertainment and any other aid
they need. (Davis, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
<P>
   DOG-FIGHTING _ It's called a blood sport. But when police raided
a dogfight in southeast Georgia's Wayne County, what officers found
was more like a bloodletting. The raid highlighted the popularity
of dogfighting in rural Georgia, where it has been a macabre
tradition for generations. But dogfighting has become more than a
rural pastime. In Georgia and across the country, police say, it is
an increasingly common hobby in urban neighborhoods, especially
among members of street gangs. (Judd, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   Y2K-ALLYEAR _ Less than two weeks from the world's date with
computer destiny, it's hard to find anyone _ even among the
original prophets of Y2K doom _ who expects a midnight meltdown
when 1999 rolls over to 2000. But while New Year's weekend should
pass without cyber-cataclysm, experts say low-grade inconveniences
related to Y2K could persist for weeks or months. (Bennett, Palm
Beach Post)
</P>
<P>
   SAMS-SONG _ Sam Taylor is a 40-year-old autistic struggling to
be normal in a world that is just out of his grasp. We witness his
struggle _ his small victories as well as his failures _ as he
comes to accept his lot. From a musical family, music soothes his
tormented mind in a special way. He eventually gets a job at the
Atlanta Symphony sorting tickets and subscribers. (Dyer, Atlanta
Journal-Constitution). 100. WITH PHOTOS.
</P>
<P>
   NORLEANS-VENDORS _ NEW ORLEANS _ Neighborhood activists in the
French Quarter are fighting street musicians again _ and the new
wave of tarot card readers too. A look at the periodic battle
between the street vendors of music and fantasy who say they're
just offering a piece of heritage and those who say they just want
to live there in peace.(Konigsmark, Atlanta Journal-Constitution)
</P>
