<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2895 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-CLINTON-LANDUSE19-COX     12-18 1272
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-CLINTON-LANDUSE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Clinton making mark with land setaside goals in West
 &HT;    By C. Patrick Cleary
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   GRAND JUNCTION, Colo. _ With one year left in office, President
Clinton is using the Western landscape to carve his place in
history _ with some concerned it will happen at the expense of the
intermountain West's residents.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton, before leaving office Jan. 20, 2001, has pledged to
change the management of millions of acres of public lands, largely
in the West. If successful, the consequences would range from
increased environmental protections to more limits on access and
how the land can be used.
</P>
<P>
   No other president since Lyndon B. Johnson _ who expanded
national seashores, created national monuments and signed the
Wilderness Act of 1964 _ has shown as much interest in how public
lands in the West and the rest of the nation have been managed.
</P>
<P>
   So far, Clinton has:
</P>
<P>
   _ Signed a bill making the Black Canyon of the Gunnison near
Montrose, Colo., the nation's 55th national park. Great Sand Dunes
National Monument in southern Colorado could also soon be expanded
and elevated to national park status.
</P>
<P>
   _ Used the Antiquities Act of 1906 to declare 1.7 million acres
of southern Utah as the Grand Staircase-Escalante National
Monument.
</P>
<P>
   The monument was created in the back rooms of the White House,
without any public input, and declared less than a year before the
1996 elections.
</P>
<P>
   Clinton could use the same law, again without congressional and
other public input, to expand the Colorado National Monument in
Mesa County, Colo. Also in the works are potentially new or
expanded monuments near Cortez, Colo., and in Arizona, California,
Montana and Oregon.
</P>
<P>
   _ Proposed a ban on construction of new roads in 40 million to
60 million acres of national forests now considered as roadless,
including 3 million acres in Colorado. If enacted, the policy could
force restrictions on snowmobiles, mountain bikes and other uses of
the forests.
</P>
<P>
   _ Pushed for the U.S. Forest Service to consider how uses of the
national forests affect the ecological welfare of the landscape.
This focus already has surfaced in the proposed White River
National Forest management plan and is expected to shape the
upcoming plans for the Grand Mesa, Uncompahgre and Gunnison
national forests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Like Theodore Roosevelt, I believe there are certain places
humankind simply cannot improve upon, places whose beauty and
interest no photograph could capture, places you simply have to see
for yourself,'' Clinton said last week in announcing that he was
considering naming new national monuments. ``We must use this time
of unparalleled prosperity to ensure people will always be able to
see these places as we see them today.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton has called this the ``legacy'' he wants his presidency
to be remembered for.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think the legacy we have in mind is a legacy for future
generations,'' said Eliott Diringer, spokesman for White House
Council on Environmental Quality. ``The president and
administration have, over the last several years, taken many
actions to protect the unique and fragile lands across the country,
from the Everglades to the California redwoods. The interest is
driven primarily by the desire to ensure future generations of
Americans can enjoy these lands.''
</P>
<P>
   U.S. Rep. Scott McInnis, R-Colo., said it's easy for him to
decipher why Clinton is using the West to help set his place in
history.
</P>
<P>
   ``The warmest, fuzziest feeling you have is family,'' McInnis
said. ``Figuring he can't build his legacy on that, the next one
down the list is parks and wilderness. He wants to do it like Teddy
Roosevelt.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton keeps making connections with Roosevelt, who set up the
national park system and protected millions of acres of Western
land.
</P>
<P>
   The announcement about potential new monuments was made in the
Roosevelt Room of the White House, and in October Clinton referred
to Roosevelt when he launched his effort to limit road construction
in national forests.
</P>
<P>
   ``He wants his legacy to be of (President William Howard) Taft
and Roosevelt,'' said Stan Broome, president of Club 20, a western
Colorado lobbying and promotional group. ``The big setasides those
guys were involved in were more far-reaching. They weren't setting
aside public lands to lock up. They were doing so for the general
use of public lands and multiple use.
</P>
<P>
   ``If that is the legacy Clinton wants, he is headed in the wrong
direction. He should take existing public agencies and enhance them
to get things done,'' Broome said.
</P>
<P>
   Broome and other detractors say Clinton is threatening the
economic livelihood of those who rely on access to public lands,
whether it is for logging, recreation or other uses.
</P>
<P>
   Environmentalists, though, say Clinton is responding to a
dwindling sanctuary of space for wildlife, humans and the natural
environment.
</P>
<P>
   ``What the nation wants is more land protection,'' said Ed
Marston, publisher of the Paonia-based High Country News, a
30-year-old environmental watchdog newspaper. ``We in the West have
to figure out how to accommodate that and not fight it.''
</P>
<P>
   Other Westerners believe the land and people in the six or seven
largely rural mountain states are being used unjustly by Clinton to
secure his place in history.
</P>
<P>
   ``They can try to sell out the entire West to save the Democrats
but that won't happen,'' said John Martin of Grand Junction, a
proponent of off-highway vehicle use on public lands. ``If you
combine the roadless issue with the new planning regulations with
the new planning on the White River and (Grand Mesa National Forest
group), and what they want to do in Utah with wilderness, what you
have is a sellout of the West.
</P>
<P>
   ``If you throw California east of the Mississippi, 80 percent of
the population would be living east of the Mississippi,'' Martin
said. ``We're becoming insignificant by population and we are a
target.''
</P>
<P>
   Many western environmentalists, though, say people intertwined
with the land for so many decades are unable to step back and see
the bigger issue.
</P>
<P>
   Jo Ann Moon of Grand Junction went to meetings about the
roadless proposal with a warning.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hear a lot of Disneyites who only think about themselves,''
Moon said during a hearing on the roadless initiative. ``The Forest
Service can't even take care of the roads it has now.
</P>
<P>
   ``Should we construct roads into pristine areas when we can't
afford to maintain what we have?'' she asked.
</P>
<P>
   Marston said the West has two choices.
</P>
<P>
   ``It can continue to proclaim its sovereignty, and carry on with
a doomed rearguard action,'' he wrote. ``Or it can strengthen its
sovereignty by figuring out how to adhere to the national desire to
protect the land while implementing that protection in a distinctly
western way.''
</P>
<P>
   Bill Cleary, a longtime congressional aide from western
Colorado, recalled when President Johnson enacted many of the
initiatives that were first proposed by Congress. Johnson, too, was
pushed by his Interior secretary, Stewart Udall, to use executive
powers, but not to the extent Clinton appears to be moving.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a joint effort between the executive and legislative
branches, I suppose,'' Cleary said. ``Compared to when I was back
there, I'm uneasy (Clinton) is doing it by executive order as
opposed to letting Congress work its will.''
</P>
<P>
   C. Patrick Cleary writes for The Daily Sentinel of Grand
Junction, Colo. He can be reached via e-mail at
cpcleary(at)gjds.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
