<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 18:40 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2896 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-LANDUSE-FAMILY19-COX     12-18 0858
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-LANDUSE-FAMILY19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Proposed land setaside threatens logging family's 116-year way
of life
 &HT;    By C. Patrick Cleary
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   PAONIA, Colo. _ Logger Ken Smith is living in the shadow of a
proposed federal rule that could mean the end of a century-long
livelihood for his family.
</P>
<P>
   The ridgeline immediately north of his Paonia sawmill/home,
Smith Forest Products, is the beginning of a roadless area on the
Grand Mesa National Forest that stretches north to Interstate 70.
The area is among the 40 million to 60 million acres of forests
nationwide the Clinton administration wants kept off limits to road
building and associated timber cutting.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm scared,'' the burly 40-year-old father of two young boys
said. ``We're four months away from having to move away to find
work. For a family that has been here 116 years, that's tough.''
</P>
<P>
   The threatened closure of potential logging territory might be
the last straw for a family and business that have seen increased
regulation and increased environmental pressure tear apart the
fabric many communities in the West are built upon.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration plan to limit road-building in
national forests is the latest in a long line of federal
regulations that Smith said might result in the Forest Service
having no timber for sale. That, he said, would drive him out of
business.
</P>
<P>
   Back in 1863 the Smith family migrated from Illinois to the
Uncompahgre Plateau. His family helped found Somerset before
eventually settling in Delta in 1883.
</P>
<P>
   Smith's grandfather, Carl Smith, was the first child born in
incorporated Delta. The family was involved in law enforcement,
worked as mining engineers and helped start Holly Sugar and Delta
Brick and Tile, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``They came west to stay out of the Civil War,'' Smith said.
``They didn't want to lose their boys to the Civil War. They were
industrialists who built anything and everything back east. These
people were looking for new challenges.''
</P>
<P>
   Smith's photo albums are filled with faded photographs of
long-dead relatives sitting atop piles of sawdust and straddling
trees.
</P>
<P>
   Those men cut trees in areas of the western Colorado landscape
that today don't look as if they have been touched, he said,
matching before and after photos.
</P>
<P>
   That work sustained families intertwined with the communities
that sprung up around them.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he hopes he carries on his family's long tradition of
community service. He is a volunteer fireman, works at the schools,
teaches first aid at the mines and has donated goods and services
to make his community a better place. He teaches classes at the
vocational college and works for an ambulance company in Grand
Junction to make ends meet. His family donated the famous Christmas
Tree of the Stinking Desert and thousands of others used by the
town of Paonia.
</P>
<P>
   ``If the school needs something ... we buy it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   This philosophy has been handed down from generation to
generation.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he doesn't think the newcomers who oppose the
multiple use concept of public lands get involved in communities to
the extent as those who have spent a lifetime working with the
land.
</P>
<P>
   Smith, for example, currently has one salvage job that could
provide work for him to support his family through the winter.
</P>
<P>
   The job, though, is providing work for seven families. He said
he could lay off those seven employees to guarantee work and income
for himself through the winter. That, though, would put seven men
out of work, seven families without an income. He said he won't do
it.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he is watching the multiple-use view of the West
change. The shadow of the ridge and its implications behind his
house looms, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Clinton administration's designs on the West are
jeopardizing more than an ability to go cut trees, said Smith, who
followed his family's footsteps and bought his first sawmill in
1978. It is jeopardizing the only way of life he has known.
</P>
<P>
   ``I grew up with waste not, want not, with the environment,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   His home is built with logs he cut himself. He didn't use whole
logs, though. He split them in half to save wood. He rails against
the mansion builders of the resorts who build the biggest log homes
only to stay in them a few weeks a year.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he knows there is no God-given right a person has to
operate a business.
</P>
<P>
   ``But if you have an individual dedicated to work, has a
terrific work ethic who is willing to donate back to the community,
and he has a reasonable business sense, he should have the
opportunity to work,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   Smith said he has worked long hours seasonally while fighting to
defend a business that he said has helped sustain the health of the
forests, the private ground and the communities that land supports.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've never taken welfare,'' he said. ``I've got two kids to
put through school.''
</P>
<P>
   C. Patrick Cleary writes for The Daily Sentinel of Grand
Junction, Colo. He can be reached via e-mail at
cpcleary(at)gjds.com.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
