<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 18:43 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2904 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-1980s-ESSAY-2ndTAKE-K     12-18 0928
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1980s-ESSAY-2ndTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DECADE OF THE '80S WAS DOMINATED BY THE ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Long-distance calls
got cheaper, but AT&AMP;T never succeeded in personal computers.
Companies like Apple, Microsoft and Intel sprang from nothing to
dominate the industry that would become essential to world
business.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Following the law of unintended consequences, the AT&AMP;T breakup
hastened the arrival of one of the phenomena of our lifetimes, the
Internet. Long-distance upstarts Sprint and MCI laid fiberoptic
cable to compete with AT&AMP;T.
</P>
<P>
   ``We got a fiber network a lot more quickly than we would have
under AT&AMP;T, and fiber is the backbone of the Internet,'' said Litan
of the Brookings Institution.
</P>
<P>
   The free-market lessons of that deregulation played out in grand
scale in Kansas City. AT&AMP;T cut jobs here. Sprint, essentially
created in 1984, in 15 years became this city's largest
private-sector employer. Now it is the target of acquisition by MCI
in what would be history's largest merger, a $115 billion deal.
</P>
<P>
   In the 1980s, American business again got serious about ``the
bottom line.'' Some businesses that didn't faced corporate raiders
like Carl Icahn and T. Boone Pickens, who threatened to take over
companies and throw out chief executive officers.
</P>
<P>
   Reorganization, global marketplace and shareholder value became
buzzwords, signals to many workers that layoffs were on the way.
Fewer workers created production gains for companies and financial
gains for Wall Street.
</P>
<P>
   For cities, ``jobs became currency,'' and companies used them to
hustle tax breaks from desperate communities. Now jobs go to the
city giving away the most. Sometimes the Kansas City area wins _
Harley-Davidson _ and sometimes it loses _ the headquarters of TWA.
</P>
<P>
   Amid the job cuts of the 1980s, two seemingly unrelated trends
came together to feed the economic wonder that America has become,
said economist David M. Jones. Many dismissed workers decided to
become entrepreneurs. The start-ups that survived found the United
States had created a ``culture of equity'' to finance their
expansion.
</P>
<P>
   Drawn into the stock market by better returns, the tax
advantages of retirement plans and the seeming simplicity of mutual
funds, we have become voracious investors. In 1980 we had $134.7
billion invested in all mutual funds. By 1990 it topped $1
trillion, and by last year it was $5.5 trillion.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 50 percent of Americans own stocks. The Dow Jones
industrial average, which measures the growth in the value of
stocks, has moved from 777 in August 1982 to more than 11,000. In
the same time the number of American jobs has grown to 133 million
from about 100 million. Inflation last year dropped to a whimpering
1.6 percent.
</P>
<P>
   By the end of the 1980s we were a little confused about where
this free-market ride was taking us. We wondered why our companies
could sublimate employee loyalty to profits for shareholders. We
called it the decade of greed, although by almost any measure the
decade of the 1990s has been more about making money than the
decade of the '80s was.
</P>
<P>
   Imperceptibly our attitudes shifted with the transformation of
the economy. Instead of complaining about slow-rising salaries, we
brag about our growing stock portfolios. We began haranguing CEOs
about quarterly earnings.
</P>
<P>
   We were asked to take ownership, and we did. How about
happiness?
</P>
<P>
   Some economic theorists believe that we are in a ``long boom''
that will continue 20 more years and that nearly every
socio-economic substratum is benefiting.
</P>
<P>
   According to a recent study, black men 16 to 24 with a high
school diploma or less, many with prison records, are working in
greater numbers, earning more and committing fewer crimes than in
the early 1990s.
</P>
<P>
   So is the legacy of the 1980s that we are making more money and
that is making us happier?
</P>
<P>
   Even as our personal wealth has grown, some observers see our
personal satisfaction deflating. With more choices has come far
greater responsibilities.
</P>
<P>
   A survey by The Kansas City Star found that 40 percent of Kansas
Citians worried that we would see a stock-market crash like the one
in 1929 preceding the Great Depression, although only 6 percent
were greatly worried.
</P>
<P>
   From 1980 until very recently, the chasm between those with the
most of everything and those with the least had grown wider and
deeper. That fact, according to the survey, is what the largest
percentage of Kansas Citians _ 35 percent _ see as the biggest
economic problem facing America as it enters the next century.
</P>
<P>
   The Internet offers easy access to an inconceivable amount of
information but makes it as easy for our children to discover
pornography as they can geography. And what about our privacy?
</P>
<P>
   The survey found that half of Kansas Citians believed the
advantages of the Internet outweighed the dangers it posed to
privacy; 29 percent thought issues of privacy outweighed the
advantages of the Internet.
</P>
<P>
   We live with a nagging uncertainty about our jobs. Global
markets and expanding businesses have brought coveted jobs to
cities, but we have no guarantee that our best corporate citizens
won't become branch offices or be swept away by mergers, like
Hoechst Marion Roussel and Sprint.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we are coming to the realization, as we come into this
sudden wealth, that there is not as much bang as we imagined,''
said McKenzie, the author. ``It doesn't bring the happiness you
imagined decades earlier.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
