</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-ADKINS-3TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVENTING A WORLD: HOW LIFE AND ART COLLIDED IN WILLIAM W. ADKINS'
DOMAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE PAUL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _In the last months of
his invented world, William W. Adkins spent many mornings at the
Plaza Library. He sat at a favorite oak table, a sheet of thick
paper rolled out in front of him and light pouring through the
reading room's tall north windows.
<TEXT>
<P>
   No one bothered him. He kept to himself. And to his paper. He
listened to the quiet. And, with his black Bic pen, he drew what he
was seeing in his mind's eye.
</P>
<P>
   He sat and drew for hours. Mostly, he made up mechanical devices
that he thought would be useful or that he might later turn into
wooden models. He labeled their parts and gave them names, so the
patent office could follow what he was doing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Earth-Quake Empty Can,'' for instance. Adkins had in mind
something that could control earthquake damage. Or ``Banana
Split-Eating Shave.'' That improbable combination of cutting device
and container would take longer toexplain.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins not only invented a world on paper. He invented a life
for himself, too.
</P>
<P>
   In his invented world, home was anywhere he landed. For as many
as 20 years, he essentially lived outdoors. And in the last of his
homeless years, he lived like an animal in the back end of a vacant
lot in Westport.
</P>
<P>
   That Adkins created anything at all is extraordinary enough,
given that his impulse to invent might have come from mental
disorders.
</P>
<P>
   That his works ended up in museums, books and on the walls of a
New York art gallery is nothing short of remarkable.
</P>
<P>
   The story of William W. Adkins has too many complications and
too many ironies to be wrapped up neatly. Or happily.
</P>
<P>
   It might have been about how art can change a life. As things
turned out, it's more about how life can get in the way of art.
Piecing it together
</P>
<P>
   ``It's just one of those things,'' Bill Adkins says more than
once, explaining how life happens. It's the closest thing to
self-awareness one can extract from him.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins is 67. He doesn't go to the library to make drawings
anymore. Most of the time he lies on his bed in the Kansas City
nursing home where he now lives. A television chatters in the
background. Groans and loud voices sputter through the hallways.
</P>
<P>
   If visitors arrive, he'll get up and walk slowly to greet them,
a rubber-tipped cane in his right hand.
</P>
<P>
   He wears cranberry sweatpants, a green sweatshirt and a ball cap
that's a little too big for his bald head. The teeth he has left
are chipped and yellowed beneath his bulbous nose. The skin of his
face is pasty white, gray at times, but mostly free of the stubble
and grime that used to greet the world.
</P>
<P>
   Every now and then he'll be reminded of something pleasant, and
his ice-blue eyes will light up, and his hands will gesture. And
then, like a balloon losing air, his voice will go flat again, and
his hands will drop to his lap and just shake a little.
</P>
<P>
   He doesn't recall exactly when he began to draw or why. ``I just
did, is all,'' he says in his slightly pinched country tenor.
</P>
<P>
   Or how he came to be living in this nursing home: ``It's just
one of those things.''
</P>
<P>
   What Adkins does remember he somehow transforms into black-ink
inventions on white poster board.
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Doan first saw one of his drawings nearly five years
ago, and she has been studying them ever since. When she visits
Adkins today, it's not only as a friend, but also as the unofficial
curator, promoter and preserver of his body of work.
</P>
<P>
   As long as she's known him, though, it has been difficult to
piece together what's true about him and what's not.
</P>
<P>
   He was born in Kansas City, Kan., on Aug. 8, 1932. He was
married and maybe divorced. He had 10 children, all of whom ended
up in foster families. He was not the world's best father or
husband. ``I like to amble and gamble, and women don't like that,''
he told Doan once.
</P>
<P>
   For a while he lived with his father in an apartment at 43rd and
Bell streets. When his father died, in the early 1970s, Adkins
apparently wandered 10 blocks east into Westport _ wandered, that
is, into the oblivion of his new, invented world.
</P>
<P>
   He just showed up one day, his Clark Avenue neighbors say. But
he appeared regularly and was willing to work.
</P>
<P>
   He patched together a concrete-and-rock wall around one couple's
house. He swept the walkways of a nearby apartment building. He
mowed lawns.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins bought food with the money he made, and some neighbors
fed him regularly. Judith Brougham set out breakfast for him as
often as three times a week. He frequently gave her drawings in
return. He gave lots of people his drawings.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins wore layers of smelly clothes and layers of hats. Sailor
Bill, they called him at the Plaza Library, because of the
captain's hat that sat atop his wool watchcap. Others knew him as
Westport Bill or Wild Bill _ not names, but labels for an odd
character.
</P>
<P>
   At some point in the 1980s a retired teacher who lived at 4143
Clark let Adkins take up residence on her back porch. When she
died, he stayed, living on the porch or even in the crawlspace
beneath it.
</P>
<P>
   The Rev. Roger Coleman, executive director of the nearby
Westport Allen Center, bought the teacher's small house in late
1990 but soon discovered he couldn't afford to bring it up to code.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman pleaded with Adkins to leave. Finally, almost a year
later, Adkins disappeared, and Coleman had the house demolished.
</P>
<P>
   By the next spring, however, in early 1992, Adkins returned to
the lot and staked a claim. He put up some boards and tin and
plastic and fashioned himself a lean-to against a telephone pole
and a clump of trees.
</P>
<P>
   Coleman could imagine Adkins to be some kind of monk ``living
under a tree,'' he says, ``taking care of himself and not bothering
anybody.''
</P>
<P>
   And Coleman saw in him a kind of grace, as if some parable were
being played out in his back yard and his own salvation depended on
how he treated this peasant who just might be God.
</P>
<P>
   When summer turned to winter and the temperature dropped to
bitter cold, Coleman told Adkins he could stay warm in the Allen
Center's boiler room. Adkins declined. He just burrowed into his
hole. His golden age
</P>
<P>
   Adkins invented on paper for many years, maybe going back to the
construction and concrete work he had done in the 1950s. But what
might be called his golden age of creativity unfolded in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   We know this, because Margaret Doan began making a record of his
works.
</P>
<P>
   Doan is an independent art historian. As a volunteer travel
coordinator at the Nelson-Atkins Museum of Art, she arranges and
leads tours for museum members to art capitals around the world.
</P>
<P>
   In early February 1995, Judith Brougham, a painter herself,
introduced Doan to the man who made these unusual drawings.
Brougham had hoped to get her homeless neighbor some recognition.
</P>
<P>
   Doan, trim and blonde, with a deliberate Kansas voice, looked
beyond the two hats he wore, the dirty boots and fingerless gloves,
and saw in him a ``polite, kind of funny'' man.
</P>
<P>
   He had a rolled-up batch of drawings under his arm, and one by
one he showed them to her. Although she found his descriptions a
little hard to follow, Doan knew instantly that she had discovered
someone special.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
