u s BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-N     12-18 1291
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NOTEBOOK-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EMPTY SEATS GIVE N.B.A. SOME CAUSE FOR CONCERN 
CARLESIMO HANGS ON
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   In the foreground of a recent television highlight, Bob Sura of
the Cleveland Cavaliers goes in for a two-hand reverse dunk against
the Boston Celtics. In the background, a smattering of fans stand
and applaud _ amid several hundred vacant seats at Gund Arena.
</P>
<P>
   The reels spin nightly, churning out the best and the worst of
the NBA: unreal athletic feats matched by declining attendance in
many cities. On the whole, the league is averaging 300 fewer paid
fans a game than it was nearly two months into last season. Through
307 games played last week, about 47,000 fewer total tickets were
sold in comparison with that period in the 1998-99 season.
</P>
<P>
   Although the numbers represent only a slight decline, the visual
evidence is striking. From Continental Arena in the Meadowlands to
New Arena in Oakland, vast empty spaces can be seen throughout the
NBA In its first 82-game season after Michael Jordan retired and a
contentious labor dispute dribbled into an abbreviated 50-game
season, the league is gradually being hit with an attention deficit
from its fan base.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're pricing people out of these arenas, that's what
happening,'' said Keith Glass, an agent for several players. ``Who
is compelling out there right now? With tickets and everything
included, I'll bet it costs $200 for a family of four to see a
Net-Clipper game. Exactly who's going to that game?''
</P>
<P>
   Commissioner David Stern said last week that attendance figures
``need improvement'' while adding that overall paid attendance is
down only about 1 percent from a year ago. ``They always have and
they continue to need improvement,'' Stern said. ``It's hard work,
given the entertainment options that people have, given all the
things they can do.''
</P>
<P>
   Washington, Orlando, New Jersey, Vancouver and Seattle are
averaging 2,000 to 3,000 fewer fans for each game than they did
last season. The league does not release figures on people who have
purchased tickets to games but do not show up. But scanning many
NBA arenas the first six weeks of the season makes it easy to see
that the announced attendance figures often inflate the actual
number of fans in the building by several thousand.
</P>
<P>
   Some blame lack of star power. With Jordan gone, Charles Barkley
recently retiring because of injury and several other veteran stars
either injured or past their prime, the league has had to rely on a
few entertainers to bring people into their buildings. Vince
Carter, Allen Iverson, Kevin Garnett and Tim Duncan are not only
responsible for lifting their franchises, but also keeping
attendance figures steady.
</P>
<P>
   ``It takes a while because you have to establish yourself as a
winner,'' Stern said. ``Michael, Magic, Larry, Isiah _ they not
only played for, they made their teams into winners. That's what
our fans are waiting to see. Which players, despite their great
talent, are going to make their teams winners? Sports is
unforgiving in terms of the judgments that they make. We make them
in terms of wins and losses.''
</P>
<P>
   What must be particularly distressing for the league is
attendance at its new arenas. At the four facilities that have
opened so far this season _ Philips Arena in Atlanta, Pepsi Center
in Denver, Staples Center in Los Angeles and Conseco Fieldhouse in
Indianapolis _ the home teams' attendance figures are up from last
year's, but only the new home of the Pacers has sold out nightly.
The Nuggets' attendance is up nearly 25 percent, but their average
announced crowd is still 4,455 short of capacity.
</P>
<P>
   Although the Pacers, the Knicks and the Sacramento Kings are the
only franchises to sell out every home game thus far, there are
other success stories. Portland has sold out all but one of its
games and is often over capacity. And the United Center, despite
the loss of Jordan, Scottie Pippen and most other vestiges of
Chicago's championship team, has managed to average more than
22,000 tickets sold per game.
</P>
<P>
   But there are just as many puzzling figures, like those at Key
Arena in Seattle. Despite the team's resurgence this season, the
SuperSonics are averaging fewer than 15,000 fans in a
17,000-capacity arena.
</P>
<P>
   Nowhere was the no-show problem more obvious than Thursday
night's game in Dallas between the Knicks and the Mavericks.
</P>
<P>
   The crowd for New York's only visit of the year was announced at
13,000, but fewer than 10,000 people were at Reunion Arena to
witness the game. At times, Gus Johnson, the Knicks' radio
announcer, could be heard as clearly as if he were doing play by
play for the entire arena.
</P>
<P>
   Several agents, including Glass, partly blame new provisions in
the collective bargaining agreement. In addition to establishing
maximum salary limits, both the league and the players union agreed
to more stringent rules regarding player movement.
</P>
<P>
   ``The inflexibility of the cba (collective bargaining agreement)
is going to kill the league,'' Glass said. ``The Nets, for
instance, have got a $52 million payroll. It's almost impossible
for them to move many of those players, given the new rules. They
can't tell their fans we're changing things. So what are they going
to do? They're stuck with that team. Fans are savvy enough to
realize it's not going to get any better with some of these
teams.''
</P>
<P>
   Glass, who represents mostly journeymen and role players, added:
``And then you have some of these GMs automatically giving out the
maximum, as if that's negotiating. It looks kind of stupid for an
agent to say that, but it's just crazy. Why do they automatically
get the maximum? Can't you say to a guy, just once: `I think you're
a really terrific player. I know I'm allowed to give you $9 million
a year, but I'm only giving you $7.2 million. And I'm sorry.' Are
you kidding me? That's where we're at. Instead, the Boston Celtics
won't be able to give Adrian Griffin an extra $25,000 because they
gave Antoine Walker every penny they have.''
</P>
<P>
   In terms of fan interest, the NBA may still be in the midst of a
lockout hangover, less than a year after it nearly lost the season
to labor strife.
</P>
<P>
   Leigh Steinberg, the agent for some of the NFL's premier
quarterbacks, said several months ago:``The NBA's battle should not
have been labor versus management. The competition should have been
for the alternate, discretionary leisure dollar out there. They
should have been battling the NFL and Walt Disney World for the
larger share of the pie. HBO. Video games. `The Water Boy.' That's
the competition. That's where the NBA hurt itself with its internal
fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Even Stern, who always seems to point to the positive, seemed to
indicate last week that the league had rested somewhat on its
laurels, that creating pop-culture superstars 10 years ago did not
translate into marketing success for the next 10 years.
</P>
<P>
   ``We used to be the hungriest,'' he said. ``And although we
continue to preach hunger, some of our teams have gotten a little
bit complacent as the market changes. We're committed to being
current.''
</P>
<P>
   In defense of profit margins and interest, Stern also mentioned
that WNBA viewership is growing, that the league's Internet site,
NBA.com, is flourishing, and that the start of a 24-hour network,
NBA.com TV, has also helped.
</P>
<P>
   ``NBA television is up to 206 countries,'' Stern added. ``Every
indication of widespread consumer acceptance is very high. But we
have to make sure it's accompanied by strong attendance. That's
very important.''
</P>
<P>
   Until those pockets of uninhabited seats are filled and
attendance steadily rises, his league is still on the comeback
trail.
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Carlesimo Hangs On
</P>
<P>
   Danny Ainge's stepping down as coach of Phoenix to spend more
time with his family was a bit of a shock. And Brian Hill's being
relieved of his duties in Vancouver, where he coached an inferior
roster, was a mild surprise. But no development in the coaching
fraternity last week was more stunning than P.J. Carlesimo's
keeping his job.
</P>
<P>
   How Carlesimo, the forever-besieged Warriors coach, managed to
avoid being first to the guillotine is a testament to the fine line
in sports and perhaps to his own resilience.
</P>
<P>
   On Dec. 11 in Minnesota, Golden State was falling apart against
the Timberwolves in the first half, losing by 43-23 at one
juncture. The Warriors were about to suffer a bad loss, return home
with a 1-3 record on their road trip and fall to 2-14 overall.
</P>
<P>
   According to a Western Conference official who requested
anonymity, General Manager Garry St. Jean had arranged to speak
with Carlesimo last Sunday, relieve him of his duties and take over
the coaching duties on Monday. Like Rick Pitino, Don Nelson and Pat
Riley, St. Jean would have overseen the organization on the floor
and off it.
</P>
<P>
   Everything but the details of the news conference had been
worked out when Carlesimo's team suddenly found heart. John Starks
scored 27 points as Golden State outscored Minnesota by 81-36 the
rest of the way. The Warriors then parlayed a respectable 2-2 trip
into a thrilling victory over Miami at home on Tuesday for their
third straight victory.
</P>
<P>
   Through all the commotion surrounding his job, Carlesimo has
been oblivious to anything other than getting his team prepared.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how he deals with it,'' said one Warrior player
who requested anonymity. ``I couldn't sleep if I knew my job was on
the line every night. But he acts like it's just another day. P.J.
can grate on you, but he's a warrior. He just keeps going, no
matter what's going on around him.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 1845EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
