<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 18:45 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2912 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-ART-ADKINS-2ndTAKE-KA     12-18 1244
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-ADKINS-2ndTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVENTING A WORLD: HOW LIFE AND ART COLLIDED IN WILLIAM W. ADKINS'
DOMAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE PAUL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ Every week or every
few days she'd drop by the lot where Adkins camped. She put on her
grubby clothes and drove down from her Briarcliff home to see what
new things came out of his head. She took him paper and pens and
Diet Cokes. Even a banana split for his birthday.
<TEXT>
<P>
   Doan sat with Adkins amid the weeds and his accumulated junk _
the dirty, old gun case he had salvaged from the trash, the odd
assemblages he had made of wood, rope and wire. Adkins explained as
best as he could each topological marvel that he put in front of
her, things such as the ``Sponge Show Honk Corn Gamble'' and the
``Giddly Gatt Cross Fill.''
</P>
<P>
   Many of Adkins' visions had to do with making work easier. He
thought up tools to pick fruit and to mend fences and to sort
through trash. He made up sports and games.
</P>
<P>
   Often he turned the back side of the paper into what to him was
an official patent document.
</P>
<P>
   The everyday utility hinted at by Adkins' descriptions seemed
familiar only on the surface. Once you looked closely, the
inventions were skewed enough to be unrecognizable and, to most
people, nonsensical.
</P>
<P>
   But one person's indecipherable nonsense is another person's
art.
</P>
<P>
   Doan recognized Adkins' inventions as works of art. They had
loopy lines and vibrant, pulsating spaces. Adkins managed to
balance shadow and light to evoke a weird, three-dimensional
quality.
</P>
<P>
   The drawings also reflected an often humorous and quite
unconventional worldview. He was poking fun at the world. He was an
original. Doan realized an uncommon wit lived beneath the stink,
and she saw a kind of poetry in his unique language.
</P>
<P>
   Did he know what he was doing? Was he striving for attention?
Was his warped vision a kind of alternative-universe intelligence?
</P>
<P>
   Doan didn't know for sure, but she knew that Adkins was smarter
than he seemed: ``The real game that Bill is running is for people
like you and me to spend all this time studying it out,'' Doan
says.
</P>
<P>
   Scholars for years have asserted the validity of art that comes
from outside mainstream traditions. And in recent years the field
of ``outsider'' or ``visionary'' art, much of it created in
obscurity and isolation, has taken on a kind of go-go momentum.
</P>
<P>
   The outsider art market has a buy-low, sell-high reputation, but
Doan's interest wasn't in the money. It was in the rare opportunity
to be there at the creation of a bona fide outsider-art talent.
</P>
<P>
   Doan struck up a deal with Adkins. She gave him money _ $5 or
$10 or $20 at a time _ and Adkins gave her his drawings. He didn't
really care what she did with them. To this day he doesn't remember
a single one.
</P>
<P>
   In her mind Doan was becoming the caretaker of an incredibly
rich body of work. Someday, maybe in 20 years, her careful effort
would pay off and the art of William W. Adkins would be famous. Or,
in the unpredictable crapshoot of the art world, maybe not.
Repository of genius
</P>
<P>
   By midsummer 1995, about five months after she and Adkins had
met, Doan had amassed dozens of his works. When she stopped by for
a visit on July 4, he had three more finished patents for her. He
had finally caught on that she'd soon be showing his work to art
enthusiasts. He had one that he thought they'd especially like.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tough Bakeialled Mask,'' he called it. He was inspired by a
Mad magazine cover that showed a screaming man and the headline,
``College Roommates from Hell.'' The face on his drawing was
``baked'' in hell, he suggested.
</P>
<P>
   The piece showed Doan something she hadn't yet seen in the work,
a sense of humanity, even pain: ``Emotion, energy, expression,''
she wrote in her notes. It was an epiphany for her, an entry into
Adkins' own, private, mad world.
</P>
<P>
   Doan empathized with Adkins' compulsive behavior. She thought
she was rather obsessive-compulsive herself. A lawyer who didn't
practice. A folk-art collector. A traveler. A mother of grown
children. She'd been passionate about art ever since her first trip
to Paris in 1963.
</P>
<P>
   She threw herself completely into everything she did _ the field
notes she made every time she visited Adkins, the catalog she was
compiling of every single one of his works. If she didn't do it,
who would? What she learned growing up in Hays, Kan., was, ``If
you're capable of handling something and it comes your way, then
you're supposed to step up to the task.''
</P>
<P>
   Doan started thinking about the nature of creativity and saw
Adkins as a repository of a kind of genius. ``No one else in the
world,'' Doan says, ``thinks like Bill does.''
</P>
<P>
   That August, Doan tested the waters for Adkins' art by renting a
booth at a weekend folk-art fair in Atlanta, a show devoted to the
work of living outsiders.
</P>
<P>
   Some passers-by admired the work: ``Looks just like Leonardo,''
someone said, evoking the Renaissance inventor and artist. And a
handful of the pieces sold.
</P>
<P>
   Although Doan didn't come close to covering what it cost her to
be there, the numbers didn't really matter, because the most
important dealings were happening behind the scenes. For better and
for worse. Invented world upended
</P>
<P>
   Roger Coleman found himself in a philosophical quandary. He knew
there was a growing frustration in the neighborhood over Adkins'
trashy encampment on the vacant lot, and he was being pressured by
his board to do something about the squatter. He also knew he had
to balance his desire to let Adkins be with his concern over the
man's welfare.
</P>
<P>
   He checked around to see what kind of help there'd be for
Westport Bill.
</P>
<P>
   When Doan returned to Kansas City from Atlanta, she learned that
social workers had been visiting Adkins. And when, in
mid-September, she returned from another trip, she found that
Adkins' invented world on the lot had been upended.
</P>
<P>
   Arrangements were being made to move him elsewhere, and
something had dulled both his vigorous behavior and his art-making
ability. She was pretty sure Adkins had been given some kind of
medication, a fact she soon confirmed.
</P>
<P>
   As it turned out, Adkins had agreed to become a client of what
was then known as Network Rehabilitative Services, a private,
nonprofit agency that since has been merged into Truman Medical
Center. It operated a program to identify mentally ill homeless
people, to help them get housing and, after a psychiatric
evaluation, whatever care and services they needed.
</P>
<P>
   Psychiatric drugs are a common and often effective tool in such
circumstances. They mitigate psychotic or delusional episodes. They
help give people the possibility of living more normal lives.
</P>
<P>
   Like many drugs of all kinds, psychiatric medications have
various side effects, too, not the least of which is the damper
they can put on the brain's creative functions.
</P>
<P>
   A caseworker helped Adkins find an apartment. Doan took him a
table at which he could sit and draw. He learned to make microwave
burritos for dinner and practiced taking the bus to counseling
sessions downtown. He seemed to understand the transformation he
was making. ``It was crazy living out there,'' he told an outreach
worker.
</P>
<P>
   But he wasn't entirely successful learning to live as most
people do. After a few months, he was transferred to a group home,
which offered more supervision and a better chance to keep him
clean.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
