<HEADER>
A2913 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-ART-ADKINS-3rdTAKE-KA     12-18 0984
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-ART-ADKINS-3rdTAKE-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INVENTING A WORLD: HOW LIFE AND ART COLLIDED IN WILLIAM W. ADKINS'
DOMAIN 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By STEVE PAUL  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _After moving indoors
Adkins' art-making dropped off, if not in quantity then noticeably
in quality. Doan blamed the drugs but knew there was more to it
than that.
<TEXT>
<P>
   ``All artists want to communicate, and he had a desire to
communicate, too,'' Doan says. ``Once his living situation was
changed, his needs to communicate were different. The obsessive
nature of it wasn't the same.''
</P>
<P>
   For their part, the social workers' mission remained clear:
Adkins was far better off being off the streets and getting
treatment; his health was more important than his art.
</P>
<P>
   Months later, one day in late 1996, Adkins walked away from the
group home.
</P>
<P>
   ``They found him covered in his own filth,'' Doan says,
``digging in garbage some place. He was out of it. They took him to
the Trinity Lutheran psych unit. By the time I got there, he was
fine....He said to me that day, `Here I am in another place.' &UR; ''
Outsider discovered
</P>
<P>
   Ever since Doan's trip to the Atlanta Folk Fest, Adkins'
``golden-age'' art had been getting enthusiastic support from
important quarters.
</P>
<P>
   The Ricco//Maresca Gallery of New York, one of the nation's top
dealers of work by outsider and self-taught artists, had decided to
handle his drawings.
</P>
<P>
   Doan that summer had shipped more than a hundred of his pieces
to New York; the gallery bought some pieces outright from her and
held others on consignment. It had planned to pay Adkins a regular
stipend for new work. But, Doan says, when it became clear, after
September 1995, that the quality of his art declined, the gallery
pulled back from that.
</P>
<P>
   Even so, Ricco//Maresca began to create interest for Adkins'
best works. The gallery showed a few of his drawings at the
Outsider Art Fair in New York in January 1996. It also arranged for
a story about Adkins to appear in Raw Vision, an art journal that
showcases outsider art.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you look at a body of his work, you can see incredible
humor and wit,'' said Eugene W. Metcalf Jr., the scholar who wrote
that article. ``There's an intellectual waspishness. He plays all
sorts of intellectual tricks and cultural tricks and visual tricks
with his art.''
</P>
<P>
   In January 1997, Ricco//Maresca put on the sort of coming-out
party that many artists, untrained or not, can only dream of: a
one-person show in New York. One of Adkins' drawings, ``Angrieyed
Apple Mask,'' even appeared in the calendar section of The New
Yorker magazine, a stamp of cultural attainment if there ever was
one.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins didn't attend the exhibit. At the same time that his
drawings were hanging on the gallery's walls, handsomely framed in
blond wood, he agreed to move into the nursing home where he now
lives with the support of Medicaid.
</P>
<P>
   Ricco//Maresca priced Adkins' works at $2,200 apiece. It has yet
to sell one, although Stephen Romano, the gallery manager, expects
that over time they will find appreciative owners. Adkins wouldn't
share in the proceeds anyway, since Doan had already paid him for
the work.
</P>
<P>
   A year after the New York exhibit, four of Adkins' drawings
appeared in a sprawling show, called ``The End Is Near,'' at the
American Visionary Art Museum in Baltimore. And two of them _
``Your Plums-Fall-Hoe Down'' and ``Banana Split-Eating Shave'' _
made it into a colorful book based on the exhibit, which appeared
in late 1998.
</P>
<P>
   Just this fall Adkins was one of five outsiders in an exhibit at
Syracuse University's Lowe Art Gallery. And his work also has
joined the collection of the High Museum of Art in Atlanta, where
it will be part of a major show in the works for July 2001. New
world, old memories
</P>
<P>
   ``OK, how are you spelling `alfalfa'?''
</P>
<P>
   Margaret Doan stood over Bill Adkins' bedside table. He had set
out the seven drawings he made since her visit three days earlier.
She was taking notes, trying to make out Adkins' scrawled
descriptions.
</P>
<P>
   Adkins spelled it out for her: ``A-h-l-f-a-f-a-l, I believe. I'm
not too sure about that.''
</P>
<P>
   Then, he added, his voice rising: ``This thing will work. I know
it will work.''
</P>
<P>
   Adkins' contraption sprawled all over a 28-by-22-inch sheet of
white poster board. It was titled ``Young Deer Catcher Mitt.''
Here's the idea: You slip it over your hand and you can feed a deer
an ear of corn or a bunch of alfalfa.
</P>
<P>
   ``I caught a deer by hand with an ear of corn one day,'' Adkins
said. ``He stayed until I let loose of it.''
</P>
<P>
   ``You know what,'' Doan said, ``all the things you've done that
have to do with deer, this is a new one on me. How did you happen
to think of this?''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know,'' Adkins said. ``It just popped into my head.''
</P>
<P>
   In the nearly three years that Adkins has lived in the nursing
home, Doan occasionally has taken him paper and pens, and every now
and then he has had some drawings to show her. Whether it's a
``setup'' to remove your shoe without bending over or the ``Young
Deer Catcher Mitt,'' they are drawn with a less-sure hand than the
often lyrical pieces he made in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   And unlike that prolific period, he now goes weeks or months
without making any drawings at all.
</P>
<P>
   ``The mind dies away,'' he says of his creative drought. ``The
mental gives out, and you have to wait till something comes out.''
</P>
<P>
   But every now and then it happens. The window blinds above his
neatly made bed are closed. The nursing-home noise around him falls
away. As he lies there on his side, it can become quiet as a
library.
</P>
<P>
   And then a memory floats up from the gray quiet in his head.
Eventually the memory turns into an urge to invent, to make a piece
of the world born of a one-of-a-kind vision. And after that,
sitting in his room, William W. Adkins says, ``I think I've got one
coming up.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
