<SLUG> BC-FBC-HERITAGE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Hampton hammers Southern
 &HT;    By J.C. Clemons
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ With about seven minutes left in Heritage Bowl IX,
Southern University's cheerleaders packed their bags and called it
a day. At least they put more effort into the outing than the
Jaguars did.
</P>
<P>
   Southern made no bones about the fact it wasn't overly thrilled
about making a fifth consecutive appearance at the Georgia Dome on
Saturday in the so-called ``Black College Super Bowl.'' The Jags
didn't want to be here, and they played that way.
</P>
<P>
   Coming off back-to-back, come-from-behind wins over its biggest
rivals before large crowds, Southern started slow against Hampton
University, never got going and fell 24-3 before 29,561.
</P>
<P>
   Roy Johnson passed for 171 yards and a touchdown and Vincent
Lewis had three interceptions as the Pirates, who finished third in
the Mid-Eastern Athletic Conference, beat the Southwestern Athletic
Conference champs.
</P>
<P>
   ``The thing is, we just weren't ready to play,'' Southern coach
Pete Richardson said. ``I sensed it when we came out of the locker
room. It's tough to keep players up for three weeks in a row.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know if it's an advantage for our conference to come
back and play a game a week after our championship game. It's just
tough on kids.''
</P>
<P>
   The Jags (11-2) were on a high after thrilling wins over
Grambling in the Bayou Classic and Jackson State in last week's
SWAC title game, but soon came crashing down.
</P>
<P>
   Hampton, 21-6 losers to Southern during the season, got
inspiration from an outside source. The Pirates (8-4) took it
personal after Richardson called them a ``third-rated team.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't know how bad Southern wanted it, but we wanted it
really bad,'' said Johnson. ``We wanted to prove to everybody that
the comment that was made was a disgrace to us.''
</P>
<P>
   Richardson stood by his charge.
</P>
<P>
   The MEAC's top two teams, Florida A&AMP;M and North Carolina A&AMP;T,
chose to chase a shot at the NCAA Div. I-AA playoffs over playing
in the Heritage Bowl, while the SWAC _ which instituted a title
game this season _ sends its champion.
</P>
<P>
   Richardson, 4-2 in Heritage Bowls, says the concept is flawed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anytime you bill this as one of the biggest games in black
college football,'' Richardson said, ``you have to find a way to
get the two best teams playing in it.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, though, had no problem with the Heritage Bowl stage.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this is your last opportunity to play college football,
and the fact you're able to play it here _ this is great,'' said
Johnson, who had about 40 family members present.
</P>
<P>
   The Jaguars may have felt better about the whole scene had they
taken advantage of a golden opportunity.
</P>
<P>
   After gaining just 58 first-half yards yet trailing only 10-3,
Southern picked up that many after taking the second-half kickoff
and driving to the Hampton 9 yardline. But linebacker Corey Cason
made a diving interception of a tipped pass.
</P>
<P>
   The Pirates responded with a 92-yard, 9:44 scoring drive to pull
away, and the party was soon on.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is such a great feeling,'' said Hampton defensive back
Rashad Muyhee, a senior from Westlake High. ``I have friends and
family here who've never seen me play _ in high school or college.
This is great for black college football.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
