<SLUG> BC-FBC-IAA-TITLE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Georgia Southern scores fifth national title
 &HT;    By Earnest Reese
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Chattanooga, Tenn. _ One year of agony finally ended for Georgia
Southern on Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   After losing in last year's national title game to
Massachusetts, the Eagles added the school's fifth national
championship by routing Youngstown State 59-24 at Finley Stadium.
The Eagles (13-2) scored 28 unanswered points in the second quarter
and ended with the second-highest margin of victory in the 22-year
history of the Division I-AA championship game.
</P>
<P>
   A crowd of 20,052 watched All-American fullback Adrian Peterson
lead the way with 247 yards and three touchdowns. Georgia
Southern's option offense had its way against Youngstown State
(12-3), gaining 638 of its 655 total yards on the ground.
</P>
<P>
   The Eagles, who had lost to Youngstown State in three previous
meetings, turned the game into a rout in the third quarter after
Peterson's final touchdown pushed the lead to 45-17. Youngstown
State, which was seeking its fifth national title, could muster
little or nothing against the Eagles' defense after taking a 14-10
lead at the top of the second period.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike in the 55-43 loss to Massachusetts in last year's
championship game, when Hill and Peterson combined for seven
turnovers that helped kill the Eagles here a year ago, Georgia
Southern did not turn the ball over a single time.
</P>
<P>
   In his second appearance in the national championship game, Hill
became the third quarterback in school history to be so successful.
Former Eagles Tracy Ham guided the program to national crowns in
'85 and '86, and Raymond Gross followed suit in '89 and '90.
</P>
<P>
   Like last year's meeting here between Georgia Southern and
Massachusetts, this game early on took on the appearance of a
shootout. Less than 16 minutes into the battle, 24 points had
scored _ 14 of them by Youngstown State.
</P>
<P>
   But after falling behind 14-10 following a 3-yard touchdown run
by Penguins quarterback Jeff Ryan, Georgia Southern opened up its
offensive flood gates.
</P>
<P>
   Led by Peterson, who had 155 yards and two touchdowns at
halftime, the Eagles rolled to 28 consecutive points in the second
period. Peterson, who put his team up 17-14 on a 3-yard to captured
an 88-yard drive with 10:25 remaining in the second quarter, broke
five tackles on a 58-yard run to set another score.
</P>
<P>
   And shortly, topped another Eagles' drive of 57 yards of more
with a 22-yard blast of tackle, punter returner Anthony Williams
got in the scoring act when returned one 72 yards for a touchdown.
</P>
<P>
   In the process of its 38-point offensive explosion, Georgia
Southern by halftime had amassed 342 yards of total offense. Hill,
who scored his team's first TD when he opted to keep on a play off
his right that netted 42 yards, completed his only pass of the game
for 17 yards.
</P>
<P>
   At that juncture, Peterson had not only had surpassed the
100-yard rushing for the 30th consecutive game, but he also
surpassed the Division I-AA single-season playoff rushing record he
established last year.
</P>
<P>
   When this rout was over, five different Eagles had scored,
including Peterson, Hill, Cunningham, punter return Anthony
Williams and backup quarterback J.R. Revere.
</P>
<P>
   The head-to-head battle between Adrian Peterson and Penguins
tailback Adrian Brown ended up no contest. Brown finished the day
with 160 yards and two touchdowns, but most of his yards came in
the first half.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
