u s BC-FBN-GEORGE19-COX     12-18 0587
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GEORGE19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    No 2nd-half fade in '99 by George
 &HT;    By Mark Schlabach
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHVILLE, Tenn. _ Since Eddie George left Ohio State with the
Heisman Trophy and joined the NFL in 1996, he has emerged as one of
the league's best running backs.
</P>
<P>
   George last week became the ninth player in league history to
rush for more than 5,000 yards in his first four seasons, joining,
among others, NFL greats Jim Brown, Earl Campbell, Eric Dickerson
and Walter Payton.
</P>
<P>
   But there has been one glaring omission on George's resume: a
playoff berth.
</P>
<P>
   The Houston/Tennessee franchise finished 8-8 in George's first
three seasons with the team. But the Titans could end that drought
today by beating the Falcons in Adelphia Coliseum, which would
clinch Tennesee at least a wild-card berth.
</P>
<P>
   George, the 14th pick in the 1996 draft, is a big reason why
Tennessee has the league's fourth-best record at 10-3 with three
games remaining.
</P>
<P>
   George, 6 feet 3 and 240 pounds, rushed for 199 yards and two
touchdowns in a 21-14 victory against the Raiders on Dec. 9. It was
the highest rushing total in the NFL this season and the
second-highest of his career.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was the best effort I've seen since he's been here,''
Titans coach Jeff Fisher said. ``He ran possessed. He feels good.
He told me after the game last week that he could play another
three quarters.''
</P>
<P>
   That wasn't the case in George's first three seasons. He seemed
to wear down in the second half of the schedule, so the Titans
would fade from the playoff race.
</P>
<P>
   George had only one 100-yard rushing game in the second half of
the 1996 season, three in the second half of '97 and one in the
second half of '98.
</P>
<P>
   This year, he has rushed for 100 yards or more in three of five
games since the midpoint of the season. He has averaged 110 yards
in those games and scored seven touchdowns. The Titans are 4-0 in
those games.
</P>
<P>
   ``Definitely, I feel better this year than I have at this point
in the past,'' George said. ``I'm taking care of my body. I've just
made the decision to do what I have to do to be one of the best.''
</P>
<P>
   George is doing it against eight- and nine-man defensive fronts.
The Titans haven't had a passing touchdown in six games, with top
receiver Yancey Thigpen sidelined by an sprained ankle. Quarterback
Steve McNair, who missed six weeks after back surgery, is bothered
by turf toe and a sprained ankle and struggles throwing downfield.
</P>
<P>
   That means George is carrying much of the load.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be the best I can be and that means doing the right
things in all phases of my career,'' George said. ``It's just about
understanding this is my career and doing all of those little
things. I just made the choice. Do you want to be average? Do you
want to be one of the great ones?
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to be as good as I can be and you can't just say that.
You have to do what's needed.''
</P>
<P>
   _ Ht., wt.: 6 feet 3, 240 pounds.
</P>
<P>
   _ Age: 26.
</P>
<P>
   _ Hometown: Philadelphia.
</P>
<P>
   _ College: Ohio State.
</P>
<P>
   _ Career highlights: The ninth player in NFL history to rush for
5,000 yards in his first four seasons. ... George needs 85 rushing
yards to become only the fourth player to gain 1,200 or more in
each of his first four seasons. ... Gained 199 yards vs. Oakland on
Dec. 9, the highest total in the NFL this season. ... Was a
consensus All-American and won the Heisman Trophy at Ohio State in
1995.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
