<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-AIRPORT-USO19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Soldiers find friendly faces in trek through Atlanta airport
 &HT;    (With photos.)
 &HT;    By Jingle Davis
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ For five weeks, 19-year-old Joe Forinash of Beverly
Hills, Calif., has been marching in formation and rising to
reveille at Georgia's Fort Benning, where he is in Army basic
training.
</P>
<P>
   But this weekend, the young private, along with 20,000 more like
him from military posts all over Georgia, is getting a reprieve.
The soldiers are heading home for the holidays in Operation Exodus,
the largest annual movement of troops outside of combat situations.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't wait to see my parents,'' Forinash said.
</P>
<P>
   The young soldiers are getting a reminder of pre-military life
at Hartsfield International Airport, where staffers and volunteers
with the United Service Organizations of Georgia are feeding them
homemade sandwiches, cookies and other goodies, wrapping their
Christmas presents, helping them untangle airline ticket snafus and
cheering them on their way.
</P>
<P>
   There's even a Santa Claus, 84-year-old George Proctor.
</P>
<P>
   ``I welcome them, tell them Merry Christmas and give them
candy,'' said Proctor, a USO volunteer for 17 years.
</P>
<P>
   Operation Exodus family day assists thousands of military
dependents as they travel to join loved ones.
</P>
<P>
   The whole point of the USO, said Mary Lou Austin, who directs
the organization's flagship center at Hartsfield, is to supply the
troops and their families with whatever they need.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're mothers, counselors, cooks, social workers,'' she said.
Austin said the USO center will be open around the clock this
weekend and again for Operation Return in early January, when the
troops head back to their posts.
</P>
<P>
   On Saturday, clean-cut young men and women in green lined up at
the center for food, napped in the quiet room, read books in the
lounge and talked about going home.
</P>
<P>
   Pvt. Nicholas Johnson, 18, on his way to Milwaukee, has been in
basic training since September.
</P>
<P>
   ``I got stuck longer because I had trouble doing pushups,'' he
said.
</P>
<P>
   Each soldier has a story and the volunteers, mostly members of
Atlanta service organizations such as the Kiwanis club, are glad to
listen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're all so interesting,'' said Patt Duquemin of suburan
Atlanta. After wrapping a Faberge egg for one soldier, she sewed
buttons on for another. Her husband, retired Army Gen. Gordon
Duquemin, helped staff the center's welcoming post.
</P>
<P>
   Sgt. Maj. Benjamin Palacios, the top non-commissioned officer
with Army Headquarters at Fort McPherson in Atlanta, was at the
airport Saturday to wish each soldier a good journey. Palacios, who
joined the Army at 19, said he remembers the joys of holiday leave.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at them; they're so young,'' he said. ``Going home is
like heaven.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
