A2927 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-Y2K-ALLYEAR19-COX     12-18 0668
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-Y2K-ALLYEAR19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Jan. 1 won't tell the full tale of Y2K
 &HT;    By George Bennett
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   Less than two weeks from the world's date with computer destiny,
it's hard to find anyone _ even among the original prophets of Y2K
doom _ who expects a midnight meltdown when 1999 rolls over to
2000.
</P>
<P>
   But while New Year's weekend should pass without
cyber-cataclysm, experts say low-grade inconveniences related to
Y2K could persist for weeks or months.
</P>
<P>
   At the very least, that means the worldwide Y2K guessing game
won't end on New Year's Day.
</P>
<P>
   ``The world will be well into January before a considered
assessment can be made of Y2K's medium-term effects,'' says a
recent report by the United Nations' special Y2K council.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a myth to think that everything that's a Y2K problem is
going to show up Jan. 1,'' says Jack Gribben, the spokesman for
President Clinton's Council on Year 2000 Conversion. The federal
group plans to be in business through the end of March.
</P>
<P>
   While not expecting major disruptions on or after Jan. 1,
Gribben says some minor problems might not be apparent for two or
three weeks afterwards.
</P>
<P>
   Analysts at the oft-cited GartnerGroup predict that only 8
percent of all Y2K system failures will occur within two weeks of
Jan. 1. Some failures won't happen until late 2001, the group says.
About 90 percent of these ``failures'' will be fixed within two
days, Gartner says.
</P>
<P>
   Other experts say it's inevitable that some date-change problems
will slip through in the billions of lines of computer code that
have been reprogrammed for Y2K. And the sheer volume of changes
makes it likely that some new glitches will be introduced.
</P>
<P>
   ``When you fix something, you sometimes put in a fresh bug that
wasn't there before,'' says Massachusetts software consultant
Capers Jones.
</P>
<P>
   Doomsayers less doomful
</P>
<P>
   Jones was one of the earliest Y2K alarmists, and he's still a
little uneasy about some foreign countries and small businesses.
But he now expects nothing more than ``spotty and intermittent
problems _ not national problems _ that will probably affect 3 or 4
percent of the country.''
</P>
<P>
   Jones doesn't plan any special preparations for New Year's Eve
and said he recently decided against buying a backup generator for
his Massachusetts home.
</P>
<P>
   Another early Y2K doomsayer, consultant and author Ian Hayes,
also dismisses New Year's catastrophism. But while Hayes isn't
stocking up on extra food or water, he says he'll be giving his
bills and financial statements extra scrutiny for the first few
months of 2000 because of possible Y2K-related errors.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody's so focused on what's going to happen at midnight
... but that's not really the issue,'' says Hayes, who spoke at
what is believed to be the first major conference on the
date-change problem, back in 1995.
</P>
<P>
   Another early doom-and-gloom lecturer, Canadian consultant Peter
de Jager, now plans to be sipping champagne on a transatlantic
flight at the stroke of midnight on New Year's Eve.
</P>
<P>
   Market fears mollified
</P>
<P>
   Even hard-core Y2K apocalypticist Gary North appears to have
softened slightly in his predictions now that the worldwide stock
market crash he expected ``months before Jan. 1, 2000'' hasn't
materialized. His Internet site once predicted a ``nightmare'' in
the first few minutes of Jan. 1. Now, his site says, ``things will
not break down all at once in early January unless the power grid
goes down and stays down.''
</P>
<P>
   Another Y2K pessimist, Wall Street strategist Ed Yardeni, still
predicts a Y2K-related recession during the first six months of
2000, but he says chances are improving that the recession will be
minor rather than major.
</P>
<P>
   And both Yardeni and Ed Yourdon, a computer consultant and
author of doomishTime Bomb 2000, note that the Y2K-fueled investor
skittishness they expected in the second half of 1999 hasn't
happened.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 1918EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0234 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 19:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2928 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-DOG-FIGHTING19-COX     12-18 1678
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-DOG-FIGHTING19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Dog fighting spreading from country to city
 &HT;    (With photos.)
 &HT;    By Alan Judd
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   WAYNE COUNTY, Ga. _ It's called a blood sport. But when police
raided a dogfight in southeast Georgia's Wayne County, what
officers found was more like a bloodletting.
</P>
<P>
   Two pit bulls competing in the evening's second fight were
slowly mauling one another. One had his teeth imbedded in the
other's throat. The plywood walls of the 10-by-10-foot wooden pit
were splattered with blood. The new tan carpet that covered the
concrete floor was saturated with gore.
</P>
<P>
   Police arrested 66 people on the isolated farm near Jesup that
night, Nov. 19. Officers confiscated $39,000 that had been wagered
on the five scheduled fights. Afterward, though, came the hard job.
First, the officers put the badly injured dog that lost the second
fight out of his misery. Then they put the ``winner'' out of his.
</P>
<P>
   The raid highlighted the popularity of dogfighting in rural
Georgia, where it has been a macabre tradition for generations. It
is so pervasive that, after the raid, police received calls from
several women looking for their husbands. Every man had been at a
dogfight that night; the wives just weren't sure which fight had
been busted.
</P>
<P>
   But dogfighting has become more than a rural pastime. In Georgia
and across the country, police say, it is an increasingly common
hobby in urban neighborhoods, especially among members of street
gangs.
</P>
<P>
   And, thanks to the Internet, this shadowy subculture is reaching
new audiences.
</P>
<P>
   Kennels with names like ``Death Row'' and ``La Cosa Nostra''
offer to sell dogs bred from champion fighters' bloodlines. In chat
rooms and on message boards, dog owners discuss breeding and
fighting strategies. In online magazines, fans read the exploits of
the sport's greatest fighters.
</P>
<P>
   ``In his five contract matches, he destroyed all,'' Pit Bull
Reporter magazine's online edition said in a typical dispatch about
a champion dog named Santa's Mongoose. ``The only one to live
jumped the pit in 15 minutes. He took dogs apart. Bite one got
their attention. Bite number two made them wish they were someplace
else. There never was a need for bite three.''
</P>
<P>
   Such fights are illegal in Georgia and in 46 other states. But
it is rare for charges to be filed unless police officers witness
the matches. Only one person is currently doing time in a Georgia
prison for dogfighting _ one fewer than for hijacking a bus. Ten
Georgians are on probation from dogfighting convictions.
</P>
<P>
   But police and animal-protection activists say the Georgia
General Assembly has a chance this winter to crack down on
dogfighting.
</P>
<P>
   Lawmakers will consider a bill that would make animal cruelty a
felony, punishable by a five-year prison sentence. Police could
file cruelty charges against owners of fighting dogs even if they
aren't caught in the act. A dog's injuries _ torn ears, gashes in
its throat, bite marks covering its body _ would provide enough
evidence to prove cruelty.
</P>
<P>
   New ways to combat dogfighting are needed, said Bill Garrett,
executive director of the Atlanta Humane Society.
</P>
<P>
   Like other animal abusers, Garrett said, the owners of fighting
dogs ``are like cockroaches. They do most of their work in the dark
and out of sight.''
</P>
<P>
   `Dogfights all the time'
</P>
<P>
   No one knows exactly how widespread dogfighting is in Georgia.
But the Humane Society of the United States ranks Georgia as one of
the sport's most active states, along with California, Florida,
Louisiana and Texas.
</P>
<P>
   ``Dogfighting is fairly prevalent,'' said Geoffrey Simmons, a
Humane Society official in California. ``It cuts across all
socio-economic boundaries. It simply is a sport that appeals to a
lot of people for a lot of different reasons.''
</P>
<P>
   In Georgia, ``there's a great deal more of it going on than
people realize,'' said Lee Sweat, the Georgia Bureau of
Investigation agent who led 50 officers on the Wayne County raid.
``We hear about dogfights all the time.''
</P>
<P>
   But few of the sport's fans are willing to discuss it publicly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Due to the negative light that the media tends to portray
these dogs in on a regular basis, I highly doubt that anyone would
be interested in discussing anything with any form of media,'' Tim
Murphy of Jefferson, Ga., who publishes an Internet magazine called
Sporting Dog Online, wrote in an e-mail to a reporter.
</P>
<P>
   Murphy's magazine features detailed blood lines of fighting
dogs. It also posts the standard rules for dogfighting. But
fight-related content, the publication says, is ``for entertainment
purposes only.''
</P>
<P>
   Regardless, after declining to talk with a reporter, Murphy sent
an e-mail to pit bull and dogfighting enthusiasts across the
country, warning of possible scrutiny.
</P>
<P>
   ``There are these types of people looking for a story about this
breed all the time,'' he wrote, ``so please keep this copy and
remember the (reporter's) name in case you are contacted.''
</P>
<P>
   `Not friendly people'
</P>
<P>
   The secrecy that surrounds dogfighting makes the laws
prohibiting it tough to enforce.
</P>
<P>
   That is especially true when it comes to so-called
streetfighters. Often members of criminal gangs, these dogfighting
enthusiasts cruise their neighborhoods with their dogs, looking for
fights.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of it's impromptu,'' said Lt. Larry Gibson of the
Clayton County Police Department's animal control unit. The fights
often take place ``right in the middle of the street, right in
somebody's front yard.''
</P>
<P>
   Still, Gibson said, ``it's very hard to catch them.'' Even if a
neighbor calls police, the fights are usually over when officers
arrive. And witnesses are often too afraid of the dogs' owners to
testify against them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of these are not friendly people,'' Gibson said of the
streetfighters. ``The witnesses have a legitimate fear. ... Eighty
percent of the people I've dealt with have gone on to bigger and
better crimes.''
</P>
<P>
   In contrast, other dogfighting fans revel in their sport's long
history and what they see as the nobility of the American pit bull
terrier. Streetfighters put any breed of dog that will fight into
matches. But traditionalists remain loyal to the pit bull _ a breed
that, they say, is as gentle with humans as it is aggressive toward
other dogs.
</P>
<P>
   Unlike the impromptu street fights, many pit bull matches are
planned for weeks or months. And they are widely, if quietly,
advertised.
</P>
<P>
   The 66 people arrested in Wayne County came from all over
Georgia and from six other states. The fight was promoted by a club
called ``20/20'' and was held on a farm where the club's secretary
lives. To promote secrecy, spectators had been told to assemble on
another farm. From there, they were led to the fight location by
the club's chief of security.
</P>
<P>
   Each fight was expected to last as long as two hours. Each would
continue, the GBI's Sweat said, ``until one dog wins by either
killing the other dog or the other dog's so incapacitated he can't
fight any more.''
</P>
<P>
   All 66 who were arrested are free on bond, awaiting trial. Few
had ever been in trouble with the law.
</P>
<P>
   ``In their own little parts of the world, they're not the street
gang drug dealers,'' Sweat said. ``Probably everybody was gainfully
employed. They all drove nice vehicles.''
</P>
<P>
   All, too, enjoyed what Sweat called ``the perverse excitement of
watching one animal tearing another one up.''
</P>
<P>
   A dogfighter's story
</P>
<P>
   Antonio Clark watched his first dogfight when he was 7. It was
the same year he began breeding pit bulls.
</P>
<P>
   With family friends, he went to fights ``all over Georgia,
Florida, Alabama, Texas,'' recalled Davis, now 28. ``It happens
everywhere in the United States.''
</P>
<P>
   The early exposure led to a lifelong enchantment with the sport
_ a fascination that ultimately brought Davis a dubious
distinction: He is the only person serving time in a Georgia prison
for dogfighting.
</P>
<P>
   He didn't start out fighting the dogs he raised, Davis said
during an interview at the Carroll County Prison, where he is
serving one year of a five-year sentence.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pit bulls, when they first started breeding them, were bred
for their gameness _ not to stop fighting,'' Davis said. ``Like
anybody else, I wanted to breed the best.''
</P>
<P>
   During the past two decades, he said, he has bred about 1,000
pit bull puppies. Each, he said, sold for $400 to $500.
</P>
<P>
   Davis wouldn't say when he started putting his dogs in fights.
But he said that before his arrest, he had success with a
particularly strong fighter he had bred. He named the dog Silkkthe
Shocka, after the rapper.
</P>
<P>
   In the summer of 1998, Davis put Silkk the Shocka in a fight
against a dog with a lesser reputation. The other dog's owner
videotaped the fight.
</P>
<P>
   Three days later, Davis and several friends were in Friendship
Park in Clarkston, watching the tape on a video camera. A police
officer drove up _ thinking, Davis said, that the group was smoking
marijuana. After seeing what was on the tape, the officer charged
Davis with dogfighting. He pleaded guilty last summer.
</P>
<P>
   Sitting in prison, wearing a white uniform a shade duller than
the white concrete walls, Davis recalled a world of large bets _
``maybe five G's, 15 G's'' _ and fight purses that reached $2,500.
</P>
<P>
   Despite his conviction, he expressed little remorse.
</P>
<P>
   ``If I'm going by the law books, yeah, I did something wrong,''
he said. ``But in society, the way people live today, no.''
</P>
<P>
   Pitting one dog against another isn't cruel, he maintained, ``no
more than it is cruel to have two men in the ring boxing. You take
care of the dogs. They have a choice to fight like a man has a
choice to fight.''
</P>
<P>
   Davis is scheduled to leave prison Feb. 4. A condition of his
probation is that he own no dogs for another four years.
</P>
<P>
   A visitor asked whether he would wait that long to resume
dogfighting.
</P>
<P>
   A smile crossed Davis' face as he replied, ``On or off the
record?''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
