A2933 &Cx1f; kan-z
r a BC-1980s-ESSAY-2TAKES-KA     12-18 0972
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-1980s-ESSAY-2TAKES-KAN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
THE DECADE OF THE '80S WAS DOMINATED BY THE ECONOMY 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By ERIC PALMER  
 c. 1999 Kansas City Star   KANSAS CITY, Mo. _ The future looked
bleak for the United States at the beginning of the 1980s.
<TEXT>
<P>
   We were exhausted by the fallout from the Vietnam War and
Watergate. Inflation was high _ 13.5 percent _ and Americans'
confidence was low.
</P>
<P>
   The attitude of many was reflected in the Jan. 20, 1981,
inaugural address of the new president, Ronald Reagan:
</P>
<P>
   ``These United States are confronted with an economic affliction
of great proportions. We suffer from the longest and one of the
worst sustained inflations in our national history.... It threatens
to shatter the lives of millions of our people. Idle industries
have cast workers into unemployment, human misery and personal
indignity.''
</P>
<P>
   It was an inauspicious beginning to a wrenching 10 years that,
in hindsight, set up the country for the tremendous economic gains
it is now producing.
</P>
<P>
   U.S. industries transformed themselves _ snatching each other up
and sloughing off managers and workers, but then creating jobs and
becoming strong global competitors. Deregulation reigned, and union
power declined. The government cut taxes and strengthened defense,
but ran up a massive debt. The stock market revived, crashed and
revived again.
</P>
<P>
   By decade's end, however, free-market economics would vault the
United States back to its place as the premier economy, and set the
world, well, free. At least free to own things.
</P>
<P>
   A growing intolerance of repressive regimes and a growing
interest in consumer products converted practitioners of communism
into devotees of capitalism. Democracy of sorts was the by-product.
</P>
<P>
   Americans did not even see the fall of communism coming. We were
worrying about jobs, mortgage rates, failing banks, AIDS, cocaine
and failing marriages.
</P>
<P>
   We realized capitalism had triumphed with the fall of the Berlin
Wall in November 1989. We caught it on CNN.
</P>
<P>
   ``When the Berlin wall came down, it sent a message to all but
North Korea and Cuba that markets had won,'' said Robert Litan of
the Brookings Institution. ``Even China has shrunk its state-owned
industries and allowed markets to grow outside of that.'' Debate
over Reagan
</P>
<P>
   When the decade began, the U.S. economy could not whip Japan,
not to mention communism. The country we vanquished in World War II
was selling us a future in which it was the economic world power.
</P>
<P>
   We found Japanese cars more reliable and their electronics more
desirable. They lectured us on quality, lessons they had learned
from American W. Edwards Deming.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan proposed restoring America's economic dominance by
cutting taxes and building a strong defense. He preached taking
personal responsibility and cutting our reliance on the federal
government.
</P>
<P>
   Reagan was popular with a majority of Americans. He also ignited
visceral feelings.
</P>
<P>
   Some credit him with reviving the economy and defeating the
Soviet Union. Others think he falsely professed a concern for
``family values'' while his administration turned its back on the
poor.
</P>
<P>
   Gerald Miller, an economics professor at Rockhurst College and
an old-line Kennedy Democrat, said he initially could not imagine
Reagan as president. But Miller became a fan.
</P>
<P>
   ``I really believe Reagan, more than any other individual,
almost single-handedly is responsible for the fabulous economy we
are enjoying,'' Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   The wealthiest Americans saw the most dramatic cuts in their tax
rates. Government spending went up, not down, creating record
federal debt.
</P>
<P>
   Yet the success of his tax cuts and supply-side economics lifted
all boats. The eventual results generated the jobs for minorities
and women that eluded the job programs that grew out of President
Lyndon B. Johnson's Great Society, Miller said.
</P>
<P>
   ``As a result we have had our longest postwar economic
expansion,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   To Marcus Raskin, co-founder of the Institute for Policy
Studies, Reagan's politics were a scripted sham.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think he was a divisive president culturally,'' said Raskin.
</P>
<P>
   He made people feel it was OK to get rich without worrying about
the plight of others, that narcissism was ``a good basis for public
policy,'' Raskin said.
</P>
<P>
   Nearly 20 years after Reagan was elected president, the chest
beating from both sides rings hollow. Recent economic data suggest
our current economic boom had its beginning with some of the Reagan
policies but was propelled by other factors.
</P>
<P>
   Crippling inflation was tamed by Federal Reserve Chairman Paul
Volcker's strangling interest rates. Productivity improvements
started after the Reagan tax cuts, as supply-siders predicted. Yet
greater productivity growth followed tax increases in 1990 and
1993.
</P>
<P>
   While a call for a smaller federal government was at the center
of the Reagan philosophy, it did not shrink until the Clinton
presidency, said Richard B. McKenzie, a Reagan supporter and author
of What Went Right in the 1980s.
</P>
<P>
   ``It is a record no one wants to acknowledge,'' McKenzie said.
``The Democrats don't want to say they out-Reaganed Reagan, and the
Reaganites don't want to acknowledge it for the same reason.''
Recipe for a remaking
</P>
<P>
   So how did America in the 1980s remake itself into the world's
dominant economic power?
</P>
<P>
   Deregulation of industries like airlines and long distance, the
reorganization of companies to do more work with fewer employees,
the emergence of the personal computer and the creation of a nation
of stock investors all came together into a beam of economic
brilliance.
</P>
<P>
   The icon of deregulation was the breakup of AT&AMP;T. It was broken
into eight independent companies and in exchange was allowed to
compete in unregulated industries, like computers.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
