<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 19:29 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2935 &Cx1f; tad-z
u a BC-NORLEANS-VENDORS19-CO     12-18 1023
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NORLEANS-VENDORS19-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Tourist haunt masks bitter New Orleans infighting
 &HT;    (With photos.)
 &HT;    By Anne Rochell Konigsmark
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW ORLEANS _ On a blustery December day in the French Quarter,
Jackson Square is alive with free entertainment.
</P>
<P>
   An eight-piece band plays jazz to one side of St. Louis
Cathedral. Artists paint pictures of courtyards and oak trees
sagging with Spanish moss. Tarot card readers entice the few
tourists who are in town to have a reading.
</P>
<P>
   This scene, which to visitors seems quintessentially New
Orleans, is ground zero in a bitter turf war that pits residents
against entertainers and entertainers against one another. And this
is no mere war of words: There have been lawsuits, shoving matches,
arrests, even firebombings. Task forces have formed and disbanded,
laws and ordinances have been passed, then overturned or ignored.
</P>
<P>
   Even the soothsayers can't predict how the struggles will be
resolved.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm quite sad that people can't live in harmony and peace,''
said Mystic Goddess, a psychic who sets up her table in front of
the church doors.
</P>
<P>
   Residents say the quarter, one of the nation's oldest and
best-preserved residential districts, is being turned into a
Disneyland entertainment center catering to the 11 million annual
tourists and the businesses that feed off them. They have filed
lawsuits complaining that the city does not enforce zoning laws by
allowing amplified music in residential zones. Jackson Square, for
example, is residential.
</P>
<P>
   Because of the pending litigation, city officials declined to
comment.
</P>
<P>
   St. Louis Cathedral parishioners say the brass bands disturb
services. The Legislature passed a noise ordinance that applied to
areas around churches and hospitals statewide, but it was struck
down in court as too restrictive.
</P>
<P>
   Down the street from the square, two bars at the French Market,
which is city property, blare music from live bands, disturbing
Stuart Smith and his neighbors. Smith, an attorney, has filed
several suits, one last week, to get the city to turn down the
volume.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those bars are not zoned for live entertainment,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   The Gazebo Bar and the Market Cafe contend that because they've
been allowed to have live music for decades, they should be able to
continue. George Mellen of the Gazebo Bar tried to get a legitimate
live entertainment license last year, and Smith went to court to
stop him.
</P>
<P>
   Mellen responded by hurling Molotov cocktails onto Smith's
Mercedes and into the courtyard of his 5,000-square-foot home.
Mellen and an associate were sentenced Thursday to three years in
prison.
</P>
<P>
   Mellen this year sold the bar to a municipal judge and a city
assessor, who were able to get the live entertainment license that
eluded Mellen. Smith filed a suit against the city last week
claiming the license is illegal.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's been allowed to happen in the French Quarter is
disgraceful,'' Smith said. ``There are right and wrong places to
party in this city, as in every city. It's destroying the
residential base of the quarter.''
</P>
<P>
   This is not a new issue. In the early 1990s, the quarter was
listed three years in a row as one of the nation's most endangered
historic treasures by the National Trust for Historic Preservation.
</P>
<P>
   The trust cited encroaching commercialism as the chief threat.
Lawsuits were filed, and a city task force in 1991 was to try to
make peace between residents and revelers.
</P>
<P>
   The revelers seem to be winning: The French Quarter's population
has declined sharply in a decade, from 7,000 to 3,000. Meanwhile,
tourism is at an all-time high, and bars, T-shirt shops and street
entertainers seem to operate by their own rules.
</P>
<P>
   Lee Tucker, an artist selling paintings in Jackson Square since
1971, said he doesn't mind street music but thinks it is
inappropriate so close to homes and the cathedral. He also thinks
it's unfair that only artists must get a city license to operate
and must pay taxes on their earnings. Musicians, mimes and other
entertainers have no such requirements.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're just too loud,'' Tucker said over the bang of a drum
and the blare of a trumpet. ``Public activity should enhance the
residential nature of the area. We feel the artists enhance the
area, the musicians do not.''
</P>
<P>
   Then there are the tarot card readers. Taking advantage of the
city's lax regulations, psychics in recent years have come from all
over the country to set up along the square. Now more than 50 vie
for the limited space.
</P>
<P>
   In October, two psychics got into a fight over a prime spot.
William Alobar Greywalker went after newcomer Margaret Avalon
Nemith with a folding chair. She twisted her ankle running away.
Police were called. The case will go to court in February, with a
mime as the key witness.
</P>
<P>
   ``You wouldn't believe the harassment,'' said Mystic Goddess,
another relative newcomer who came to Nemith's aid. ``The other
readers call me a transvestite! And residents say they don't like
the way we look or how loud we are. Am I loud? Is a mime loud?''
</P>
<P>
   But Mystic Goddess sides with residents when it comes to the
brass band.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're offensive, obnoxious,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Lawrence and Doreen Ketchens have been playing with whoever else
comes up with an instrument for 10 years in Jackson Square.
</P>
<P>
   On a wintry afternoon, they are attracting all the attention. A
crowd of tourists lingers, sometimes for hours, to listen to the
trombone, the tuba and a little crooning.
</P>
<P>
   Phyllis and Lou Zanner, visiting from Sonoma, Calif., were
surprised to hear that anyone would object to the music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oh, hamburger!'' Phyllis Zanner said. ``Where's the fun in
life anymore? Tell the residents to go somewhere where it's quiet.
This is New Orleans.''
</P>
<P>
   Doreen Ketchens agreed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Music has been here for centuries,'' she said. ``This has
always been a public square. Anyone who came and looked at
apartments here and moved here knew there was music. To come in and
try and change the culture is hypocritical.''
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
