<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 19:31 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2938 &Cx1f; tad-z
u l BC-SAMS-SONG19-TAKE1-COX     12-18 3821
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-SAMS-SONG19-TAKE1-COX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
&HT;   
</HEADLINE>
 &HT;    Music helps Sam Taylor conduct a bittersweet life of
independence with autism
 &HT;    (Moving in two takes. With photos. Moving in (a) national and
(l) lifestyle categories.)
 &HT;    By Jim Dyer
 &HT;    c. 1999 Cox News Service
<TEXT>
<P>
   ATLANTA _ Sam Taylor walked through downtown Atlanta untangling
public telephone cords, straightening strange men's ties and
putting order in a world he could never understand.
</P>
<P>
   He loped down the streets, his left pinkie finger extended on
even blocks and his right pinkie on odd ones. In his wallet, he
carried a few dollar bills that he'd starched and pressed to smooth
out the wrinkles.
</P>
<P>
   As he marched, he hummed a rhythmic chant in time with his gait.
It spilled out loudly, drowning out the din of the streets as if it
were off-key.
</P>
<P>
   Sam stopped and memorized the text of posters, plaques and
historical monuments, and struck up conversations with passers-by.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do you know any Secret Service agents to the president of the
United States?'' he asked a man carrying a briefcase. The man
squinted in confusion and went on without replying. Sam raised his
finger and mumbled, ``Check. Top secret. Top secret.''
</P>
<P>
   Two blocks later, he asked a woman if she knew Ted Turner. When
she furrowed her eyebrows, he rattled off the history of Turner's
TBS station, its earlier years as WTCG and WJRJ and its programs.
</P>
<P>
   She smiled _ there was something innocent in his voice _ and
commented that Sam must be an expert on television.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am. I am. I am am am am am am ...'' he said, his voice
booming from his 6-foot-3 frame like a jackhammer. ``I'm also a
Georgia Tech Yellow Jackets fan. Been one my whole life.''
</P>
<P>
   Continuing on his journey, he walked across to Underground
Atlanta where he passed a woman in tight jeans and lacy blouse
leaning against a wall.
</P>
<P>
   ``Hi, there,'' she said alluringly. ``You want a date?''
</P>
<P>
   ``No, thank you, ma'am. I'm going to see the governor,'' he
replied and walked past. Ten feet away he turned and shouted back
to her: ``Don't forget to turn your clock back one hour to Eastern
Standard Time.''
</P>
<P>
   On this warm autumn afternoon, the world seemed hospitable,
rather than hostile. People seemed friendlier, and Sam, a
40-year-old autistic man, was enjoying himself.
</P>
<P>
   Gone was the 6-foot fence that confined the strange blond boy
who screamed and threw glass milk bottles and bit himself. Gone
were the weeks at Milledgeville's state mental institution, where a
5-year-old Sam learned how to curse, smoke and endure cigarette
burns without crying. Gone were the doctors who said Sam would
never be normal or learn to talk.
</P>
<P>
   Although Sam exceeded the experts' predictions, he still suffers
from autism, an incurable neurological disorder characterized by
extreme withdrawal, impaired communication and emotional
detachment. It affects between 1 and 2 of every 1,000 newborns.
</P>
<P>
   Now, he struggles to be as independent and self-reliant as the
people he passes in the streets. He wants to drive, to live alone,
to have a girlfriend, to go to college.
</P>
<P>
   Goals attained in a different world from Sam's, a world just out
of reach.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not autistic anymore,'' he often shouts.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam is very bright _ a walking database of facts and
information, but he can't process it,'' said Nan Pigot, a
58-year-old cousin who lived with Sam's family for several years
when Sam was young.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's been a life of frustration because he wants to be like
other people but he can't, and deep down he knows he can't.''
</P>
<P>
   The music child
</P>
<P>
   As a baby, Sam rarely slept and never cried. He became stiff and
robotic when his mother picked him up or tried to nurse him.
</P>
<P>
   So little was known about autism during Sam's first 10 years
that his family searched in vain for answers.
</P>
<P>
   ``There were days I wanted to cry,'' said his mother, Lenora
Taylor. ``I prayed to God to show me where the button was that I
pushed to make him normal.''
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, though, there had been the music.
</P>
<P>
   Sam's parents were professional musicians, and his mother
noticed early on that when she sang or played music, Sam was
transformed from an indifferent infant to a warm cuddling baby.
</P>
<P>
   As a young boy, he spent hours cuddling against the washing
machine, absorbing the vibrations and humming in key to the
machine.
</P>
<P>
   For years he didn't speak, but adeptly hummed jingles from TV
and radio in perfect pitch. If his family sang jingles off-key, Sam
grew angry and corrected them with his own humming.
</P>
<P>
   By humming and chanting, Sam was imposing his own rhythm on the
world.
</P>
<P>
   Like most autistic children, he grew up socially withdrawn and
unable to process emotions outside of anger and frustration. He
didn't laugh at jokes because he didn't understand humor. He didn't
cry because he didn't understand sadness. When his grandmother
died, he walked uncomfortably among the mourners at her funeral and
finally approached his brother.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to cry,'' he said. ``If I put an onion under my eye,
will I cry?''
</P>
<P>
   In 1969, his mother took him to the first national conference on
autism in Washington. Sam distanced himself from the other autistic
children and spent the day conversing with adults, especially those
he perceived to be important.
</P>
<P>
   He needed absolute order and symmetry in his world. Little
things, like toothbrushes not facing the same direction, sent him
into explosive tantrums. He often intentionally injured himself or
destroyed things in the house.
</P>
<P>
   Sam's disruptive behavior put intense pressure on the family.
For years, his two older brothers watched most of the basic
parental support being redirected toward Sam. Normal family outings
to restaurants or movies were impossible.
</P>
<P>
   The family's unity began to fray and his mother and father
separated and eventually divorced. Sam took it hard and blamed
himself.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why did I have to be born autistic?'' the 14-year-old shouted
at his brother when his father moved out.
</P>
<P>
   But through music and his mother's persistence, Sam eventually
learned to read and write, and eventually attended special
education courses in school. He had rare gifts of perfect pitch and
photographic memory, but he still had difficulty fitting in.
</P>
<P>
   When the outside world became too frustrating for him, Sam would
sit on the carpet or in bed, head tilted to one side, and hum. He
closed his eyes and smiled, seemingly lost in another world while
he rocked back and forth.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a special moment between Sam and himself, a time when
he seemed at ease and was not screaming or destructive,'' said his
brother Jeff Taylor, 44, a professional musician.
</P>
<P>
   ``We called it 'Sam's Song.'''The coach
</P>
<P>
   Every Wednesday evening, Creative Community Services, an
organization that provides supported home care for disabled adults,
takes Sam to a bowling alley with about two dozen disabled adults
with autism, mental retardation or schizophrenia.
</P>
<P>
   But Sam never bowls. Just as he did as a child, he distances
himself from his peers. Sam sits alone, smoking cigars and eating
double cheeseburgers and french fries.
</P>
<P>
   For two hours, the group laughs and shouts and bowls. They share
Cokes and candy and give each other tips and pats on the back.
</P>
<P>
   From his solitary table, Sam looks down at the group with cold
indifference.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not like them,'' he says, picking up french fries with
alternating hands _ first the right, then the left _ and placing
them in his mouth. ``I'm not autistic anymore.''
</P>
<P>
   Once or twice during the evening, Sam walks behind the lanes and
claps his hands loudly.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let's go. Let's go. LET'S GO!'' the self-appointed coach
shouts.
</P>
<P>
   He once chastised a young, mildly retarded man who was teasing
one of the Creative Community Services employees.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why do you have to be yelling so loud?'' the man snapped back.
</P>
<P>
   ``Because I'm the coach, and you have to do what I say,'' Sam
shouted.
</P>
<P>
   Sam's never bowled before, but he understands the importance of
a coach. Although he has higher abilities than most of the
developmentally disabled adults on the bowling team, he couldn't
function in the adult world without a coach for work and one for
home.
</P>
<P>
   His job coach from Briggs &AMP; Associates helps map out his
professional life, getting him job interviews, helping employers
train him, dictating how he should behave with coworkers and
customers. His home coach from Creative Community Services helps
organize his personal life, taking him to appointments, to the
grocery store, telling him how much money he can spend and what
types of food he should buy.
</P>
<P>
   But sometimes, Sam feels the support cuts into his lifelong goal
of being normal and independent. His two older brothers are married
and have families, good jobs, cars and independence.
</P>
<P>
   But everywhere Sam goes, people _ his family, his job coach, his
home coach _ dictate what he should buy, where he should work, how
he should live.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam is smart enough to know that he's not running his own
life,'' his mother said. And it frustrates him.
</P>
<P>
   He can't even buy a can of tuna fish in oil without getting a
lecture.
</P>
<P>
   ``Just try the tuna in spring water,'' his home coach, Kathryn
Flight, explained recently at Sam's neighborhood grocery store.
``There's less calories.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I have a right to be fat,'' Sam shouted, his 256-pound body
tensing up. ``I do. I do. I do-do-do-do-do-doooo! You're trying to
violate my rights.''
</P>
<P>
   She tried to reason with him about eating healthy, but Sam had
heard enough.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm fed up with everybody fussing,'' he said. ``I'm an adult
and registered voter and I have a right to eat what I want and live
alone and drive a car and do what I want.''
</P>
<P>
   First job
</P>
<P>
   When Sam walked up on stage in 1978 to receive his high school
diploma in special education, the entire senior class from
Atlanta's Northside High School gave him a standing ovation. It was
a glorious moment for the 19-year-old and his family.
</P>
<P>
   But 11 years would pass before Sam would find much meaning in
the adult world. He wandered the streets, worked in sheltered
workshops for developmentally disabled adults, and earned pocket
money by walking the neighbor's dogs or cutting the grass. He
looked enviously at his older brothers Bud and Jeff, who moved out
and landed jobs at symphonies. Bud plays for the Columbus and Macon
symphonies, and Jeff freelances for the Lyric Opera Symphony of
Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   In 1989, Briggs &AMP; Associates landed Sam a job as a bagger at the
Kroger store off Roswell Road near Chastain Park. Sam was elated.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, he arrived dressed in his Sunday best _ blue slacks,
shirt, tie _ and carrying a black leather briefcase.
</P>
<P>
   During training, his managers told him to be quick and polite.
Every time he bagged groceries, they said, he needed to ask the
customers their bag preference.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you like paper or plastic, ma'am?'' Sam asked his first
customer.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plastic, please.''
</P>
<P>
   Seconds later, after filling her first bag, Sam turned to her
again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you like paper or plastic, ma'am?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Plastic,'' she replied. ``I already said plastic.''
</P>
<P>
   When Sam loaded up the second bag, he asked again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Would you like paper or plastic, ma'am?''
</P>
<P>
   His managers sighed.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam took things extremely literal,'' said Gary Libowsky, the
store manager at the time. ``We had to make sure we were talking on
the same level with him.''
</P>
<P>
   In the first few months, Sam became obsessed with making sure
customers were happy and that the store attracted as many shoppers
as possible. One afternoon, coworkers had to frantically pull him
out of the middle of Roswell Road as he directed lanes of angry
motorists into the store's parking lot. He was also told not to
yell at people who said they preferred to shop elsewhere. He
followed Kroger's stock daily and whenever it fell on the market,
he'd run into work the next day and demand to speak with the
company's president in Cincinnati, Ohio, to inform him of the loss.
</P>
<P>
   After working through the initial difficulties, Sam's
supervisors discovered he was reliable, never late, always eager to
work and extremely personable with customers.
</P>
<P>
   In his first six months, Sam was named Kroger employee of the
period.
</P>
<P>
   As part of his reward, he met the company president, Atlanta
Mayor Maynard Jackson, and Gov. Joe Frank Harris at the state
Capitol.
</P>
<P>
   Sam basked in the attention. Never before did he feel so
accepted in the world. Since his youth, Sam was always fascinated
with VIPS.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was seeking approval,'' his mother said. ``Talking to them
made him feel accepted and important and, in a sense, normal.''
</P>
<P>
   But after winning the award and meeting the governor, Sam's
attitude changed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have autism anymore,'' he defiantly told his job
coach. Sam swaggered around work like he was invincible. His
behavior began to deteriorate.
</P>
<P>
   His photographic memory became a curse. When he carried out
customers' groceries, he remembered their names, the type of cars
they drove, the county where they lived, even the license plate
numbers. Women began complaining that Sam was stalking them.
</P>
<P>
   His job coach told Sam to talk only about work, weather or
sports with customers, but Sam found loopholes.
</P>
<P>
   ``It sure was hot yesterday,'' he began asking women. ``What
sort of lingerie did you wear to bed last night?'' Trouble at work
bled over to his private life.
</P>
<P>
   He met prostitutes. They picked him up every Friday when he was
paid in cash and persuaded him to buy them fancy clothes and
dinners at lavish restaurants. When he woke up Saturday morning, he
was broke. He began wandering the streets, going to strip clubs,
sometimes returning home after 2 a.m. His mother grew worried and
both she and his job coach tried to intercede.
</P>
<P>
   But Sam became more obstinate. He didn't need anyone's help, he
told them. After all, he was an award-winning employee who knew he
wasn't autistic anymore.
</P>
<P>
   At work, his behavior worsened. When he was brought into
disciplinary meetings with the manager, he claimed that his rights
of free speech were being violated.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam got too big for his britches,'' Libowsky recalled.
</P>
<P>
   In April 1995, after five and a half years of working at Kroger,
Sam was fired.
</P>
<P>
   The new job
</P>
<P>
   Today when Sam wakes up to shower, shave and dress, he does so
in his own apartment. When he sets off for work, it's not just for
any job. He works for the Atlanta Symphony Orchestra.
</P>
<P>
   ``Keep the blinds closed,'' he shouts at his roommate, also a
developmentally disabled adult.
</P>
<P>
   ``Calm down, Sam,'' his roommate replies. ``I'm just looking
outside.''
</P>
<P>
   ``I want them closed,'' Sam yells. ``I do, I do. I do do do.''
</P>
<P>
   With a bowl full of Nesquik chocolate-flavored cereal and whole
milk, Sam sits down in his recliner to have breakfast and watch
Channel 11. There's never a deviation. Recliner. Channel 11.
Nesquik. Newspapers and magazines that he's read and memorized are
strewn about the room. World Championship Wrestling star Goldberg
glowers down from a poster in the kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Sam hums as he shovels spoonfuls of cereal into his mouth. He
closes his eyes while he chews.
</P>
<P>
   On his way outside, he checks to make sure he has everything he
needs: Wallet. Keys. Airhorn.
</P>
<P>
   He sits on a small wall alongside Ashford Dunwoody Road and hums
while waiting for the 29 MARTA bus. Cars whiz past in the rush hour
traffic. Drivers honk at each other.
</P>
<P>
   The noise disrupts Sam's internal rhythm.
</P>
<P>
   He pulls out his airhorn and blasts back at the cars.
</P>
<P>
   At the Chamblee MARTA Station, he transfers to the southbound
train and gets off at the Arts Center.
</P>
<P>
   When he reaches his office across the street, he greets his
boss, Charlotte Hankins, grabs a large stack of papers and begins
filing the names of past ticketholders. He flips through the
papers, memorizing a special code for the ticketholder's home
location, and meticulously arranges them in neat stacks on his
desk. He then sorts them into stacks of 25 for telemarketers on the
day and night shifts.
</P>
<P>
   His job coach at Briggs &AMP; Associates knew that because of his
family's background in music, Sam would feel at home working with
the symphony.
</P>
<P>
   ``Plus Sam has some rough edges, and I thought that the art
world would be a little more accepting,'' Lee Sanders said.
</P>
<P>
   When Sam told his family about the new job, he could hardly
contain his excitement.
</P>
<P>
   ``I haven't seen him that excited in a long time,'' his mother
recalled.
</P>
<P>
   Hankins lauded Sam's skills.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's a great worker and very well liked,'' she said. ``He has
his days, but so does everyone.''
</P>
<P>
   Although Sam's job coach instructed him not to strike up
conversations with female colleagues, Sam still does, especially
with minority women.
</P>
<P>
   Every day, an attractive female colleague with Korean ancestry
enters the office and Sam watches her from his chair. And every day
Sam strikes up the same conversation with her about her heritage.
</P>
<P>
   ``Welcome to America,'' he says in the end and smiles. Later on,
he explains that as a Southern man, he never embraced a hatred
toward minorities.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't like prejudice and I don't like racism and I don't
like segregation, but I do like Great Danes.''
</P>
<P>
   After especially busy weeks, his boss often rewards his hard
work with free symphony tickets. Recently, she booked him a seat
for a Friday morning Coffee Concert.
</P>
<P>
   ``Make sure you dress nice, Sam,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Georgia Tech
</P>
<P>
   He had a job. With the symphony no less.
</P>
<P>
   He had an apartment and a relatively independent life. But he
had not achieved one lifelong dream: a college degree from his
favorite school, Georgia Tech.
</P>
<P>
   The timing this fall seemed right. Tech's football team was
winning, led by a Heisman Trophy candidate. The campus was only a
short distance from work. He felt more confident than ever.
</P>
<P>
   One day after work, he loped across Georgia Tech's sun-dappled
campus, humming, reading plaques and posters and following a line
of insects.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look at the bumblebees,'' he said to a passing student.
``Bzzzzzzzz. Bzzzzzzz.''
</P>
<P>
   By the time he reached the admissions office, he was wiping
sweat from his brow.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'd like to go to Georgia Tech because I've been a Yellow
Jackets fan my whole life,'' Sam told Ingrid Hayes, associate
director of admissions.
</P>
<P>
   ``What are you interested in as a major?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Everything,'' he said. ``A-L-L.''
</P>
<P>
   Hayes furrowed her eyebrows, but proceeded to detail the
requirements to enter Georgia Tech, discussing the necessary
background classes in mathematics, science and English.
</P>
<P>
   Sam smiled as she spoke but focused his eyes on the Georgia Tech
alumni mug on the corner of her desk. When she finished, he
grinned.
</P>
<P>
   ``Do they sell those at the Georgia Tech bookstore?'' he asked
pointing to the mug. ``And ... those Georgia Tech golf umbrellas?''
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes,'' she said and smiled. She gently moved the conversation
back to college admissions, but Sam interrupted again.
</P>
<P>
   ``Where's the president's office?'' he asked and began rattling
off the names of past presidents of Georgia Tech _ Marion Luther
Brittain, Joseph Pettit, Isaac Hopkins. He knew them all, their
birthdates, their accomplishments.
</P>
<P>
   It took 25 minutes before Sam mentioned that in high school, he
had been in special education.
</P>
<P>
   ``What types of courses did you take in special education?'' she
inquired.
</P>
<P>
   ``I took everything. Everything. Everything. EVERYTHING!'' Sam
shouted.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes could see that he was getting agitated, so she gently
explained the goals of Georgia Tech and detailed many of the
options that he could take to gain entrance.
</P>
<P>
   But Sam wasn't listening. ``May I see that Georgia Tech football
schedule behind you?'' he interrupted. Minutes later, he was
flipping through a picture book of Georgia Tech's history and
commenting on important figures and dates he knew.
</P>
<P>
   Hayes slipped out of the office and returned with a football
schedule and poster of Tech's football team.
</P>
<P>
   Sam left her office beaming, his hand clasping the rolled-up
poster like it was a college diploma. He passed through campus,
closing open doors, untangling telephone cords, and cleaning the
leaves off of the Georgia Tech sign on North Avenue.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't have to go to Georgia Tech to be a Georgia Tech fan,''
he said as he walked up North Avenue. ``I don't. I don't. I don't
don't don't ...''
</P>
<P>
   The concert
</P>
<P>
   Sam, wearing a suit and tie, lumbered among the elegantly
dressed patrons, cordially greeting them as if he were the host.
</P>
<P>
   ``Good morning. Welcome,'' he said. ``How are you?''
</P>
<P>
   He approached a table of pastries and coffee and began shoveling
free muffins into his mouth. Then he stood at the coffee dispenser
and poured packet after packet of sugar into his coffee cup,
carefully flicking every last granule into his coffee. A long line
of concert goers stood behind him, impatiently. He shouted that
there was no more cream.
</P>
<P>
   ``Are you finished, sir?'' a woman behind him snapped.
</P>
<P>
   ``Well, I am,'' he replied. ``I am. I am. I am. I am. I am ...''
</P>
<P>
   Minutes later, the lights flickered on and off and Sam rushed
into the auditorium.
</P>
<P>
   He sat down and looked up at the musicians tuning their
instruments on stage.
</P>
<P>
   Longtime emcee Miles Hoffman warmly greeted the crowd of several
hundred and urged them to relax. Coffee concerts are casual, more
laid-back than evening performances, he said.
</P>
<P>
   ``But after the concert,'' he joked, ``there will be a test on
the names of all the musicians and their birthstones.''
</P>
<P>
   Everyone laughed but Sam.
</P>
<P>
   He feverishly opened his concert booklet and flipped through the
pages. On page 22, he began running through the list of musicians,
fingering down through their names. First violin. Cecylia Arzewski,
Beth Newdome, Jun-Chung Lin. ...
</P>
<P>
   He turned the page and memorized more.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman continued charming the audience, mixing jokes with a
discussion of the three composers, Stravinsky, Debussy and de
Falla. Sam continued memorizing names.
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman told the audience that each of the musical pieces had
elusive melodies.
</P>
<P>
   An elusive melody. Like Sam's life.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have rhythm with just enough melody to make it
interesting,'' Hoffman said.
</P>
<P>
   As Sam continued memorizing names, Hoffman said, ``They are
fragments of melody, not connected.''
</P>
<P>
   Hoffman left the stage and the conductor raised his arms.
</P>
<P>
   The first notes hit Sam like a tranquilizer.
</P>
<P>
   He closed his eyes, smiled, and bowed his head.
</P>
<P>
   Stravinsky's sumptuous mixture of violins, clarinets and harp
washed over Sam and he began to rock gently as he had as a child.
</P>
<P>
   In seat L-F-22, there was no traffic congestion. No crooked ties
or tangled phone cords. No unattainable goals.
</P>
<P>
   Now, it was just him and the music.
</P>
<P>
   ``Sam's song'' was playing again.
</P>
<P>
   Story Filed By Cox Newspapers
</P>
<P>
   For Use By Clients of the New York Times News Service
</P>
