<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-SUNDAY-MOVIE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
OLIVER STONE STRIVING FOR ACCURACY IN `ANY GIVEN SUNDAY'
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By MIKE FREEMAN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   There is very little that surprises Oliver Stone. He won the
bronze star for valor as an infantryman in Vietnam in the late
1960s. He has been nominated for 11 Academy Awards as a
screenwriter, producer and director of such movies as ``Platoon.''
But in preparing for and directing the new movie ``Any Given
Sunday,'' an accurate look at life in the NFL, even the hardened
Stone could not believe some of the things he encountered.
</P>
<P>
   The list begins with the strong reaction of the NFL, which
refused to cooperate in the making of the film. There was the
lawsuit filed against the studio, Warner Brothers, by a former
Oakland Raiders team physician who said he was not given credit for
his contributions to Stone's script. And there was the more than
competent acting of the current and former NFL players who appear
in the film, and who contributed their knowledge of the sport and
its inner workings.
</P>
<P>
   But at the top of Stone's list of surprises was the speed of the
game. He filmed game scenes that featured actual professional
players and saw the devastating hitting at speeds he thought
impossible for human beings to attain.
</P>
<P>
   In those scenes, Stone used Arena Football League players in
addition to past and current NFL stars like former Giant Lawrence
Taylor, San Francisco wide receiver Terrell Owens, Washington wide
receiver Irving Fryar and Seattle running back Ricky Watters. He
also held an eight-week training camp, the way NFL teams do.
</P>
<P>
   ``Even now, I think about how fast these guys were running and
how hard they were hitting and it still shocks me,'' Stone said in
a telephone interview last week. ``This movie is a tribute to the
players of the NFL, because they sacrifice everything to play this
sport.''
</P>
<P>
   Taylor plays an aging linebacker named Luther Lavay, who makes a
game-saving tackle on fourth-and-short late in the fictional game
(something Taylor, the Hall of Fame linebacker, probably did a
half-dozen times in his 12-year professional career). The running
back in that scene is Watters who, like Taylor, is extremely
competitive.
</P>
<P>
   While practicing the play during rehearsals, Watters dived over
the pile of bodies and collided viciously with Taylor. Then came
more than half a dozen takes, with each hit becoming harder. Taylor
and Watters were feeding off one another. After the last hit, Stone
and others who were present said, Taylor was seriously dazed, lying
on the field, his head throbbing. Filming had to stop for nearly 30
minutes while doctors looked after Taylor.
</P>
<P>
   ``L.T. took far more hits than he needed to,'' Stone said of
Taylor. ``But he is so competitive. The Arena League guys were
saying, `Hey, L.T., I'll knock your head off.' That got L.T.
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Film critics will discuss the movie's quality when it opens on
Wednesday. But the incident with Taylor shows how hard Stone and
the athlete-actors worked to achieve a certain degree of realism.
And they were successful.
</P>
<P>
   Stone's look into the league went far beyond what happens on the
field. He dug into every nook and cranny, spending five years
interviewing dozens of people in every aspect of NFL life. Stone
spoke to team owners like Dallas' Jerry Jones (who helped get Stone
into Texas Stadium to film the climactic game scene).
</P>
<P>
   He talked to coaches like the Jets' Bill Parcells, Carolina's
George Seifert and San Francisco's Steve Mariucci. Their
experiences formed the character played by Al Pacino, that of a
head coach having a difficult time blending the personalities of
players from different generations, dealing with the demands of
management and coming to grips with how the game has affected his
personal life. NFL head coaches maintain that those are three of
the toughest aspects of their jobs.
</P>
<P>
   Other contributions came from quarterback Warren Moon, and
former San Francisco tight end Jamie Williams was a technical
adviser. Past greats like Y.A. Tittle, Dick Butkus and Johnny
Unitas worked closely with Stone, and Butkus and Unitas appear in
the film as coaches.
</P>
<P>
   Stone talked with team physicians, and to the wives and
girlfriends of players. The movie shows how, if two players in a
locker room do not like each other, the players' wives or
girlfriends will dislike each other as well. Such a scenario has
happened several times with recent Giants teams.
</P>
<P>
   The overall result is a depiction of professional football that
almost anyone closely associated with the sport will recognize as
extremely truthful.
</P>
<P>
   ``Oliver was around the San Francisco facility a number of times
when I was coaching there,'' Seifert said. ``The one thing I always
noticed was how much he knew about the inside stuff of the game. He
really did his homework.''
</P>
<P>
   The movie pays particular attention to how the game looks and
sounds. The characters use all the proper terminology, such as
``max protect'' (keeping as many people in to safeguard the
quarterback as possible), and actual NFL audibles that quarterbacks
use to change plays at the line of scrimmage. The foul language,
the cheap shots at the bottoms of piles of bodies, the offensive
and defensive formations, the arguments and near fistfights on the
sideline during the game, as well as the pregame and halftime
speeches delivered by Pacino, are all accurate.
</P>
<P>
   Stone may be criticized for the way black characters use a
racial epithet to refer to each other, and for the way players
sometimes talk about women in derogatory terms. While all players
in the NFL do not speak that way, a significant number do. Again,
it is a realistic touch.
</P>
<P>
   Stone also addresses the tough decisions team doctors face. Such
physicians are always walking a fine ethical line between
protecting a player's health and getting him back on the field.
That part of the movie is based, in part, on the 1994 book by the
former Oakland team physician Robert Huizenga, ``You're Okay, It's
Just a Bruise.'' Huizenga confirmed in an interview that he sued
Warner Brothers last month, claiming he should have received part
credit for the script.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rob is just wrong on that issue,'' Stone claimed, saying he
had to limit his comments because of the pending legal action.
Stone acknowledged that he had had extensive conversations with
Huizenga.
</P>
<P>
   Stone said trying to get the NFL to cooperate was almost as
tough as making the movie. In a series of meetings over a
four-month period, Stone spoke with several high-ranking NFL
officials, hoping to receive permission to use the league's
extensive video library as well as its logos and uniforms. Stone
said the NFL wanted script approval, and that he declined and no
deal was made.
</P>
<P>
   Former NFL president Neil Austrian sent a memo in July 1998 to
each team that explained the league's decision. In his note,
Austrian wrote that the script did not ``accurately or positively
portray our players, club owners or club personnel.''
</P>
<P>
   The league's main reason for not cooperating? According to
Stone, it was that the NFL was ``very worried about the domestic
violence issue. They thought the movie was going to get heavily
into that.''
</P>
<P>
   An NFL official confirmed last week that that was a major
concern for the league. The film, however, does not explore that
issue.
</P>
<P>
   In the end, Stone made a movie that looks and feels like a real
NFL season. ``There is no question he really studied our lives,''
Fryar said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 1940EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
