<SLUG> BC-TEMPORARY-HOME-REAL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LONG-STAY HOTELS CATER TO FAMILIES 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Wash., Fla., N.Y.)  (js) 
 By JAY ROMANO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Any owner of a house or apartment who has suffered through a
lengthy renovation or redecoration project quickly learns that a
house is hardly a home when strangers with saws, hammers and drills
are traipsing about.
</P>
<P>
   And any contractor who has attempted to accomplish such a
project knows all too well that work will proceed more quickly and
more efficiently _ and perhaps even less expensively _ if the
occupants are out of their house rather than out of their minds
with dust-induced stress.
</P>
<P>
   And while it might at first seem that getting an entire family
out of the house and into temporary lodgings during a renovation
project could end up costing more than the project itself, there
are increasing numbers of relatively inexpensive options available
for doing just that.
</P>
<P>
   While most extended-stay hotels, whether in cities or suburbs,
cater primarily to business travelers, many are more than happy to
extend their hospitality to families hoping to escape the noisy
hordes of contractors who have invaded their real home for a
renovation or redecoration project.
</P>
<P>
   ``Basically, what we offer is a home away from home,'' said
Jennifer Coleman, marketing services manager for Manhattan East
Suite Hotels.``We're a very family-oriented company. Kids and dogs
are fine with us.''
</P>
<P>
   Manhattan East. which has 10 all-suite hotels scattered around
Midtown, is one of a growing number of companies offering
extended-stay lodgings that include all the amenities an individual
or family needs to feel at home.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the all-suite hotels in the chain, said Ms. Coleman,
have various-sized suites to accommodate families of most sizes.
The company's 300- to 400-square-foot studio suites, for example,
contain an oversized sleeping room with a dining or sitting area
and kitchen facilities. The two-bedroom suites, on the other hand,
range in size from 700 to 950 square feet and contain a living
room, separate bedrooms and a fully appointed kitchen. In between
are ``junior'' and one-bedroom suites that range from 400 to 650
square feet, including kitchen facilities.
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Coleman explained that while the nightly rates at Manhattan
East hotels range from $164 for a guest room to $725 for the most
expensive two-bedroom suite, most accommodations range from $200 to
$300. Reduced rates are available for stays of more than 30 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``The extended-stay rates are negotiated rates that depend on
the total length of stay,'' she said, adding that her company's
most ``family-friendly'' building was the Surrey Hotel on 76th
Street between Fifth and Madison avenues.
</P>
<P>
   One of the main draws of extended-stay facilities, particularly
for families, is their ability to provide _ quite literally _ soup
to nuts services for their guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, we do offer grocery-shopping services,'' said Gordon
Lambourne, a vice president of Marriott International, the
Washington-based hotel chain that pioneered the extended-stay
concept with its Residence Inn Hotels.
</P>
<P>
   ``The first thing people have to know about our extended-stay
facilities is the concept of the descending rate,'' Lambourne said.
``That means that the longer you stay, the less you pay.''
Generally speaking, he said, rates for the company's Residence Inn
suites in the New York City area start at about $99 a night for the
smaller units.
</P>
<P>
   ``Most of our suites have a sitting area, a separate bedroom,
and a fully equipped kitchen with a stove, microwave, full-sized
refrigerator and all the china, silverware and glassware you
need,'' Lambourne said. ``Some even have working fireplaces.''
</P>
<P>
   And unlike some extended-stay hotels, he said, Marriott does not
have a minimum-stay requirement. ``The average stay is probably
five nights to two weeks,'' Lambourne said.
</P>
<P>
   Another company that has extended-stay lodging is Extended
StayAmerica, based in Fort Lauderdale, Fla. ``For us, seven nights
or more are considered an extended stay,'' said Monique Damiano, a
spokeswoman for the company. ``And at our hotels, there's no need
to negotiate with the hotel manager over your room rate. Guests pay
the same rate as their neighbor in similarly sized rooms or
suites.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. Damiano explained that each of the company's hotel brands
offered different types of room arrangements and services. For
example, she said, Extended StayAmerica's Crossland Economy Studios
are generally 227 square feet in size and furnished with a double
bed, kitchenette, refrigerator-freezer, two-burner stove, a
microwave and all necessary utensils and tableware. Rates for such
rooms range from $159 to $199 a week.
</P>
<P>
   The company's Extended StayAmerica Efficiency Studios hotel
brand, which are about 300 square feet and similarly furnished,
range from $199 to $299 a week.
</P>
<P>
   And the company's StudioPlus Deluxe Studios hotel brand, Ms.
Damiano said, has suites of about 425 square feet, generally with
separate living, sleeping and eating areas and a pull-out sleeper
sofa. The rates for those units, she said, range from $299 to $399
a week.
</P>
<P>
   ``To keep our rates affordable, our hotels don't have
restaurants, bars, meeting spaces or little plastic shoe-shine kits
in the rooms,'' Ms. Damiano said. ``But they do have all the things
you need for a comfortable stay.''
</P>
<P>
   She added that while guests might request daily housekeeping
services, extended-stay guests can generally save money by using
housekeeping services just once a week. In addition, she said, all
of the company's hotels offer on-premises, coin-operated guest
laundry rooms, free local phone calls and a room wired with a
dedicated computer data port.
</P>
<P>
   For those who prefer the ambiance of a real Manhattan apartment
while their own apartment is being torn asunder, there is a company
in Manhattan that rents one- and two-bedroom apartments at rates
that are, in some cases, less than what it would cost to rent a
similarly sized unfurnished Manhattan apartment on the open market.
</P>
<P>
   ``We don't have all the services of a hotel, but when people see
our rates, they're usually willing to make their own beds,'' said
Elizabeth Calogero, a spokeswoman for A Hospitality Company, a
Manhattan-based company that owns about 150 apartments that it
rents out to extended-stay guests.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our flagship property is the Hospitality House,'' Ms. Calogero
said, referring to the 36-unit building the company owns on 49th
Street between Lexington and Third avenues. Apartments in the
building, which start at $99 a night for a small studio, have all
the necessary furniture and furnishings, including a fully-equipped
kitchen.
</P>
<P>
   Apartments in other buildings scattered throughout Manhattan,
she said, range from small studios to large, two-bedroom units, all
similarly furnished. Rates in those buildings range from $99 to
$325 a night or, for stays of 30 days or more, from $1,950 to
$5,750 a month.
</P>
<P>
   ``We obviously prefer longer corporate stays,'' Ms. Calogero
said. ``But our two-bedroom apartments sleep six people
comfortably, so we're family-friendly, too.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
