<SLUG> BC-BKN-LAKERS-NOTES-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
LAKERS NOT CONTENT WITH JUST WINNING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By HOWARD BECK  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   TORONTO _ It could be a sign of growing maturity, a new
self-awareness inspired by coach Phil Jackson or perhaps just a
case of grouchiness, but the Lakers are getting harder to please.
</P>
<P>
   At the halfway point of a four-game road trip that Jackson has
called an early season barometer, the Lakers are 2-0, have a
five-game winning streak and the best record in the league (20-5).
And yet they found any number of ways to censure themselves _ and
occasionally each other _ after turning a 20-point lead into a mere
97-88 win Friday at Minnesota.
</P>
<P>
   And maybe that's a good thing.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think it's the maturity of the team,'' Glen Rice said.
``You realize that it was definitely not one of our better games
and we could have played a lot better. And we learn from that. We
learn from the times when we go out there and lose and also when we
win and it's not particularly so pretty, we learn from that as
well.''
</P>
<P>
   All that learning has translated to 12 wins in 13 games and an
8-3 road record that rates as the second best in the league. And
they actually have a chance to sweep their first significant road
trip of the season, which continues today against the Toronto
Raptors and concludes Monday night against the Boston Celtics.
</P>
<P>
   ``It would be great for us if we can come out of this road trip
undefeated,'' Rice said. ``It really says a lot about this team at
the early stage that would give us something to build on.''
</P>
<P>
   Critique: There was more than enough grousing to go around
Friday.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson criticized Shaquille O'Neal, O'Neal took a swipe at his
teammates and everyone else just offered general discontent with
their inability to sustain the rout.
</P>
<P>
   ``Shaq didn't rebound at all in the second half,'' Jackson said.
``I think he got one rebound.... He had a lackadaisical effort the
second half.''
</P>
<P>
   Countered O'Neal: ``I had more (rebounds) than that. The local
statisticians don't want me to get the league lead in
rebounding.... I had more than one (bleeping) rebound.''
</P>
<P>
   O'Neal was equally unhappy with his teammates taking
``ill-advised shots'' instead of getting him the ball more often,
especially in the fourth quarter, when he took just four shots.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yeah, a lot of dribbling going on,'' O'Neal said, naming no
one in particular. ``When a team's double-teaming (me) like that,
and everybody's getting open shots, you should want to throw it
down to me.''
</P>
<P>
   On that last note, Jackson and O'Neal agreed. ``I was upset that
they didn't find him and get him the ball and we were willing to
just take the available shots,'' Jackson said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
