<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-WOLF-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
GRIZZLIES' WOES MORE THAN A MOLE-HILL
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients)  
 &HT;     By SCOTT WOLF  
 c.1999 Los Angeles Daily News  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ The team's ownership is uncertain, there's
speculation it could relocate, and a revamped roster has produced a
record that is just as bad as a year ago.
</P>
<P>
   So what did the Vancouver Grizzlies do to reassure fans about
the stability of their franchise?
</P>
<P>
   Fire coach Brian Hill, of course.
</P>
<P>
   Hill was fired by general manager Stu Jackson, who many would
like to see leave next, to demonstrate the Grizzlies should be more
than a lottery team this season.
</P>
<P>
   But Vancouver's problems go far deeper than Hill's coaching.
Team owner John E. McCaw Jr. of Seattle announced in September he
was selling the team to Missouri billionaire Bill Laurie.
</P>
<P>
   The NBA has not approved the deal, telling Laurie and Orca Bay
Sports and Entertainment (the Grizzlies' parent company) to rework
the deal so the franchise might stay in Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   That's done little to silence skeptics, who believe Laurie can't
wait to move the team to St. Louis.
</P>
<P>
   It hasn't helped that the Grizzlies have lost several million
dollars the past two years, which was one reason McCaw is believed
to have sold the team.
</P>
<P>
   ``I can't see this business turning a profit under this current
structure,'' former top executive Stephen Bellringer told the
Toronto Globe and Mail this week.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, nothing Jackson does seems to work. He drafted point
guard Mike Bibby with the No. 2 pick, a good but not franchise
player. Of course, no one else really thought Vince Carter would be
the best player available that draft.
</P>
<P>
   Last summer, he passed on Lamar Odom, but so did a lot of other
teams, and took Steve Francis. He then traded Francis to Houston
essentially for Michael Dickerson, Othella Harrington and the
Rockets' No. 1 pick, which looks like a lottery selection.
</P>
<P>
   That would give Vancouver two lottery picks in next year's
draft.
</P>
<P>
   A nice future thought, but it does little to soothe the
frustrations over this season.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think we all agree that this is the most talented team that
we have had and it's the deepest team that we have had,'' Jackson
said. ``I personally have expected better from this unit. I'm not
real happy with the play of our club.''
</P>
<P>
   So Jackson did what any GM does when the pressure builds, by
firing Hill and replacing him with assistant coach Lionel Hollins.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody has to be accountable. I'm talking about the
players, myself, the coaching staff, our general staff,'' Jackson
said. ``We all have to look at what we can do better.''
</P>
<P>
   It's likely Jackson will be the next to go, considering he is in
the final year of his contract.
</P>
<P>
   ``For someone to imply that my strategy or my decisions are
going to be compromised based upon my own personal situation is
insulting and not warranted,'' Jackson said.
</P>
<P>
   Trade talk: About 130 players became eligible to change teams
Wednesday. Under a new NBA rule, players who signed new contracts
during the season couldn't be traded until three months later or
Dec. 15, whichever was later.
</P>
<P>
   That opened possibilities for more deals, and nearly every NBA
team was listening to some type of proposal.
</P>
<P>
   Charlotte was believed to have offered Anthony Mason to the
Lakers, Bucks and Magic, who all politely said no thanks.
</P>
<P>
   The Nuggets, who fear losing Ron Mercer to free agency (after
rejecting his offer to sign a new contract in the summer),
reportedly offered Mercer and Bryant Stith to the 76ers for point
guard Larry Hughes and forward Tyrone Hill.
</P>
<P>
   The Sixers offered the same package to the Sonics for Horace
Grant and Brent Barry, and were quickly rejected.
</P>
<P>
   Unattractive tractor: One player who is clearly on the block is
Milwaukee's Robert Traylor, a first-round draft choice in 1998. Few
teams want the former Michigan star, because he is too small to
play center and unable to play power forward.
</P>
<P>
   Davis gets fingered: Raptors center Antonio Davis was fined
$5,000 for making an obscene gesture to a fan during Toronto's
105-97 win against the Indiana Pacers on Tuesday.
</P>
<P>
   After shooting a free throw in the fourth quarter against his
former team, Davis reacted to a fan sitting near Indiana's bench by
making a hand gesture.
</P>
<P>
   Davis denied any wrongdoing, but the NBA disagreed after
reviewing the videotape.
</P>
<P>
   Family man: Danny Ainge has been frustrated over all the
speculation surrounding his resignation as Phoenix Suns coach.
Ainge said he resigned to spend more time with his family, although
he wasn't exactly thrilled with the way the Suns were playing.
</P>
<P>
   Ainge said former players have called seeking ``the real
reason,'' he quit. Among the stories: He would coach Brigham
Young's basketball team; did not like assistant coach Scott Skiles,
or had a family medical emergency.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've probably talked to 25 guys who are coaches or general
managers or they've been coaches,'' Ainge said. ``They all believe
me. You can't really understand it unless you've been a coach _ and
you have six kids.''
</P>
<P>
   New role: Former Laker Eddie Jones, who was often criticized for
being too unselfish, has decided to become the Charlotte Hornets'
go-to guy.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is what I want _ to be held responsible for whether we
win or lose,'' Jones said. ``If it takes me going and taking (the
ball) out of someone else's hands, to create my own thing or for
someone else, I'll do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Rookie of the Year? Houston Rockets point guard Steve Francis
has been overshadowed by the Clippers' Odom, but he leads all
rookies in scoring (17.4) and assists (6.0). &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
