<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOMB-ARREST-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
2ND MAN SOUGHT FOR QUESTIONING IN BOMB PLOT
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By SAM HOWE VERHOVEK   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   SEATTLE _ American and Canadian officials are searching for a
man who may have been an accomplice to a man who was arrested
Tuesday with powerful bomb-making materials, the authorities said
Saturday as they continued their investigation into the apparent
terrorist plot.
</P>
<P>
   In Montreal, which the authorities say served as a base for the
arrested suspect, Ahmed Ressam, before he traveled to Vancouver
several weeks ago, police officers evacuated a block on Friday
night that included the apartment building where Ressam lived. But
the bomb squad of the Royal Canadian Mounted Police found no
evidence of explosives there, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam, a 32-year-old Algerian native, is being held without
bail here in connection with the Tuesday night incident. He was
arrested after driving off the ferry from Victoria, B.C., to Port
Angeles, Wash. Customs Service authorities found liquid
nitroglycerine, urea powder and timing devices in the man's car
that one government official said Saturday could have made a bomb
capable of causing tremendous damage in a city office building or a
crowd of people.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam, carrying a fake Quebec driver's license, had made a
motel reservation under the fictitious name of Benni A. Noris for
Tuesday night in Seattle and had a reservation to fly the next day
to New York City, with a connecting flight to London.
</P>
<P>
   The authorities said the second man being sought Saturday had
stayed with Ressam for the last three weeks at a motel south of
downtown Vancouver, B.C. That room was also reserved in the Noris
name, the authorities said. They said they knew little about the
second man and were not certain the man was an accomplice, but they
were seeking him for questioning.
</P>
<P>
   One official, speaking on condition of anonymity, said Saturday
that the authorities believed the second man had returned to
Montreal, which Canadian authorities have described as the base of
an ``Algerian cell'' created to finance terrorist organizations
elsewhere. Agence France-Presse, the French news agency, quoted
Canadian officials Saturday as saying that Ressam belongs to the
Islamic Armed Group, a terrorist organization that operates
primarily in North Africa and Europe. The officials told the news
agency that Ressam had recently tried to obtain Canadian
citizenship, but was denied it.
</P>
<P>
   Eleven men, most of Algerian origin, are awaiting trial in
Quebec on theft charges in connection with the financing of
Algerian terrorist groups operating in France and elsewhere, the
Montreal Urban Community Police Service said.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam has a Canadian criminal record for theft under $5,000 and
was being sought on a Canadian immigration arrest warrant for theft
under $5,000, according to court papers filed by federal
prosecutors.
</P>
<P>
   Customs officials in Washington, D.C., announced Friday that, as
a precaution, they were imposing more stringent questioning and
search procedures at border checkpoints around the nation, a move
expected to lengthen crossings for travelers at least through the
new year.
</P>
<P>
   Ressam, a diminutive man with short black hair who said nothing
Friday during an appearance before a federal magistrate but
listened intently as a translator described the proceedings in
Arabic, has not cooperated with authorities.
</P>
<P>
   After Magistrate Judge David E. Wilson ordered on Friday that
the remainder of the nitroglycerine be destroyed as a safety
measure, Ressam's court-appointed lawyers objected that the defense
had not been able to test it, but the lawyers have otherwise made
no public comment on Ressam's behalf.
</P>
<P>
   Intelligence officials said they strongly believed that Ressam
was not acting alone, but they have not publicly tied him to any
other suspect or terrorist organization.
</P>
<P>
   The FBI and the CIA have taken over the investigation from the
U.S. Customs Service.
</P>
<P>
   Raymond Kelly, commissioner of the Customs Service, said
Saturday that his agency was increasing security at remote entry
points like the one where the suspect attempted to enter the United
States.
</P>
<P>
   Kelly said that after the incident he ordered the agency to send
agents from other locations and have them work overtime so more
people passing at these points would be subjected to interrogations
like the one that caught the suspect.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have 301 entry points into the United States, and some of
them are pretty remote,'' Kelly said. ``Port Angeles was one.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
