<SLUG> BC-BKN-HILL-COLUMN-LBPT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A CLIPPERS CHRISTMAS STORY
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY HILL  
 Long Beach Press-Telegram  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ With last Tuesday's Laker calamity promoting a
spirit of giving up, we have decided to offer up that timely
Christmas classic, ``A Clip per Carol.''
</P>
<P>
   Fade in: the hammock of team owner Ebenezer T. Sterling.
Sterling is either sleeping or faking it really well. We hear a
knock on a door we can't even see.
</P>
<P>
   STERLING: I don't need any more magazines. Go away!
</P>
<P>
   VOICE: I'm the Ghost of Clippers past ... let me in.
</P>
<P>
   STERLING: A party? Cool. (Sterling gets up and opens the door we
still can't see.) Hey, you're Clippers announcer Ralph Lawler.
</P>
<P>
   GHOST: Bingo!
</P>
<P>
   STERLING: I'm not payin' over time for this.
</P>
<P>
   GHOST: Oh, I suppose I can exhale now. Anyway, fasten your seat
belt ... I'm taking you on a trip.
</P>
<P>
   STERLING: Whoa, we're up so high, I can almost see Jerry Buss.
Say, spirit, who's that down there.
</P>
<P>
   GHOST: That's Larry Brown, the greatest coach in Clipper
history.
</P>
<P>
   STERLING: Isn't that like being the valedictorian of summer
school? Don't answer. What's Larry doing?
</P>
<P>
   GHOST: He's putting his letter of resignation in a bottle and
preparing to hurl it into the San Gabriel River because you didn't
give him a lifetime contract.
</P>
<P>
   STERLING: (After 30 seconds of laughter) Oh, yeah. Say, spirit,
what's that way over there, one of my apartment buildings?
</P>
<P>
   GHOST: No, that's the Pond in Anaheim. You could've been the
main tenant, remember?
</P>
<P>
   STERLING: Yeah, well look how far it is from Hollywood. After
all that Perrier, my celebrity friends would have to ask the limo
driver to pull over two or three times on the trip down. Say, who's
that man over there?
</P>
<P>
   GHOST: That's Bill Fitch, and he's busy trading Antonio McDyess,
refusing to give Darrell Armstrong guaranteed money to play on our
summer league team, and threatening to throw a tantrum if we draft
a high school kid.
</P>
<P>
   STERLING: What high school kid?
</P>
<P>
   GHOST: Kobe Bryant. Well, we're done here.
</P>
<P>
   (Sterling returns to his hammock. Again, we hear knocking.)
</P>
<P>
   STERLING: It's open. Hey, Ralph, you're back.
</P>
<P>
   GHOST: Yeah, I'm also the Ghost of Christmas Present. We're
working on a budget here.
</P>
<P>
   STERLING: Good. Let's ride. Hey, is that Chris Ford down there?
</P>
<P>
   GHOST: Indeed. He's shaking his head because you refused to let
Elgin Baylor hire some veterans to go with all of the young kids we
have, and because you didn't renew the contract of assistant coach
Jim Brewer.
</P>
<P>
   STERLING: Is that Laker game my fault, too?
</P>
<P>
   GHOST: No, that's on him and the players.
</P>
<P>
   STERLING: Why haven't I fired Chris?
</P>
<P>
   GHOST: You hired him. It was your idea. And because you don't
want to finish the season paying two head coaches.
</P>
<P>
   STERLING: I'm a smart guy, Ralph. Ralph? Hey, you're not Ralph,
you're Bill Walton.
</P>
<P>
   GHOST: Bingo!
</P>
<P>
   STERLING: It just isn't the same when you say it.
</P>
<P>
   GHOST: Sorry. By the way, I'm the Ghost of Christmas Future.
Pull my finger ... just kidding.
</P>
<P>
   STERLING: Oh, Bill. Hey, who's that down there?
</P>
<P>
   GHOST: That's me. I'm sitting on the bench because I'm going to
be your head coach.
</P>
<P>
   STERLING: Interesting. Why the head phones?
</P>
<P>
   GHOST: I'm also your lead broadcaster.
</P>
<P>
   STERLING: Where are Ralph and Mike Smith?
</P>
<P>
   GHOST: Long Beach. They were hired by that new CBA team down
there. Selling out every game.
</P>
<P>
   STERLING: Bah, hamburger. Long Beach is too far from Hollywood.
Say, redhead. Is that Lamar Odom over there?
</P>
<P>
   GHOST: You bet.
</P>
<P>
   STERLING: Look, he's become so good, he's playing with one arm
tied behind his back.
</P>
<P>
   GHOST: That's a sling. And that piece of paper on his jersey is
his price tag.
</P>
<P>
   STERLING: Who are those other guys?
</P>
<P>
   GHOST: Bo Kimble and Randy Woods.
</P>
<P>
   GHOST: Wow, we hire those guys again? I'll bet they'll play for
the minimum! This is a wonderful dream, Bill. Bill? Hey, I think I
see Tiny Tim Hardaway. If we wait a few years, I'll bet we could
sign him for almost nothing.
</P>
<P>
   Strange Ainge
</P>
<P>
   While Danny Ainge insists it was his decision to quit coaching
the Phoenix Suns, league chatterboxes aren't buying it.
</P>
<P>
   The fraternal order of gossiping assistant coaches has endorsed
the notion that Suns boss Jerry Colangelo pulled the plug, then
orchestrated some tidy spin in an agreement with Ainge.
</P>
<P>
   It would go something like this:
</P>
<P>
   Ainge looks like a saint for putting family first and leaving
big-contract money on the table; Colangelo doesn't smell like
George Steinbrenner for firing a coach whose team was 13-7,
including a seven-game winning streak.
</P>
<P>
   For the Suns and new coach Scott Skiles, who began his expected
honeymoon period at 2-0, the move could turn out swell. According
to sources close to the Suns, Ainge didn't exactly promote
excellence through tough and thorough practices. Skiles, an
ex-point guard who once went after teammate Shaquille O'Neal during
a practice in Orlando, is considered tougher than getting a paying
raise from Ebenezer T. Sterling.
</P>
<P>
   Shot-clock violations
</P>
<P>
   The why-are-they-still unemployed? NBA coaches list includes
former Cavalier sharpie Mike Fratello - whose methodical approach
to offense scares owners who prefer selling tickets -- and
ex-Hornets dictator Dave Cowens - whose reputation for player
relations is bad and amplified when he walked out on his team in a
contract dispute before last season. ... Underclass men (and high
school hotshots) always alter the order of an NBA Draft, but many
scouts think Cincinnati power forward Kenyon Martin could be the
first senior selected next June. Martin is only 6-foot-8, but his
eye-popping athleticism, strength and relentless nature should make
him very ef fective. ... Denver point guard Nick Van Exel stirred
things up last week when he said reporters wouldn't swoon over
flashy Jason Williams if the Sacramento playmaker had black skin.
Van Exel is right. ...Clipper free-agent-to-be Maurice Taylor said
he and crony Jalen Rose (a Pacer on his way to free agency) are
hoping to go in a package deal. Their hometown of Detroit is one
target, Orlando is another. But when the tricky nature of cap room
is factored, the odds look long. ... Clipper back- back-backup
center Keith Closs paid tribute to the throwback style of Conseco
Fieldhouse in Indianapolis by wearing canvas Chuck Taylor hi-tops
during last weekend's visit. But when the Pacers began pulling away
and Closs looked ripe to participate in garbage time, he asked
equipment manager Pete Serrano to break out the standard,
post-apocalyptic leather Nikes.
</P>
</TEXT>
