<SLUG> BC-OBIT-SMITH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RODNEY SMITH, 97, DEPUTY CHIEF IN THE ARMY CORPS OF ENGINEERS 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Va.)  (js) 
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   C. Rodney Smith, a retired major general in the Army Corps of
Engineers and later the director of Radio Free Europe, died Nov. 28
at his home in Annandale, Va. He was 97.
</P>
<P>
   Smith spent 31 years in the Army Corps of Engineers, retiring as
a deputy chief of engineers, the No. 2 position in the corps, in
1957; he had been promoted to major general in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   He then worked for three years with International Telephone and
Telegraph Corp. in Paris and Chicago before taking a position as a
vice president of Free Europe Inc. in New York City, the parent
company of Radio Free Europe, in 1960.
</P>
<P>
   Shortly afterward, Smith became the director of Radio Free
Europe in Munich, a post he held for seven years. At the time,
Radio Free Europe was in turmoil in the wake of the Hungarian
uprising in 1956.
</P>
<P>
   Many believed that the radio system, which was then financed by
the CIA, helped incite the revolt against a hard-line Communist
government and led Hungarian freedom-fighters to believe that the
United States would intervene. No such assistance arrived, and the
revolution was quickly crushed by the Soviet Union.
</P>
<P>
   ``Rodney Smith restored morale at Radio Free Europe after the
Soviet crackdown triggered by the 1956 revolt in Hungary and helped
Radio Free Europe build up the democracy movements of the late
1960s,'' said Paul Gobel, a spokesman for the radio service.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Radio Free Europe in 1967, Smith spent a decade as
an arbitrator with the International Court of Arbitration. He also
worked as a consultant to the Board for International Broadcasting.
</P>
<P>
   Clerin Rodney Smith graduated from the U. S. Military Academy at
West Point in 1926. He taught military history and engineering at
West Point from 1936 to 1940. After serving in World War II in
Europe and the Far East, he graduated from the Army Industrial
College.
</P>
<P>
   Smith was awarded the Legion of Merit three times by the United
States and the Cavalier Cross of the Order of Merit by Poland.
</P>
<P>
   His first wife, Ethel, died in 1967. His son Rodney was killed
in the Vietnam war the same year his mother died.
</P>
<P>
   Smith is survived by his wife, Katherine de Dory Smith; a son,
Brig. Gen. Anthony A. Smith of Alexandria, Va., who is retired from
the Army; a sister, Faye Eggert of Casper, Wyo.; six grandchildren,
and five great-grandchildren.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 2026EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
