<SLUG> BC-NY-GORE-SPEECH-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IN HIS OWN WORDS: AL GORE 
</HEADLINE>
   (With NY-GORE-CAMPAIGN) 
(rk) 
 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Al Gore, at a fund-raiser in Brooklyn last week, talking about
vouchers for private school:
</P>
<P>
   ``I understand the feeling that payment of taxes in support of
the public schools and simultaneously paying tuition in private
schools can create the feeling that there is a problem that must be
addressed with changes in public policy. I'm well aware that most
of you here feel that way. I have to tell you that I have not
supported vouchers for private schools and I want to tell you why.
</P>
<P>
   ``Since early in the last century, this has been an issue in the
United States. When Abraham Lincoln ran for the state legislature
in Illinois, it was an issue in his race. The prevailing opinion
after much debate, repeated many times in our history, assumes that
if the national government begins to put taxpayer funding into
religious schools in response to the political divide of this
community or that community, then the line which is crossed is a
line that was originally put in place to protect religious freedom
and to guard against religious intolerance. ``Many came to the
United States generations ago, and in this generation, to seek
religious freedom. The history of the founding of the United States
conveys with it a definition of religious freedom which is
dominated by the concept of freedom from government participation
in religion.
</P>
<P>
   ``The religious faith as practiced by minorities in this
country, whether Catholic some time back, whether Huegonots, as my
mother's family were so many generations ago, or Jews, especially
in parts of our country, such as rural middle Tennessee, where I
represented a congressional district for so long _ minority faiths
have been protected and have been a part of this country to an
exactly equal degree as the faith traditions of the largest
congregation of the largest religious tradition. In order to keep
it that way, I think the separation of church and state is a
principle which must be respected. ''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 2034EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
