<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0256 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 20:36 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2959 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-NY-BUILDING-COLLAPSE-     12-18 0331
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NY-BUILDING-COLLAPSE-NYT </SLUG>
  
 WORKERS HURT AS 3 FLOORS OF HARLEM BUILDING COLLAPSE  (jw) 
 By JAYSON BLAIR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Three floors of a building under renovation in Harlem
collapsed Saturday, seriously injuring at least two workers as they
fell to the basement of the structure, officials said.
</P>
<P>
   The building, at North General Hospital, was scheduled to open
in the spring and provide shelter to Harlem's growing number of
AIDS patients. The third floor of the structure gave way about 11
a.m. as bricklayers were trying to shift scaffolding, officials
said.
</P>
<P>
   The officials said it was unclear what had caused the collapse.
</P>
<P>
   Records of the Department of Buildings showed 14 violations
under investigation on the five-story red brick building, which had
recently been gutted with explosives for renovation.
</P>
<P>
   The collapse follows other construction accidents in Manhattan
in recent months in which people have been injured or killed. Fire
officials said the workers at the Harlem site appeared to have been
installing floor joists, the same items that failed in a fatal
collapse in Brooklyn last month.
</P>
<P>
   Building inspectors were looking at the building and poring over
records Saturday to see whether the type of work being done had
been authorized and whether the remaining structure would have to
be demolished.
</P>
<P>
   One of the injured, who was a bricklayer's assistant, suffered
severe head and leg injuries after the floor fell from under him,
creating a cascading effect that hurled the man onto the first
floor as it buckled.
</P>
<P>
   The man was taken to St. Luke's Medical Center in Harlem after
being removed from the building by the police, officials added.
</P>
<P>
   Chris Cottingham, a police spokesman, said that worker was in
critical condition.
</P>
<P>
   The identities of the injured were not immediately available.
</P>
<P>
   The collapsed building is at 1997 Lexington Ave., near 121st
Street. Renovation began about six months ago.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
