<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 20:51 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2960 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKN-KNICKS-WIZARDS-NY     12-18 0819
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-KNICKS-WIZARDS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
KNICKS DON'T WAKE UP, AND WIZARDS ROLL 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By MIKE WISE   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Without an NBC camera for motivation _ and without a
night game to warm up for _ Latrell Sprewell fought his energy
level all afternoon Saturday , trying anything to conjure up enough
strength for a quiet matinee with the woeful Washington Wizards. He
finally lifted off from the left baseline with 7 minutes 3 seconds
left in the game, a few inches away from jolting the New York
Knicks and Madison Square Garden from their slumber.
</P>
<P>
   Aaron Williams rose, too. The Wizards' spry forward sent
Sprewell's dunk attempt ferociously to the floor, as clear an
illustration as any that some people like to get up early and play
basketball more than others.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm just not a morning person,'' Sprewell said after
Washington's 95-83 victory ended the Knicks' five-game winning
streak. ``I'm not. Me, personally, I like later games. I feel like
I should be resting at that time.''
</P>
<P>
   Williams' block came after the Wizards had built a 12-point
lead, and it encapsulated not only Sprewell's abysmal 3-for-11 day
from the field but also the Knicks' utter inability to get back in
the game. The Garden crowd was hushed for most of the game, but it
voiced its displeasure by unleashing a few boos as the final buzzer
sounded.
</P>
<P>
   The fans came to see a surging team that had played smart and
well the past 10 days, piling up victories with intelligence and
intensity in the final minutes of tight games. Instead, they
watched an uninspired unit go through the motions for most of the
first three quarters before understanding how much trouble it was
in.
</P>
<P>
   ``We lost more or less because of the way we came out, the way
we executed,'' Sprewell said.
</P>
<P>
   Allan Houston, who missed 9 of his 14 shots but still managed to
lead the Knicks with 20 points, said: ``We never got the intensity
or enough energy to get over the hump. A game like this shows that
we aren't there yet.''
</P>
<P>
   Coach Jeff Van Gundy stood there in a charcoal-black suit for
much of the game, the look on his face somewhere between perturbed
and disgusted. As usual, he was playing the part of funeral home
director well. Before the game, he remarked on the MSG network that
he was bothered by a recent newspaper headline that labeled him
``Van Grinch.''
</P>
<P>
   The coach who stole Christmas proceeded to say the Knicks were
fooling themselves if they believed they had truly accomplished
something special by winning five straight games. After all, he
said, knocking off Golden State and a Philadelphia team without
Allen Iverson, holding off Boston at home and then beating depleted
Houston and dismal Dallas on the road was nothing to get excited
about.
</P>
<P>
   As pessimistic as he sounded, his concerns proved prophetic.
</P>
<P>
   Midway through the second quarter, the Knicks (15-10) were on
the verge of taking a seven-point lead. But defensive miscues
helped the Wizards (8-17) erase the deficit and creep to within
45-44 at halftime.
</P>
<P>
   Larry Johnson's departure for the training room in the first
quarter because of a severely upset stomach _ he did not return
until the start of the third quarter _ did not help the Knicks.
Without their defensive anchor, they were exploited inside.
</P>
<P>
   ``I just think you have to work hard to win an NBA game,'' Van
Gundy said. ``You have to work extremely hard. We had a couple of
guys do that, but mostly we were very slow reacting.''
</P>
<P>
   The Knicks usually take all the heat when they lose. Saturday
the Wizards had much to do with their demise. Washington is as good
an example of wasted potential as there is in the NBA, but for an
afternoon it showed its promise. Mitch Richmond (19 points on
9-of-15 shooting) and Rod Strickland (10 points, eight assists)
looked at times like one of the most potent backcourts in the game.
Juwan Howard scored 12 points and distributed six assists. He was a
nice complement at forward, moving the ball when he was
double-teamed and employing a nice little jump hook shot when he
was not.
</P>
<P>
   And Jahidi White may have been the most effective Georgetown
center in the building, scoring 15 points and snatching 10 rebounds
away from a more prominent former Hoya. Patrick Ewing finished with
18 points and eight rebounds. He moved fairly well and hit some
difficult shots, but he was neutralized by White.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a great experience playing that well against Patrick,''
White said. ``He was one of the biggest reasons I went to
Georgetown and I have always admired his game.''
</P>
<P>
   There was little to admire about Ewing's team Saturday. Marcus
Camby played through an eye infection and gave the Knicks energy
Sprewell and others did not. But the Wizards shot 49.3 percent from
the field, better than any team New York has seen this season.
</P>
<P>
   That is apparently what happens when you don't wake up and play
defense.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 2051EST &QL; 
