<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 21:04 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2962 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-FBC-STAGG-BOWL-NYT &LR;      12-18 0585
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBC-STAGG-BOWL-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PACIFIC LUTHERAN AS GOOD ON FIELD AS ON FILM
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   RON DICKER   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
<P>
   SALEM, Va. _ Rowan Coach K.C. Keeler's worry before Saturday's
Division III national championship game was not that Rowan might
experience a letdown after beating its nemesis, Mount Union, in the
semifinals last week. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   It was not over Rowan's sorry history in the final, either.
</P>
<P>
   What alarmed Keeler was film that he watched of Rowan's opponent
in the title game, Pacific Lutheran of Tacoma, Wash., which had
beaten four higher-seeded playoff teams on the road. Rowan had not
faced an offense quite like Lutheran's, full of misdirection plays
and angle blocking.
</P>
<P>
   And on defense the Lutes' four linebackers flew through the
frames, blitzing and cutting off passing lanes.
</P>
<P>
   After Pacific Lutheran's 42-13 victory Saturday in the Amos
Alonzo Stagg Bowl before 4,101 fans at Salem Stadium, Keeler
acknowledged, ``My worst fears were realized.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The logo on the opponents' helmets has changed, but Rowan's
futility in the Stagg Bowl has not. The Profs lost the final for a
record fifth time in seven years. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Asked if the disappointment increased with each defeat,
linebacker John Gavlick replied: ``I've been on that playing field
three times and the feeling is the same. I refuse to hang my
head.'' &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Against a Rowan defense that was eager to commit, Chad Johnson
of Pacific Lutheran completed 18 of 28 passes, mostly on dump-offs
and look-ins, with splashy results: 276 yards and two touchdowns.
</P>
<P>
   Anthony Hicks, a 230-pound transfer from the University of
Washington, battered the Profs with 73 yards and two touchdowns and
finessed them with four receptions for 78 yards, including a
45-yard catch that set up his 1-yard touchdown burst to put
Lutheran ahead for good at the end of the first quarter. ``It's
something we're not used to,'' Gavlick said. ``That's not an
excuse. I take my hats off to them. They executed, we didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   Execution for Rowan on offense was similar, with Mike Warker
throwing two interceptions and absorbing five sacks as the Profs
limped to minus-63 yards rushing. One of the few positives for
Rowan was Taman Bryant, who had a Stagg Bowl-record 13 catches for
141 yards and a touchdown. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   While the same old story prevailed for Rowan (12-2), Pacific
Lutheran (13-1) romped to a happy ending in the kind of feel-good
story that makes small-college football so compelling. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Lutes' 72-year-old coach, Frosty Westering, is a former
Marine drill sergeant who gathers his players to watch the sunset
after practice and has them hold hands as they run off the field
during games. His son, Scott Westering, is the offensive
coordinator, and his grandson is Johnson, the quarterback and a
former ballboy. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Lutes took advantage of their first title shot and Rowan's
game-opening jitters. The Lutes pounced on a fumble by Jason
Frabasile on Rowan's first offensive play and turned it into a
31-yard touchdown strike from Johnson to Todd McDevitt. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Warker, who was 26 of 46 passing for 264 yards, tied the score
at 7-7 on a one-yard sneak late in the first quarter before Pacific
Lutheran reeled off 28 unanswered points. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   ``We love the game so much that the scoreboard takes care of
itself,'' Frosty Westering said. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   The Profs, however, faced an eight-hour bus ride home to
Glassboro, N.J., to contemplate their latest loss. It was a road
they have taken many times before.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
