r a BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR &LR;      12-18 0685
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MONTINI-COL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
YES, IN LOO OF FUN, STUFF HAPPENS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By E.J. MONTINI  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It was a lovely weekday morning and nothing seemed better to
Shari Cohen than a brisk hike through the city's North Mountain
Preserve. For the past several years, Cohen has used the trail at
Shaw Butte as a way to fill her lungs and clear her mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a beautiful spot,'' she says. ``It's not at all the type
of place where you expect your worst nightmare to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   In life and Wes Craven movies, such a statement is referred to
as ``famous last words.''
</P>
<P>
   Shari's bad dream began shortly after she arrived at the
mountain preserve _ when nature called.
</P>
<P>
   ``Next to the parking lot there was one portable toilet,'' she
says. ``That's it. One. It wasn't like I had a lot of choice, you
know, so I went in. I don't mean to gross you out, but . . .'' She
did, mostly because there's no genteel way to describe a lone
outhouse frequented by a procession of fiber-conscious hikers.
</P>
<P>
   Upon entering the loo, Shari set about performing a
contortionist act familiar to anyone who's been to the circus or a
Michael Jackson concert.
</P>
<P>
   The idea is to achieve your desired goal without having any part
of the structure come into contact with any part of your body,
including, if possible, the soles of your feet. &QL; 
WOULD YOU BELIEVE IT?
</P>
<P>
   During one particularly taxing arabesque, or perhaps it was in
mid-pirouette, Shari felt the keys to her house and car slip from
her pocket and fall into the EEEEEEEUUUUUUUUUU.
</P>
<P>
   For the past 10 years, Shari Cohen has worked as a flight
attendant. She's a mature woman with a husband and a small child.
She's been trained to deal with airplane emergencies ranging from
heart attacks to terrorist assaults.
</P>
<P>
   She calmly assessed the situation inside the outhouse,
contemplated her options, determined the most logical course of
action, then let out a Blair Witch-like scream featuring the short
unprintable word that most succinctly described her predicament,
given where the keys landed.
</P>
<P>
   ``I couldn't believe it,'' she says. ``You think, `This can't be
happening to me.' Here are your keys in this . . . stuff, and you
just feel so stupid.''
</P>
<P>
   Needing assistance, Shari went outside and explained her
situation to newly arriving hikers. They behaved the way any
caring, compassionate person would when confronted by a frantic
woman standing next to a public toilet.
</P>
<P>
   They slowly backed away until reaching their cars, then sped
off.
</P>
<P>
   No one had a portable phone (or would admit having one.) No one
had a pair of rubber gloves, or a coat hanger.
</P>
<P>
   ``One guy did have a Baggie,'' she says, ``but that doesn't
cover much of your hand and when I looked at it closely there were
a few holes in it.'' &QL; 
BEEN THERE, DONE THAT
</P>
<P>
   Just then, a couple in their late 50s or early 60s came along.
Shari outlined her quandary for them and the man smiled and told
her not to fret.
</P>
<P>
   ``He took the plastic bag and put it on his hand,'' she says.
``Then he went into the john and, in a minute, came out with my
keys. He said he was an old farmer who had stuck his hands in
(expletive) many times before.''
</P>
<P>
   With that, the man and his wife set off on their hike.
</P>
<P>
   ``I asked them if I could buy them lunch,'' Shari says. ``I
asked if I could bake them cookies. I asked for their names and
addresses so I could send them a thank-you note. But they didn't
want anything. They said they simply were helping a stranger. Can
you believe that? I don't know many people willing to do something
like that. Do you?''
</P>
<P>
   Actually, I've been told many times that, professionally, I
stick my hand in such places each and every day. I've also been
told that reading what I produce is, for some, like reaching into
such a place. But that is only an opinion.
</P>
<P>
   What Shari Cohen's experience provides is documentation of two
far greater truths.
</P>
<P>
   First, it's correct what the bumper sticker (more or less) says:
Stuff happens. Second, it's also true that sometimes, in response:
Good stuff happens. &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 2104EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0260 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 21:05 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2964 &Cx1f; taf-z
u a BC-OBIT-LADD-NYT &LR;      12-18 0474
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OBIT-LADD-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
EVERETT LADD JR., 62, EXPERT IN POLLING AT THE ROPER CENTER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Conn.)  (js) 
 By NICK RAVO   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   Everett Carll Ladd Jr., a widely published polling expert who
was executive director of the Roper Center for Public Opinion
Research at the University of Connecticut, died on Dec. 8 at a
hospital in Willimantic, Conn. He was 62.
</P>
<P>
   He died of heart failure, said Karen A. Grava, a spokeswoman for
the university.
</P>
<P>
   Ladd, who lived in Storrs, Conn., was a longtime professor of
political science at the university. The Roper Center is one of the
world's largest archives of polling data, with records on more than
14,000 national and foreign surveys.
</P>
<P>
   Under Ladd's leadership, the Roper Center, which was founded in
1946, started a series of publications, including Public
Perspective and America at the Polls.
</P>
<P>
   Burns Roper, son of the founder of the Roper Center, Elmo Roper,
said the recognition the polling center had received in the last 20
years ``is due almost entirely to Everett and the staff he
assembled.''
</P>
<P>
   Ladd was also the director of the Institute for Social Inquiry,
a polling group that is affiliated with the Roper Center and is
part of the university.
</P>
<P>
   In recent years, Ladd became well known as a critic of some
trends in polling. He said polls often concentrated too much on the
horse race aspect of elections. In 1996, he said that other
polltakers had overstated President Clinton's strength in the
presidential election and unfairly labeled the Republican
candidate, Bob Dole, as destined to lose.
</P>
<P>
   Ladd was born on Sept. 24, 1937, in Saco, Maine. He graduated
from Bates College and earned a Ph.D. from Cornell University. He
began teaching at the University of Connecticut in 1964 and retired
a few months ago.
</P>
<P>
   He also taught at the American Enterprise Institute for Public
Policy Research in Washington and held fellowships from the Ford,
Guggenheim and Rockefeller foundations, as well as the Center for
International Studies at Harvard, the Hoover Institution at
Stanford and the Center for Advanced Study in the Behavioral
Sciences in Palo Alto, Calif.
</P>
<P>
   Ladd wrote 20 books, including ``The American Polity,'' a
textbook now in its sixth edition. He was also a frequent
contributor to general interest newspapers and magazines. From 1987
through 1995, he was a columnist for The Christian Science Monitor.
He spent 10 years as senior editor of Public Opinion magazine and
six years as opinion-sampling editor at The American Enterprise
magazine.
</P>
<P>
   Ladd is survived by his wife, Cynthia; two sons, Everett Carll
Ladd III of Hebron, Conn., and Benjamin Ladd of Savannah, Ga.; two
daughters, Corina Ladd of Willimantic and Melissa Teed of Midland,
Mich.; a sister, Mary Tucker of Biddeford, Me., and five
grandchildren.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 2105EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
</DOC>
<DOC>
<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0261 </DOCNO>
