u s BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-LENDZIO     12-18 1785
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-GLF-GOLFNOTES-LENDZION-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DREAM HELPS LENDZION COPE WITH HIS GRIEF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JIM McCABE  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   His enthusiasm melted away when he heard the news. Playing golf,
said Bob Lendzion, suddenly wasn't even in the picture, not with
the death of his sister, Merrill.
</P>
<P>
   ``It was a shock. She had a stroke and just never recovered,''
said Lendzion, who was in California preparing for the first stage
of Senior PGA Tour qualifying when he got the call from his mother
in Las Vegas.
</P>
<P>
   ``She (Merrill) lived next door to my mother and helped take
care of her,'' said Lendzion, ``so it was hard.''
</P>
<P>
   Lendzion's mother talked him out of withdrawing, and as the
events unfolded, he is thankful she did. In a few weeks, Lendzion
will realize a dream when he tees it up as a full-fledged member of
the Senior PGA Tour and he doesn't deny that visions of another New
England club pro _ Dana Quigley _ sometimes cross his mind.
</P>
<P>
   ``I hope to use (Quigley) as a front-runner,'' said Lendzion of
his former New England colleague, who has gone over $1 million in
earnings in each of the last two seasons. ``He has improved quite a
bit since I played against him. I don't think I'm at his level and
I've never had this tough a competition, but I think I'm good
enough to compete.''
</P>
<P>
   That he has the opportunity is still somewhat of a surprise, for
at the final stage of qualifying in Arizona Lendzion was a few
shots out of the eighth (and final) spot entering the final round.
Lendzion figured he had to put up a red number, but as birdie
chance after birdie chance slipped away, thoughts of returning to
the European Senior Tour loomed.
</P>
<P>
   At his 72d hole, Lendzion drained a 15-footer for par,
completing his 1-over 73_289. ``Good for 16th, I thought,'' said
Lendzion, ``but the conditions were so hard that day _ cold, windy
_ that the scores weren't very good.''
</P>
<P>
   The 73 looked like a 63 as contenders stumbled in with 76s and
77s. Lendzion vaulted into a tie for eighth, earning a coveted card
to walk the same fairways with Hale Irwin, Tom Watson, Tom Kite,
and the stars of the senior circuit.
</P>
<P>
   Not a bad little trip for the guy who laughingly calls himself
``a fair-weather Vermonter.'' That's because in the 24 years he
spent in the Green Mountain state (12 at Stratton, 12 at Quechee),
Lendzion was never there in the winter.
</P>
<P>
   ``I fell in love with Vermont,'' said the California native,
``but I loved to travel and play golf, too.''
</P>
<P>
   The winter trips were to South America and South Africa, to Asia
and Australia, then back to Vermont for summer. He was New England
PGA Player of the Year in 1992 and also won the national club pro
championship.
</P>
<P>
   After leaving Quechee a few years ago, Lendzion settled into a
job in New York and kept his game polished, determined to give it
another shot once he turned 50. His two years with the European
seniors produced a victory in Turkey, but at Senior PGA Tour
qualifying in 1998, he wilted.
</P>
<P>
   ``I didn't have the confidence,'' said Lendzion. ``I was a
little bit intimidated when I got there and saw Jim Thorpe, Gary
McCord, Bruce Fleisher, Ed Dougherty _ guys who had played in these
things all their life. I was only messing around with it.''
</P>
<P>
   He came up short in '98, but wasn't discouraged. Not as long as
he has a travel bag for his clubs.
</P>
<P>
   ``A long time ago I bought a blank world map,'' said Lendzion,
52, ``and I marked in red all the spots I had been to. It was a lot
of fun. There's a lot of red _ but there's still a lot of white.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll resume that coloring project starting Feb. 4 at the Royal
Caribbean Classic in Key Biscayne, Fla., the first of many weekends
he has booked for 2000. Computer glitches don't concern him, not
when he is faced with such competition.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's a bit scary to think about, to tell the truth,'' said
Lendzion. ``It takes about $600,000 to (stay in the top 31 and)
keep your card. That's wild for me to think about. Heck, $60,000 is
a good year.''
</P>
<P>
   Continental divide
</P>
<P>
   He authored a rather strange stat in 1999 _ finishing 78th on
money lists in both the United States and Europe _ but for good
measure, Scott Dunlap added success on another continent when he
won last weekend's Argentine Open in Buenos Aires. The 36-year-old
held off a noteworthy leaderboard _ Ian Woosnam, Carlos Franco,
Craig Stadler, and native son Eduardo Romero. Dunlap earned
$533,027 on the US PGA Tour, his season proof positive that you
don't have to win, you just have to be close a few times to earn
some hefty cash. His only Top 10 finishes _ third at Doral, 10th at
British Open, seventh at Canadian Open _ accounted for more than
half ($273,418) his season earnings . . . How to celebrate Tiger
Woods's 24th birthday? What about 24 hours of his golfing
highlights? That's The Golf Channel's present to enthusiasts,
starting Dec. 30 at 6 a.m. . . . When Jack Nicklaus teamed with Tom
Watson to win last weekend's Senior PGA Tour title in the Diners
Club matches, he earned a check for $100,000. Doesn't sound that
impressive given the financial climate in the pro golf world, but
consider this morsel: When he won the 1986 Masters, Nicklaus
received the largest check of his impeccable PGA Tour career _
$144,000 . . . The three-win ``silly season'' cash flow for Fred
Couples ($100,000 at the Diners Club matches with Mark
Calcavecchia, $635,000 at the Skins Game, $175,000 at the Shark
Shootout with David Duval) borders on the obscene, considering that
the total ($910,000) for seven days of golf in less than a month
was more than he made ($769,192) during the season. ``I keep
walking up the fairway in these events and wonder why I can't play
like this during the regular season.'' What regular season? The
tournament or two he squeezes in between vacations? Remember, he
played in two events after July 1, just 16 in all. Wonderful
player, but it's very hard to accept the fact that he skipped the
British Open yet cashed in on all these made-for-TV bonanzas . . .
Then again, some guys can't step into luck even in these
low-pressure offseason tournaments. Bobby Wadkins, many times a
bridesmaid, never a winner in his 25-year tour career, lost in a
playoff to Robin Freeman at the Puerto Rico Challenge . . . Good
financial news is usually reserved for the men, but the women got a
double dose of it recently. The Evian Masters in Switzerland will
be part of the LPGA Tour schedule in 2000 and its purse of $1.8
million makes it the richest stop. Next, officials at the Shoprite
LPGA Classic in New Jersey increased the purse to $1.1 million . .
. Englishman David Carroll's dream of qualifying for the European
Senior Tour came to a crashing halt when he opened with an 86 at
Gloria GC in Turkey. ``I found too many trees,'' said Carroll, who
faced long odds since he is (a) 60 years old, and (b) blind in his
right eye . . . Let the kids have Pokemon, golfers will settle for
books that capture the game's rich history. Two wonderful additions
are selling very well _ ``Pebble Beach Golf Links: The Official
History,'' and ``St. Andrews &AMP; The Open Championship: The Official
History.'' Perfect timing, too, for those fabled courses are
hosting the US and British Opens next summer . . . What are they
feeding these amateurs Down Under? First, 18-year-old Aaron
Baddeley wins the Australian Open, then Brett Rumford, 22, takes
the ANZ Players Championship. Indeed, Rumford drew inspiration from
his fellow amateur in the days between events. ``We went out to
dinner,'' said Rumford, ``and Aaron was waiting for me in the bar,
surrounded by five women. I thought that was really good.'' There
is still plenty of buzz in Australia over Baddeley, and Bruce
Devlin reportedly told Baddeley's father he will lobby on his
behalf for a spot in the Masters, where in the spirit of Bobby
Jones, amateurs are well-liked . . . Baddeley is playing in this
week's Coolum Classic in Australia, but it is a pro-am event and he
is forced to play from forward tees, thus ineligible for the
championship. Still, he attracted the largest gallery . . .
Speaking of the Masters, W.W. ``Hootie'' Johnson, chairman of
Augusta National, recently told a reporter that the club batted
.500 with last year's changes to the famed layout. The 1-inch cut
of ``rough'' was a good decision, he said, but lengthening the
par-4 17th wasn't. ``We really missed it on 17,'' Johnson is quoted
as saying, ``but we've made adjustments.''
</P>
<P>
   Due recognition
</P>
<P>
   As purses keep soaring, more praise should go toward the
backbone of pro tournaments _ the volunteers. Of course, that
doesn't happen, which is too bad. But here's a round of applause
for one volunteer, Pete Ziner of Sudbury, a fixture at the
BankBoston Classic the past eight years. The 76-year-old Ziner,
long retired from the construction business, was named Volunteer of
the Year (Senior PGA Tour division) by the PGA Tour. ``I knew my
name had been submitted,'' said Ziner, ``but I'm quite honored, but
quite surprised, too.'' He should be honored, but not surprised.
You can't find anyone involved in this event at Nashawtuc CC in
Concord who doesn't sing his praises. Ziner was a general volunteer
for years, but in August he came through in the clutch, assuming
the duties of chairperson of the greens reporters just one week
before the event began . . . Mike San Filippo is riding a pretty
good wave these days. The head pro at Nashawtuc recently won the
Resort Suites Club Professional Invitational in Scottsdale, Ariz.
Returning to his winter home in Florida, San Filippo triumphed
three times in the PGA Tournament Series, the second win at the
expense of Mark Brown, the Milton native who is head professional
at Tam O'Shanter GC in Brookville, N.Y. In that event, John Fields
of Belmont CC finished in a tie for sixth . . . Bermuda shorts:
Paul Parajeckas of Woburn CC finished third and Joe Carr first in
the senior division at what used to be called the Belmont
Invitational. At Port Royal GC, Ron Philo Jr. of the CC of Vermont
triumphed in a playoff at the Goodwill Invitational . . . When the
Golf Course Superintendents Association of America holds its 71st
annual international show in February, Stephen Tibbetts of
Segregansett CC in Rehoboth will be on hand to receive recognition
as a chapter winner . . . Melanie Curtin of Weymouth has decided to
take on the challenge of professional golf, playing on the Futures
Tour in 2000. To help her in this quest, Curtin's friends are
planning a fund-raiser Jan. 21 at the Weymouth Elks Club. For
information, call Patty Buck (617-325-0156), Peter Hess
(617-770-2746), or Lisa Kennedy (781-740-8358).
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
