<SLUG> BC-OBIT-BAIDA-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
PETER BAIDA, 49, PRIZE-WINNING WRITER 
</HEADLINE>
  
 (ATTN: Md.)  (lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Peter Baida, a writer who won first prize in the 1999
O. Henry Awards short-story competition, died on Dec. 10 at New
York Hospital in Manhattan. He was 49 and lived in Manhattan.
</P>
<P>
   The causes were liver failure and postsurgical complications,
said his wife, Diane Cole.
</P>
<P>
   Baida won with his tale titled ``A Nurse's Story,'' which his
wife said was based on an account of a nurses' strike that appeared
in The Nation.
</P>
<P>
   The story is also in a new book-length collection, ``Prize
Stories 1999: The O. Henry Awards.'' In the book, the novelist
Sherman Alexie, a judge in the competition, writes of ``A Nurse's
Story'': ``There are no forced epiphanies here, no sermons on the
roofs of churches or hospitals. There are union strikes, tragic
deaths and the small realization that: `A good death. That's what
everybody wants.'''
</P>
<P>
   In a note Baida wrote for the book, he said 22 editors turned
the story down before it was accepted by The Gettysburg Review.
</P>
<P>
   Baida was also the author of a nonfiction book, ``Poor Richard's
Legacy'' (1990), about American business values.
</P>
<P>
   Baida, a native of Baltimore, graduated magna cum laude from
Harvard College and received master's degrees from Boston
University in creative writing and from the University of
Pennsylvania in business administration.
</P>
<P>
   At his death, he was a fund-raising executive at Memorial
Sloan-Kettering Cancer Center.
</P>
<P>
   In addition to his wife, he is survived by a son, Edward, and
his parents, Erwin and Lillian Baida of Baltimore.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
