u s BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-BESTLIST     12-18 1617
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BOX-BOXNOTES-BESTLIST-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
A LIST WORTH FIGHTING FOR 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   As the new millennium closes in, America has become a nation of
lists.
</P>
<P>
   The 10 Greatest This, The 10 Worst That, The 10 Most Memorable
Whatevers. There are more lists being made this month than there
are at the North Pole on Christmas Eve.
</P>
<P>
   The idea of such lists is to spur interest, conversation, debate
and, since most are published in newspapers and magazines,
readership. Knowing that, the Associated Press has released its Top
10 fighters of the century. The list was broken down by weight
division, but it also included the predictable top 10 of all time,
regardless of tonnage.
</P>
<P>
   One could debate many of these selections all day, especially as
one reviews the top 10 rankings in any weight class over the last
100 years. For example, were there really four welterweights better
than Barney Ross? Was Miguel Canto really better than Jimmy Wilde,
who went 132-3-1 and had 101 knockouts as a flyweight back in the
early years of this century?
</P>
<P>
   Many are the hours you could chew up arguing whether Roberto
Duran or Benny Leonard was the greatest lightweight of all time and
long-time boxing trainer Don Turner insisted, ``They better move
Emile Griffith up to third (among the all-time welterweights)
because he'd beat everybody but Robinson, Henry Armstrong, and
maybe Leonard.''
</P>
<P>
   Fight guys, regular guys, and barber shop guys will argue for
days over the list, which would make the AP happy, but for the
moment let's skip the divisional breakdowns and just debate AP's
top 10 fighters of the century.
</P>
<P>
   According to a five-man panel that included veteran trainers
Eddie Futch, Angelo Dundee, Lou Duva, Gil Clancy, and long-time
West Coast matchmaker and promoter Don Chargin, they are:
</P>
<P>
   1. Ray Robinson
</P>
<P>
   2. Muhammad Ali
</P>
<P>
   3. Henry Armstrong
</P>
<P>
   4. Joe Louis
</P>
<P>
   5. Willie Pep
</P>
<P>
   6. Jack Dempsey
</P>
<P>
   7. Roberto Duran
</P>
<P>
   8. Benny Leonard
</P>
<P>
   9. Billy Conn
</P>
<P>
   10. Harry Greb
</P>
<P>
   Solid as that list is, several names are missing in action.
Where's Sugar Ray Leonard? Where's Barney Ross? Where's Jack
Johnson and, if he's on the list, where's Sam Langford? Johnson
refused to fight The Boston Tar Baby after he won the title because
he knew what was coming _ which was a hard day's night.
</P>
<P>
   Where's Tony Canzoneri, who was the youngest featherweight
champion in history and went on to not only win the lightweight and
junior welterweight titles, but also fight well enough to convince
the panel to rate him third among junior welterweights behind Aaron
Pryor and Ross, third among lightweights behind Duran and Leonard,
and fourth among featherweights behind Pep, Sandy Saddler, and
Salvador Sanchez. Who else was in the top four in three weight
classes in the opinion of these experts?
</P>
<P>
   Nobody, that's who, which makes it dificult to believe a guy
could be among the top three or four fighters to box in the last
100 years in three weight classes yet not be considered among the
top 10 in all weight classes.
</P>
<P>
   The one unarguable point is that Sugar Ray Robinson was the
sweetest fighter of all time. That is in the opinion of most anyone
who ever watched him. Robinson was the only fighter to top three
lists _ the all-time fighters' list, the middleweight list, and the
welterweight list. Considering that he never lost to a
welterweight, it's easy to see why he was ahead of both Armstrong
and Leonard at 147 pounds. And considering that he won the
middleweight title five times between 1951 and 1958 it's fair to
say he belongs ahead of Greb and even our local hero, Marvelous
Marvin Hagler, although I'd have paid money to watch Hagler fight
Robinson in their heydays.
</P>
<P>
   So where the debate really begins is in the bottom half of the
all-time top 10 (unless, like Turner, you have a beef with Pep
being fifth because he lost three of four fights to Saddler).
</P>
<P>
   Of Nos. 6-10, the most debatable seem to be Duran and Conn.
Although you could certainly make a case for Duran, what about
Conn?
</P>
<P>
   I know of his great fight with Joe Louis. In fact, I've seen it
on old fight films many times and it was a marvelous show until he
got knocked stiff in the 13th round, but one night is not reason
enough to put him in the top 10.
</P>
<P>
   Perhaps, you might argue, his greatness as a light heavyweight
would carry the day for him, but it didn't even carry the day for
the panel that placed him ninth among all fighters because the same
guys didn't even select him as the best light heavyweight of all
time. That spot went to Archie Moore, who didn't get a title shot
until his 159th fight, 16 years after his pro career began. Moore
finished 194-16-8 with 141 knockouts while Conn finished 63-11-1
with only 14 KOs, so you can see how Moore nosed him out. That
being the case, how did Conn end up in the top 10 all-time if Moore
did not?
</P>
<P>
   How can a guy be the ninth-rated fighter of the last 100 years
among everyone who ever boxed and yet not be rated first in his own
weight class? This baffles the mind. What is more baffling is that
Conn's presence resulted in the exclusion of the following: Rocky
Marciano, Langford, Johnson, Canzoneri, Ross, Wilde, and Sugar Ray
Leonard.
</P>
<P>
   Many will say the mention of Marciano in this corner is a
hometown decision, and maybe so, but only one heavyweight champion
in history has retired undefeated. I don't care who you're fighting
_ if you go 49-0, you could fight better than anybody in your era.
</P>
<P>
   Marciano, whose career ended in 1956, was the dominant
heavyweight of his time, and the panel voted him ahead of Dempsey
on the heavyweight list. Yet, they listed Dempsey on the all-time
top 10 and not Marciano. Apparently there's no consistency in
boxing ratings, even if not issued by the WBC, WBA, or IBF.
</P>
<P>
   While it's true Marciano was a small man by heavyweight
standards, so was Joe Frazier, and go ask Ali what it was like to
fight him. Marciano came with a big heart and the kind of power
that scrambled an opponent's mind with one punch. One-punch power
is the essence of heavyweight boxing. Who had it more than
Marciano?
</P>
<P>
   Langford fought at every level from featherweight to heayweight
and is the greatest fighter never to get a title shot, going
167-38-37 with 117 knockouts and 48 no decisions between 1902 and
1926. Both Johnson and Dempsey refused to fight Langford when they
held the heavyweight title for fear of the consequences, yet he was
ninth on the heavyweight list and not on the pound-for-pound list.
</P>
<P>
   Johnson, of course, was the first black to hold the heavyweight
title and that alone would seem to far exceed any accomplishments
of Conn.
</P>
<P>
   And what of Canzoneri, who won the featherweight title at age 19
and championships in two other weight classes? Or, if you would
quarrel with his selection over Conn, what about Ross, who twice
beat Canzoneri and was rated fifth among all-time welterweights and
third among all-time junior welters?
</P>
<P>
   Wilde, a flyweight, is surely someone most people never hear of
any more but the experts had him second behind Canto and Pancho
Villa, who ended Wilde's career. Yet the same panel gave Wilde two
of the four first-place votes in that weight class with the fifth
abstaining. So a majority of the experts thought he was the best
flyweight of all time yet he doesn't make the top 10 over a guy who
wasn't judged best at 175 pounds?
</P>
<P>
   And now we come to Sugar Ray Leonard. Surely he, like all
fighters, should be punished for lifting Ray Robinson's nickname
because once you saw Robinson fight everyone else was tart at best,
but Leonard still won titles in five weight classes from
welterweight to light heavyweight, dominated his era, and defeated
both Duran and Thomas Hearns when they were at or near their best.
He also beat everyone else of his time at 147, which was his best
weight, and managed to con the judges into giving him a close
victory over Hagler when both were past their prime as
middleweights in his last great moment.
</P>
<P>
   To put Duran ahead of Leonard, who defeated Duran in two of
their three meetings when both were the same age defies logic, even
though you could argue Duran was the greatest lightweight of all
time and Leonard was not the greatest at any of his chosen weights
because the real Sugar Ray, was better.
</P>
<P>
   But how does Conn get in ahead of Leonard on the all-time list?
Or ahead of the others already mentioned?
</P>
<P>
   Who knows, but his presence there makes for a good fight . . .
which is the goal of the fight game and of Top 10 lists.
</P>
<P>
   &QL; 
A taxing date
</P>
<P>
   Difficult though his night was with Winky Wright, IBF junior
middleweight champion Fernando Vargas is still planning on
defending the title against ex-WBA welterweight champion Ike
Quartey on April 15 in Las Vegas. That deal is done and Quartey
will not take an interim fight even though he hasn't fought since
he was beaten by Oscar De La Hoya in March . . . Pity poor Zab
Judah. A purse bid for a fight with IBF junior welterweight
champion Terron Millett was scheduled for Dec. 8 but had to be
postponed 90 days when it was learned Millett had a broken hand.
Judah does hold the infamous ``interim'' junior welterweight title
(I thought all titles were interim unless your name is Marciano,
who's still waiting for someone to beat him), and is free to defend
it, which he is set to do in February . . . Dan Goossen and America
Presents have signed IBF No. 1 heavyweight David Tua away from Main
Events, marking another defection from the newly revamped company
started by Dan Duva. Word is Tua received a $1 million signing
bonus, although Goossen denied it.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 2110EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
