u s BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-IAFRATE-     12-18 2438
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-NHLNOTES-IAFRATE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
IAFRATE PAINED BY THOUGHTS OF CAREER END 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By KEVIN PAUL DUPONT  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   He's 33 years old, with crusty, creaky knees that have required
nine operations, and he's less than a year removed from his second
back surgery, but he believes _ even if only whimsically _ that he
could play again in the NHL.
</P>
<P>
   ``I'm not saying this because I think I'm better than anyone
else,'' said one-time Bruins defenseman Al Iafrate, reached last
week at his home in Livonia, Mich. ``But I know that pretty soon I
could go out there and play one game as good or better than most
defensemen who are playing today. Part of the reason I say that is,
there's just a lot of young defensemen out there who don't know the
game.
</P>
<P>
   ``But, you know, it's the NHL, and you don't go out there for
one game. It's one game, five games, 10 games . . . sure, you can
go out there and be right back in it, but how long's it going to be
before everything falls apart? The question wouldn't be what I
could do. The question would be, how long could I do it for?''
</P>
<P>
   Once one of the most talented, fearsome, hardest-shooting
blueliners in the NHL, the 6-foot-3-inch Iafrate today finds his
passion for the game in the challenges and triumphs his son Max, 5,
and daughter Meg, 9, encounter on the ice. He works on
rehabilitating his back, dabbles in the stock market, and otherwise
lives out life in hockey suburbia, shuttling his kids from one rink
to another.
</P>
<P>
   ``Max, he's a rocket, a big kid, sort of a Peter Bondra type,''
said the proud Planet, whose upper-body tattoos and avant-garde,
off-the-cuff remarks earned him his out-there-somewhere reputation.
``And Meg, she's like me, back when I was in my prime, like 1989 to
1994, when I was making the All-Star team all the time _ she can
stride, man, she has that leg strength.''
</P>
<P>
   Iafrate's time in Boston was brief. Picked up from Washington in
a swap for Joe Juneau at the March '94 trading deadline, he still
had ample traces of the strength, talent, and raw ferocity that he
displayed in Toronto and Washington spanning some 10 seasons. But
his knees were buckling even before he hit the Hub. His last
hurrah, really, came only weeks later when he led the Bruins to a
Game 7 victory over the Canadiens in the opening round of the '94
playoffs. He was the bouncer, the Garden his saloon, the Habs his
prey. Until last spring's victory over the Hurricanes, that stood
as the last postseason series won by the Bruins.
</P>
<P>
   ``I loved it in Boston,'' recalled Iafrate, who never played
again for the Bruins after that '94 playoff season, his knee woes
sidelining him for two full seasons before he was dealt to San
Jose. ``What a bummer, the way it turned out. It seemed great when
I got there, and then it got ugly. But, hey, that's the past.''
</P>
<P>
   Now he's facing retirement, although that specific word won't
come from his lips, and he doesn't otherwise talk about post-career
planning. Regular season and playoffs included, he has 870 games
under his name, 498 points.
</P>
<P>
   ``That's a pretty long time, I guess,'' he said. ``When you're
young and you're fast and strong, you think you can play forever,
especially when you're big. But big guys, in contact sports like
hockey and football, over time you're carrying 40 extra pounds
every stride, every game, and things break down over time. I loved
to play. I felt like I was free, you know? To be healthy, to have
the genetics to be fast, to have the hard shot and all that stuff .
. . when I was 27, pfff, I thought, `I'll play 15 years, easy.'
Then all of a sudden it's my knee, my shoulder, my back. Heck, when
I hit 29, it was like someone had a voodoo doll of me, or
something.''
</P>
<P>
   Prior to last season, Iafrate signed a deal with the Hurricanes
that could have paid, with all incentives met, up to $3 million.
But his back kept him from playing and, last April, he needed a
second surgery to clean up a bulging disk.
</P>
<P>
   ``Let me tell you, I'd take 10 more knee operations before I had
one more back operation _ they're tough,'' he said. ``The only
thing that's good about a back operation is that you get instant
relief. My leg was numb, I couldn't control my foot, but they make
that cut and, bang, you're OK.''
</P>
<P>
   He'll occasionally make the 40-minute drive to the Joe, home of
the Red Wings, to watch an NHL game. He was there recently to see
the 'Canes. If the day ever came that he felt healthy enough, he'd
call up Pete Karmanos, owner of the 'Canes and Iafrate's friend
from amateur hockey days, and ask for one more shot.
</P>
<P>
   ``I miss it a lot,'' said the Planet. ``But I know I did
everything that I possibly could do to get back and play. I wanted
to play. In fact, I probably played more games than I should have,
given my back and knee operations. But I guess it's always in you.
You always think you can still play.
</P>
<P>
   ``What's next? I don't know. I haven't thought of it, maybe
because I haven't come to terms with letting go yet. Maybe I'm
still wandering aimlessly in my head, thinking that I might play
again.''
</P>
<P>
   Neilson rates well
</P>
<P>
   Flyers coach Roger Neilson, recently diagnosed with cancer in
his bone marrow, was expected to begin chemotherapy Wednesday, but
it was delayed until Monday while more tests were taken. Neilson,
65, planned to stay on the job, receiving treatments as an
outpatient, but he will be sidelined for some six weeks when he
undergoes a marrow transplant in late February. Meanwhile, he
continues to ride his mountain bike to Flyers' practice in
Voorhees, N.J., each day and applies large doses of humor to his
medical odyssey at hand. To wit: ``Clarkie (Flyer general manager
Bob Clarke) said I have a different tie every night,'' Neilson was
quoted in the Associated Press. ``I should get a different wig
every night. I don't know if I could go for that or not. You've got
to see what you look like. I may look really good without hair.''
Just one more example of how hockey guys view injury and illness
far more as a nuisance than a hinderance. Look for ex-Sabre wing
Craig Ramsey, now in his second season as a Flyer assistant coach,
to take over the bench in Neilson's absence, projected to be some
15 games . . . Prior to his signing with Dallas on Wednesday,
rumors that same day had the Bruins picking up 33-year-old Kirk
Muller, the former No. 2 draft pick (after Mario Lemieux in '84),
who last year made $2 million with the Florida Panthers. Muller
might help win a few faceoffs, and that's always helpful, but
adding more old guys is not the answer here in the Hub. The idea is
supposed to be to move ahead with a new, energized product with
upside, not to be running a vintage car show on ice . . . The Dec.
24 Hockey News includes an entertaining, two-page spread
highlighting the game's most colorful personalities. Included in
the top 10, three ex-Bruins: Eddie Shack (No. 1), Eddie Shore (No.
3), and Don Cherry (No. 7). Shack, who wore the Black and Gold for
120 games (1967-69), actually developed his lovable personality in
his years with the Leafs prior to joining Boston. Now retired at
age 62, after years of selling Christmas trees and running his own
golf course, Shack eschews suggestions that he had the tools and
talent to be a high-profile NHLer. Shack to Hockey News writer Eric
Duhatschek: ``There's no use even thinking like that, because
there's nothing I want out of life that I don't have.'' . . . A
Gino Odjick (Islanders) crosscheck left Doug Weight with cracked
ribs last week, leaving the Oilers without a sizable chunk of their
offense for the forseeable future. Once again, what point are these
guys trying to make by maiming one another? The sport has enough
inherent danger that they don't have to go out there intending to
injure . . . Montreal forward Brian Savage, recovering from three
broken vertabrae, is expected to make a full recovery, but word
around the Habs is that he won't skate again this season . . . If
the infighting among the thirtysomething Oiler owners doesn't
abate, no one will be surprised if ex-Bruin Glen Sather, the Oilers
boss who structured the one-time dynasty around Wayne Gretzky in
the '80s, just up and walks. The 56-year-old Slats would get his
pick of available president/GM posts . . . How many shorthanded
goals a season are lost, not even attempted, by clubs that simply
fire the puck down the other end of the ice when killing a penalty?
Not only has the trap mentality muted the game's creativity at
5-on-5, it has stopped clubs from even thinking attack when
opportunities present themselves even, yes, when shorthanded. Be
safe. Be boring . . . The Bruins used a sixth-round pick, No. 179
overall, this past June to select goalie Don Choukalos. ``An
absolute steal,'' raves his GM in junior hockey, Brent Parker of
the Regina Pats. ``He's that typical big (6-3) butterfly goalie in
the style of a Patrick Roy _ not that I want to put that kind of
pressure on the kid, even to think of making that kind of
comparison. We're the second-youngest team in the (Western Hockey
League) right now, part of the reason his goals against average is
a little higher (3.50) than you might like. But he's made 27 starts
for us so far, and I've got no doubt he'll be a dominant goalie in
this league next year.'' . . . Belmont Hill's Paul Mara returned to
the Bolts' lineup last week after missing a month-plus with a
broken jaw . . . The Blues picked up free agent Bob Bassen for some
checking grit, knocking ex-Leaf Derek King out of work. The Blues
lost some of their bite when pinball Tyler Nash went to the
sideline with a concussion . . . As of Wednesday night, the
Penguins were 4-0 in the wake of Herb Brooks replacing Kevin
Constantine. Brooks has the Penguins playing the best defensive
game of all _ maintaining possession of the puck, exactly what he
was preaching when he entered the league with the Rangers following
his '80 Olympic gold medal.
</P>
<P>
   Flying start for Murphy
</P>
<P>
   He hasn't shown a trace of scoring touch yet, but night after
night, 32-year-old Joe Murphy is the Bruins' most energized skater.
I'm just not sure if that's the good news or the bad news . . . The
Canucks, paying Mark Messier $6 million this season, can keep him
for the same price next season or cut him free with a $2 million
buyout. Given how the market for older guys (he'll be 39 on Jan.
18) has collapsed the last six months, Messier might not command $1
million as a free agent. Perhaps next summer's most interesting
salary case: What will unrestricted free agent Brendan Shanahan
bring on the open market? He's at $4 million this season with the
Red Wings. Prior to last summer, he could figure on bumping up to
about $7 million or $8 million. But with the start of a new salary
structure finally taking place _ everywhere but on Broadway _ the
then 31-year-old Shanahan could be faced with a pay cut . . . OK,
it's not exactly novel, but how about plopping Joel Prpic in the
middle of a second power-play unit, just to see if he can use that
6-7 frame of his to bang in a couple? . . . Hard day in hockey last
week when Charles Schulz, not wanting to work with a daily deadline
anymore, announced that he'll pen his last Peanuts cartoon just
after the New Year. The game's always had a friend in Schulz, who
routinely sent Snoopy over the boards for a shift on the frozen
birdbath. Personally, I hope his last panel has Lucy once and for
all keeping the football in place and Charlie Brown kicking one to
infinity and beyond _ and then falling flat on his back . . . The
Blackhawks slapped a 5-2 loss on the Sharks in San Jose Tuesday
night with help from rookie center/forward Kyle Calder. The No. 130
pick in the '97 draft stepped onto the No. 1 line with Alexei
Zhamnov and Tony Amonte and drove in his first career goal. Hmm. A
rookie named Calder. There's got to be some competitive edge in
that . . . Two guys who were listed as healthy scratches last week
who have some interesting upside: Geoff Sanderson (Buffalo) and
Blair Atcheynum (Chicago). In his Whale days, Sanderson had the
shot and speed to make one believe he could be a 40-goal guy for 10
or 12 years (last time was 1993-94). Atcheynum has enough size
(6-2, 210 pounds) to make him interesting for a third or fourth
line . . . Rumors persist that Vancouver is trying to pry netminder
Felix Potvin from the Isles. If it happens, Wrentham's Garth Snow
likely would be Uniondale-bound in the exchange . . . What a night
in the pipes for Calgary's Fred Brathwaite, Calgary's diminutive
backstop, who turned back 49 St. Louis shots Tuesday in a 1-1 tie.
Brathwaite (cheapest No. 1 goalie in the NHL at $400,000) turned
back 10 shots each from Al MacInnis and Chris Pronger, while his
fellow Flamers could muster only 17 shots at the other end . . .
San Jose's Owen Nolan, chosen No. 1 overall by Quebec in 1990, was
named NHL Player of the Week (four goals and two assists in three
games). A sure-shot, can't-miss, got-all-the-tools prospect coming
out of juniors, Nolan now has been named player of the week exactly
twice (previously, April '95). Need more proof that the 18-year-old
amateur draft is like spotting a poet laureat at a junior high
spelling bee? . . . Ex-Bruin first-round pick Kevyn Adams, who
never signed with Boston, is getting yet another shot with the
Maple Leafs . . . Prior to Wednesday night's six-goal explosion in
the first period, en route to an 8-3 trouncing of the Kings, the
Rangers were a mind-numbing 9 for 112 on the power play. That's an
8.03 percent success ratio. It doesn't get much worse than that,
$60 million payroll or no $60 million payroll . . . They're piling
on north of the border. On the heels of Ottawa owner Rod Bryden
threatening to sell his Senators if the Canadian goernment doesn't
throw him millions in tax relief, the Canucks last week reported a
$17 million loss last season, prompting club chairman Stanley
McCammon to say, ``It is simply not reasonable to expect any owner
of any business to continue in such an adverse situation.''
Vancouver's problems in McCammon's view: rocketing salaries, a weak
Canadian buck, and an unattractive tax base. For two years, the
Canucks have lost close to $40 million (Canadian). Look out over
the holidays. If the Canadian government can hoodwink the public
into underwriting these clubs with lottery dough or big tax breaks,
it likely will come while vox populi has its attention fixed on
peace, goodwill, and the wonders and worries of Y2K _ not unlike
slipping a guy out of the penalty box for a backdoor breakaway.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
