<SLUG> BC-FBN-HOLLEY-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ATHLETES IN NEED OF CHARACTER CHECK 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By MICHAEL HOLLEY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Some words experience a full-fledged identity crisis when they
find themselves in the pro sports world. ``Character'' is like
that. If you say a colonial home has character, you don't have to
explain yourself. If you say a pro team has character, you're
virtually begging for a three-day panel discussion.
</P>
<P>
   A team with character. Does such a thing exist? If it does, what
does it mean? How far will an owner go to ensure that it remains?
And do fans truly care if their team has an athlete who goes home
and makes other peoples' lives miserable (and sometimes ends those
lives)?
</P>
<P>
   I used to think character was one of the corniest words in
sports, reserved for exaggerated ``Rocky'' and ``Rudy'' storylines.
But after watching the last few months in the NFL, from Steve
Muhammad to Rae Carruth, I think it would be nearly impossible for
anyone to be dismissive of an athlete's personal character, no
matter how interpretive the definition may be.
</P>
<P>
   That is, unless you live in Indianapolis and root for the Colts.
There will be a lot of fuzzy stories about the revived Colts, who
could clinch the AFC East title Sunday. But I don't have an ounce
of respect for the organization nor the people who run it. Not only
are they enablers, they are silent enablers. They could lose their
divisional playoff game by 40 points and it wouldn't come close to
erasing the negative karma they have welcomed into their exclusive
circle.
</P>
<P>
   Last month, Muhammad, the Colts defensive back, found tragedy
when his wife, Nichole, died shortly after delivering a stillborn
child. A couple of weeks before his wife's death, Muhammad was
arrested and charged with three counts of misdemeanor battery.
Nichole's 6-year-old son, Eric, was pushed aside when he tried to
protect his pregnant mother from being hit.
</P>
<P>
   Character may be hard to describe, but I would say that a man
who chooses to be physical with his pregnant wife does not have it.
Neither does a team that fails to suspend the offending player for,
at least, half the season.
</P>
<P>
   I'm not saying Muhammad shouldn't be able to support himself for
making a mistake _ if he is even conscious that he made a mistake _
but there is no way my binoculars should have picked up this last
Sunday at the RCA Dome: a man in a blue ``Muhammad'' jersey, on the
field playing against the Patriots. For some reason, I thought the
Colts would either waive Muhammad or keep him inactive for the rest
of the season. Apparently, they are as oblivious as he was the
night he raised his hands and immediately put three people (his
wife, her son, and the unborn child) in danger.
</P>
<P>
   You know what's sick? Muhammad probably will be the most hated
man in Indiana if he misses the tackle that costs the Colts a
playoff game. His teammates would never forget that and neither
would fans. The community becomes less unified when his personal
life becomes the story.
</P>
<P>
   Character may be too much of an ideal or cliche to be a factor
in the sports world. But the haunting tale of Cherica Adams and
Carruth proves that at least some people, not necessarily athletes,
have it.
</P>
<P>
   By now you have seen the television and newspaper images of a
slight Carruth, escorted by FBI agents. The former Carolina
Panthers receiver is accused of conspiring to murder his
girlfriend, Adams, who died Tuesday. Prosecutors will argue that
Carruth and three accomplices masterminded a drive-by shooting
scheme that eventually resulted in a wounded Adams calling 911,
ironically, from a street that runs off of Rea Road in Charlotte.
Adams was six months pregnant when she was shot four times in the
chest. Her baby boy _ who is believed to be Carruth's _ was
delivered 10 weeks prematurely.
</P>
<P>
   Most of the news reports have focused on the potential pathos of
Carruth, who majored in English at the University of Colorado and
spoke of wanting to write novels. There were some _ but not as many
_ stories about the stunningly beautiful Adams, who knew many NBA
and NFL players, modeled, and sold real estate. But one story in
the Charlotte Observer seemed to touch what we mean when we speak
so gratuitously of character.
</P>
<P>
   The night Adams was shot, a 61-year-old man named Farrell
Blalock was in his home reading. He heard four shots and then
noticed that a car _ horn honking and headlights flashing into his
front window _ was moving toward his home. The car, driven by the
injured Adams, was 8 feet from his door. He called 911 and began to
open his front door. His wife told him not to, but he did anyway.
When he got outside, police had arrived to assist Adams.
</P>
<P>
   Blalock told the newspaper that Adams probably drove her black
BMW toward his house because she saw that his lights were on and
that, maybe, he could help. He did, even though it would have been
easy not to. I don't know if Carruth killed his girlfriend, but at
the very least it is safe to say that he did not help her by
initially refusing to speak with anyone and then becoming a
fugitive who was captured in the trunk of a car.
</P>
<P>
   Maybe now we will all hear something different when an athlete
protests, ``I am a regular person, just like you. I have the same
problems that other people have.'' Maybe now we will believe them
when they say their tremendous contracts do not relieve them from
stress and domestic problems; that their fame does not equate to
clear thinking.
</P>
<P>
   Pro athletes always say it's not about the money. They are
right.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 2113EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
