<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0268 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 21:14 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2972 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-BKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS &LR;      12-18 1112
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-RYAN-COLUMN-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BARKLEY DOESN'T NEED RING TO ENTER HALL 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By BOB RYAN  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Charles Barkley gave it 15 shots, and he now retires without
ever having played on an NBA championship team. Although some
people seem to feel different, this makes him neither a bad person
nor a failure.
</P>
<P>
   It just means he was unlucky.
</P>
<P>
   Two factors go into the making of an individual champion in a
team sport. The first is skill. You've got to be good enough to
make a professional team. The second, and far more important aspect
for most everyone who has ever played any sport, is luck. Who you
play with and when you play with them matters.
</P>
<P>
   Charles Barkley was a very good basketball player. A strong case
can be made that he is either the fourth- or fifth-best individual
player of the past 15 years, depending on what you think of Karl
Malone. (No one would seriously argue that either one approaches
Michael Jordan, Magic Johnson, or Larry Bird). Yet during his long
and distinguished NBA career, he made only one appearance in the
NBA Finals, his Phoenix team losing in six games to Chicago in
1993.
</P>
<P>
   For the record, neither Malone nor his buddy and fellow
sure-to-be first-ballot Hall of Famer John Stockton, have won an
NBA title, either. It's not easy, and it's harder now that ever,
given that the overall talent is dispersed among the ridiculous
number of 29 teams.
</P>
<P>
   Furthermore, it is only in very recent times that people have
made winning a championship the key factor in evaluating the career
of great players. In Ye Olden Days, people seemed to recognize
inherently that it's very hard to win it all, and that the gods
must be with you. Not everyone can be a Bill Russell (11
championships in 13 years) or Yogi Berra (11 World Series titles in
18 seasons as a Yankee) or even a Charles Haley (five Super Bowl
rings). Alfred P. Doolittle had it right. A man does indeed need
``A Little Bit O' Luck'' to be left standing at the end of an
athletic campaign.
</P>
<P>
   Consider some basketball greats who finished up ringless:
</P>
<P>
   Elgin Baylor (14 years), Dave Bing (12 years), Alex English (15
years), Artis Gilmore (12 NBA years), Kevin Johnson (11 years),
Bernard King (16 years), Bob Lanier (11 years), Pete Maravich (10
years), Sidney Moncrief (11 years), Calvin Murphy (10 years), Guy
Rodgers (12 years), Nate Thurmond (14 years), and Buck Williams (17
years).
</P>
<P>
   Baseball offers a long list of Hall of Famers who never played
on a World Series winner:
</P>
<P>
   Luke Appling (20 years), Richie Ashburn (15 years), Earl Averill
(13 years), Ernie Banks (19 years), Jim Bunning (17 years), Rod
Carew (19 years), Ty Cobb (24 years) _ betcha didn't know that _
Nellie Fox (19 years), Gabby Hartnett (20 years), Harry Heilmann
(17 years), Billy Herman (15 years), Harmon Killebrew (22 years),
Chuck Klein (17 years), Napoleon Lajoie (21 years), Bob Lemon (15
years), Ted Lyons (21 years), Heinie Manush (17 years), Juan
Marichal (16 years), Rube Marquard (18 years), Willie McCovey (22
years), Phil Niekro (24 years), Eppa Rixey (21 years), Robin
Roberts (no, not her; the great Phillies-Orioles-Astros-Cubs
righthander, 19 years), Lloyd Waner/Paul Waner (combined 39 years
and 5,611 brotherly base hits), Billy Williams (18 years), Ted
Williams (19 years), Carl Yastrzemski (23 years), and Robin Yount
(19 years). And I may have missed one or two.
</P>
<P>
   In football we don't have to go any further than Dan Marino. And
who in this town doesn't know about Ray Bourque?
</P>
<P>
   Think of the absurdity of evaluating player vs. player on the
basis of championships alone. Do you think, for example, that the
Yankees could have won these past two years if Derek Jeter had been
replaced by either Alex Rodriguez or Nomar Garciaparra? Or how
about this? Hank Bauer was a nice, solid, professional right
fielder for the Yankees of the 1940s and '50s, but he was nowhere
near as feared and respected a hitter as Roy Sievers, whose lot in
life was to do his prime-of-life slugging for the hapless St. Louis
Browns and equally hapless Washington Senators while Bauer was
playing on seven championship teams.
</P>
<P>
   For all but the starriest of superstars, it's all luck. Listen,
if Eddie Yost, a.k.a. ``The Walking Man,'' had been lucky enough to
be with the Yankees, as opposed to the Senators, Tigers, and
Angels, he might be in the Hall of Fame. Exhibit A is K.C. Jones,
who wasn't even as good a player as Al Attles, but who has enjoyed
a near lifetime benefit of an association with Bill Russell. Jones
is in the Basketball Hall of Fame. Suggest Attles for the Hall of
Fame and await the laughter. But Attles was the same player, only
better, since he did everything Jones did while also putting the
ball in the basket.
</P>
<P>
   We've got to abandon this ring mania. Is Steve Kerr a better
player than Charles Barkley because he's got four rings to
Barkley's none? Would you take Charles Barkley or Luc Longley?
Charles Barkley or Dennis Rodman? Charles Barkley or Mario Elie?
They've all got more rings than Charles Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   Injuries matter. Bad calls matter. Back up to the Celtics' Game
5 victory over Philadelphia in '81, and if Tiny Archibald doesn't
get a phantom call on a late 3-point play in the Eastern Conference
Finals the Celtics don't win that game and they're out. It's that
capricious.
</P>
<P>
   Most of all, who you're with and when you're with them matter
the most. Think of luckless Tom Van Arsdale, a terrific NBA player
for 12 years (14,232 points). Forget about a ring. All he wanted
was to get in the playoffs. He played with horrible Detroit and
Cincinnati teams for 11 years without ever getting into the
playoffs. He was picked up by a Phoenix team coming off a berth in
the Finals for the 1976-77 season. He would be re-united with his
twin brother Dick and there was no way he'd get cheated this time.
Wrong. The 1977-78 season was the only time in a nine-year stretch
the Suns failed to make the playoffs. No NBA player even remotely
as good as Tom Van Arsdale failed to participate in at least one
playoff game.
</P>
<P>
   And that's just making the playoffs. Winning a championship is
exponentially harder. If you're lucky enough to play with the
incomparable Bill Russell and it's a 14, 12, 10, or even an
eight-team league, and there are as few as two playoff rounds, you
may get a ring (hello there, Bennie Swain). If your misfortune was
to spend your prime years in a league dominated by demigods named
Magic, Larry, and Michael, you don't get one. It doesn't mean you
weren't a magnificent player.
</P>
<P>
   So I ask you: Would you take Charles Barkley or Bennie Swain?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
