<HEADLINE>
JACKSON PUTS LAKERS ALL ON SAME PAGE 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By PETER MAY  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   We missed the NBA champs last year. The San Antonio Spurs never
made it to Boston and the Celtics never made it to Texas. That
won't be the case this season. You'll see the 2000 NBA champions _
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, it's early, but I've seen enough already, even if the
Lakers have been the out-of-the-box favorites the last few years
and fizzled. Phil Jackson has done what a bunch of others could not
do _ get Shaquille O'Neal to rebound, defend, and block shots _ and
the result is a guy playing the way he should have been playing the
last several years. He has been a certifiable terror.
</P>
<P>
   ``You know,'' said Bucks general manager Ernie Grunfeld,
``before the year started, if you asked me which player I might
want, I'd have said (Tim) Duncan or maybe (Kevin) Garnett. But now,
it has to be Shaq.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers started East this past week with the best record in
the league and won in Atlanta on Thursday with Shaq doing basically
nothing. Kobe Bryant merely stepped up and scored 30. Ho hum. The
game in Boston will be the Lakers' fourth in five nights, so if
you're going to see any warts, that might be the time and place.
</P>
<P>
   But, so far, there haven't been too many. OK, there isn't a
brute at power forward. That might need to be addressed, but
really, does Shaq need anyone the way he's going now? (Anthony
Mason is, as they say, available.) Point guard? In Jackson's
system, you don't need one. Bryant has become Scottie Pippen.
</P>
<P>
   For the last few years, the Lakers always were presumed to have
the best talent and the worst chemistry. Utah (twice) and San
Antonio (once) systematically destroyed them in the playoffs,
making them look petty and juvenile in the process.
</P>
<P>
   Jackson had to look at the Lakers and see what he saw in Chicago
in 1990 _ a team with a couple of superstars hungry to win but not
knowing how to do it. His arrival and the cachet he instantly
brought with him should have cured the internal mess. But he also
brought with him a game plan: the old triple post (triangle) which
worked so well in Chicago.
</P>
<P>
   ``I've been on talented teams with game plans, but they could be
defended,'' Rick Fox said. ``If we lose now, it's because we beat
ourselves.''
</P>
<P>
   And the talent? ``I don't feel we're the most talented team in
the league,'' Fox said. ``But I found out that being on the most
talented team doesn't always mean you're going to win.''
</P>
<P>
   Like last year. And the year before that. The Lakers were
outsmarted by the Jazz and Spurs, who were disciplined and driven.
They may still be. But the Lakers are, too.
</P>
<P>
   ``Offensively, knowing what we're doing has made it easier to
play defense,'' Fox said. ``There are no errant shots. No one is
breaking out. We know where the shot is being taken and when.
There's more structure. There's a lot to be said about coming to
work every day knowing what your day is going to be like and what
is going to be required of you.''
</P>
<P>
   The Lakers made a lot of changes after last season's sweep at
the hands of the Spurs _ a new arena, new uniforms.
</P>
<P>
   ``Life as a Laker, each year, is always new,'' Fox said.
</P>
<P>
   And this year, it will also be fulfilling.
</P>
<P>
   Home for holidays
</P>
<P>
   It was a great thing Danny Ainge did this past week. But it's
also nice to be able to have the resources to do what he did. There
are thousands of fathers _ not to mention mothers _ who would kill
to have more time with their families, but work somehow manages to
get in the way. But it's also hard to go from something to nothing,
especially for someone as ultracompetitive as Ainge. He'll need
something soon or he'll go crazy . . . Randy Wittman, the Cavs'
first-year coach, said he's discovering that one can get easily
consumed with the job. ``The time involved is so much more than
when you're a player,'' he said. ``That has been the biggest thing
for me _ time management. You can't do everything. You have to
delegate and let people do their jobs. At first, I tried to do
everything and it drove me nuts. You could be here (at the arena)
all day. It took time for me to understand that.'' . . . The
Chicago Bulls went into the weekend as the only team still to have
not scored 100 points in a game. There was speculation last week
that Khalid Reeves might be joining the Bulls to help their
beleagured backcourt (as opposed to helping them win, which is not
in the grand design). He was playing in Greece, but apparently left
the team over a pay dispute. Then again, some of his teammates
thought he was ignoring the plays to run up his stats, a shocking,
shocking charge, if true . . . The Nets had a bit of a good stretch
this past week (before losing in Washington) and a lot of it had to
do with the return of Kerry Kittles. ``His presence has been a
major plus at both ends,'' GM John Nash said. Nash said Jayson
Williams is two weeks away from returning to practice and a month
away from returning to live action. Should that schedule be
correct, it might be worthy to see how Keith Van Horn responds. The
Nets feel that Van Horn's soft play is due in large part to not
having Williams around to protect him and boost him. But even with
the return of Williams, Nash said the club still needs a real post
presence and will have to get one either in the draft or via free
agency. As for the team's hideous (2-15) start, ``I still can't
believe it,'' he said. ``It was a major, major disappointment. It's
hard to win only twice in 17 games. With all the parity, a good
team can have a bad game and you win by default. That really
stunned all of us.'' . . . Brian Hill left Vancouver with the
following legacy: his 31 victories over two-plus seasons makes him
the winningest coach in franchise history. Brian Winters is next
with 25 . . . The Spurs figured things would not change all that
much with the new rules. They feel otherwise now. ``They definitely
hurt us,'' Mario Elie said. ``These guys are so quick that with one
crossover, they're at the hole and if you've got guys spread out,
it's going to be a SportsCenter highlight if you're too late. I
really don't like the new rules. I don't know why they changed
them. For a guy like me, a physical player, it takes away from my
game. I'm 36. I don't think people expect me to slow down guys like
Vince Carter or Grant Hill. It's impossible.'' Avery Johnson
concurs. ``We thought the rules wouldn't really bother us because
we have shot blocking. But our perimeter guys are more physical
players, they are more like post defenders than isolation
defenders. With them not being able to put a forearm on anyone, not
to be able to touch them in any shape, form or fashion, it makes
things a little difficult.''
</P>
<P>
   Still no go
</P>
<P>
   Tim Hardaway went through a full practice Friday with the Heat.
He then pronounced himself not quite ready to return to duty. The
Heat have been without their playmaker (jammed knee) for 12 games
(counting Saturday night) and he said Friday, ``It still doesn't
feel right.'' He vowed not to return until it does, always a wise
decision. Miami, meanwhile, won seven of its first eight without
Hardaway (the lone loss coming to the Celtics) but then dropped its
last two on a Western swing _ Hardaway said he had to leave his
house he was so upset watching the losses to Seattle and Golden
State _ and a close one at home Thursday to Milwaukee. ``What's
happening now,'' said coach Pat Riley, ``is that the freshness and
honeymoon of playing without Tim has worn off. Now, the routine of
playing without Tim is getting to us. We miss him, dramatically.''
The Heat, by the way, have two more games left in Miami Arena
before moving into their new digs, American Airlines Arena, for a
Jan. 3 game against Orlando . . . Wishful thinking from Phoenix GM
Bryan Colangelo: ``I'm going to push for realignment. I just wish
we were in another division.'' . . . Leaving Utah to sign in
Houston was a financial risk for Shandon Anderson. It's also turned
out to be an on-the-court disaster; the Jazz seemed to have gotten
their act together while the injury-ravaged Rockets are already
rebuilding. ``You can't foresee everything,'' Anderson said. ``Look
what happened to the Broncos. Look what happened to the Falcons.
You have a contending team, one or two players go down and then
everything becomes a struggle.'' Still, he says he has no regrets.
``I don't expect anyone to understand it,'' he said of his decision
to leave the Jazz. Utah offered him $24 million over five years. He
signed for $20 million less with Houston. ``We always liked
Shandon,'' said Jazz owner Larry Miller. ``But I don't think we
really knew who he was. He's obviously looking for something we
don't have here.'' Anderson said it was pretty simple. ``It was
time for a change,'' he said. ``You have to live your own life. I
was ready to get on a young team.'' Miller said he does regret
letting Anderson go for nothing. Anderson had pressed for a
sign-and-trade, but, as Miller recalled it, ``there were a couple
of players proposed and I didn't even know who they were.'' . . .
The Cavaliers are hopeful that they'll soon get a clearer picture
of Zydrunas Ilgauskas's cloudy future. ``In the month of January,
we'll know, one way or another,'' said GM Jim Paxson of his center,
who has been sidelined all season because of a stress fracture in
his navicular bone. The Cavs have Ilgauskas on one of these techno
marvel machines that stimulates bone growth. The machine needs 12
hours just to recharge, so Ilgauskas can't be on it as much as
they'd like. Still, he's walking, has no cast, and the Cavs are
holding their collective breath. But if the foot is still sore next
month, then season-ending surgery is likely . . . The Cavs, by the
way, are the only Eastern Conference team still to have not played
a Western Conference team on the road. (Milwaukee has played one,
but goes out West this week. The Celtics have played two, but go
out West next week.) The Cavs' first roadie against a Western
Conference foe is not until Jan. 12, when they open a seven-game,
11-day trip in Portland . . . How long before Dallas coach Don
Nelson goes into Bigman.com and puts ``rebounder'' into the search
field? Through their first 24 games, including Thursday's loss to
the Knicks, the Mavs had yet to outrebound an opponent . . . Asked
how he felt about his team last Friday, Sixers president Pat Croce
said, ``I don't know. I haven't seen them yet. This will be the
first time.'' The club Larry Brown and Billy King envisioned
finally suited up for the Bulls game, as Theo Ratliff was able to
go. Either Ratliff, Allen Iverson, or Matt Geiger has been hors de
combat at some point this season and, through 24 games, the club
had 14 different starting lineups. Through it all, the Sixers went
12-12, which, in the East, puts them right in the thick of things.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
