<SLUG> BC-BBO-BBNOTES-EVERETT-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAJOR DEAL FOR EVERETT COULD BITE SOX 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By GORDON EDES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   While the Red Sox were left congratulating themselves, and
deservedly so, for acquiring center fielder Carl Everett from the
Houston Astros, the deal was not completed without one piece of odd
business that had everyone tight-lipped afterward.
</P>
<P>
   Before making the deal, the Sox purchased the contract of minor
league shortstop Adam (no relation) Everett, gave him a $725,000
signing bonus, and a two-year major league deal. Under normal
circumstances, none of that was necessary, which raises the
question of whether the Sox had made promises of dubious legality
to Everett and his agents that they were obligated to keep even
though he would no longer be their property.
</P>
<P>
   The Sox weren't talking about it. Mike Port, the Sox assistant
general manager who handles many of the club's contracts, referred
all questions to Dan Duquette. Club spokesman Kevin Shea, asked for
an explanation from Duquette, called back and said that all he
could say was that the team had purchased Everett's contract from
Trenton.
</P>
<P>
   The Astros weren't talking about it. Astros GM Gerry Hunsicker
did not return phone calls on the matter, and assistant GM Tim
Purpura said only Hunsicker could address the issue.
</P>
<P>
   How about the agent, Bob Gilhooly? If Duquette had nothing to
say, Gilhooly said, then he had no comment. All Gilhooly said was
that the two-year deal was ``something we've been working on for a
long time.''
</P>
<P>
   All this secrecy for a minor league player with two years'
experience in pro ball?
</P>
<P>
   The puzzling aspect of the whole matter is why Everett was given
a guaranteed two-year major league contract. Interestingly,
according to the contracts registered with Major League Baseball,
Everett was given a $1 million bonus to sign as a No. 1 draft pick
in 1998, though published reports set the bonus at $1.725 million.
</P>
<P>
   The $725,000 included in the signing bonus he received this
week, the player said Saturday night, was counted against his
original signing bonus. But why didn't he receive the entire amount
at the time he was drafted by the Sox? It smells of a side deal,
which is illegal by definition (remember Roger Clemens and
Toronto), and leads to speculation that the Sox gave Adam Everett a
two-year major league contract as part of a private agreement
connected with the delay in receiving his entire bonus.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's something that's kind of hard to explain,'' Adam Everett
said by phone Friday night. ``I really don't want to get into the
details.''
</P>
<P>
   Neither, obviously, does anyone else.
</P>
<P>
   Realistically, he said, he expects to play on the Triple A level
next season.
</P>
<P>
   It turns out that the Sox and Astros had pretty much hammered
out a deal for Carl Everett last Sunday, but what delayed the
announcement was working out the details of the Adam Everett
contract. The Sox are obligated to pay the bonus, while the Astros
pick up the rest of the contract. Hunsicker was forced to clear out
space on his 40-man roster when he wouldn't have been required to
do so in the absence of the Sox contract signing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Very odd. Extremely odd,'' said one club executive.
</P>
<P>
   Adam Everett, incidentally, expressed enthusiasm for the deal.
``It's a good opportunity for me,'' he said. ``As you know, the Red
Sox already have an outstanding shortstop.''
</P>
<P>
   It wasn't the only oddity associated with the deal. The Astros
had interest in Korean righthander Sun Woo Kim, only to discover
that Kim had a no-trade clause in his contract. That's unusual for
a minor league player.
</P>
<P>
   Carl Everett, meanwhile, had yet to make any public statements
about the trade, though there was talk he might be coming to town
Tuesday. His initial reaction apparently fell far short of
jubilation, however. Everett, who had a career year last season
after indifferent results with three other organizations, was very
happy in Houston. How willing will he be to make a long-term
commitment to the Sox? Duquette is expected to open discussions
this week with agent Larry Reynolds on the matter. Just remember:
Pedro Martinez was said to be initially cool to the idea of making
Boston home, until Duquette gave him 75 million reasons to
reconsider.
</P>
<P>
   In the hunt
</P>
<P>
   The Red Sox remain a front-runner for lefthander Jeff Fassero,
who had dinner in August with Joe Kerrigan, the Sox pitching coach
he considers his mentor, when the Sox were in Texas last season.
Fassero, who had an awful year (5-14, 7.20 ERA) coming off elbow
surgery, nonetheless is attracting a good deal of interest and
isn't likely to sign until the middle of this week. Fassero, like
Chuck Finley, is 37, and won 57 games his previous four seasons
before coming apart last year. The Sox would like him as a starter,
but could also see him pairing with Rheal Cormier as the team's
second lefty in the pen. Reliever Ricky Bottalico, who probably
won't be tendered a contract by the Cardinals this week, also
should expect to count the Sox among his suitors . . . Former Sox
outfielder Darren Bragg is another Cardinal who expects to become a
free agent if the Cardinals nontender him. Bragg, who suffered a
season-ending knee injury last summer, will find a team that covets
his dirty-uniform approach . . . The Sox have had some contact with
Tommy Harper about becoming Jimy Williams's bench coach. Harper, a
highly respected member of Felipe Alou's Expos staff, was one of
Martinez's closest friends in Montreal and would be the type of
wise head who could make Carl Everett's transition to Boston easier
. . . Agent Tony Attanasio, who is representing top Japanese closer
Kazuhiro Sasaki, has no use for Duquette or Ray Poitevint, who
oversees Boston's Asian operation. Attanasio said he sent a
videotape of Sasaki's American workouts to Port but mocked Duquette
to reporters at the winter meetings and said Poitevint ``can't be
trusted.'' Sasaki signed a two-year contract with the Mariners
Saturday. Duquette remained in Southern California after the winter
meetings and was expecting to sign a couple of Asian minor league
prospects . . . Although kid closer Matt Mantei played a big role
in Arizona's drive to the playoffs after being acquired from
Florida, the Marlins appear to have made out quite nicely in the
deal. Not only did the Marlins receive pitchers Vladimir Nunez and
Brad Penny, both of whom could be in the Marlins' rotation in 2000,
but the player to be named was outfielder Abraham Nunez, considered
one of the top prospects in Arizona's system. Nunez, just 19, had
57 extra-base hits for Class A High Desert, including 22 home runs
. . . New Colorado Rockies GM Dan O'Dowd, a party to last week's
four-team deal that landed him third baseman Jeff Cirillo and
lefthander Scott Karl from Milwaukee and righthander Rolando Arrojo
and infielder Aaron Ledesma from Tampa Bay, took a subtle dig at
Dodgers GM Kevin Malone in talking about the revamping of the
Rocks, who have 16 new faces since the season ended. ``There's no
new sheriff in town, not even a deputy,'' O'Dowd said, an allusion
to Malone's declaration about a new sheriff when he took over the
Dodgers a year ago. ``We're just trying to push the train up the
hill a little more every day.'' How much power are the Rockies
giving away in surrendering Vinny Castilla, who went to Tampa Bay,
for Cirillo? Well, Cirillo hit just 15 home runs last season,
matching his career high, but his slugging percentage was .461,
just slightly below Castilla's .478, even though Castilla hit 33
home runs . . . And how about the mixed signals the Dodgers are
sending? They have $105 million pitcher Kevin Brown and $84 million
outfielder Shawn Green, then give up a solid starting pitcher
(Ismael Valdes) with second baseman Eric Young in a salary dump to
the Cubs, who surrendered middling reliever Terry Adams in exchange
. . . The Mets, shot down by Junior Griffey, also talked about a
deal with Toronto in which the Jays would have parted with
lefthander David Wells and outfielder Jose Cruz, in exchange for
righthander Octavio Dotel, outfielder Roger Cedeno, and outfielder
Jay Payton. But it never materialized, and Jays manager Jim Fregosi
didn't sound eager to move Wells.
</P>
<P>
   Bomb squad
</P>
<P>
   After trading for Castilla and signing Greg Vaughn as a free
agent, the Devil Rays now have four hitters whose total home run
production over the last two seasons surpassed any foursome on any
big league team. Castilla, Vaughn, Fred McGriff, and Jose Canseco
hit 305, 23 more than Seattle's current combination of Griffey,
Alex Rodriguez, Edgar Martinez, and John Olerud. ``They're awesome
in the middle of the lineup, I can tell you that,'' said Fregosi.
``Their lineup definitely gives you something to think about.
They're making this into the black-and-blue division now.'' . . .
Besides being a big bat in the middle of the lineup, Vaughn proved
to be quite accomplished in getting his way in Cincinnati last
season. Vaughn was the force behind the lifting of the ``no facial
hair rule'' in Cincinnati. Vaughn was the one who complained the
grass was too high at the Sarasota spring training complex and got
it cut lower. Vaughn was the one who lobbied for the removal of
third-base coach Harry Dunlop. Vaughn also was the one who demanded
that a cappuccino maker and special coffee be packed for every trip
. . . Mike Lowell, who overcame testicular cancer to play third
base for the Marlins last season, will be the recipient of the Tony
Conigliaro Award for courage at the Boston Baseball Writers Dinner
Jan. 13 . . . Wal-Mart major-domo David Glass, weighing a run at
the Kansas City Royals, is apparently considering joining forces
with Hall of Famer George Brett in a bid to buy the ballclub. ``The
easiest thing to do would be to do it with just my family, for us
to do it ourselves,'' Glass said of his proposal to buy the club.
``But I want to make sure I take advantage of every opportunity to
make the Royals better.'' . . . It didn't hurt the Indians that, in
landing free agent Finley, Dick Pole, who was Finley's pitching
coach in Anaheim, was hired for the same job in Cleveland. The
Tribe also scored points by signing close Finley buddy Mark
Langston to a minor league deal . . . Despite rumors of a possible
trade with the Mets, Indians GM John Hart said there are no plans
to trade Manny Ramirez, who is eligible for free agency after the
2000 season. ``We have not discussed Manny with any teams. We are
under no mandate to trade him,'' Hart said. ``He's a big part of
our club. We have been approached by clubs about Manny, but not
found anything that made sense to us. They are all dead deals
now.'' You can give 37-year-old 12-game winners $27 million, like
the Indians did, when it's 373 and counting for the number of
consecutive sellouts at Cleveland's Jacobs Field. The last
non-sellout at The Jake was June 12, 1995 . . . How worried is
Mariners manager Lou Piniella about the potential distraction of
Griffey staying put next season in Seattle, a la Randy Johnson in
his walk year? Not terribly. ``The way I look at it, how can I lose
as a manager if he's back playing center field?'' Piniella said.
``I've always had a good relationship with Junior. He'll go out and
play. He's always done that, and it's always been appreciated.
That's not the concern. The concern is the distraction.'' . . . The
Braves are excited about 19-year-old shortstop Rafael Furcal, who
hasn't played above Class A but has been one of the best players in
the Dominican Winter League. ``I just left a meeting and some of
our guys think that he's real close,'' said Braves manager Bobby
Cox. ``It may be a bit early next year (2000) and all that, to see
him playing every day. But some of the guys like him an awful lot.
They like him as a true shortstop or even maybe quicker as a second
baseman. He can go both ways. But the stuff sounds really good on
him, a true leadoff guy.'' . . . And did you catch the name of the
player selected by the Marlins in Monday's Rule 5 draft? Wynter N.
Phoenix. Selected from the Dodgers, Phoenix is a native of San
Diego . . . And speaking of the cost-cutting Padres, GM Kevin
Towers's job would be a lot easier if he didn't have $6.25 million
committed next season to reliever Randy Myers, who didn't throw a
pitch in 1999. And no, Duquette said, Tom Gordon's contract was not
insured. The $3.75 million that goes to the injured Gordon next
season will be out of the Trust.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
