<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-OLY-OLYNOTES-IOC-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
AFTER SAMARANCH, WILL IOC CHANGE? 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By JOHN POWERS  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Historic as those Olympic reforms are (and they're by far the
most sweeping ever), the same old faces will belong to the
International Olympic Committee for years, if not decades. The age
limit of 70 applies only to new members; all 102 incumbents get to
stay until they're 80. And the new eight-year term limits are
renewable.
</P>
<P>
   The only Lord of the Rings leaving anytime soon is 79-year-old
patriarch Juan Antonio Samaranch, who'll step down when his term
ends in July 2001. That's when the true measure of the reforms can
be taken since the most controversial ones, like visits to bid
cities, went through only because Samaranch was pushing for them.
</P>
<P>
   ``Many, many people were against some of the proposals,'' said
Mario Pescante of Italy, ``but we decided almost unanimously that
we would support the president.''
</P>
<P>
   Had the vote been by secret ballot, the IOC might have voted to
keep the visits, which was what caused the whole sordid mess in the
first place. Three dozen members spoke on the issue, most opposing
a ban. But when Samaranch called for a show of hands after more
than two hours of debate with the world media watching on
closed-circuit TV, only 10 still favored visits.
</P>
<P>
   ``A lot of this is what the media has asked for, and this is
what you've got,'' said Princess Anne of England, who wanted
visits. ``If you think it's going to work, well, fine. I suspect
you're going to find otherwise.''
</P>
<P>
   The IOC picked its 2006 winter site (Turin, Italy) without
visits, based on information from its site evaluation group. But
none of the bid cities, not even Turin, was happy about it. ``I
think the candidate cities will link arms and come to us and say,
this is really stupid,'' said vice president Richard Pound of
Canada, who opposes visits. ``They'll say, `You've got to come to
see our cities. You can't do it with postcards.' ''
</P>
<P>
   Though the ``new'' IOC will be much more diverse in theory, with
45 of the 115 members coming from international sports federations,
national Olympic committees, and recent athletes, two things won't
change: Everybody still will have what John Hancock chief (and IOC
critic) David D'Alessandro calls ``Olympic DNA,'' and the IOC still
will get to elect them. Which means that the IOC will remain what
it has always been _ self-perpetuating.
</P>
<P>
   If the Americans do some deft lobbying (or arm-twisting), they
could end up with as many as five members on the expanded IOC. With
Anita DeFrantz and James Easton and former volleyball player Bob
Ctvrtlik, who was one of the athletes added last week, the United
States now has three. It could get another two if it can wangle one
of the additional 15 reserved for international sports federation
presidents (Don Porter runs softball) or the 15 for national
Olympic committee presidents (Bill Hybl). Whether the Lords want
the Yanks wielding that much influence, though, is another matter.
</P>
<P>
   Samaranch didn't get to run the world's most exclusive (and
political) club by being a diplomatic rube. When he read his
opening statement before the House subcommittee that was grilling
him on Olympic corruption in Washington last week, Samaranch spoke
in English. As soon as he was put under oath, Samaranch switched to
Spanish and used a brace of interpreters. The two-way translation
effectively halved the number of questions Samaranch needed to
answer in the three hours he was there.
</P>
<P>
   With far less time to get things in balance (nine months instead
of two years), the Sydney organizers have finally had to admit what
their Salt Lake counterparts did: their sponsor revenue assumptions
are cuckoo. Instead of their original $548 million, the Aussies are
now figuring on $460 million.
</P>
<P>
   Do I hear . . . ?
</P>
<P>
   To cut down on scalping and get cash for the $40 million Olympic
legacy fund they've promised to set up, the Salt Lake organizers
will auction off 10 percent of their top-shelf tickets on the
Internet, where the public will also be able to buy seats at normal
prices. To register for information, check the committee Web site
(www.slc2002.org) . . . Jenny Thompson, the swimmer from Dover,
N.H., who broke one of Mary T. Meagher's two ``unbreakable'' world
butterfly marks, is a finalist for the USOC's SportsWoman of the
Year award, along with soccer player Michelle Akers and tennis
player Serena Williams. Sprinter Maurice Green, cyclist Lance
Armstrong, and tennis player Andre Agassi are the SportsMan
finalists, and the US women's soccer team, US women's softball
team, and cycling's US Postal Service team are finalists for Team
of the Year. Winners will be announced Jan. 8 in Indianapolis . . .
First it was Olympic figure skaters (Katarina Witt and Maria
Butyrskaya) baring all or most for the camera. Now it's soccer
players and gymnasts. The Matildas, Australia's women's squad, did
full frontals for a racy calendar to raise money. And Corina
Ungureanu, a member of Romania's world champion team, posed nude
for her country's edition of Playboy. ``It shows a lack of
decency,'' huffed federation president Nicolae Vieru. ``She
probably did it for the money.'' . . . Two weeks before they leave
for Down Under and playdates with the Aussies, Czechs, and Swedes,
the US women's soccer team still doesn't have a coach. The
federation has been scrambling ever since Tony DiCicco said he was
stepping down last month, and may have to go with assistants Lauren
Gregg and Jay Hoffman as interims.
</P>
<P>
   It's all downhill
</P>
<P>
   As usual, the Austrian men are treating the World Cup Alpine ski
circuit as their intramural league. They hold four of the top five
overall places, 11 of the top 18, and eight of 10 in the downhill,
with Hermann Maier running away with the overall title ahead of
teammate Stephan Eberharter. With Croatia's Janica Kostelic down
for the season and maybe more after tearing up a knee last week,
Italy's Isolde Kostner will be fighting Austria's Michaela
Dorfmeister and Renate Goetschl for the women's crown. The top
American so far has been Daron Rahlves, who ranks 10th in the men's
super G . . . Tough road for the US men's team at next week's world
junior ice hockey championships in Sweden. The Yanks, who placed
eighth last time, are drawn with defending medalists Canada and
Slovakia, plus the Czechs and Finns. On the roster are Boston
University goalie Rick DiPietro and defenseman Pat Aufiero, Boston
College defenseman Brooks Orpik, New Hampshire forward Patrick
Foley, Harvard forward Brett Nowak, Northeastern forward Willie
Levesque, Maine defenseman Doug Janik and forward Barrett Heisten,
and UMass-Lowell defenseman Ron Hainsey.
</P>
<P>
   Russians are coming
</P>
<P>
   The Russians will be sending a small army to next month's Grand
Prix figure skating final in Lyon. They qualified nine skaters,
including four women, and will be favored to win three gold medals
with world champions Alexei Yagudin and Butyrskaya and the pair of
Maria Petrova and Alexei Tikhonov. The United States has only two
entrants _ Michelle Kwan and Tim Goebel _ but both should make the
podium . . . Creditable fourth-place showing by the US baseball
team at the recent Intercontinental Cup in Sydney. The squad,
cobbled together from independent minor league teams like the Zion
Pioneerzz and the Albany Diamond Dogs, managed to beat both the
Japanese and South Koreans before losing to the Cubans in the medal
round . . . Yes, proclaiming that you have no Olympic affiliation
whatever does count as ``ambush marketing.'' When the Brighton ski
area near Salt Lake City advertised that it was ``proud host of
ZERO Olympic events'' (unlike rivals Snowbasin, Park City, and Deer
Valley), the US Olympic Committee sent the management a stern
letter telling them to knock it off.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 2118EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
