<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0272 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 21:19 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2976 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-NET-RURAL-AZR &LR;      12-18 1196
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NET-RURAL-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
INFORMATION SUPERHIGHWAY BYPASSES RURAL AREAS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By SHAUN MCKINNON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   It's the great promise of the Internet: For 20 bucks a month and
a local phone line, the world is yours. Plug in, dial up and click
_ you're surfing across continents, fetching information from
faraway capitals, chatting up cyberpals in London, Tokyo, Buenos
Aires . . .
</P>
<P>
   Anywhere but Wickenburg.
</P>
<P>
   In Wickenburg, electronically speaking, you can't get there from
here. Internet access remains a rarity for the town's 5,000
residents. Only two providers offer service and neither has had the
ability to accept new customers for the better part of a year. The
lucky few with accounts often find themselves logging on after
midnight to avoid bad daytime connections.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're 30 miles from a major metropolitan area, so we didn't
give it a thought when we moved here. We just assumed we'd have
Internet access,'' said Ron Long, who settled in Wickenburg in May.
``We're in the process of opening a new business, but we're having
to give it second thoughts. A modern company really can't run
without the Internet.''
</P>
<P>
   Wickenburg, in northwestern Maricopa County, is an extreme
example of how the increasing demand for Internet access can
quickly outpace supply, especially in fast-growing Arizona. Access
providers can't sign up customers if the telephone company hasn't
installed enough phone lines, and the phone company can barely keep
up with basic service needs.
</P>
<P>
   ``We're at the mercy of the local telephone company
infrastructure and it's a problem in some areas,'' said Ben
Preusser, director of technical operations for Cyber Trails, which
offers Internet access in some of Arizona's remotest corners.
``We've heard the outcry from Wickenburg. It's the same in Winslow.
To get a dedicated line to the high school there, we had to wait 12
months.'' &QL; 
SERVICE IS EXPENSIVE &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Cyber Trails has established service in Chinle and Tuba City on
the Navajo Reservation, and the company installed its own
infrastructure to serve areas in the White Mountains, Preusser
said.
</P>
<P>
   But the costs add up if the phone company isn't prepared and as
customers get more savvy about higher connection speeds, the
expenses can climb faster, he said. A so-called T-1 backbone line
that might cost the provider $400 to $600 a month in Phoenix, for
example, can cost $2,000 a month in Pinetop-Lakeside.
</P>
<P>
   Even in metro Phoenix, access providers can't always offer the
level of service requested. Although almost anyone in the three
urban area codes can dial up an Internet account, surfers with a
need for speed may be out of luck if they've moved to newer
neighborhoods on the fringe of the Phoenix area.
</P>
<P>
   Although Cox Communications is offering lightning-fast cable
connections in more and more homes, US West is struggling to keep
up with high-speed services like digital subscriber lines, which
require a user to live within three miles of a switching station.
</P>
<P>
   US West spokesman Jim Roof said that only about 30 percent of
Phoenix area customers could purchase high-speed digital service
right now, but the company is investing heavily to expand its
network.
</P>
<P>
   ``Whenever we hear from customers, probably every third question
is about high-speed Internet capability,'' he said. ``It's a
sizable challenge keeping up with it in a metro area like
Phoenix.'' &QL; 
LONG-DISTANCE CALL AWAY &QL; 
Which brings us back to Wickenburg. Wickenburg's woes lie in its
location. The town hugs the inside border of northwest Maricopa
County, but landed outside its area codes and is a long-distance
call from the Phoenix area.
</P>
<P>
   Other towns like Buckeye and Queen Creek sit nearly as far from
the urban center, but their residents own a 623 or a 480 area code,
which lets them use any of the Phoenix area's Internet providers.
Even Apache Junction, which straddles Maricopa and Pinal counties,
uses a 480.
</P>
<P>
   Wickenburg residents are long-distance even to their closest 520
neighbors in Prescott. Long found that out when he arrived from
Mount Shasta, Calif., an equally remote little town that
nonetheless offered excellent Internet services.
</P>
<P>
   ``We picked Wickenburg because it's a beautiful place to live,''
he said. ``But our business requires e-mail and technical research
on the Internet. Our long-distance bill is running $300 to $400 a
month and we're not doing any surfing. It's been really
frustrating.''
</P>
<P>
   Two service providers _ FutureOne and Primenet, now known as
Global Center _ set up business in Wickenburg several years ago,
when demand was lower. In the past year, both companies had to stop
taking new customers because they simply ran out of phone line
capacity.
</P>
<P>
   None of the national service providers offer local access
numbers and most, like America Online, charge premium rates to
connect using toll-free numbers. &QL; 
TROUBLE SIGNING ON &QL; 
Roy Reyer works as an e-commerce manager in Wickenburg and runs a
Web-based community directory site. He has an account with one of
the local providers, but has trouble signing on during the day and
more often waits until late at night to do much of his work.
</P>
<P>
   ``A community like Wickenburg is going to be left in the dust,''
he said. ``We're going to suffer economically and educationally.
There are people for example who would love to take classes on the
Internet, but that requires that you log on at a specific date and
time to conference with professors and classmates and you cannot do
that.''
</P>
<P>
   And as for Net-intensive activities like day-trading or
operating a Web-based business _ not gonna happen, Reyer said:
``This is the back roads.''
</P>
<P>
   Julie Brooks, executive director of the Wickenburg Chamber of
Commerce, said area business owners worry about what they're
missing without Internet access and the chamber worries about what
new businesses it may be missing.
</P>
<P>
   ``Businesses that may want to relocate here ask about it and our
answer has been there is no Internet access at this point,'' she
said. She offers information on buying a Phoenix-based phone line
or using an 800 number, but both options are expensive.
</P>
<P>
   Roof said US West understands the frustrations of Wickenburg
residents, but can't do much to solve the problem right away. Cost
is the biggest issue _ it's just too expensive to install the
needed lines and equipment compared with the demand and the
customer base.
</P>
<P>
   Also, Roof said, the company is in the process of selling its
Wickenburg exchange to Citizens Telecom, which provides phone
service to many rural Arizona communities. US West will allow the
new utility to decide how to invest in phone infrastructure.
</P>
<P>
   An Internet provider that offers service in nearby Prescott may
be prepared to move into Wickenburg after the first of the year,
but until then, residents and businesses can only wait.
</P>
<P>
   Long said all he seems to do lately is wait.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anyone who's committed to living outside a metro area learns
to accept some inconveniences,'' he said, ``but this . . . this . .
. I don't think it's severe enough for us not to stay, but it's
enough to stay and pull our hair out.'' &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 2119EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
