<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 21:20 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2977 &Cx1f; tdt-z
u s BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-PATRIOTS     12-18 3381
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-NFLNOTES-PATRIOTS-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
MAKE OR BREAK TIME FOR PATRIOTS STAFF 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By RON BORGES  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ The next three Sundays will be make or break time
for more than the members of the New England Patriots and their
coaches. It will be judgment time for the regime of Bobby Grier and
Andy Wasynczuk.
</P>
<P>
   Already looking at an uphill climb just to make the playoffs,
the Patriots' front office denizens are also facing the worst of
scenarios, unless all the evidence that has preceded this stretch
run has been a lie. Now they will have to play all those players
they brought in and all those draft picks who were supposed to
sustain the future.
</P>
<P>
   Now there will be no hiding from the sad truth, because the
truth is they blew it.
</P>
<P>
   Ty Law is definitely out for the rest of the regular season.
Cornerback Steve Israel is limping, as is safety Chris Carter. Left
tackle Bruce Armstrong will play on a sprained knee Sunday against
the Eagles, but for how long is anyone's guess. Kevin Faulk is down
for the count and Ted Johnson is already limping on a bad calf
after only two games, pressed into service by nothing but panic.
</P>
<P>
   What all this means is not only a more difficult time of it
against the Eagles, Bills, and Ravens the next three weekends. It
means players like Tebucky Jones, Tony George, Ed Ellis, Heath
Irwin, Max Lane, Lamont Warren, Kato Serwanga, and others will have
to come through or someone is going to be asking some hard
questions about why they didn't.
</P>
<P>
   Same is true of second-year receiver Tony Simmons, who has
caught two passes in the last seven weeks. When the season began,
coach Pete Carroll predicted big things from the former No. 2 draft
choice, yet Vincent Brisby, despite making only 12 catches, has
played more than Simmons. And that's in a pass offense all but
grounded most of the past five weeks.
</P>
<P>
   Carroll tried to justify Simmons's disappearance last week by
saying ``there hasn't been any need'' to play him because his other
receivers have been healthy. If Simmons could catch the ball when
he does get open, his services would be needed. But he hasn't and
so there isn't.
</P>
<P>
   Early in the season, Simmons had a seven-catch day against the
Chiefs, something of a breakthrough game. It turned out to be a
tease. Simmons had critical drops in the games against the Jets and
Dolphins last month, and poorly run routes that were sometimes
difficult to analyze. Since then, he has been conspicuous by his
absence in an offense that is floundering.
</P>
<P>
   The fact is, Simmons has yet to come close to the potential he
showed at Wisconsin, with a reputation for possessing sprinter's
speed but questionable production. To say there has been no need
for a deep threat who could get open and catch the ball, especially
in the last month, is to defy logic. The problem with Simmons is
not that he's been outplayed by Brisby. The problem is that he
hasn't played consistently enough to stay on the field ahead of him
and that is not the same thing.
</P>
<P>
   But Simmons is not the only problem, he's not even the most
egregious error. Here, in a nutshell, are the four draft picks
acquired for Bill Parcells: Andy Katzenmoyer, Simmons, Sedrick
Shaw, and Damon Denson. Two of those players are already gone, a
third hasn't caught a pass in two weeks, and the other hit the
skids after a fast start and was replaced in the middle by a guy
with one arm and now a bad calf. This does not look like a good
trade to me.
</P>
<P>
   Here, in a nutshell, are the two draft picks acquired for Curtis
Martin: Robert Edwards and Chris Floyd. Edwards's career appears
over after one season and a terrible knee injury, and Floyd appears
on the field about as often as Edwards.
</P>
<P>
   Meanwhile, Vonnie Holliday, taken by the Packers after the
Patriots chose Edwards, flourishes in Green Bay at defensive end
and Martin has rushed for 1,121 yards for the Jets, the
third-highest total in the AFC, carrying the ball 287 times. It is
the fifth straight season Martin has rushed for more than 1,000
yards.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots' personnel people said Martin was damaged goods
when he left, and didn't have many productive years left, according
to what the computer told them. Well, even if he stops right where
he is Sunday, Martin has rushed for more career yards in less than
five full seasons than any back in Patriots history. Just how many
guys will the computers find like that? In Patriot history, the
answer is one and he's playing elsewhere.
</P>
<P>
   This season, Terry Allen, Faulk, and Warren have combined for
1,032 yards, which means three guys are not as good as one. A year
ago, Martin became one of only six players in NFL history to rush
for 1,000 yards in each of his first four seasons, when he gained
1,287 yards for the Jets. Edwards, the replacement that cost the
Patriots Holliday _ and an improved pass rush _ gained 1,115 yards.
</P>
<P>
   It is sad that Edwards is unlikely to play again, but the fact
is, who's damaged goods now, the back who came into the NFL with a
long injury history (Edwards) or the guy who had four 1,000-yard
seasons for the Patriots?
</P>
<P>
   Since the departure of Parcells and Charley Armey (who now picks
players for the 11-2 St. Louis Rams), the Patriots have had 21
draft picks in the first four rounds. Of those picks, three have
emerged as starters, if you include Katzenmoyer, who was pressed
into action as a rookie because of Johnson's biceps tendon injury.
Three starters on a team that appears unlikely to make the playoffs
without a miracle, and less likely to stay there for long without
another miracle.
</P>
<P>
   Of those 21 picks, four were traded. Of the 17 players
remaining, not one has been an impact player, and that includes
Edwards, who worked hard but looked like a reincarnation of a
plodding Leonard Russell.
</P>
<P>
   But now some of those players will have to play the next few
weeks, with reputations and jobs on the line. As Terry Glenn said
last week, ``If we don't make the playoffs, it'll be real nasty
around here. For those of us who came in four years ago and went to
the Super Bowl, we don't know what it's like not to go to the
playoffs.''
</P>
<P>
   If the young players who have arrived since Grier took control
of the personnel department and Wasynczuk took control of the
salary cap play well enough for the Patriots to reach the
postseason, they will have built a team that has been in steady
decline since Grier's and Wasynczuk's ascendency. Pro football is a
production business and results speak for themselves.
</P>
<P>
   Oddly, if the Patriots win all three games and still fail to
make the playoffs, a distinct possibility, Carroll's record will be
29-19, a winning percentage of .604. It would be the highest career
winning percentage of any coach in Patriots history, including the
portly Parcells (34-34, including playoffs).
</P>
<P>
   How do you fire a coach with such a record?
</P>
<P>
   Not easily, but eventually someone has to be held accountable if
players like Jones, Ellis, Carter, George, Simmons, Floyd, Tony
Carter, Brandon Mitchell, and more than a few others do not make an
impact. Owner Bob Kraft must hold someone accountable or his team
will continue to drift downward.
</P>
<P>
   One longtime general manager was asked to assess the biggest
mistake made by the Patriots since the loss of Martin and Parcells.
He agreed to do it in exchange for anonymity. He had two nominees,
one obvious, one not so obvious. The most glaring was the wasted
No. 1 pick on Chris Canty, when soon-to-be All-Pro Sam Madison was
available. ``I don't know three teams that had Canty rated ahead of
Madison,'' he said. ``When they made that pick I was shocked. I
have no idea who came to that conclusion, unless they had a bad
speed time on Canty. We had a fast time on him too, but when we
looked into it, he'd run in track cleats, so we went back and got a
new time. It wasn't very fast. You have to do your homework.''
</P>
<P>
   He said the other major mistake was the decision not to re-sign
free agent center Dave Wohlabaugh, despite the price tag. Cleveland
made him the game's highest-paid center.
</P>
<P>
   ``They had a guy they could play there for 12 years in
Wohlabaugh,'' he said. ``Pay the SOB and go get a skill player with
the first pick who can help you. They didn't improve their team.
They went lateral. You can't let that happen.
</P>
<P>
   ``They should have seen Cleveland coming in with all that money
and locked Wohlabaugh up the year before. Once he got into free
agency, there was no way New England could compete if Cleveland
wanted him. They had to see that coming and avoid it. They
didn't.''
</P>
<P>
   He went on to make another point, comparing the selections of
the tiny Canty one year, to the massive Jones the next, two corners
who could not be more opposite in size, style, and skill. His point
was this: ``Do they have a plan there? Usually teams want a certain
style of corner, a certain type of running back. They have a
formula. What's their formula? I look at what they've done the last
three years and it looks like they've destroyed that team from a
personnel standpoint when they could have really solidified it long
term if they just hit on just a third of all those picks.''
</P>
<P>
   Just a third? How about on one of them? Over the next three
Sundays, many of those picks will have to play and they will either
thrive or be exposed. Jones will get his chance to prove the
skeptics wrong. He'll get the chance to prove he can be an NFL
corner rather than a penalty machine.
</P>
<P>
   It's likely George will get to show what he can do at safety,
and then we will see what the future holds because the future is
not Chris Carter.
</P>
<P>
   Same is true at receiver, if Simmons continues to languish on
the bench while the offense continues to languish on the field. The
story will have been told about that choice without a word being
said.
</P>
<P>
   As the running game struggles, we will watch the blocks of an
offensive line that needs to be revamped. The team's brain trust
has selected nine offensive linemen the last four years, seven
since Parcells left. It has netted one starter in Irwin, and a
second, Damien Woody, who was pressed into action because of the
loss of Wohlabaugh. Nine linemen drafted in four years and only one
could beat out an incumbent on a team that can't run to the
refrigerator, and of late seems to have forgotten how to protect
the quarterback.
</P>
<P>
   And what of the replacements for fullback Sam Gash? Can you
remember the last crushing block on the goal line thrown by Carter
or Floyd? If there aren't many these next three games, someone will
have to answer for that decision, too.
</P>
<P>
   Frankly, they should. A lot more coaches get fired in this
league than deserve to get fired. Often, they are scapegoats for
other problems, especially the assistants, who labor in anonymity.
That has been the case in New England for three years now, even
though the bulk of those coaches have done a sound job, especially
on defense.
</P>
<P>
   Over the next three Sundays, we'll get a chance to see a little
clearer just what those coaches, including Carroll, really had to
work with. If it's not enough, somebody must answer for it or Bob
Kraft will soon get to preside over the same kind of teams Victor
Kiam, Billy Sullivan, and James B. Orthwein presided over during
most of their time in the owners' box.
</P>
<P>
   Bad ones.
</P>
<P>
   Here's mud in your eye
</P>
<P>
   The NFL is investigating an incident in which Denver cornerback
Dale Carter was caught by a Jaguar video camera spitting in the
direction of Jacksonville tackle Tony Boselli Monday night. Boselli
confirmed the incident, but Carter has denied it, claiming, ``If
anything, he tried to spit on me.'' To that, an angry Boselli
replied, ``That's an absolute lie. That would not happen.''
Apparently, there is no video evidence, but there is a clear
picture of Carter spitting at Boselli as he headed to the sideline.
Friday, the league office in New York received a copy of the tape
at its request and will likely make a ruling early next week. It
was nearly two years ago to the day (Dec. 15, 1997) that Carter's
teammate, Bill Romanowski, was caught by an ABC camera spitting in
the face of 49er wide receiver J.J. Stokes. Romanowski was fined
$7,500 and some commentators tried to put a racial twist to the
issue because Romanowski is white and Stokes is black. Romanowski
even had to stand up at a team meeting and explain himself because
of the shock the incident caused his minority teammates. Now we
have the reverse situation and many players are watching closely to
see if the NFL takes a similar stance with the roles reversed.
Perhaps the best take on the incident, though, came from Boselli's
teammate, tackle Leon Searcy, who said of Carter, ``Maybe he has a
gland problem. I don't know what it is with the Broncos and spit.''
. . . The league fined Romanowski $10,000 for a questionable late
hit on Tony Gonzalez in the same game. It was the second time this
season the league has charged him for hitting Gonzalez late.
Romanowski has become a marked man with officials, and the league
office is watching his behavior . . . Here's one from the
not-learning-from-your-mistakes department. Thanksgiving Day, Glenn
was nearly three hours late for practice, then was fined and
benched for the first quarter of an important game against Buffalo.
Did he learn from this? Well, last Sunday, Glenn missed the final
bus to the RCA Dome in Indianapolis and did not arrive at the
stadium until 11:15 a.m., when he should have been there by 10:35.
Although he was on time for pregame warmups, missing the last bus
violates team policy. Several of Glenn's teammates were irked by
his behavior and irresponsibility and made their feelings known to
management. Some guys just don't get it . . . New England is not
the only place where the coach is being questioned and the approach
is dissected. In Miami last week, Jimmy Johnson's two Super Bowl
rings have not left him immune from doubters as his team fades from
what was once first place in the AFC East. Johnson's record is
35-26 in his four seasons running the Dolphins, a record similar to
Don Shula's 39-25 in his final four years, and people are
questioning whether Johnson's approach will lead Miami back to the
Super Bowl. ``That's tough to answer,'' cornerback Terrell Buckley
said, when asked if the Dolphins were better now than when Johnson
arrived. ``It's tough to make that assessment. We made the playoffs
here two years in a row, right? So I'd like to say we're better
off, but we made the playoffs then (before Johnson), too. So it's
hard to tell.'' Sound familiar? What has happened is a similar
record but a complete role reversal. Under Shula, the offense was
ranked fifth, second, first, and eighth in his last four years,
while the defense was ranked in the top 10 only once. Under
Johnson, the defense has become the strength but the offense is
ranked 22d this year. Under Shula, Miami was not in the top 20 on
offense only once in 26 seasons. Better off or not? They don't know
yet in Miami, even with a defense that led the league in fewest
points allowed a year ago and is fifth in the league this season.
So what is the problem? Same as it is in New England. The Dolphins
can't run the ball across the street. Miami has not had a running
game exceed or even equal the league average per carry since 1984,
and this year _ after drafting three running backs and a No. 1 a
year earlier _ the ground game is gaining 3.2 yards a carry. The
league average is 3.8. The aging team Johnson inherited four years
ago has been replaced by a team that's even older. The average age
of starters in 1995, Shula's last year, was 27.4. Today it's 28.2.
So where are they headed? It has become a familiar question this
month and not just in New England . . . Here's an interesting
juxtaposition. As of this morning, Parcells and Carroll have
identical records with their present teams, but who inherited the
better situation? I rest my case on that score . . . Mike Hollis
hasn't lost his compass. The Jaguars' kicker is the NFL's all-time
leader in field goal accuracy for both the regular season (83.4
percent) and playoffs (93.3) and this season is no exception. He
leads the NFL with a 90.7 accuracy rate (29 of 32). New England's
Adam Vinatieri is at 86 percent (20 of 23). I don't know if this
means anything, but Detroit's Jason Hanson has the longest field
goal per average kick at 39.8 yards on his 24 successful kicks.
Hanson and Denver's Jason Elam have four kicks longer than 50
yards, which says more about kicking at high altitude or in a dome
than it does about anything else . . . Speaking of kickers, how's
this for reversals of fortune? A year ago, Minnesota kicker Gary
Anderson didn't miss a field goal until the one that cost the
Vikings the NFC Championship. This year he's having the worst
season of his 18-year career. Anderson is 17 of 27 and is the only
kicker who has not made a kick beyond 40 yards. Such is the torment
of the kicker who misses with a Super Bowl on the line . . .
Departed Broncos' quarterback Chris Miller had a poignant moment
recently while being interviewed for HBO's ``Real Sports'' by Jim
Lampley. Miller was forced back into retirement because of
persistent concussions this year after having taken a three-year
layoff for the same reason. Asked if he is resistant to the word
concussion, Miller admitted, ``Yeah. I think it's something you
just kind of want to deny. You want to call it a ding because we
feel like a concussion is a major thing.'' When Lampley followed up
and asked if he was in denial, since he has lost some short-term
and long-term memory, and his coach, Mike Shanahan, has told him if
he were his son he would urge him to retire, Miller said, ``No. I'm
not in denial. I'm realistic about the fact. I know I got dinged.
I'll call it a ding. Ding is a lot easier to say than concussion .
. . I've got some decisions to make.'' The first one is to start
admitting he keeps getting knocked out, and if it happens enough it
can lead to something called punch drunkenness in boxing, and it's
not a pretty sight . . . Anyone interested in giving the Drew
Bledsoe-Peyton Manning ``How to Play Quarterback'' video for a
Christmas present can order a copy by calling 877-877-5200 or go on
line to www.nflcoaches.com. The proceeds go to assist ex-NFL
coaches facing financial difficulties who are not eligible for
pension or medical benefits from the league. It's a good video and
a better cause.
</P>
<P>
   Shortsighted investment
</P>
<P>
   When things go bad, sometimes they stay bad. When the Jets
acquired quarterback Rick Mirer for a sixth-round draft choice from
Green Bay, it seemed a small price to pay. But then Mirer had to
play, which was bad enough, but now it turns out he's actually
going to cost the Jets a fourth-round pick because he played too
much, even though he will surely be released at the end of the
season. If not, the Jets have to pay him $3.5 million, which is a
real Y2K problem . . . The Colts need to win two of their last
three games to become the team with the greatest single-season
turnaround in NFL history. If they can beat the Redskins Sunday,
they would tie the 1963 Raiders and 1929 Giants, who both made a
nine-game improvement . . . How good are the St. Louis Rams at the
TWA Dome? They're not only undefeated but have been winning by an
incredible 25.6 points per game at home. But before you bet your
child's college fund on the Rams to win the Super Bowl, consider
this: Those home wins have come over the Browns, Falcons, Saints,
Ravens, 49ers, and Panthers . . . Pity the poor Saints. New Orleans
has now lost 11 of its last 12 games and are the laughingstock of
the league because of their decision to burn their entire draft to
land running back Ricky Williams. But understand this, for all his
injuries and his team's inconsistency, Williams has rushed for 816
yards and still has a shot at 1,000. Unfortunately, because of the
way his contract is written, a 1,000-yard season doesn't get him an
extra nickel . . . Speaking in the converse, do you think the
Redskins wish they'd signed Stephen Davis to a contract extension
instead of looking at a 1,300-yard-and-counting rusher going on the
open market in March?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
