<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-PATRIOTS-ADVANCE-BOS </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BLEDSOE MUST NAVIGATE MURKY WATERS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
 By NICK CAFARDO  
 c.1999 The Boston Globe  
 
<TEXT>
<P>
   PHILADELPHIA _ He walked around stoically last week, looking
straight ahead, rarely making eye contact. When he walks into a
room, everyone looks at him, and he'll glance back, but he could
have been walking barefoot on glass and there would have been no
expression.
</P>
<P>
   Drew Bledsoe was ticked off.
</P>
<P>
   Sick of postgame press conferences expounding on the
could-haves, would-haves, and should-haves. Bledsoe is not only
trying to right the offense; he must be wondering about his own
performance. At midseason, he was a legitimate MVP candidate, and
now he is far down on the list of quarterback ratings.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe was once the best, but now he's taken a back seat to a
sophomore _ Peyton Manning.
</P>
<P>
   He had beaten the Colts like a drum since 1996, eight straight
wins before last Sunday's crushing 20-15 loss.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe watched the pretty play-action fakes of Manning, his
ability to move away from pressure, and he watched how this young
quarterback was able to get rid of the ball so quickly, avoiding
sacks.
</P>
<P>
   Last year, Bledsoe rode out on his white horse, beating Buffalo
and Miami with a busted finger, saving the season. The amazing
thing is he's been healthy all season, and is the only quarterback
in the NFL to handle all of his team's passing.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe had to watch the last three games of the 1998 season
from the bench, while the Patriots clinched a playoff berth against
San Francisco, lost the regular-season finale to the Jets, and were
eliminated from the playoffs by Jacksonville.
</P>
<P>
   He called it the worst moment of his NFL career, feeling so
helpless.
</P>
<P>
   Bledsoe has so much pent-up anger and frustration that in a game
so meaningful _ with the Patriots' playoff chances hanging in the
balance _ he should have a monster game.
</P>
<P>
   ``(The Eagles are) going to bring everything at us, and they've
been doing that all year,'' said Bledsoe. ``They've had their own
struggles on offense and so they've been trying to create points
and create field position with their defense. We have to get the
ball out quick and guys have to be open for me at the right time.
They can leave themselves vulnerable and that's when we have to
take advantage of it.''
</P>
<P>
   Patriots receivers were sent this message loud and clear: No
matter what the coverage, get open and get open quickly.
</P>
<P>
   The Patriots will continue with the four- and five-wide receiver
sets and their quick options to Terry Glenn and to the backs. But
Bledsoe is going to take shots down the field Sunday. &UR;  &LR;  He wants to
score a lot of points early, make people forget the Patriots have a
scoring problem, show the NFL that the Patriots will be in it the
rest of the way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Everybody in the locker room knows that we're capable of being
in the playoffs. We can win out, but we can't look past this team.
They're home and they have people who can make plays. We have to
attack them from the start. We can't take anything for granted,''
said Lamont Warren, who figures to have a prominent role in the
offense with rookie running back Kevin Faulk out for the season
with a fractured ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Jefferson, looking down the road, said, ``If we can win
these next three and make the playoffs, we're going to the Super
Bowl.''
</P>
<P>
   There aren't many fans who seem to see that far down the road.
In fact, most are expecting a dead end.
</P>
<P>
   There are many hurdles and obstacles before that bold statement
can come to fruition. It is still a desperate situation.
</P>
<P>
   ``The reason we haven't been winning these games is because we
haven't been scoring enough points,'' said Bledsoe. ``Our defense
is playing fine, but we can't keep putting the pressure on them
every week.''
</P>
<P>
   Clearly, the pressure is on Bledsoe and he has never been more
determined to right the ship, because if he doesn't, the Patriots
will be shipwrecked and Bledsoe's credentials as one of the best
might be hard aground, as well.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
