<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 21:25 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2979 &Cx1f; tta-z
u p BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-1STLD-W     12-18 1077
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BUSH-CAMPAIGN-1STLD-WRITETHRU-2TAKES-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
BUSH'S NEW HAMPSHIRE ALLIES SAY HE'S VULNERABLE THERE 
</HEADLINE>
   (ADDS staff being overwhelmed by crowds in 15th graf; ADDS name of
most influential figure in New Hampshire campaign 6 grafs from
end.) 
 (EXCLUSIVE; 4 p.m. ET EMBARGO for print media; 7 p.m. ET EMBARGO
for electronic media.) 
(nk) 
 By RICHARD L. BERKE    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NASHUA, N.H. _ Many of Gov. George W. Bush's allies in New
Hampshire are blaming his Texas-based campaign for early lapses
that they say have left him unnecessarily vulnerable against Sen.
John McCain in the state that holds the first presidential primary
in only six weeks.
</P>
<P>
   A combination of aloofness and overconfidence, they say, led
advisers unfamiliar with the peculiarities of New Hampshire's
politics to let Bush adopt a sound-bite style that voters here
disdain, and to forgo the time-honored approach of personal
campaigning.
</P>
<P>
   After months of appearing unstoppable elsewhere, Bush has seen
his lead in the New Hampshire polls evaporate, and some surveys
show McCain is continuing to surge. Several of Bush's top advisers
now concede that he could lose the primary on Feb. 1.
</P>
<P>
   If that happens, Bush would still be the clear favorite for the
Republican nomination. He holds a commanding lead in polls in every
other battleground state and sits atop a daunting treasury.
</P>
<P>
   New Hampshire may no longer be the make-or-break state it once
was for presidential aspirants. Still, no matter what happens, many
Bush supporters in New Hampshire said the campaign should never
have put itself in jeopardy. Their recrimination underscores a
tension _ one that many strategists say was inevitable _ between
the campaign's tightly run high command in Austin, Texas, and its
supporters on the ground in this tiny state.
</P>
<P>
   Former Gov. Stephen E. Merrill of New Hampshire, who ran Bob
Dole's campaign here in 1996 and backs Bush, spoke out for the
first time in an interview about his qualms about the governor's
organization.
</P>
<P>
   ``The Bush campaign believed it was the front-runner in New
Hampshire,'' said Merrill, who did not seek re-election in 1996.
``There's no such thing as the front-runner in New Hampshire. You
simply become the biggest target. This state demands personal
attention _ and is not easily impressed by either money or poll
numbers.''
</P>
<P>
   Emphasizing his belief in Bush himself, Merrill added: ``I love
this guy. He'd make a great president. That's what's so
frustrating. There is no inevitability in any presidential primary.
The great irony is that the candidate understands that. I'm not
sure everybody else does.''
</P>
<P>
   Indeed, many of Bush's backers in New Hampshire argued that the
governor's top national advisers did not grasp the idiosyncratic,
even quaint, requirements for stumping in New Hampshire.
</P>
<P>
   First of all, they complained that Bush, seeming to take his
lead for granted, did not spend nearly enough time in the state and
passed up early debates with his rivals. When he did venture here,
they said, Bush staged mostly large events where the voters had
little chance to quiz him, a cherished state tradition.
</P>
<P>
   He also took pains not to engage McCain directly, and Bush's
supporters said he did not develop a crisp message early on to
answer the Arizona senator's call for campaign finance reform.
</P>
<P>
   And they said he has been slower than Vice President Al Gore in
trying to shed his entourage, as the vice president did when former
Sen. Bill Bradley mounted an unexpectedly vigorous challenge here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't think they understand New Hampshire; they don't get
it,'' said Jane E. O'Hearn, a state representative from Nashua, in
the south of the state, who endorsed Bush in May. ``I don't think
they are complying with the way New Hampshire has done things. They
are treating every state probably the same way _ it's sound bites
in every state.''
</P>
<P>
   Ms. O'Hearn, who is so exasperated she is toying with the idea
of defecting to McCain, added: ``George Bush's sound bites are all
the same. I don't think he's coming across with the depth he needs
to reach the people of New Hampshire. The man is good, he is
sincere, and just needs an opportunity to show that. And I hope the
Bush campaign allows that to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   Several Bush operatives here said they were overwhelmed by unex-
pected crowds at the governor's events, which made it more
difficult for him to interact with voters.
</P>
<P>
   Ed Dupont, a former state Senate president from Concord who is a
member of Bush's state steering committee, said it had been a
nightmare trying to set up an appearance in September at the
international speedway here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I spent two days with Texas Rangers and advance staff for a
two-hour event,'' he said. ``He couldn't ride in a golf cart, had
to have a closed vehicle.'' In the end, Bush had to scrap the event
because of a shooting in Texas.
</P>
<P>
   But McCain swooped in with almost no advance planning. ``They
stuck him in a golf cart and drove him down to the infield and he
shook 400 hands,'' Dupont recalled. ``That is part of what the
McCain message has been: throw your jacket over your shoulder and
go ahead and do it.''
</P>
<P>
   Dupont echoed many Bush backers who had nothing but praise for
how McCain has mounted his campaign.
</P>
<P>
   ``When this race started, it was Bush's to lose and McCain was
clearly the underdog,'' he said. ``But when McCain wraps the United
States flag around himself, people want to salute. And he's
deserving of that. He's definitely caught on in New Hampshire. The
Bush campaign certainly has the ability to even this thing up in
New Hampshire and win. But time is running short.''
</P>
<P>
   Tom Corrigan, a commissioner in Coos County in northern New
Hampshire who is a town chairman for Bush and has been active in
politics for three decades, said: ``The people from the Concord
office were getting their orders from Texas. They had their methods
set even before they came to New Hampshire. We had strangers coming
in trying to run a campaign.''
</P>
<P>
   But Karl Rove, Bush's chief strategist, said many of the
decisions were made jointly.
</P>
<P>
   ``We do the mechanical stuff here,'' he said. ``The TV ads are
produced here, but they are carefully vetted there. For all the
volunteer activity on the ground, and decisions about where does
Bush go, they come up with a plan that they discuss with us. What
does Bush say? It's a mutual discussion between them and us.''
</P>
<P>
   nn
</P>
<P>
   Bush's advisers insist that they are not rattled now that they
are threatened by a potent rival in the Granite State. But their
calm exteriors belie several steps they have taken in recent weeks
to be more competitive.
</P>
<P>
   After saying he would not take part in any debates until
January, Bush participated in three this year, and the first was in
New Hampshire. He has significantly stepped up his travel schedule
to the state. And at events here he now allows far more time for
questions and answers from residents than in most other states.
</P>
<P>
   ``Look, the front-runner always has a rough patch in the road
somewhere,'' said Rove. ``And the way to plow your way though is to
stay disciplined and to stay focused _ make alternatives and keep
going.''
</P>
<P>
   Rove said he was doing other things to become more competitive,
but would not describe them ``because it would be showing our
cards.''
</P>
<P>
   A victory by McCain in New Hampshire could fortify the Arizona
senator's entire operation as the campaign moves into a fast-paced
schedule of contests. And there is always the possibility _ remote
as it may seem _ that a humiliating defeat could unhinge the entire
Bush operation.
</P>
<P>
   Some Bush supporters said McCain's rise was inevitable, because
it is political custom for there to be an intense skirmish here.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am not shocked or stunned or anything like that,'' said Rep.
Charles Bass, R-N.H., one of the Bush campaign's top lieutenants
here. ``Frankly, I don't think Bush is either. I've been pounding
this every time I've been with him: `We're going to be behind and
don't worry about it.'''
</P>
<P>
   But Todd Harris, the McCain campaign's spokesman in New
Hampshire, said the Bush campaign ought to be worried. ``Their
definitive victory line in the sand keeps getting pulled back
further and further every day,'' he said. ``It used to be, we'll
defeat them here in New Hampshire. Now, they're talking about a
firewall in Michigan.''
</P>
<ANNOTATION>
   (STORY CAN END HERE. OPTIONAL MATERIAL FOLLOWS)
</ANNOTATION>
<P>
   Joel Maiola, the Bush campaign director in New Hampshire, argued
that McCain's rise had come about because the Arizona senator drew
new support each time one of the other alternatives to Bush dropped
out of the race earlier in the year.
</P>
<P>
   Asked why he thought many Bush supporters had publicly
criticized the candidate's operation, Maiola said: ``In New
Hampshire, there's a lot of agendas and a lot of reasons for saying
different things. In New Hampshire, you can never get enough of a
candidate.''
</P>
<P>
   The most influential New Hamp- shire figure in the campaign is
Sen. Judd Gregg, who installed Maiola, his longtime chief of staff
and campaign manager, to run the statewide drive.
</P>
<P>
   Bush's aides defended their operation by arguing that McCain is
concentrating his effort in New Hampshire, completely bypassing the
Iowa caucuses a week before and skimping in other states as well.
By contrast, Bush is running a full-fledged national campaign. As
of Saturday, Bush had spent 19 days in New Hampshire this year;
McCain had been here 42 days.
</P>
<P>
   ``Our object is to compete everywhere and to win everywhere,''
Rove said. ``You can't claim to be a national candidate worthy of
the nomination of the Republican Party if you say you're going to
pick and choose every contest.''
</P>
<P>
   Rhona Charbonneau, who is chairman of the Bush campaign in
Hillsborough County, said she had been worried that the candidate
did not spend enough time here. ``I don't think they understood New
Hampshire politics,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   But she said she had become more confident because the candidate
was coming here more _ and because she was being overwhelmed by
people who wanted to attend a reception for Bush at her house on
Monday night.
</P>
<P>
   ``They're going to be hanging from the ceilings,'' she said.
``I've got 180 people coming to my home, and I've had to turn
people away.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
