<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-FBN-GALLOWAY-COLUMN-TEX </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
HEY, CHAN: WINNING, PASSING GO HAND IN HAND
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By RANDY GALLOWAY 
c.1999 Fort Worth Star-Telegram 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Pat Summerall, my favorite Fox-man, spends the week viewing game
film from around the NFL. The better, Pat says, to back up his TV
comments with fact.
</P>
<P>
   Some of us, obviously, have never considered mixing fact with
opinion, but ...
</P>
<P>
   Summerall turned off his video machine long enough the other day
to discuss a vanishing breed in the NFL. Good offense. Where has it
gone?
</P>
<P>
   ``Every week before we do a Sunday game, John \RMadden\S and I
sit down with the two coaches to talk about what their team has to
do to win,'' Summerall said. ``Without exception, the first answer
from every coach is always the same _ be successful running the
football.''
</P>
<P>
   With a raised eyebrow, Summerall added, ``What is this _ a
habit? Coaches always say that, and have for years, but who cares
how you get to the end zone? Throw it, run it, just get there.
</P>
<P>
   ``From what I've seen about offense in the league this season,
you've got to be able to throw it to win. The defensive mindset is
to stop the run. If you can throw it, and you can pass block, you
can win.''
</P>
<P>
   Attention, please, Chan Gailey. Are you hearing this?
</P>
<P>
   The surprising season of the St. Louis Rams backs up the
Summerall opinion. But while the Indy Colts have been just as big a
surprise, the Colts are considered more of a Super Bowl contender
than the Rams. Which goes beyond coming from a tougher division and
conference.
</P>
<P>
   ``All you have to do is watch the Colts to know a passing game
doesn't have to be complicated,'' Summerall said. ``They are so
simple in what they do. \RQuarterback\S Peyton Manning, of course,
makes it look easy. He doesn't get sacked because he knows how to
avoid sacks. The offensive line is set up to help him avoid sacks.
It's a simple blocking scheme but so effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Those linemen know who to block, and they don't take
penalties. That may sound elementary, but believe me, it's not
happening everywhere.''
</P>
<P>
   Yes, we know. Exactly the opposite occurs locally almost every
week.
</P>
<P>
   Around here, when football pleasantries are exchanged, the
logical subject is Cowboys' defense. And then everyone quickly
moves on to a more lively debate.
</P>
<P>
   Angry words are heard over what the heck Chan Gailey thinks he's
doing with this offense. Do you know yet? Does Gailey?
</P>
<P>
   Weekly Chan-speak goes like this:
</P>
<P>
   ``We've got to get better.''
</P>
<P>
   Waiting for that to happen has been the same as waiting on
Christmas. Unfortunately for Gailey, Christmas may arrive first.
</P>
<P>
   Depending on the opinion-giver, offensive improvement was noted
against the Eagles, at least in the form of a Gailey philosophy
change with the passing game. Total disagreement, however, was
heard from Gailey, who claims there was no change.
</P>
<P>
   Whatever, the final three games, and the playoffs, and the
season, and maybe even Chan's job security, ride on one thing:
</P>
<P>
   Offense.
</P>
<P>
   Popular theory says otherwise. It says defense will have to
carry the Cowboys down the stretch.
</P>
<P>
   But from the Dept. of
I-read-it-in-the-sports-page-so-it-must-be-true, all hail to Dave
Campo. And not for his Cowboys' defense, but for his sound
reasoning.
</P>
<P>
   Mr. Campo said this week that he has stripped the walls clean in
the defensive war room at Valley Ranch. There are no more weekly
``goals'' posted for his group, such as holding the opposition to
17 points or less, or placing a ceiling on rushing yards, passing
yards, etc.
</P>
<P>
   Just win the game. That is now the lone goal.
</P>
<P>
   As you know, Campo and the defense have maxed out on
productivity for the season. These people have performed above and
beyond the call of duty. All expectations have been exceeded.
</P>
<P>
   But even so, what's the team record?
</P>
<P>
   A measly 7-and-6 has the Cowboys forced into a win-out-or-else
stretch run. Summerall says he can count six ``impact'' players on
the Campo defense _ Alonzo Spellman, Leon Lett, Deion Sanders,
Darren Woodson, George Teague and Randall Godfrey _ which is above
the league norm.
</P>
<P>
   But despite all that, defense couldn't carry the Cowboys this
season. Just like defense couldn't carry Miami. Tampa Bay is very
hot, and is a defensive exception at the moment. But when the Super
Bowl is won in late January, here's a friendly wager the new champ
will be the team that has the best offense//passing game.
</P>
<P>
   Which brings us back to the Cowboys, who are just trying to make
the playoffs. To do so, Gailey will have to get his offense right
before Christmas. Actually, it had better be right today against
the Jets. Hurry, Chan.
nn
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
