<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TOWNS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
(ATTN: N.J.)  
 CYBERCLYSM OR COOKOUT, THEY'RE READY 
</HEADLINE>
  (jw) 
 By MATTHEW PURDY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PARAMUS, N.J. _ Bradley Luberto, a salesman at Ramsey Outdoor,
was helping a family interested in butane camp stoves the other
night when he asked the threshold question: ``Are you going to use
this for camping or indoors?''
</P>
<P>
   Diana Heredia, 17, looked at her parents with a hint of a smile.
``Indoors,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Luberto knew immediately what that meant. Y2Kers.
</P>
<P>
   ``We have the big jugs of water and now we're trying to get the
stove and the lantern,'' Ms. Heredia said. ``We also have canned
food.''
</P>
<P>
   They are members of a new and growing breed of suburban
survivalists readying themselves in the aisles of camping stores,
military surplus shops and hardware stores for whatever the first
moments of Jan. 1 might bring.
</P>
<P>
   Who can blame them? It is now fairly certain that with the
arrival of the year 2000, life will be disrupted _ either by
Armageddon or by the need to reset the clock on the VCR. There is
also the risk the government never talks about: unending phone
calls from friends and relatives searching for scraps of evidence
to prove that the year 2000 problem disrupted life.
</P>
<P>
   Despite all the government assurances that most potential
Y2K-related problems have been erased _ or maybe because of them _
fear of a breakdown in the supply of power, water or money, or of
some greater chaos, has taken hold.
</P>
<P>
   That accounts for the upswing in sales of camping gear at Ramsey
Outdoor and of meals ready to eat (or MRE's) at Central Military
Surplus in Pearl River, N.Y.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had one woman who set aside $5,000 for Y2K,'' said Hanna
Rozzo, the owner of Central Military. The woman wanted three cases
of MRE's, a bunch of gas masks, two large water filters, a dozen
butane stoves and on and on.
</P>
<P>
   The thermonuclear shelter dwellers were preparing months ago,
and salespeople remember them fondly. At Ramsey Outdoor, they talk
of the man who feared the new year would bring mass chaos and
wanted a flashlight that would deliver a blinding flash to stun an
approaching anarchist and make him an easier target.
</P>
<P>
   Those people were easy to laugh at in July. But as the moment
approaches, few seem able to completely disregard it.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think deep down inside, people are a little scared,'' John
Basilone, a driver for Home Depot in Clifton, said while standing
near a prominent display of portable generators at the store. ``You
have men here who, being men, would never admit it. I think that
women, who in my opinion are more honest anyway, are letting it
out.''
</P>
<P>
   As if to prove his point, he said his wife was buying water and
canned food and arranging for their extended family to be together
on New Year's Eve. ``Personally, I have a lot of faith,'' Basilone
said. ``I don't think anything's going to happen.''
</P>
<P>
   In some men, the advent of Y2K unleashes the
flintlock-over-the-mantel spirit that once made buffalo and Indians
scarce across the land.
</P>
<P>
   A man purchasing a children's camouflage outfit at Central
Military the other night said: ``My wife is actually buying water.
I have guns. I have bullets. I live near the woods and there are
deer in my backyard. I'm not worried about meat.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people seemed uncomfortable acknowledging concern. Consider
this scene Friday morning at Ramsey Outdoor:
</P>
<P>
   Bystander: ``What do you think will happen?''
</P>
<P>
   Man looking at camping stoves: ``Nothing. You might want to ask
my wife.''
</P>
<P>
   Wife: ``I'm not worried about it. He is.''
</P>
<P>
   A short time later, the sale of one camping stove is completed.
</P>
<P>
   Leave it to a self-described soccer mom to just come out with
it. ``You don't want to do nothing just in case something
happens,'' Kate Beckelman said. ``You don't want to feel like an
idiot.''
</P>
<P>
   So she is preparing as she would for a blizzard. Buying a few
extra cans of soup and maybe some water. Checking to make sure that
extra blankets are handy. Putting a working flashlight in every
room.
</P>
<P>
   But it is no obsession. She said she was shopping for powerful
flashlights less for Y2K than for K9BM. ``We also have to walk the
dog in the backyard at night,'' she said.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
