<DOCNO> NYT19991218.0279 </DOCNO>
<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 21:48 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2984 &Cx1f; taf-z
u s BC-BKW-RUTGERS-TEXAS-NYT     12-18 0698
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKW-RUTGERS-TEXAS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RUTGERS RALLIES AND GIVES STRINGER NO. 600
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By   FRANK LITSKY    
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   PISCATAWAY, N.J. _ For 27 years, C. Vivian Stringer has been
coaching women's college basketball, regularly taking Cheyney, Iowa
and Rutgers to the national championship tournament. Saturday, she
became only the third women's coach in Division I history to win
600 games.
</P>
<P>
   Saturday afternoon, at the Louis Brown Athletic Center, her
Scarlet Knights played disorganized one moment and fired up and
slick the next _ just as they have all season. In a game marked by
17 lead changes and eight ties, Rutgers trailed until the last four
minutes. Then Rutgers' top players, Shawnetta Stewart and Tasha
Pointer, led a frenetic defense that broke a good Texas team, and
Rutgers won, 68-64.
</P>
<P>
   At the final buzzer, Stringer was mobbed by her players. They
presented her with a bouquet. They lifted her onto their shoulders.
Not until the players formed lines for the customary handshakes
could Jody Conradt, the Texas coach, reach her longtime friend.
They embraced.
</P>
<P>
   ``I told her I was happy for her,'' Conradt said. ``I said she
deserved it, but I would have liked to delay it for one more
game.''
</P>
<P>
   The only women's coaches with more victories than Stringer are
Conradt (732 in 30 years) and Pat Summitt of Tennessee (702 in 26
years). So it was no surprise that the 2,877 spectators, including
many of Stringer's players from years past, gave her a standing
ovation and kept standing for a small ceremony. With her sons,
David and Justin, at her side, Stringer was presented with a
commemorative basketball and poster and a proclamation from the
governor.
</P>
<P>
   Later, Stringer, 50, was reflective. ``I'm just grateful to have
the opportunity to be in the luckiest profession in the world,''
she said, ``where you can touch so many lives and be able to
translate what happens on the basketball court into the game of
life. In this game, the human spirit prevailed. It was a great win
because of how it was done. This is the point where we want to
start, right here.''
</P>
<P>
   The game had special importance because Rutgers had endured so
many ups and downs in a season in which many people and preseason
polls had predicted the team would reach the Final Four. But after
a lethargic opening loss to North Carolina State, Stringer replaced
most of her starters, including Pointer, the mercurial point guard,
and Stewart, the perimeter bomber. They did not start again until
Saturday.
</P>
<P>
   This was Rutgers' game to win or lose, and the hustle of those
two stars allowed the Scarlet Knights to prevail. The statistics
reflected their paradoxical performances.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart shot 7 for 20, scored a game-high 23 points and had four
assists and four steals. Pointer shot 2 for 9 and scored eight
points, with four assists and five steals. But the numbers did not
fully reflect Rutgers' defensive fury.
</P>
<P>
   Stewart's 3-pointer with 3 minutes 14 seconds left tied the
score at 58-58, and when Rutgers trapped Texas after the inbounds
pass, she stole the ball, was fouled and made two free throws. When
Texas regained the lead on Alisha Sare's 3-pointer, Stewart's layup
put Rutgers ahead for good. Pointer kept the ball away from the
Texas press, and with 15.5 seconds to go she drove to the basket
and banked in a layup.
</P>
<P>
   ``The way we won symbolizes us,'' Stringer said. ``In the last
minutes, I knew we were not going to be denied.''
</P>
<P>
   Rutgers is ranked 16th and Texas 25th in the Associated Press
poll of news media. Rutgers improved its record to 5-2 and the
Longhorns, who had won four straight, fell to 7-3. Texas got a huge
game from forward Edwina Brown, the team's only senior, who had 19
points, seven assists and three steals.
</P>
<P>
   Pointer seemed to speak for her teammates when she said of
Stringer, ``She taught us to dream and dream big.'' Stringer said
the dreaming was over.
</P>
<P>
   ``I slept in this morning,'' she said. ``I didn't get my second
wake-up call. We can sleep through life. We have to call ourselves.
We don't need anyone else to give us our wake-up call. We have our
wake-up call. This is the way we have to play.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
