<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 21:50 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2985 &Cx1f; ttj-z
u s BC-BKN-OLAJUWON-COLUMN-H     12-18 1433
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-OLAJUWON-COLUMN-HNS </SLUG>
  
 (For use by New York Times News Service clients)  
Rumors of Hakeem's demise exaggerated
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; By FRAN BLINEBURY &LR;  &QL; 
 &UR; c. 1999, Houston Chronicle &LR;  &QL;
</P>
<P>
   In the past two weeks, he has seen Charles Barkley go down with
a career-ending knee injury and watched his once-proud team sink
steadily in the standings.
</P>
<P>
   But instead of discouragement, Hakeem Olajuwon feels
determination. Rather than surrendering to the sense of gloom and
looking to rebuild for tomorrow, he still seeks the salvation of a
final Rockets fight for today.
</P>
<P>
   ``This is not the way I want to go out, not the way I want to
end my career,'' Olajuwon said. ``It hurts too much to see us
losing every night and after all that I have been through in 16
years and helped to accomplish with this team, it is not the way I
want people to remember the conclusion.
</P>
<P>
   ``What I want to do is rehabilitate my injury, get back into the
lineup as soon as possible and do anything I can to turn this
around and to play out my contract through next season with the
Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   ``I want to end my career here in Houston. I cannot picture
myself being anywhere else or wearing any other uniform. This is
where everything has happened and where it should come naturally to
its conclusion.''
</P>
<P>
   Since undergoing hernia surgery Dec. 1 that has him sidelined
until at least January, Olajuwon has heard all the gossip and rumor
and innuendo coming from within the Rockets organization and from
assorted hangers-on and locker-room leeches, who say he lacks the
fire and the competitiveness that carried the franchise to two NBA
championships and is looking for the easy way out.
</P>
<P>
   He admits he raised the possibility of the Rockets paying off
the last year of his contract ($16 million for 2000-2001) and
making this his final season. But Olajuwon said that came as one
small part of a wide-ranging discussion of the direction of the
franchise last June with team owner Leslie Alexander and came from
a consideration of going out of the NBA at the same time as
Barkley.
</P>
<P>
   ``We came into the league in the same year and I thought maybe
it would make good timing if we went out together,'' Olajuwon said.
``Les was talking about bringing Charles back for one year and
making this a kind of last run at another championship and I
suggested the possibility.''
</P>
<P>
   It even went so far as to Olajuwon broaching the subject with
coach Rudy Tomjanovich before the season opener and to have a
representative discuss terms of an early buyout with the Rockets.
</P>
<P>
   But that notion was squashed by Olajuwon's injury and the
ensuing catastrophic collapse of Barkley. At first, it all made him
feel sad. Then it made him more determined.
</P>
<P>
   So at halftime of Tuesday's game with the New York Knicks,
Olajuwon met again with Tomjanovich and informed the coach of his
decision to play out his contract, to do everything to help the
Rockets out of their current situation.
</P>
<P>
   Then he talked about the playoffs. This year.
</P>
<P>
   ``Why not?'' Olajuwon said. ``It is December and we have only
played a little more than 20 games. I have never entered a season
in my career where I didn't think it was possible to compete for a
championship and I have never been in a season where anyone gave up
this early.
</P>
<P>
   ``It disturbs me to hear talk of the future, of next year
already. It sounds like you don't want to compete. I know that to a
lot of people, making the playoffs looks impossible to accomplish.
But isn't that where Clutch City came from originally? Didn't most
people think it was impossible in 1994 and 1995?''
</P>
<P>
   He hears the whispers about his age (37 on Jan. 21) and the talk
that he is not the player he once was.
</P>
<P>
   ``Yes, I am getting older, like everyone else in the world,'' he
said. ``But the truth is that before the hernia, this was the first
time in three years that I was feeling pain-free on the court and
able to do all of the things I want to do.
</P>
<P>
   ``People saw me playing in those previous years, but didn't
understand the pain I had in my knees that restricted my play. I
have been working with (Olympic long jumper) Frank Rutherford and
my conditioning now is as good as it was in the championship
seasons.
</P>
<P>
   ``Before anyone says that I cannot do things, I would like the
opportunity to do them first.''
</P>
<P>
   Fingers are pointed to his losing one-on-one matchup with
Shaquille O'Neal last spring in the playoffs.
</P>
<P>
   ``Tell me who can stop Shaq right now in the NBA,'' Olajuwon
said. ``Nobody. But you can beat his team with a strategy that
incorporates everyone and I can be effective.
</P>
<P>
   ``Go back and look at the tapes of the 1995 Finals when we swept
Orlando. Shaq was just as big and I didn't beat him one-on-one. I
beat him in the flow, in the rhythm, by having Clyde (Drexler)
drive and me there to take a pass when Shaq left me. I just played
basketball in the Orlando series and let the opportunities come to
me. I didn't beat Orlando. We beat Orlando.''
</P>
<P>
   He has heard the talk, on the call-in radio shows and on the
street, that he is satisfied with his two NBA titles and is no
longer willing to work. But look at the record. Olajuwon was voted
third-team All-NBA just last season.
</P>
<P>
   He began his rehabilitation from hernia surgery last Monday, the
first day he was released by team physicians.
</P>
<P>
   ``Anybody who has ever had a taste of a championship would know
that the ideal situation is to taste it again,'' Olajuwon said.
``It doesn't make you satisfied. It makes you motivated. Because
nothing else tastes as good.
</P>
<P>
   ``What those people have not looked at is the physical handicaps
I have had to deal with in recent seasons. I did all that I could
with knees that gave me pain and didn't allow the freedom on the
court I would like. But I have also spent more than a year working
to rehabilitate those knees. Would I have done that, put in that
work, if I was already satisfied? What I'm saying is to give me a
chance with those knees and a body that feels good now.''
</P>
<P>
   The knocks have even come from the area of religion, the wild
speculation that because Olajuwon is so devoted to the Islamic
faith, it has made him too much of a pacifist to fight the NBA
wars.
</P>
<P>
   ``I was deep into Islam when we won two championships,'' he
said. ``It gives you strength.
</P>
<P>
   ``I will tell you this about Islam. No NBA owner has ever had to
worry about me. Not about me embarrassing the league or the team or
anyone in Houston that I represent. I act professionally. I act
right. And Islam has made me that way.
</P>
<P>
   ``What Islam has also taught me is to enjoy the present and not
to worry about things that I cannot change. I guess there are those
who say that when we lost the last two years in the first round of
the playoffs and I did not scream or jump up and down, that meant I
didn't care. Well, I have seen guys kick trash cans or make a scene
on the court when they lose. All it does is attract attention to
them. It doesn't mean they care more.
</P>
<P>
   ``When we won the first championship in 1994 and the big
celebration was going on out on the floor, I went to the press
table and sat down and watched it all. I wanted to take in the
experience and remember the feeling, and I will always have it with
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``I had the same beliefs in Islam then that I have now. To say
the difference is my religion is ignorance. In fact, according to
Islam, it would be a criminal act for me to take the full amount of
my salary and not give a full effort. If I care so much about
Islam, about God, then that is exactly the thing that would not let
me give up. In that way, I am my own safety check.''
</P>
<P>
   Olajuwon has been talking for more than an hour now, seated at a
table in an upscale restaurant, but moving, twisting, turning,
simulating shots and moves on the court in between bites of fish
and scallops, those chocolate brown eyes dancing with life.
</P>
<P>
   ``I don't want to stand in anybody's way,'' he said. ``I don't
want to impose myself on a generation of players that thinks my
time is done. I don't want to stand in the way of coaches or
ownership.
</P>
<P>
   ``But after what happened with Charles, after seeing the way the
games have gone, all the losses, I am committed to having this end
the right way.
</P>
<P>
   ``Maybe I'm alone, but I think we have players who can win and
I'm not ready to write off the year.
</P>
<P>
   ``I am going to play next season and I would like it to come to
an end in Houston. It would be 17 years, all here, the way it
should be.''
</P>
<P>
   Some might say the fitting end to a Dream.
</P>
<P>
   ``But I'm telling you,'' Hakeem Olajuwon said, ``it isn't
over.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
