<DOCTYPE> NEWS STORY </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 21:55 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A2989 &Cx1f; tic-z
r a BC-MAY-RESERVE-AZR &LR;      12-18 1379
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-MAY-RESERVE-AZR </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
RELUCTANT MAY FORCED TO
 STAND IN THE LIMELIGHT
</HEADLINE>
  (For use by N.Y. Times News Service
 clients) 
 By MARK SHAFFER 
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic 
<TEXT>
<P>
   Steve May quickens his pace toward his office in the state
House.
</P>
<P>
   He stops a research analyst in the corridor. Why shouldn't
chiroprac tors be allowed to join HMOs? Why can't the state create
a fund for the working poor who make too much to qualify for
AHCCCS?
</P>
<P>
   Another analyst is within earshot. Give me a bill, quick, that
makes House members declare conflicts of interest if they have
business before other representatives.
</P>
<P>
   May slips into his office, dominated by a bust of Abraham
Lincoln. The phone rings. A worker at his herb import store in
Tempe has been caught downloading porn on the company computers.
He's got to be fired, May says.
</P>
<P>
   ``La vida loca,'' May says repeatedly of the dizzying pace.
</P>
<P>
   The crazy life.
</P>
<P>
   But mostly these days, people want to slow down the freshman
legislator and freeze-frame the one issue he feels uncomfortable
about.
</P>
<P>
   May wishes they wouldn't ask. Be cause he's got a lot more to
tell beyond being gay and fighting to save his military career.
</P>
<P>
   It's the one irony, the one conun drum of Steve May: the public
limelight and national prominence he's bathing in stem from a
disclo sure he was loath to make.
</P>
<P>
   He is wary because he wants to be known as a serious legislator,
not the Rosa Parks of gays in the military. He is wary because his
sexual orientation has become a constant qualifier: conservative,
but gay; Re publican, but gay; military officer, but gay; rising
political star, but gay.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think my constituents are tired of hearing about my private
life. I am tired of talking about it,'' May wrote in an e-mail to
The Republic about this profile. ``If my constituents are led to
believe that all I do is talk about my private life or spend all my
time fighting this military policy, they may choose not to vote for
me.
</P>
<P>
   ``In fact, I wouldn't vote for myself if that were true.''
</P>
<P>
   May has always sought to safeguard his privacy, even among
family. This, long before a fellow Army reservist complained about
May's public ad mission of being gay, triggering an investigation
that now threatens to drum him out of the armed services.
</P>
<P>
   May's sister, Shannon, a Chinese-studies student at Harvard,
said she was in the dark until four years ago, when she visited his
alma mater, Claremont McKenna College in Cal ifornia, on a
recruiting trip.
</P>
<P>
   ``I went to this party and there were these friends of his
talking about how good he looked at Halloween in drag. I walked
around the campus for five hours that night thinking and trying to
sort all that out,'' Shannon May said.
</P>
<P>
   She said she kept dropping hints to her brother, trying to find
out more details about his life.
</P>
<P>
   ``Finally, he was at a party one night with his significant
other and looked at me and said, `He's it,' and then just walked
away,'' she said.
</P>
<P>
   Jim May, an old-school Mormon, said he was crushed when his son
told him a decade ago that he was gay and wouldn't be going on a
mission for the church. Jim says he prays daily for Steve, who once
taught Sunday school in the faith, to come back to the fold and
receive his ``higher spiritual blessing.'' But he offers one small
caveat.
</P>
<P>
   ``You have flaming homosexuals, but Steve is definitely not
that. I've never seen him and his partner touch one another and
display it in public,'' Jim said.
</P>
<P>
   There are detractors, such as Rep. Karen Johnson, who say that
despite Steve May's protestation otherwise, his sexuality is part
of his politics.
</P>
<P>
   ``He's an extremely angry man who knows his lifestyle is wrong
but is doing everything he can to try to validate it,'' said
Johnson, R-Mesa. The two clashed bitterly earlier this year over
proposed legislation that would deny insurance benefits to gay and
unmarried couples. The bill failed.
</P>
<P>
   ``We were talking in my office once about it and he said,
`You're attack ing me and my family' and got very angry,'' she
said. ``He said that people like Pat Robertson and others will burn
in hell for what they were doing on that issue.''
</P>
<P>
   Johnson also said that May ``tries to turn everything into a
homosexual issue.''
</P>
<P>
   ``He changed his vote once on the floor because he said he got
an e-mail from his `spouse' wanting him to,'' Johnson said.
</P>
<P>
   May's significant other, Paul Quinn, an instructor at Arizona
State Uni versity, said May would have chosen to stay in the closet
had a campaign supporter not outed him three years ago.
</P>
<P>
   ``It hurt me because he felt he had to hide me,'' Quinn said.
``But being gay is a part of him that he can't put aside. At times,
I've thought and wondered whether I or politics come first.''
</P>
<P>
   May has always been somewhat of a political animal, who toiled
in calcu lated fashion to fulfill his ambitions.
</P>
<P>
   Classmates in the eighth grade called him ``Mr. President.''
Shannon said her brother carried a copy of the Bill of Rights in
his backpack to junior high and wouldn't hesitate to go with it to
the principal's office when he felt a disadvantaged student was
being hassled.
</P>
<P>
   At Arcadia High School, where he was president of his class for
two years, May led a massive demonstra tion when he was a freshman
in protest of the campus being closed at lunchtime. He later spoke
to the School Board about the matter.
</P>
<P>
   There was the time in college when he got rid of his bed so he
could put a large desk from the ROTC depart ment in his room and
study through out the night. He would throw down a sleeping bag at
times and catch a couple hours of shut eye.
</P>
<P>
   Colleagues at the Legislature say he's well-prepared and
doggedly deter mined.
</P>
<P>
   May said he originally had intended to go into the Navy until he
spent two months of boring duty aboard a nuclear submarine. He then
switched to the Army, where he was stationed at Fort Riley, Kan.,
from 1993 until 1995 where he was a nuclear, biologi cal and
chemical defense officer.
</P>
<P>
   The most eventful thing during that time, May said, was having
the misfortune of having a mailbox located next to Oklahoma City
bombing accomplice Terry Nichols, who also had been stationed at
Fort Riley. Because May also had traveled to Oklahoma City, albeit
to help victims of the bombing, he attracted an uncomfortable
amount of interest from FBI agents.
</P>
<P>
   After his military time was over and he went on inactive reserve
until being called up last spring, May poured his energy into the
family business, importing stevia, a leaf extract from Paraguay
that has become a popular sweetener in Asia.
</P>
<P>
   That coincided with Steve May's leaving the military. He jumped
in to the private sector with gusto for research and development
and re cently started marketing the herb, which he hopes will
ultimately give artificial sugar products a run for their money.
</P>
<P>
   ``I would have brought that product online in 1997,'' May said.
``But I've got this stupid political habit.''
</P>
<P>
   Political savvy, too. He handicaps his sexual orientation and
figures that about 20 percent of the electorate will outright not
support him. May concentrates on crafting his political message to
the rest.
</P>
<P>
   Even his battle with the Army over the ``Don't ask, don't tell''
policy seems more for self-preservation and political image rather
than for gay rights.
</P>
<P>
   ``I think if there was an office he really wanted, like
president, he would renounce his homosexuality,'' said Air Force
Capt. Rachel Jacobs, May's best friend while growing up in Phoenix.
</P>
<P>
   But even though he is trying to raise $100,000 on his Web site
to pay for his legal fight, May maintains he is not an advocate of
gay rights. Nor does he want his political career to be defined by
such a narrow issue.
</P>
<P>
   ``My electoral challenge is to demon strate to my voters that I
am a good legislator _ that I am not fighting the Army, but
fighting for our common political agenda of better schools, lower
taxes, smaller govern ment, more liberty, better health care. . . .
</P>
<P>
   ``I have never chosen to make my private life public, but
circumstances gave me no other option. Many politicians would fight
ferociously for this level of attention. I don't want to be
well-known, just well-re spected.''
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
