<HEADLINE>
CLINTON CRITIC BLAMES OTHERS, TOO 
</HEADLINE>
   (For use by N.Y. Times News Service clients)  
 By BY STEVE WILSON  
 c.1999 The Arizona Republic  
<TEXT>
<P>
   The Arizona Republic &QL; 
Richard A. Posner has one of the keenest minds in America.
</P>
<P>
   He graduated summa cum laude from Yale and No. 1 in his class at
Harvard Law School. American Lawyer magazine called him ``the most
brilliant judge in the country.''
</P>
<P>
   He was appointed to the 7th U.S. Circuit Court of Appeals by
Ronald Reagan. Though conservatively in clined, Posner is famously
unpre dictable and holds some unconservative views, such as sup
porting the legalization of mari juana.
</P>
<P>
   Now 60, he's also written 30 books and hundreds of articles. His
influential output has brought com parisons to the great Oliver
Wendell Holmes.
</P>
<P>
   ``I read Richard Posner for the same reason I watch Jean-Claude
Van Damme movies,'' said Stephen Presser, a law professor at North
western University. ``In both cases, you get to see the master of a
discipline pulverize his foes.''
</P>
<P>
   He was recently picked to medi ate talks in the Microsoft case.
Antitrust experts say if anyone can get Bill Gates and Janet Reno
to agree, Posner can.
</P>
<P>
   I'm writing about him, however, because of his insight into a
differ ent matter: the impeachment one year ago of President
Clinton.
</P>
<P>
   His book, An Affair of State, is the most lucid that's been
written. Posner delivers a level-headed and withering appraisal of
virtually ev eryone involved.
</P>
<P>
   He faults the U.S. Supreme Court for its ``naive and imprudent''
decision that enabled Paula Jones to proceed with her lawsuit while
Clinton was still in office. He accuses Ken Starr of invading
Clinton's privacy by including too much gratuitous sex in his
report. He scorns ``Clinton haters'' and ``moralistic
conservatives'' who be came apoplectic over the sexual affair.
</P>
<P>
   But Posner comes down hardest on the president. He finds the
evidence ``clear beyond reasonable doubt'' that Clinton obstructed
jus tice by:
</P>
<P>
   1. Perjuring himself repeatedly in his deposition in the Paula
Jones case, in his testimony before the grand jury, and in his
responses to the House Judiciary Committee.
</P>
<P>
   2. Tampering with a witness, Monica Lewinsky, by encouraging her
to give a false affidavit and hide gifts he gave her.
</P>
<P>
   3. Suborning perjury by suggest ing to Lewinsky that she give a
false explanation about why she was transferred from the White
House to the Pentagon.
</P>
<P>
   The president's defense infuriated Posner. He described it as
``grounded in quibbling, hairsplit ting, equivocation and brazen
denial of the obvious.''
</P>
<P>
   So Clinton should have been convicted as well as impeached,
right?
</P>
<P>
   Posner doesn't say, choosing in stead to explain why reasonable
minds would disagree, depending on whether they were ``rigorists''
or ``pragmatists.''
</P>
<P>
   Most people who wanted Clinton convicted, the rigorists, focused
on the rule of law and moral values. In both regards, they felt his
conduct warranted removal from office.
</P>
<P>
   Most on the pro-Clinton side were pragmatists and more likely to
place more importance on other factors. These include the impeach
ment's highly partisan nature, weak ening of the presidency in
favor of Congress, and overturning popular will, as reflected in
both the '96 election and the opinion polls.
</P>
<P>
   Although Posner withholds judg ment, he leans toward the view
that impeachment was warranted and conviction wasn't. He notes that
Clinton could not receive legal justice in the Senate, since nearly
all of the 100 senators were so biased they would been bounced in a
real trial. Their assessment of the facts was at best unreliable.
</P>
<P>
   Posner's powerful intellect doesn't make him right, but I think
he's dead-on. Neither side was com pletely right or wrong; they
placed priority on different values. Yet the public debate, as well
as the one in Congress, was unbending, ugly and often foolish.
</P>
<P>
   He cites ``the recklessness with which many intelligent people,
in cluding academics, took sides pas sionately and dogmatically
before it was possible to know what the facts were, their refusal
to face the facts when they became known, their unwillingness to
concede any merit to points made by opponents, their proneness to
exaggeration, distor tion and oversimplification, and the sheer
unreason demonstrated by so many.''
</P>
<P>
   Clinton's conduct was bad. The shrill response was no better.
We're lucky things didn't turn out worse.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 2235EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
