<SLUG> BC-NY-FATAL-FUMES-1STLD-WRITETHRU-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
WORKER KILLED AND SEVERAL SICKENED BY FUMES AT TIMES SQUARE CLUB
</HEADLINE>
  (UPDATES throughout) 
 (jw) 
 By KATHERINE E. FINKELSTEIN   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Carbon monoxide fumes from a defective heating system
killed a kitchen worker at a popular supper club near Times Square
Saturday and left four others hospitalized, two in critical
condition.
</P>
<P>
   Five rescue workers who helped treat the victims were also
overcome by fumes and three were admitted to hospitals, while two
were treated and released.
</P>
<P>
   An employee who first discovered the unconscious men in the
basement of the restaurant, Laura Belle at 120 W. 43rd St., was
treated at the scene, where 19 emergency vehicles converged
Saturday morning. The police closed off the block, evacuated a
building next door and checked manholes and nearby basements for
further evidence of the gas.
</P>
<P>
   A Fire Department spokesman, Paul Iannizzotto, said that a
faulty heating system had caused carbon monoxide levels to soar in
the basement.
</P>
<P>
   Police detectives, with help from Consolidated Edison and the
city's Department of Buildings, were investigating the cause of the
fumes and the death, said Det Joseph Pentangelo, a police
spokesman. ``No arrests have been made or summonses issued at this
time,'' he said, calling the case active.
</P>
<P>
   But one police official who spoke on condition of anonymity said
that investigators were focusing on whether the workers, who
appeared to be sleeping in the basement with their shoes off and
tablecloths draped over them for blankets, had tampered with an oil
burner, perhaps in an effort to adjust the heat.
</P>
<P>
   The level of carbon monoxide in the basement was extremely high,
said Thomas Galvin, a Fire Department division chief. In some areas
firefighters recorded levels of over 500 parts per million,
compared with a safe level of 35 parts per million, he said.
</P>
<P>
   The deadly effects of the carbon monoxide may have been
aggravated by a mixture of cleaning fluids found in the basement _
a noxious blend of ammonia, window cleaner and bleach, Galvin said.
</P>
<P>
   As firefighters dragged the five unconscious workers from the
restaurant shortly after 10 a.m., a manager and several workers
from the day shift stood in the faint winter sun and wept. ``I left
here at 2 a.m.,'' said Joanne O'Connor, the club's banquet manager,
who stood surrounded by firefighters and plainclothes police
officers. ``Everything was fine.''
</P>
<P>
   The restaurant owner, Michael ``Buzzy'' O'Keefee, who also owns
the River Cafe and Water Club, said through a spokesman that all
the workers were legal immigrants, and that to his knowledge they
did not sleep in the building. He said that at the Fire
Department's request, he would not discuss matters being
investigated. The spokesman, Ken Frydman, said that O'Keefee was
cooperating with the investigation and planned to visit the workers
and their families at the hospital Saturday night. ``It's a very
odd and tragic accident,'' Frydman said. ``That staff is like a
family.''
</P>
<P>
   The two-story brick building is owned by the 121 West 42nd
Street Associates. One of the company directors, Robert Z. Brandt,
reached by telephone Saturday night, said that O'Keefee, as the
tenant of the building, was responsible for its upkeep and
operation.
</P>
<P>
   The workers, who began their shifts at 10 p.m. on Friday night,
were still wearing white kitchen uniforms when they were hefted
onto stretchers and raced to waiting ambulances. One worker, Ernest
Freycinet, 53, died of cardiac arrest en route to St.
Luke's-Roosevelt Hospital Center, said a hospital spokesman.
</P>
<P>
   The four other workers were transferred from two Manhattan
hospitals to Jacobi Medical Center in the Bronx, for oxygen
treatment in a hyperbaric chamber, said Nancy I.
McPartlin-Gardella, a hospital spokeswoman. Two of them _ Yeves
Robert Herve, 25, and Siloe Mirlin, who is in his 20s _ were in
critical condition, she said. Two others, Yvon Joseph, 30, and
Victor St. Ives, 43, were in stable condition, she said.
</P>
<P>
   The employees were first discovered shortly after 9:30 a.m.,
when Gary Marcius, a day-shift employee, arrived to lock up the
night club and found the five workers unconscious on the basement
floor, one in a small office. ``I go downstairs, and all of them
lay down,'' Marcius said outside of Laura Belle, his eyes welling
with tears. ``I say, `What is it?' but nobody talking.''
</P>
<P>
   Marcius said that he then raced upstairs and called 911.
</P>
<P>
   The first ambulance arrived at 10 a.m. and two emergency medical
technicians, along with a police officer, descended into the club,
called for backup and brought out Freycinet, the most seriously
injured, said Iannizzotto of the Fire Department.
</P>
<P>
   Three minutes later, firefighters with masks arrived and dragged
out the four remaining men.
</P>
<P>
   Those rescue workers first on the scene quickly began to feel
ill. As the ambulance bearing Freycinet sped toward St. Clare's
Hospital and Health Center, the two emergency medical technicians
and the police officer developed headaches and nausea, and pulled
to the curb and radioed for help, Iannizzotto said.
</P>
<P>
   Ambulances arrived and took Freycinet to Roosevelt Hospital,
where he was pronounced dead on arrival. The two emergency workers
were taken to New York-Presbyterian Hospital, where they were hosed
down as a precautionary measure and were in stable condition with
respiratory problems, one of their co-workers said. The Fire
Department did not release their names.
</P>
<P>
   The police officer was taken to St. Clare's Hospital, and was in
stable condition.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
NYT-12-18-99 2239EST &QL; 
</TRAILER>
