<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-HKN-DEVILS-CAPITALS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DEVILS WIN BATTLE OF BACKUP GOALIES OVER CAPITALS 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By ALEX YANNIS   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   EAST RUTHERFORD, N.J. _ Two starting goaltenders who played for
the first time this month offered nothing spectacular. Chris
Terreri of the Devils was slightly better than Craig Billington of
the Capitals, however, and helped the Devils to a 5-4 victory over
Washington Saturday night before nearly 7,000 empty seats at
Continental Arena.
</P>
<P>
   Two goals 66 seconds apart early in the third period, by John
Madden and Patrik Elias, the second of the night for each, gave the
Devils their third consecutive victory for the first time this
season.
</P>
<P>
   Claude Lemieux scored the other goal for the Devils, who
improved to 18-10-3.
</P>
<P>
   Terreri posted his first victory of the season on 17 saves and
improved his record to 1-3-0. He allowed two goals to Sergei
Gonchar and one each to Chris Simon and Jeff Halpern. Terreri had
much more protection than Billington, who faced 43 shots and was
often left completely exposed to the Devils.
</P>
<P>
   For the Capitals (12-14-5), who beat the Rangers in overtime a
night earlier, the game was their third on the road in four nights
and ended a two-game winning streak. &QL;
</P>
<P>
   Terreri's previous start was Nov. 25, in a loss to Phoenix,
while Billington's previous start was two days later, in a victory
over the Islanders. This was Terreri's fifth appearance of the
season and Billington's sixth.
</P>
<P>
   Billington was greeted with a barrage of shots from the outset.
He faced the first eight shots in the game and 16 before the first
intermission. His glove saves on Petr Sykora in the 10th minute and
Scott Gomez in the last minute of the period were his most
difficult.
</P>
<P>
   Terreri had little to do for the first 10 minutes but then
allowed Simon's sixth goal of the season on the first shot he
faced, 10 minutes 11 seconds into the game. Simon started the play
when he took the puck from Sheldon Souray behind Terreri, left it
there and went in front to beat Terreri with a rising shot after a
pass by Adam Oates.
</P>
<P>
   Loss of concentration cost the Devils early in the second
period. They were caught with too many men on the ice 2:26 into the
period, and Washington capitalized 30 seconds later when Gonchar
beat Terreri from the slot with help from Ulf Dahlen's screen.
</P>
<P>
   A good move on the right by Brian Rafalksi and a pass from the
left side by Scott Stevens found Madden in the slot for his fourth
goal of the season, 4:41 into the period, to narrow the gap to 2-1.
</P>
<P>
   Halpern scored at 12:32 of the second period to give Washington
a 3-1 lead. But two power-play goals, by Elias with 4:19 left and
Lemieux with 2:51 left, tied the score for the Devils, who had a
two-man advantage when Elias scored his third goal of the season.
Lemieux's goal was his ninth.
</P>
<P>
   The Capitals retook the lead just eight seconds later, however,
when Gonchar beat Terreri from close range on the right for his
second goal of the night to make it 4-3.  &QL; 
 &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
