<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKN-NETS-CAVALIERS-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NETS OVERCOME LOSSES IN WIN OVER CAVALIERS, 98-74 
</HEADLINE>
  (rk) 
 By CHUCK MURR   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   CLEVELAND _ The final score does not reflect it, but the New
Jersey Nets overcame plenty of adversity Saturday night in a 98-74
rout of the Cleveland Cavaliers, just the fourth time the Nets have
won in their last 30 games in Cleveland.
</P>
<P>
   The perimeter shooting of Kerry Kittles, Johnny Newman and
Stephon Marbury lifted the Nets to an easy victory even though
forwards Keith Van Horn and Kendall Gill missed much of the game.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn was in foul trouble throughout, scoring just four
points in 13 minutes, and Gill went out with 5 minutes 50 seconds
left in the first quarter with an ankle injury. Both, however,
contributed in a decisive third quarter in which the Nets (7-17)
outscored Cleveland, 27-9.
</P>
<P>
   Kittles and Marbury each scored 18 points and Newman added 17 in
the Nets' biggest margin of victory this season. The Nets have won
five of their last seven games.
</P>
<P>
   Kittles did much of his damage from the free-throw line, hitting
8 of 9 free throws.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets' defensive effort and Cleveland's lackluster play in
the second and third quarters resulted in two decisive runs for the
Nets, with easy transition baskets.
</P>
<P>
   The Cavaliers were scoreless for 4:58 late in the second
quarter, then opened the third quarter without a point for the
first 4:01.
</P>
<P>
   Van Horn, scoreless in the first half, had his four points at
the outset of the second half before picking up a fifth foul and
going to the bench to stay. Gill had two points in the quarter
before also going to the bench to rest his ankle.
</P>
<P>
   Shawn Kemp, who had scored 36 points in Cleveland's 111-101 loss
at the Meadowlands on Wednesday night, scored 14 to lead the
Cavaliers (11-12).
</P>
<P>
   Last week Cleveland guard Bob Sura had lamented that his team
should have a much better record. ``Teams are coming out and
punching us in the mouth, and we don't respond,'' he said after
consecutive road losses to the Nets and the Charlotte Hornets.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets took command with a 17-2 run to open the second half.
The Nets' defense forced the Cavaliers into four turnovers in their
first eight possessions while Kittles and Marbury hit their shots
from the perimeter to give the Nets a 63-45 lead.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland scored just nine points in the third quarter as the
Nets opened a 73-52 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets started the game badly. They had just two free throws
by Kittles in their first six possessions. On their other five
possessions, they committed two offensive fouls, twice turned the
ball over on bad passes and had another pass stolen by Kemp.
</P>
<P>
   Cleveland, coming off a 99-86 loss Friday night in Charlotte,
got its running game in gear early to take a 15-12 lead.
</P>
<P>
   The Nets turned the game around midway through the first period,
however, when Newman replaced Gill. Newman sparked an 18-2 run by
the Nets.
</P>
<P>
   Newman made a 19-foot jump shot from the right side and a
3-point shot from the left baseline to start the run. Kittles had
consecutive 3-pointers in the spurt that gave the Nets a 30-17
lead.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
