<DOCTYPE> MISCELLANEOUS TEXT (slug-filter) </DOCTYPE>
<DATE_TIME> 1999-12-18 23:06 </DATE_TIME>
<HEADER>
A3220 &Cx1f; taf-z
s e BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS     12-18 0850
</HEADER>
<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-NOTEWORTHY-PAPERBACKS-$ADV26-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
NEW &AMP; NOTEWORTHY PAPERBACKS 
</HEADLINE>
   (For release Sunday, Dec. 26)  
(lb) 
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service   
<TEXT>
<P>
   &UR; NORWOOD &LR;  By Charles Portis. Overlook, $13.95. The author's
first novel follows the picaresque adventures of Norwood Pratt, a
good-hearted ex-marine and folk singer whose cross-country odyssey
takes him through the bowling alleys, roller dromes, chili parlors
and bus stations of 1960s America. In 1966 the reviewer Martin
Levin called this a ``delightfully original'' tale imbued with
``the magic of a fable.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE VICTORS: Eisenhower and His Boys. The Men of World War II &LR; 
By Stephen E. Ambrose. Touchstone/Simon &AMP; Schuster, $16. This
account of the Allied campaign in Europe, which draws heavily from
unit histories and interviews (and five of the author's previous
books), combines the experiences of infantrymen with a portrait of
Gen. Dwight D. Eisenhower's formidable leadership, which echoed
down through the ranks. ``Ambrose is a superb historian,''
Nathaniel Tripp wrote in 1998. ``He has the details and he has the
voice.''
</P>
<P>
   In  &UR; THE SUPREME COMMANDER: The War Years of General Dwight D.
Eisenhower &LR;  (University Press of Mississippi, $20), Ambrose
chronicles the making of a general, creating a portrait of a lucky
and gifted leader who blended great self-assurance with a capacity
to listen to others and learn from them. The result is an
``extraordinarily fascinating book,'' Gordon Harrison wrote in the
Book Review in 1970.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE RUM DIARY &LR;  By Hunter Thompson. Scribner, $12. There are no
drugs but lots of sex and booze in the author's first novel,
written in his pre-gonzo days, which chronicles the escapades of a
morose New York journalist in Puerto Rico in the 1950s. Last year
the reviewer David Kelly said Thompson evokes the exuberant world
of San Juan ``with some flair.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; THE PHYSICS OF CHRISTMAS: From the Aerodynamics of Reindeer to
the Thermodynamics of Turkey &LR;  By Roger Highfield. Back Bay/Little,
Brown, $12.95. Why is Rudolph's nose red? Can Christmas trees be
cloned? A British journalist holds forth on a wide range of
yuletide phenomena, including holiday hangovers and the mystery of
the Star of Bethlehem. Last year the reviewer Simon Singh called
this ``a delightful compendium of seasonal science'' filled with
``genuine insights as well as fanciful speculation.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; GATES OF EDEN: Stories &LR;  By Ethan Coen. Delta, $12.95. The
writing half of the Coen brothers' moviemaking franchise spins 14
tales about dog castration, Minneapolis mafiosi, deaf private eyes
and the like. It's ``a parallel universe similar to our own _
except it's weirder, funnier and better edited,'' Mark Lindquist
wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; MY FIRST COUSIN ONCE REMOVED: Money, Madness, and the Family of
Robert Lowell &LR;  By Sarah Payne Stuart. HarperPerennial, $13. This
memoir is about a proudly eccentric family of Boston aristocrats,
among them the poet Robert Lowell, for whom stoicism often runs
side by side with mental illness. ``It is a survivor's story, with
so much intelligence, humor and affection ... that even the
monsters it occasionally offers up are appealing,'' Reeve Lindbergh
wrote last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; WALK ON WATER: A Memoir &LR; , by Lorian Hemingway
(Harvest/Harcourt, $13), is another survivor's story, in which a
granddaughter of Ernest Hemingway writes of her passion for fishing
and her struggle with alcoholism. ``Eloquent, raw, funny, this
Hemingway has a voice all her own,'' Carol Peace Robins wrote in
1998.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JOURNEY TO THE LAND OF THE FLIES: And Other Travels &LR;  By Aldo
Buzzi. Steerforth, $10. In these erudite travel essays, the Italian
author skips from present to past to future in discussing the
cuisine, toilet habits and cultural quirks he has encountered in
places like Moscow, Gorgonzola, London and Jakarta. In 1996 the
reviewer Harlow Robinson called Buzzi a ``well-read and extremely
imaginative'' tour guide and praised his ``bizarre and vivid
scholarship.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; ROAD-SIDE DOG &LR;  By Czeslaw Milosz. Farrar, Straus &AMP; Giroux, $13.
This collection of poems, anecdotes and cryptic essays by the
Polish writer dwells on themes like memory, aging and the need to
create order out of the chaos of history. It is ``a difficult
pleasure, but it is a pleasure,'' Richard Bernstein wrote in The
Times last year.
</P>
<P>
   &UR; JOHN DOLLAR &LR;  By Marianne Wiggins. Washington Square/Pocket
Books, $14. In 1917, a British schoolteacher is stranded on a
remote Burmese island with her lover and eight girls after a tidal
wave capsizes their boat, leaving them to play out a female version
of ``Lord of the Flies.'' In 1989 the reviewer Michael Gorra called
this a ``provocative novel'' and admired its ``pitiless and
brilliant prose.''
</P>
<P>
   &UR; STORM TIDE &LR;  By Marge Piercy and Ira Wood. Fawcett/Ballantine,
$12.95. This novel about the political and romantic education of a
failed baseball player in his hometown on Cape Cod is the
collaborative effort of a husband-and-wife team. ``But the book
itself speaks with one powerful voice,'' Ruth Coughlin wrote in
1998.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
<TRAILER>
