<SLUG> BC-BKN-ODOM-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
ODOM BRINGS MAGIC TO CLIPPERS
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By ANDREW BAGGARLY  
 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ You watch Lamar Odom zing cross-court outlets and
take long strides to the basket, and yes, you have to admit it.
</P>
<P>
   There's a hint of Magic in his game.
</P>
<P>
   The celebrated Clippers rookie has the same court awareness as
Magic Johnson, the same ability to find open teammates while
staring straight ahead. You watch the 6-foot-10 Odom survey the
floor from the top of the key and you can't help but envision the
6-9 Magic Man, looking for James Worthy on the wing.
</P>
<P>
   ``It's the compliment of a lifetime,'' Odom said. ``He
accomplished so many great things and made a big impact on the
game. To be mentioned with him is a great honor.''
</P>
<P>
   But such a comparison probably isn't good for a fragile
19-year-old _ especially when you play in the same city where
Johnson reigned, and for the team with a chronic inferiority
complex to Johnson's Lakers.
</P>
<P>
   Even though the comparison sets up expectations of greatness,
Odom welcomes the added pressure.
</P>
<P>
   ``Pressure makes you elevate,'' Odom said. ``I like to have
pressure. All good players do. It makes you perform.''
</P>
<P>
   The Clippers knew they had a special player when Odom went for
30 points and 12 rebounds in his debut against Seattle. He scored
in double figures in each of his first 19 games.
</P>
<P>
   But then he made just 3-of-14 from the floor in scoring eight
points against Indiana last Saturday. Foul trouble held him to
eight again Monday against Vancouver.
</P>
<P>
   Then, with the Clippers wearing road jerseys against their
Staples Center co-tenants on Tuesday, Odom _ and the rest of the
team _ suffered a complete collapse.
</P>
<P>
   With Johnson watching from the second row of the stands, Odom
failed to make a field goal for the first time in his NBA career,
finishing with two points in 22 minutes. The exasperated and
intimidated Clippers scored an NBA-record low 19 points in the
first half.
</P>
<P>
   Odom knew the Clippers couldn't let that punishing loss linger.
So the next game against Golden State on Friday, he did something
about it.
</P>
<P>
   The Warriors were up five with 1:11 to play when Odom made two
free throws, stole a pass, assisted on a Tyrone Nesby dunk, grabbed
a defensive rebound, scored the go-ahead basket over Donyell
Marshall with 11.9 to play, then knocked away a loose ball as time
expired.
</P>
<P>
   Yes, all that in one minute.
</P>
<P>
   ``He was spectacular. He put the team on his back,'' Ford said.
</P>
<P>
   ``He elevated his game over everyone else,'' said Keith Closs,
who bear-hugged Odom after the buzzer sounded, just like when Magic
wrapped his arms around Kareem Abdul-Jabbar after his first pro
game.
</P>
<P>
   This wasn't Odom's first game. But it wasn't the last one he'll
win in the final seconds, either.
</P>
<P>
   ``The game was on the line, and a play had to be made by
someone,'' Odom said. ``After losing to the Lakers the way we did,
we had to get a win to start over.''
</P>
<P>
   Odom has many of Magic's attributes. All that's missing are the
tall socks and the too-tight shorts.
</P>
<P>
   And one more thing. A supporting cast.
</P>
<P>
   Odom has yet to record his first triple-double. He keeps coming
up short in assists, where his career high is seven.
</P>
<P>
   ``Lamar could make the greatest pass on earth,'' Clippers coach
Chris Ford said, ``but it doesn't count if the other guy doesn't
make the basket. If you haven't noticed, we haven't been making a
lot of shots.''
</P>
<P>
   But even though these are the Clippers, they still benefit from
Odom's presence.
</P>
<P>
   ``He makes everyone around him better,'' Closs said.
</P>
<P>
   Didn't they say that about an oversized point guard from
Michigan State?
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
