<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-BKC-OBERJUERGE-COLUMN-LADN </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
UCLA KEEPS FANS GUESSING
</HEADLINE>
 (For use by NYTimes News Service clients) 
By PAUL OBERJUERGE  
 San Bernardino County Sun  
<TEXT>
<P>
   LOS ANGELES _ Buckle up, UCLA basketball fans, and keep your
hands inside the compartment at all times. It's going to be another
one of those roller-coaster seasons.
</P>
<P>
   Giddy highs. Stomach-churning lows.
</P>
<P>
   Times so good as to defy our powers of description. Stretches of
incompetence so deep, so profound as to bring the future of the
program into question.
</P>
<P>
   There's something about UCLA under coach Steve Lavin _ or is it
the nature of modern college basketball? _ that makes for a
penthouse/outhouse existence, with precious little in between.
</P>
<P>
   Already, the 1999-2000 Bruins have shown a pronounced bipolar
condition. On successive Saturdays at Pauley Pavilion they were
thrashed by 24th-ranked Gonzaga, 59-43 ... and routed 19th-ranked
DePaul, 76-58.
</P>
<P>
   Which team is the real Bruins?
</P>
<P>
   Both of them, as usual.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the Bruins have talent aplenty, both in terms of
individual brilliance and athletic virtuosity. ``Top five, six,
seven talent,'' former UCLA coach Jim Harrick said. Talent enough,
certainly, to defeat nearly any team in the nation.
</P>
<P>
   Again, the Bruins have faults aplenty to render them helpless
against any opponent. Particularly patient, seasoned, well-coached
opponents.
</P>
<P>
   Even within the context of a single game, the Good Bruins and
the Bad Bruins are on display.
</P>
<P>
   The good Bruins are impressive. A couple of active 7-foot
sophomores in Dan Gadzuric and Jerome Moiso. A fearless freshman
forward, Jason Kapono, who knows you can't make shots without
taking them. A create-a-look wing in Ray Young. A heady point guard
in Earl Watson.
</P>
<P>
   It was that crew that broke open a 30-28 game Saturday with a
23-3 surge. It featured unselfish play, frenetic defense, a trio of
three-pointers by Kapono and 10 points in the paint by the big men.
</P>
<P>
   The bad Bruins, however, are scary. They throw passes into the
stands. They yap at each other. Their fundamentals bring to mind
junior high. They string together more bonehead plays than a
quintet of Neanderthals.
</P>
<P>
   That was the gang that let DePaul lead 26-24 at half despite 38
percent shooting. That nearly drove Pauley Pavilion fans to
distraction by casting off three three-pointers in the final two
minutes pf a 12-point game when a clever team pulls the ball out
and milks the clock.
</P>
<P>
   ``Obviously, there are things we need to work on,'' Lavin said.
``We're not a finished product, after five games.''
</P>
<P>
   And, as always, there are off-court issues.
</P>
<P>
   JaRon Rush, the team's No.3 scorer, is sitting out while the
school investigates possible NCAA violations. Billy Knight, a
useful forward, only Saturday regained his eligibility because of
academic difficulties.
</P>
<P>
   Through it all, Lavin keeps up his steady patter of positive
thinking. We're getting better. We're learning. We're coming along.
</P>
<P>
   We know from experience, though, that Lavin's Bruins are always
a bit behind the learning curve. Often, their sheer talent pulls
them through. On other occasions, against a Detroit Mercy or a
Gonzaga, they melt down.
</P>
<P>
   Bottom line? UCLA probably is good enough to finish in the top
four of the Pac-10, maintain a top-25 ranking and make the NCAA
tournament.
</P>
<P>
   But UCLA also isn't vaguely steady enough to last long in the
playoffs. Every roller-coaster has a big dip coming any moment.
</P>
<P>
   &QL;
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
