<BODY>
<SLUG> BC-TAXI-SALE-NYT </SLUG>
<HEADLINE>
DUELING FOR CAB, ARMS UP, BUT THIS TIME AT SOTHEBY'S
</HEADLINE>
   (rk) 
 By TINA KELLEY   
 c.1999 N.Y. Times News Service    
<TEXT>
<P>
   NEW YORK _ Like riders trying to flag a taxi on a rainy day,
bidders competed Saturday for the last Checker cab to roam the
streets of New York _ which was auctioned off for $134,500.
</P>
<P>
   The cab, which has traveled 994,050 miles, about 40 times the
circumference of the earth, belonged to its original owner and
driver, Earl Johnson, who retired in July and moved to Montego Bay,
Jamaica.
</P>
<P>
   In a telephone interview after the sale, Johnson said he
remembered paying about $9,000 for the cab, a 1978 Marathon sedan.
He drove for more than 20 years, carrying, among others, Walter
Cronkite, Muhammad Ali, and two riders from Wall Street to Grand
Central Terminal _ the only passengers who ever cheated him out of
a fare.
</P>
<P>
   He reminisced about the cab that had gone so many miles. ``I do
miss it. I don't know when I will ever get over it,'' he said.
</P>
<P>
   His daughter, Winsome Fennell of Queens, who attended the
auction, said she remembered riding around Chinatown and Queens in
the cab.
</P>
<P>
   ``He always went to a special car wash to get it cleaned
properly,'' she said of her father, who called the cab Janie, after
an old sweetheart.
</P>
<P>
   The Checker Motor Co., which produced the familiar and
distinctive cars that became a symbol of New York, stopped making
the cabs four years after Johnson bought his.
</P>
<P>
   The cab had been expected to sell at Sotheby's auction house for
$20,000 to $30,000, according to the catalog, which described it in
terms that made it sound toothsome: ``traditional New York exterior
yellow livery with checkerboarding.'' And not to be missed:
``interior black Naugahyde in good condition with one small
repaired scratch to upper portion of back seat.'' The cab included
a cellular phone and slightly dented hubcaps.
</P>
<P>
   The bids started at $15,000 and climbed by increments of $5,000,
then $10,000, which were converted on an electronic board to
francs, pounds, marks, Canadian and Hong Kong dollars, euros, yen,
and lira.
</P>
<P>
   Paul Gunther, development director of the New-York Historical
Society, quit bidding at $50,000. He had hoped to display the coach
next to the coach George Washington used in his inauguration.
</P>
<P>
   A battle then ensued between a bidder on the phone and a taxi
medallion broker. The final bid from the telephone caller, whose
name Sotheby's did not divulge, was $120,000, plus a $14,500
premium that went to the auction house.
</P>
<P>
   Andy Murstein, 35, dropped out at $110,000, just before the
winning bid. He is the president of Medallion Financial Corp.,
which sells taxi medallions and makes loans to taxi drivers. He had
hoped to use the Checker as both a personal car and a company
vehicle. Murstein said that his grandfather had bought one of the
first taxi medallions sold by the city, for $10, in 1937.
Medallions now sell for about $250,000.
</P>
<P>
   ``Taxis are just a great part of New York,'' said Murstein, who
drives a Lincoln Navigator and plans to try to buy another Checker
cab from private owners. He has his eye on one with only 700,000
city miles under its belts.
</P>
<P>
   ``This was our first choice,'' he said of the 1978 model. ``This
one had a little bit more sentimentality to it.''
</P>
<P>
   Like a faltering rock band, the taxi was hired out for weddings
and anniversaries in its twilight years. Saturday, a magnet
announcing ``I am New York'' decorated the dashboard, along with a
small calendar, turned to August.
</P>
<P>
   As she drove the cab to a storage garage, Laura Harden, senior
manager of the Sotheby's car department, headed north on York
Avenue with the on-duty light on. Two men on the corner of East
72nd Street tried to hail it. As often seems the case when the
competition for a cab is intense, Janie passed them by.
</P>
</TEXT>
</BODY>
